<HEADLINE>
PINCAY DOESN'T HAVE TO WIN TO HAVE FUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL MAR, Calif. _ Laffit Pincay got beat in the Pacific Classic
on Saturday but seemed to have fun anyway. You might have forgotten
it could work that way for the winningest jockey of all time.
</P>
<P>
   For years now, the highlights of Pincay's great career have been
painted by the numbers, chronicled with a calculator. There was the
heroic drive for victory No.8,000 (accomplished at Del Mar Aug. 29,
1993). The drama of the record-tying No.8,833 (Hollywood Park, Dec.
9, 1999). The ecstasy of No.8,834 (the next day). And lately the
climb toward 9,000.
</P>
<P>
   As if the wins are all that matters.
</P>
<P>
   But something important had been missing as Pincay grew into the
role of elder statesman among the nation's elite riders. When it
came to the major races, the ones that really get the blood
pumping, the 53-year-old Panamanian had gotten used to being passed
over by horse owners and trainers in favor of younger jockeys.
</P>
<P>
   The snub is, well, an old story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been riding in the big races,'' said a
matter-of-fact Pincay, who hadn't had a mount in the Pacific
Classic since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Which explains why, when Corey Nakatani was injured in a heavy
fall an hour before the 10th Pacific Classic, leaving favorite and
defending champion General Challenge without a jockey, Pincay
didn't expect to be named as the replacement.
</P>
<P>
   He might have been the only one.
</P>
<P>
   When Nakatani and a filly named Candace in Paris went down after
clipping another horse's heels on the turn for home in the sixth
race, and Nakatani went to the hospital with a hairline fracture of
his left collarbone, everybody with a program in his pocket turned
to the jockey standings and knew Pincay was the best alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay was tied for second with 21 wins at Del Mar. Of the top
nine, only Pincay, Alex Solis (out of town) and Tyler Baze (a
17-year-old apprentice) weren't locked into other Pacific Classic
assignments.
</P>
<P>
   General Challenge's trainer, Bob Baffert, didn't hesitate to
choose Pincay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even have to use a lifeline,'' Baffert said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Del Mar managed to prolong the unexpected drama. The
horses were coming into the saddling paddock, less than 20 minutes
before the $1 million race, and the bettors hadn't been told who'd
be riding the even-money favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's riding, Bob?'' a couple of guys yelled at Baffert as he
ambled into the walking ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laffit,'' Baffert shouted back. A small hurrah erupted among
the fans close enough to hear.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Trevor Denman made the announcement, and the public
murmured its approval.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay strode out of the jockeys' room and a television
interviewer stuck a microphone in his face. All eyes were on the
muscular little man in the burgundy and gold of Golden Eagle Farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I made the right move,'' Baffert told him, ``because
as soon as your name was announced, everybody cheered.'' Pincay
beamed.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's third race, he had ridden the Del Mar-loving mare
Theresa's Tizzy to a gritty victory in a $150,000 sprint. That was
No.8,971, and he would add one to that tally later on.
</P>
<P>
   Could he get General Challenge to the wire in front in the
all-important eighth race, in what would have been Pincay's first
million-dollar victory since he won the 1993 Breeders' Cup Juvenile
Fillies at Santa Anita aboard Phone Chatter?
</P>
<P>
   Alas, he couldn't. But it was hardly Pincay's fault. General
Challenge just wasn't good enough Saturday to handle Skimming.
Pincay put the 4-year-old in position to win. General Challenge
couldn't stay with the front-runner in the stretch and finished
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very difficult to ride. To put Laffit in that situation
is tough,'' Baffert said. Then the trainer dispelled the notion
that General Challenge lost because Pincay had never ridden him
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't look quite right coming down the stretch,'' Baffert
said of the horse, not the jockey. ``Something happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, reporters gathered around Pincay, just as they did in
the good old days when it wouldn't have been a major race without
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just didn't fire today,'' Pincay said of General Challenge.
``When he got in the clear, I expected a big finish.''
</P>
<P>
   Pincay didn't get his big finish. But he got a shot at glory.
That was something.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it would have been nicer to win it,'' he said. ``But it
was nice.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kevin Modesti's column appears in the Daily News three days a week.
He can be reached at (818) 713-3616. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
