<SLUG> BC-FBC-TECH-NEW-MEXICO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE STEALS SHOW IN TEXAS TECH'S WIN AGAINST NEW MEXICO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUBBOCK, Texas _ As have many this summer who ply their trade
through the friendly skies, Air Raider last night experienced its
share of system glitches.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mike Leach era at Texas Tech nevertheless got off the
ground as the Red Raiders defeated New Mexico, 24-3, in the
inaugural Transamerica Hispanic College Fund Classic before an
announced crowd of 42,238.
</P>
<P>
   Leach's pass-happy offensive scheme had few stellar moments,
producing 186 passing yards and only 255 yards total offense.
Quarterback Kliff Kingsbury completed 21 of 47 passes for 186 yards
and two touchdown passes _ 6 yards to running back Ricky Williams
and 8 yards to wideout Derek Dorris. But the expected explosion did
not materialize.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't play well and made too many bad reads,'' Kingsbury
said. ``We had some opportunities to get our offense going. I just
don't feel like I played well enough to get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech coordinator Greg McMackin's new defense stole the spotlight
and iced the victory with a 63-yard touchdown return on a fumble
recovery by defensive end Aaron Hunt with 8 minutes, 22 seconds in
the fourth quarter. Tech defenders limited the Lobos to 167 yards
total offense and also held on downs late in the game after New
Mexico had first-and-goal from the two after a pass-interference
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question the defense rose to the occasion and shut
them down,'' Leach said. ``Offense and special teams need to get
better. We expect to get better, no question about it. We need to
polish and protect the quarterback better.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunt's rumble with the fumble was the play of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Down 17-3, New Mexico grasped what proved to be its last chance
to get back into the game when David Mauer blocked Eric Rosiles'
punt to set the Lobos up at the Tech 30. On third-and-nine,
quarterback Jeremy Denson moved left on the option and was covered
by black shirts. End Devon Lemons knocked the ball loose, Hunt
picked it up and was gone.
</P>
<P>
   The defense also produced three pivotal plays in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``McMackin has them playing like their hair is on fire,'' New
Mexico coach Rocky Long said.
</P>
<P>
   On New Mexico's first possession of the second half, the Red
Raiders held on fourth-and-three from their 17 when Denson bobbled
the snap and the play lost 4 yards. That prevented New Mexico from
answering Tech's 72-yard scoring drive that opened the third
quarter, capped by Kingsbury's 8-yard scoring pass on a slant
pattern to Dorris.
</P>
<P>
   Tech cornerback Antwan Alexander, the Raiders' player of the
game, then turned in big plays on successive series. He went high
to come down with an interception of a deep pass off Denson's arm
at the Raiders' 3-yard-line. Then, after New Mexico had taken over
on an interception at the Tech 21, Alexander picked up a loose
fumble at the 7-yard line and returned the ball down the left side
to the end zone. But officials called a clip by linebacker Dorian
Pitts on the return, and the ball was brought back to the New
Mexico 39.
</P>
<P>
   Tech couldn't score and settled for Chris Birkholz's 33-yard
field goal with 33 seconds left in the third quarter for the 17-3
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Tech led 7-3 at the half after New Mexico's Vladimir Borombozin
kicked a 49-yard field goal on the last play.
</P>
<P>
   Williams scored Tech's only first-half touchdown, taking a short
toss in the right flat and scoring untouched from the 6-yard line
at 6:44 of the first quarter. Williams' first touchdown reception
of his career came on the fourth play of a 40-yard drive after a
short New Mexico punt. The Lobos failed to move to a first down
after Tech's Shaud Williams downed Rosiles' 57-yard punt at the New
Mexico 1-yard line. \Nsubheds:Briefly Texas Tech leads the all-time
series with New Mexico 30-5-2 and has won the past seven games
against the Lobos. ... The Red Raiders wore new black uniforms. ...
Tech officials relented yesterday afternoon and lifted a local
television blackout they had imposed Thursday because of lagging
ticket sales. ... Running back Ricky Williams played the entire
game without apparent problems with his rehabilitated left knee,
gaining 78 yards on 15 carries ... Derek Dorris led all receivers
with 4 catches for 53 yards.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
