r s BC-FBC-OKLAHOMA-HEUPEL-T     08-27 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-OKLAHOMA-HEUPEL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOONERS QUARTERBACK HASN'T CHANGED DESPITE THE EXPECTATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORMAN, Okla. _ Greater expectations don't appear to bother
Oklahoma quarterback Josh Heupel a pip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Josh remembers that before everyone knew him as Josh Heupel
the Oklahoma quarterback, they were skeptical of what he could do,
and he didn't give that much thought then,'' teammate and roommate
Josh Norman said. ``Now that people do know who Josh is and they're
expecting big things of him, he still doesn't pay attention.''
</P>
<P>
   The same guy as always looks back from whatever mirror Heupel
happens to see himself in, Norman explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Josh can't forget who he was, what it took to get him here,''
he said. ``And he knows it will take the same thing to keep him
here and keep him constantly getting better.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll do what it takes. And if that means not paying attention
to whatever people are saying about him, not paying attention to
what they expect of him, then that's what he's going to do. The
first thing that I think of when I think of Josh Heupel is
dedication. Dedication to anything he does, regardless.''
</P>
<P>
   Record-setting Sooners quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Heisman Trophy candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Strong arm. Quick mind.
</P>
<P>
   The player who more than anyone else is responsible for the
sense among eager OU fans that the Sooners are on the verge of
reasserting themselves as one of college football's elite programs.
Son of a small-town football coach from the northeast corner of
South Dakota who seldom reads the sports pages or watches sports on
television, yet is acutely conscious of the position to which he
has been thrust.
</P>
<P>
   ``God puts people in certain situations,'' Heupel said
matter-of-factly. ``I've done nothing to create all this, and I
realize what a blessing this all has been. But I enjoy the position
I'm in and the responsibility placed on my shoulders. I'm humbled
by this every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``My expectations of myself are no different than they have ever
been. The only thing that has changed is the expectations of the
fans and the media.''
</P>
<P>
   Justifiably so. An unknown quarterback from an obscure junior
college (Snow) in Utah, the left-hander emerged last season in OU's
pass-happy offense to become the Big 12 offensive newcomer of the
year. He set school and conference season passing records for
attempts (500), completions (310), yards (3,460) and touchdown
passes (30) in leading the Sooners to a 7-5 record and their first
bowl appearance in five seasons. He also set and reset five OU
single-game passing marks.
</P>
<P>
   Spring ratings from National Football Scouting Inc. _ a firm
that provides analyses to NFL teams _ ranks him behind only
Purdue's Drew Brees among this year's crop of senior college
quarterbacks. He is a major reason why the Sooners at No. 19 are
ranked in The Associated Press preseason poll for the first time in
five years and are picked as the major contender to Texas for the
Big 12 South crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our expectations of Josh as well as of our offense is that
both should be better,'' Sooners coach Bob Stoops said. ``There are
several factors that should help Josh improve. He's worked hard on
strength, conditioning, technique and fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not fond of comparing people, but he has that \Rformer
Florida quarterback\S Danny Wuerfel-type poise and calm. I see that
in Josh. Danny didn't have a strong arm, but he had touch and so
does Josh. And they both have great minds for getting you out of a
bad play into a good one.''
</P>
<P>
   One key to Heupel's sensed improvement this season is new
quarterback coach and passing-game coordinator Chuck Long, the
former Iowa quarterback who won the Davey O'Brien and Maxwell
trophies in 1985 and spent eight seasons in the NFL. Long in effect
filled the slot of former OU assistant Mike Leach, now head coach
at Texas Tech, after five seasons on the Iowa staff.
</P>
<P>
   Though Leach and Heupel were close, and shared endless hours in
discussion and film study, Long has brought a new dimension to
Heupel's game _ both physically and mentally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Leach and I had a good working relationship,'' Heupel
said. ``His door was always open and once you spend a lot of time
with a person, you tend to think a lot alike. We had the same views
on offense. But coach Long and I can share experiences as
quarterbacks that coach Leach and I didn't have.''
</P>
<P>
   Careful not to step on any toes, Long agreed that having played
the position helps.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of very good coaches who have not played the
game, but who have studied the game and know what they're doing,''
Long said. ``But there is a rapport there \Rbetween a former
quarterback and pupil\S that no one else has.''
</P>
<P>
   You notice things others don't. When he joined the Sooners'
staff in December, before the Independence Bowl, Long immediately
began refining Heupel's throwing mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Josh was a chronic back-foot thrower,'' Long said. ``He was
awfully accurate last year but could have been even more accurate
not throwing off his back foot as much. Getting more weight balance
in your drop and setup, you can follow through better.
Follow-through creates accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, when you throw off your back foot, your arm wears down
over the course of the season. We want Josh strong in the fourth
quarter and strong at the end of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Long was immediately impressed with Heupel's dedication and
knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is as good as I have seen at this level as far as work
ethic and being a student of the game,'' Long said. ``And he's a
lot better than a lot of them at the next level. If he carries that
through for the rest of his career, it will be extended for a long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Heupel does not like to talk about himself and is a little
embarrassed by the Heisman hype. But that doesn't mean he is not
mindful of the aura surrounding what could be his legacy in the
glorious history of Oklahoma football, which is on graphic display
in the 7,000-square-foot Legends Lobby in the Barry Switzer Center
that also houses team facilities adjacent to Memorial Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Included among the memorabilia are tributes to OU's three former
Heisman Trophy winners _ Billy Vessels (1952), Steve Owens (1969)
and Billy Sims (1978).
</P>
<P>
   ``I walk through the Switzer Center every day,'' Heupel said.
``One reason I came to Oklahoma was because of the tradition of
success you see in those rooms. I realize the great history, and to
me that places a great responsibility on my shoulders to uphold
that tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Should he win the Heisman, Heupel said, ``It won't be based
really on anything I do but putting the team in a position to win
every Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   That he has already done. \Ntagtop:Mike Jones, (817) 390-7760
\Ntagbottom:jonz\Nstar-telegram.com
The Heupel file
</P>
<P>
   Position: Quarterback
</P>
<P>
   Class: Senior
</P>
<P>
   Height: 6-foot-2
</P>
<P>
   Weight: 210 pounds
</P>
<P>
   Hometown: Aberdeen, S.D.
</P>
<P>
   Career: 1995 South Dakota Prep Player of the Year at Aberdeen
Central High School. ... Began his college career at Weber State.
Redshirted in 1996 and played in only four games in 1997. ...
Transferred to Snow (Utah) Junior College in 1998. Earned first
team NJCAA All-America honors after throwing for 2,308 yards and 28
touchdowns with only five interceptions. ... Transferred to
Oklahoma in 1999 and immediately worked his way into the starting
lineup. Named Big 12 Conference newcomer of the year by several
news outlets. Set school and conference records for attempts (500),
completions (310), percentage (.620), yards (3,460) and touchdown
passes (30). Heupel's highs
</P>
<P>
   Passing yards: 429 yards, vs. Louisville
</P>
<P>
   Touchdown passes: 5, vs. Indiana State and Louisville
</P>
<P>
   Completions: 37, vs. Baylor
</P>
<P>
   Attempts: 58, vs. Colorado
</P>
<P>
   Source: University of Oklahoma
nn
</P>
