<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX GET THEIR KICKS 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ROYALS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ A night after Sox starter Jeff Fassero verbally
kicked his boss for pulling him out of a game, another starter,
Rolando Arrojo, Saturday &UR;  &LR; night lasted no longer than Fassero. But
Arrojo kicked an object instead of his boss.
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo, who was coasting after the Sox seized a 4-0 lead in
their first at-bat, turned on himself after giving up a two-out,
two-run homer to Johnny Damon in the fifth. When he reached the
dugout after the inning, the generally placid Arrojo kicked in
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess he kicked a bucket,'' manager Jimy Williams said. ``I
just told him not to drink the water.''
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo wasn't sure what he kicked _ a fence, a bucket, a cooler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't even looking,'' he said through one of the world's
most highly paid translators, Pedro Martinez. ``I just kicked. I
was frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Two pitches into the sixth, he was gone, lost for the night with
a right ankle contusion.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Sox, they were not lost without him, as they
were bolstered yet again by the league's stingiest bullpen and
outlasted the Royals, 5-3, before 30,199 at Kauffman Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The victory kept the Sox a half-game ahead of Cleveland in the
American League wild-card race and dropped Oakland a full game
behind. Boston stayed three games behind the Yankees in the AL
East.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Lowe posted his 31st save, despite a ``Twilight Zone''
episode in which he balked by turning to throw to first to hold on
a runner, Gregg Zaun, who already had stolen second.
</P>
<P>
   That put Zaun at third with two outs and the ever-dangerous
Damon representing the tying run at the plate. With Lowe grinning
sheepishly, Williams rushed to the mound to settle him down.
</P>
<P>
   The manager joked to Lowe that he must have allowed Zaun to take
third because he wanted to pitch from the windup. ``I didn't want
him to focus on what just happened,'' Williams said. ``I wanted to
get him back on the hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Damon grounded out, and Lowe finished his 50th game of the
season, after Hipolito Pichardo and Rich Garces set him up. He said
afterward he never checks runners because the Sox don't try to hold
them at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mental mistake,'' he said. ``Luckily, it didn't come
back to haunt us.''
</P>
<P>
   There was also something mental about Arrojo's mistake. But he
said the injury was minor and would not force him to miss his next
start, which is a good sign for the Sox since they have won all
five games he has started since he lost his Sox debut July 30.
</P>
<P>
   He scattered five hits and didn't allow a walk for the first
time since he joined the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo credited Martinez in part for his improved control. Just
before he started the game, Martinez advised Arrojo to ``block out
everything else and just pitch straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Too bad he didn't think straight in the sixth. ``I have never
done that before,'' he said of his kung fu moment. ``It was
something that just happened. I felt bad because I made a
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when he sat in the dugout after the kick, he said to
Martinez, ``Why am I doing that?''
</P>
<P>
   He threw two pitches in the sixth, retiring Mike Sweeney before
summoning Williams. ``I wanted to stay in the game,'' he said,
``but I thought I could help the team better by just telling the
manager what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams agreed. ``That was the smart thing to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the Sox scored all the runs they needed in the
first.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks after Royals starter Brian Meadows frustrated the
Sox, holding them to one run in 6 2/3 innings of relief in a 7-5
Royals victory at Fenway, Boston hitters struck swiftly.
</P>
<P>
   After Jose Offerman slapped a single to left to open the game,
Brian Daubach took Meadows to the waterfall beyond the right-field
fence, a 418-foot shot that gave the Sox a 2-0 edge.
</P>
<P>
   The home run was Daubach's 19th. And it was unusual, in that
Daubach has developed a habit of going deep when the Sox need it
most in the late innings. Of his 70 RBIs, 32 have come in the
seventh inning or later.
</P>
<P>
   The homer was particularly sweet for Daubach because he crushed
it in front of his family and many friends, who motored to the game
from his hometown of Belleville, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   They had seen the Sox lose, 6-2, the night before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming off a tough loss, it's always good to score early in
the game,'' Daubach said. ``It was a big lift for everyone, and it
helped Arrojo relax a little bit. He did a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra, who went 3 for 4, improving his average to
.373 after returning from a three-game absence because of a
strained left hamstring, followed Daubach's shot with a single to
center. He moved to third on Troy O'Leary's double, and Scott
Hatteberg drove in both Garciaparra and O'Leary with a single into
the left-field corner for the four-run advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo took it from there, making one mistake, the pitch to
Damon, before yielding to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has pitched some solid games,'' Williams said. ``He has a
resilient arm. He can take you deep in a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Barring a kick here or there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
