<HEADLINE>
ZARLEY TAKES SENIORS LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
 CLASSIC-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, Mass. _ One by one, they took their turns on the
leaderboard, and just as quickly as they got there, they fell off.
</P>
<P>
   First-round co-leaders Larry Nelson, Simon Hobday, and Harold
Henning clung to the top rung before falling back. Jim Ahern gave
it a whirl. So, very briefly, did Dana Quigley.
</P>
<P>
   But the man standing alone at the end of the day was Kermit
Zarley, a nonwinner since 1994 who checked in with a 5-under 67,
for a two-day total of 136, to lead the Senior PGA Tour FleetBoston
Classic under another picture-postcard day at Nashawtuc CC.
</P>
<P>
   He goes into Sunday's final round of the $1.3 million tournament
with a one-stroke lead over Nelson, who birdied the 18th to set up
an interesting final.
</P>
<P>
   Another stroke behind at 138 were Ahern and Terry Dill.
</P>
<P>
   But there are a few others within striking distance, too.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Trevino is just three shots behind Zarley after digging deep
into his bag of tricks to fire 65_139 in a round that featured
seven birdies. Dave Stockton (70) is also at 139, as are David
Graham (70), Leonard Thompson (68), Chuck Moran (71), Ed Dougherty
(70).
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the last putt dropped, Zarley playfully began
playing mind games with Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some really good players out there,'' he said, ``and
Larry Nelson is one of them. Hey, there's no question about it,
Larry Nelson is a better player than I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, who was awaiting his turn at the podium, said, ``But
Kermit is playing better than I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Zarley overcame a double bogey on the par-3, 189-yard second,
with birdies at holes 4, 7, and 9, to go 6 under and make the turn
in 33. He picked up another stroke with an 8-foot birdie on the
15th and yet another, a 20-footer, on 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a lucky break on 13,'' said Nelson about the par-3,
203-yard hole. ``I hit a 3-iron to the left of the hole, but it hit
a fir tree and dropped down just 8-10 feet off the green. I was
able to save par there rather than lose a stroke.''
</P>
<P>
   Zarley credited his caddie son, Mike, 29, with detecting a flaw
in his swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Canada (AT&AMP;T Canada Senior Open), I was back in about 40th
place. I was disgusted with the way I was hitting the ball. I asked
him what I was doing wrong and asked him to watch me swing and see
what he could find.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a smart kid and he told me my swing was too fast in the
transition. That I was trying to slow it down, but that it still
looked like I was trying to kill the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   His son obviously knew what he was seeing, because the next
week, at the Novell Utah Showdown, Zarley had rounds of 65-68-71 en
route to a fourth-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson followed Friday's opening-round 67 with a lackluster 70.
He had just three birdies and admitted his putting was way off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I putted just awful,'' he said. ``If that comes around, I feel
pretty good about my game. Every green out there today seemed a
little different. Some were firmer than others. I don't know that
anything is safe tomorrow because the scores are so bunched. I feel
like someone is going to shoot low.''
</P>
<P>
   Dill, who started the day 1 under at 71, had five birdies to not
only win the Georgia-Pacific Super Seniors segment of the
FleetBoston, but to thrust himself firmly into contention to win
the whole shooting match.
</P>
<P>
   He, like Zarley, credited a member of his family with detecting
a flaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife (Linda) gave me a putting lesson (Friday). It had to
do with my posture when I stand over a putt. I worked on it in
front of the mirror. I think she knew what she was doing because I
made six birdies, all with pretty good putts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
