<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TANTRUM LEAVES ARROJO ON FENCE 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ANALYSIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ If there is an insurance policy protecting
Red Sox starting pitchers against freak injuries, the premiums shot
sky-high again Saturday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   The team that already lost one pitcher because he slept on his
pillow wrong (Jeff Fassero), another because he rolled out of bed
onto a drinking glass (Paxton Crawford), and a third because a
teammate in Pawtucket decided to practice some martial arts on his
face (Tomo Ohka), lost Rolando Arrojo Saturday &UR;  &LR; night when he
elected to test his place-kicking technique on the protective fence
in front of the visitors' dugout here.
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo apparently planted his right foot into the fence en route
to the bench after giving up a two-run homer to Johnny Damon of the
Royals with two out in the fifth, cutting the Sox lead to 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo struck out the next batter, Rey Sanchez, on three pitches
to end the inning, but the man who seldom shows any emotion while
on the mound took his anger out on the fence, and the fence won.
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo came out for the sixth, but after throwing just two
pitches to Mike Sweeney, who lined out to Trot Nixon in right,
Arrojo immediately looked into the dugout, which brought manager
Jimy Williams hustling to the mound. With Jose Offerman acting as
translator, Williams quickly deduced the Cuban righthander was done
for the night.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, another early call went out to the bullpen, but
unlike Fassero's complaint the night before, this one had nothing
to do with Williams's quick hook. And the Sox relievers, as they
have done almost all season, were equal to the task, including
Hipolito Pichardo, whose surgically repaired elbow has been put to
a severe test this summer and who is starting to show alarming
signs of wearing down.
</P>
<P>
   According to the pressbox announcement during the game, Arrojo
had a contusion on his right ankle, which doesn't sound serious.
Arrojo, who said he wasn't sure what he kicked, explained after the
game that the doctor said he was OK and Arrojo could make his next
start. The Sox can only hope.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake about it: Until Ramon Martinez comes back and
shows he's capable of pitching here the way he did Friday in
Buffalo, when he held the Triple A Bisons to two hits in seven
innings, Arrojo is the Sox' No. 2 pitcher behind Pedro Martinez and
perhaps the key to the Sox returning to the postseason for a third
straight season.
</P>
<P>
   With 36 games left in the season, Arrojo figures to make seven
more starts for the Sox, almost all against playoff contenders. As
the schedule stands now, he would face the Mariners Friday night in
Fenway Park, the A's the following Wednesday, the Yankees in Yankee
Stadium Sept. 11, the suddenly hot Tigers in Detroit Sept. 16, the
Indians in Fenway Park Sept. 21, and the White Sox in Chicago Sept.
26.
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo, who warmed up for this pennant race by pitching in games
in which Fidel Castro took an intense personal interest, hasn't
lost since his first start for the Sox July 30, after coming from
Colorado with Mike Lansing in the Brian Rose/Jeff Frye/John Wasdin
trade.
</P>
<P>
   He had three wins and two no-decisions in his last five starts,
and the Sox have won all those games, including Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's
5-3 victory.
</P>
<P>
   He has the live fastball, the hard breaking stuff, and the
commanding mound demeanor of a big-game pitcher. He certainly has
the experience: He pitched a full decade for the Cuban national
team before his dramatic defection, and Sox general manager Dan
Duquette was among the first to laugh openly about Arrojo's age
when he signed a $7 million bonus to pitch for the Tampa Bay Devil
Rays. His bio says he is 32. If that's his age, the Sox should
invite Luis Tiant back to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   But at any age, he is central to the Sox' hopes of playing in
October. Which is why they can't afford to have him lose his
temper. They've already seen how costly that can be with a certain
center fielder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
