<SLUG> BC-McCARTHY-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEN PALS MEET AT LAST
</HEADLINE>
 
(Conn., Visalia, Calif. ATTN) 
(EDITORS: Saturday in story refers to Aug. 26.) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Dennis McCarthy is a columnist for the Los Angeles Daily News.) 
By DENNIS McCARTHY  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They've been acting like a couple of little kids
getting ready for a play date, all excited and giddy, their
families say _ these two 73-year-old women meeting for the first
time Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   You can't blame them. Carolyn Blanchard and Valerie Mulhair have
been the best of friends for 57 years.
</P>
<P>
   By mail.
</P>
<P>
   Every week, they've written each other letters pouring out their
lives, every Christmas and on birthdays their families have
exchanged cards.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they were getting ready to meet face-to-face _ not living
behind their words anymore. And they were nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I called her, and told her who I was, we both got so
excited because we had never even heard each other's voices
before,'' Carolyn said Friday from the suburban Canyon Country home
of her son and daughter-in-law where the meeting would take place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started laughing because we had to yell to make each other
heard. Our hearing's not what it used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Not much usually is after 73 years of living, but there's
nothing wrong with their memories.
</P>
<P>
   They might not be able to remember exactly what was in that
first letter Valerie mailed Carolyn from her parents' home in
Sydney, Australia, in 1943, but Carolyn remembers like it was
yesterday, looking in her mailbox in the tiny town of Seymour,
Conn., and wondering who the heck did she know in Australia?
</P>
<P>
   ``I had met her uncle, Timmy, when he was on leave from the Army
in Sydney, and he told me about his niece back in the States who
was my age,'' Valerie said Friday from Visalia, Calif. her home
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought it would be a great idea if we became pen pals, so
we did. Fifty-seven years later, we still are.''
</P>
<P>
   The need for regular dialysis treatment has kept Carolyn from
making the long cross country trip to visit her son, Robert, living
in Canyon County, but her daughter-in-law, Lori, was determined
that the two women should finally meet in person.
</P>
<P>
   ``We arranged for her medical needs, and a clinic for her
dialysis treatments every other day,'' Lori said. ``This was just
too important not to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a strange thing, both women say being a pen pal that many
years. They've gone from FDR to Clinton together, from the days of
radio to a crazy new invention called television to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Through their letters, they've laughed and cried together,
watched each other's families grow up and have families of their
own, and leaned on each other shoulders through illnesses and
heartbreak.
</P>
<P>
   In so many ways, they say, they are truly best friends even
though they've never formally met.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie named her first daughter after Carolyn, and Carolyn
poured out her heart to her Australian friend as a young woman,
afraid she would never meet the right man, get married and have
children.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie told her, nonsense, she would. And, of course, she did.
</P>
<P>
   There's something so completely honest and true about having a
friend who knows you only from your words in a letter, both women
say.
</P>
<P>
   No pretensions, no petty jealousy, no promising to meet next
week for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   It's the main reason they've never met before. Why would you
want to spoil something so special? A friendship that has been
allowed to evolve over 57 years in more than 5,000 letters, with an
occasional photo to get an image in your mind.
</P>
<P>
   But now it was finally time to meet, and both women were as
nervous as could be Saturday morning as Valerie Mulhair's car
pulled onto Carolyn Blanchard's street.
</P>
<P>
   It was an emotional meeting, how could it not be? Both woman
stood in the middle of the street embracing and crying
</P>
<P>
   their families standing on the curb trying hard not to cry
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``They held up traffic on the street for five minutes just
standing out there hugging,'' Lori said. ``They wouldn't let go of
one another.''
</P>
<P>
   When they finally did, Valerie reached into her purse and handed
Carolyn a picture of her Uncle Timmy standing next to a young girl
from Australia in 1943.
</P>
<P>
   ``He set us up,'' Valerie said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, he did,'' Carolyn said, taking her friend's arm in hers,
and walking her into the house both of them laughing and carrying
on like a couple of kids on a play date.
</P>
<P>
   Two 73-year-old pen pals finally able to hug and touch each
other after 57 years of living behind words.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-00 0230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
