<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-CREW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARRIS, REVOLUTION TOP CREW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Revolution appear to have finally
developed a playoff mentality. And that compensated for their flaws
in a 2-1 win over Columbus Saturday &UR;  &LR; night which launched them
ahead of the Crew into seventh place in the MLS.
</P>
<P>
   The late-game mistakes which have plagued the Revolution have
been reduced in the last eight days as the team earned two
successive victories with concentrated defending, an effective
central midfield combination, and the consistent individual
striking efforts of Wolde Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Harris converted the winning goal in the 51st minute, scoring in
his seventh successive game to tie the MLS record set by Raul Diaz
Arce of D.C. United in 1997. Harris, who will play for Jamaica
against the Cayman Islands Sunday afternoon, dribbled past Todd
Yeagley and finished with a low shot into the far left corner of
the net in the 51st minute for his 15th goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution's game plan was based on purposeful
defending, keyed by libero Mauricio Wright, the midfield trio of
Leonel Alvarez, Joe Franchino, and John Harkes, and the pressing of
forward William Sunsing.
</P>
<P>
   Franchino stayed with Crew midfielder John Wilmar Perez, whose
choreographing had been a key to Columbus' 3-1 and 4-1 wins over
the Revolution earlier in the season. Alvarez limited the
effectiveness of Brian McBride, who played as a withdrawn forward,
in the second half, after McBride had converted a 20th-minute
penalty for the first goal of the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a great win because it proved we could concentrate
for 90 minutes and get a result,'' Revolution coach Fernando
Clavijo said.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have 39 points, 1 more than Columbus and 2 more
than the team record set in 1997, and will meet D.C. United at
Foxboro Stadium Wednesday and in Washington Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole team has confidence we can defend a one-goal lead to
the end,'' said Harris, who was replaced by Jamar Beasley in the
81st minute. ``I wanted to come out of the game because I felt my
calves tightening. It was a good move because it gave us a chance
to get some fresh legs out there to pressure the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution spent most of the game doing just that.
</P>
<P>
   Sunsing, nicknamed ``El Travieso'' (``The Menace''), disrupted
the rhythm of the Crew's strong, but predictable, back line,
forcing them to increase the pace of their clearances. Crew
goalkeeper Mark Dougherty twice left the penalty area to make
headed clearances.
</P>
<P>
   The Crew, lacking Robert Warzycha (suspended) in midfield,
struggled to complement Perez. And Revolution defenders Adam Eyre,
Rusty Pierce, and Wright kept the Columbus forwards in check,
though they received a major break on a call by referee Rich Grady
in the final minute of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the game was marked by what appeared to be makeup calls
by Grady, one possibly dating back to Aug. 5, when the Revs were
denied a possible penalty kick in a 1-1 tie with the Crew. Grady
issued eight cautions and called two penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Grady whistled a second penalty kick when Todd Yeagley and
Wright collided with both players moving away from the goal near
the edge of the penalty area. Imad Baba converted the penalty for
his seventh goal of the season in the 35th minute to tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution also capitalized as Grady awarded a free kick to
Columbus instead of allowing Jeff Cunningham to complete a solo
move against Juergen Sommer in the 45th minute, and survived two
Crew shots off the post _ by Jason Farrell in the 13th minute and
McBride in second-half injury time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a physical game from start to finish but we knew it
would be,'' said Sommer, who won for the first time against his
former team. ``I though the refereeing slowed down the game because
of so many calls. The challenges were tough but not nasty, and it's
a physical sport in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Columbus put a lot of pressure on us and had the better of the
chances. But we have a more cohesive, more balanced team out there
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
