<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY MAY HAVE BEEN AT ROOT OF EWING DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It has been more than one week since the news surfaced
that Patrick Ewing might be dealt from New York to Seattle for Vin
Baker. It has been more than 48 hours since the Knicks, in an
extraordinary confessional in this day of subterfuge and deception,
owned up to trying to do the deal.
</P>
<P>
   But even after New York general manager Scott Layden's admission
that the deal was all but completed, something still begs for an
answer: Why?
</P>
<P>
   The prevailing suspicion was that Ewing, who is finishing up a
four-year, $68 million diamond parachute, had forced the Knicks'
hand by demanding an extension. Or, perhaps, suggesting an
extension. Layden said that was not the case. ``I want to make that
clear,'' he said. That's his story and he's sticking to it.
</P>
<P>
   OK, how then, did Ewing suddenly go from indispensable to
disposable in the span of two months?
</P>
<P>
   The only possible answer: Ewing wanted an extension and the
Knicks, wisely, thought that it was not such a good idea. Wounded,
Ewing agreed to waive his no-trade clause and gave the Knicks
permission to go shopping.
</P>
<P>
   No other scenario makes any sense. Ewing fed up with Knicks
fans? How was this year different from any other? Ewing hoping to
win a title? How does he come closer with playoff wannabe Seattle
than playoff fixture New York? How are the Knicks better with
Baker? Ewing unhappy with his role?
</P>
<P>
   Ewing had to have forced this. The Knicks have always championed
him and his contributions; coach Jeff Van Gundy has been an
unflagging defender; and Layden said in June that the team's title
hopes were best served with Ewing in the middle. Two months later,
he's on the block.
</P>
<P>
   If this were strictly a basketball matter _ and very few deals
these days seem to qualify as that _ then it would be a no-brainer.
As they say in politics, go to the record. It's there in black and
white, and while Ewing may have an unrealistic opinion of his own
ability, there is no disputing what happens to the Knicks when he
plays: They win a lot more than they lose.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Ewing missed the first 20 games and the Knicks went
11-9. They were 39-23 in the games he did play, and that includes
the season-ending no-show at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing bashers point out he didn't have a basket in the fourth
quarters of the last two playoff games against Indiana. But the
Knicks might never have gotten that far had he not gone for 20
points and 10 rebounds in Game 7 at Miami, including, lest we
forget, the game-winning basket. He had gone for 15 and 18 in Game
6, when the Knicks rallied from a huge hole to send the series back
to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   But he's also 38, has battled injuries the last few years, and,
frankly, the absolute last thing he should be contemplating at this
point is an extension. It's not like he needs the money or the
security. He has plenty of both.
</P>
<P>
   He has no NBA championship rings, however, and that will be his
enduring legacy in New York, where he has a conflicted and
sometimes tortured relationship with the MSG faithful. (Although
those fans, like so many others, appreciate Ewing a lot more when
the Knicks win.) He always has come up short. But he has plenty of
company _ Charles Barkley and Karl Malone to name two. Like Ewing,
they had the misfortune of trying to win when a guy named Michael
Jordan was around.
</P>
<P>
   Layden now says that Ewing will likely stay a Knick, which
should make for an interesting fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a consummate professional,'' Layden said. ``I expect him
to come back and have a great season with the Knicks.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what he had to be expecting in June, too. Why the
about-face? There's only one story that makes any sense. Yup,
that's right: Greed. It's about the money.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of money, that was one of the driving forces behind the
Celtics' interest in the four-way trade with Utah, Golden State,
and Dallas. Lost amid all the players changing places was the
Celtics' receipt of $3 million of Mark Cuban's loose change. Add
Dana Barros's $3.7 million and the Celtics actually made $250,000
in the deal. (They assumed $6.45 million in salaries.) Some of the
principals involved said the Celtics were fixated on money during
the talks, which may explain why they and they alone came up empty
in the deal. Utah got Donyell Marshall. Golden State got Danny
Fortson (seven years, $41 million), and Dallas got Howard Eisley.
The Celtics got some extra money, two beaten-up players, and a
draft pick (see below). Rick Pitino has stated time and again that
he is under budget restraints and that he is allowed to spend the
salary cap ($35.5 million) plus the two exceptions ($3.45 million).
That works out to about $39 million. The Celtics' payroll for this
season is more than $51 million. Even taking Cuban's $3 million and
possibly some insurance relief from Hot Rod Williams's $2.11
million deal and Greg Minor's $3.24 million, that still leaves
Pitino considerably over budget . . . That deal, by the way, was
all but complete when someone noted that Bruno Sundov was unsigned.
Agent Frank Catapano, who represents the 7-foot-2-inch Sundov, then
got a call and the deal was delayed for two days until Catapano got
a deal for the Croatian center. Sundov was shipped from Dallas to
Utah after agreeing to a three-year, guaranteed deal. However, the
Jazz are liable for only the first year unless they keep him on the
roster after Oct. 1. If they don't, Catapano says he has two NBA
teams ready to pounce on Sundov, who appeared in 14 games (61
minutes) for Dallas last season . . . Another money matter: We
noted a few weeks ago that the NBA had told its teams to plan on a
salary cap of around $42.7 million next season, a 20 percent jump.
Huh? Did we miss a new television deal or three new expansion
teams? No. The salary cap for this coming season would have been
around $39 million save for a one-time credit cap the league
received because it spent more than the agreed-upon amount on
salaries. The credit will not be in place next season, hence the
big jump. However, what will be in place next season is the escrow
provision, which allows the league to withhold 10 percent of every
player's salary if it pays out more than an agreed-on percentage.
(Projections indicate they will.) The withdrawals will occur from
November to April, be placed in the bank, and, if the league's
projections are on target, will then be distributed back to the
owners. Additionally, players who customarily received their salary
in a lump sum in the summertime won't be able to do that starting
with next season. The new labor deal stipulates that each player
receive at least 30 percent of his salary from November to April,
allowing the league to make the withdrawals . . . Antoine Walker
may not like the fact that his name is being mentioned in trade
talks, and despite the obligatory team denials, he is available.
``It's not a secret,'' said Walker's agent, Mike Higgins. ``If the
right deal is out there, they'd move him. But I believe that when
it's all said and done, he will be with the Celtics when the season
starts.'' Walker also does not like to see his name and the word
``weight'' mentioned in the same sentence, which Pitino has a habit
of doing . . . The new top assistant to Isiah Thomas in Indiana is
Brendan Malone. That's the same guy Thomas hired to guide the
expansion Toronto Raptors out of the box and then summarily
dismissed after one season when the two couldn't agree on how best
to proceed. (Thomas wanted the young players to play more. Malone
wanted to win.) Malone had been an assistant with Detroit for seven
years, collecting two title rings in the process and marveling at
his new boss. ``He was the best player, leader, and competitor I've
ever been around,'' Malone said. ``I've always had this
schizophrenic relationship with Isiah. He gave me the opportunity
to be a head coach in the NBA. I appreciated that. What I didn't
appreciate is that he fired me (after a 21-61 season). But in this
business, you have to let bygones be bygones. It's been five years
since Toronto, and I've seen Isiah a lot since then.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing the Celtics simply announced that they had
received one of Utah's two first-rounders in next June's draft in
the Fortson trade. Anything else would have required the folks at
MIT to explain. After you read this, you may understand why the
trade took so long to complete. Utah has two picks in the 2001
draft, its own and one from Denver. If both picks fall in the top
15 (unlikely), Utah gets the better one. If one pick falls in the
top 15 (likely), Utah gets that one. If neither fall in the top 15
(unlikely), the Celtics get the better pick. Based on that
scenario, the Celtics would likely end up with the Jazz's pick
because Denver probably will be in the top 15 and Utah won't. Aha,
but that's only part of it. There are conditions on the Denver
pick. The Nuggets have two picks, their own and one from either
Cleveland or Phoenix. If Cleveland's pick is 14 or higher _
unlikely _ it goes to Denver. If it's in the lottery, then the
Cavaliers keep the pick and the Nuggets end up with the Suns' pick,
which likely will be in the 20s. Denver then sends the less
favorable of the two picks to Utah (probably Phoenix's) in which
case both picks would be in the 20s. Still with me? The final
option is that the Celtics could exercise their right to Denver's
own No. 1 (protected for the top picks), and the Nuggets would then
send the other one to Utah. Bottom line: If things go as expected,
Utah will likely end up with its own pick and that of the Suns.
Both should be in the mid 20s, and Boston will get the better of
the two . . . Oregon Live, a website in Portland, has conducted a
vote the last couple of weeks modeled on the TV hit ``Survivor.''
Fans were asked to vote on which member of the Trail Blazers would
remain on the island. The first to be kicked off was Jermaine
O'Neal, which is not surprising given that he wants out of town.
Damon Stoudamire was the next to go. It came down to Scottie Pippen
and Rasheed Wallace, with Wallace surviving by a 2-1 vote . . .
Everyone else seems to be wondering what the Pistons are doing
(hint: freeing up cap room doesn't make free agents want to play
for a bad team in a cold climate), but Jerry Stackhouse apparently
is not one of them. The additions of Ben Wallace, Chucky Atkins,
Billy Owens, and Mateen Cleaves has, in his mind, made the Pistons
tougher. ``I don't want to seem as just because I'm a part of the
team, I'm optimistic,'' Stackhouse told the Detroit News. ``But I
really am optimistic because we're becoming tougher. And that's
what it's all about. It's not about having the most talented guys.
These guys have talent, but they won't get frail when things go
bad.'' Did that mean that the departed Grant Hill and the
soon-to-be-departing Christian Laettner are, um, soft? ``I'm not
going to talk about what the problem was.'' Laettner (and,
possibly, Terry Mills) is presumed to be heading to Dallas for
Cedric Ceballos, John Wallace, and Eric Murdock. That deal is
expected to be announced Monday, two months since the Mavericks
acquired Wallace and Murdock in draft day deals. The Dallas Morning
News also said that newly acquired Barros and Billy Curley may be
heading to Detroit in a separate deal for the all-but-finished Loy
Vaught.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-00 0234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
