<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 02:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3273 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      08-27 1668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINDEN WILL SUBTRACT IF HOLDOUTS DISTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPES-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ If the three unsigned Bruins elect to sit out training
camp, it could wind up costing them a good deal of money.
</P>
<P>
   Anson Carter, Joe Thornton, and Sergei Samsonov are all
restricted free agents, and with training camp just over a week
away, none is close to reaching a deal with the club.
President/general manager Harry Sinden said that after the
disastrous season the team endured last year, he doesn't want the
kind of distractions at training camp that pretty well crippled the
Bruins well into November when goalie Byron Dafoe was sitting out
in a contract dispute.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid that, Sinden said, he and assistant GM Mike O'Connell
are seriously considering punishing players financially if they
don't sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the biggest damage is to the rest of the players on
the team,'' said Sinden. ``It's very tough for the coach,
especially when it's a high-profile player like Byron, to run his
training camp with the full attention of everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a $3 million offer at the beginning and he had a $3
million offer when he signed. We took off the games he missed, he
didn't get paid for that. But he didn't lose anything for missing
training camp because he wasn't getting paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a way that we're considering to drop the offers if
they miss camp and screw up and disrupt our training camp. For
example, if we're offering you $1.5 million, it's going to drop to
$1.45 million for each day you're not here or each three days.
Teams have done it, particularly New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you why I think it's proper. Even though they only
get paid during the regular season, their contract covers preseason
and the playoffs but their pay period is spread throughout the
regular season. When they miss training camp, they didn't provide
their services. If they're going to screw up this team by sitting
out, then they're going to pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden asked O'Connell to recheck the team's offers to the three
players to make sure they were fair with regard to what other
players of comparable ability are making. They came to the
conclusion that the offers were proper, although the players don't
agree. In the case of Carter, the sides are believed to be a
million dollars apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to Mike, `I don't know what else we can do. I just
don't,' '' said Sinden. ``We didn't make the playoffs, we had a
lousy team. They were a big part of it. They were no more the cause
than anybody else, but they were regular players. We must have had
a hell of team last year, didn't we? Here, we've got three guys who
are regular forwards on the team who must have made a nice
contribution to what happened to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter freely admits that his perception of his worth is
different than the Bruins'. Sinden said that if Carter wants to be
paid for what he believes he can do rather than be rewarded for
what he's done, it isn't going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is the odd player you're willing to do that with,'' he
said. ``If Bourque's contract was up or Orr's contract, a star
player who you knew was getting better every year, you might do it.
But right now, the way things go now, it's `What did you do last
year?' `What have you done in your career?' and that's where you
fit for the next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how the arbitration goes, and that's where we're coming
from. We compare them in all categories to the comparables. Two of
them didn't have arbitration and one elected not to go. Anson, if
he thought he could've gotten it, he should've gone. The other two,
if they think they can get it from the arbitrator like Radek Bonk
did, they're going to have to wait like Bonk did.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of leverage here. We could say, `I don't care
what your numbers are. That's all you're getting. You got too much
your first three years and we want it back.' But we're not saying
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said in the case of Carter, the sides are a long way
apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had to raise a suspicion in my mind that he wanted us to
trade him to somebody who would give him what they're asking,''
said Sinden. ``But you can't let them dictate. If every time you
trade a guy he gets what he wants, what is the sense? We'd have to
get a player absolutely as comparable or probably better to do it.
He's a long, long way from being a complete player. A long way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say we're close with any of them but we're further
along with Thornton. We've had more conversations with (agent) Mike
Barnett than we've had with the others.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said in addition to considering financial penalties, he
and O'Connell are also pondering whether to set a hard and fast
deadline for getting Carter signed, as Phoenix did with Nikolai
Khabibulin last year and Ottawa did with Alexei Yashin.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is either perceived or imagined as a big distraction that
screwed up this team last year, we'd have to consider it,'' Sinden
said. ``It would be one thing if they were trying to do that
because we were trying to cheat them, but we can show them the
numbers and they can't really argue.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't look as though forward Martin Rucinsky will be in
Montreal's training camp. He seems poised to sit out for the second
time in three seasons because of a contract dispute. The Canadiens
made him a qualifying offer of $2.4 million, the same salary he
made last season, after declining to pick up a $2.7 million option.
Rucinsky said he's considering playing for Litvinov in his native
Czech Republic, the same club former Coyote Robert Reichel plays
for. ``With him being there, it would make it an easier decision
for me,'' said Rucinsky. ``We played on the same line for 10 or 12
years. One thing is certain, I won't be inactive for a whole season
like Petr Nedved did a couple of years ago. I'm in the same boat as
Jose Theodore, Sheldon Souray, and Craig Rivet. I still haven't
signed a new contract. I won't go to camp without one. It's too
risky. I was surprised and disappointed at their offer. My option
year wasn't for $4 million like it was for Saku Koivu or Shayne
Corson. In my case, it was only a $300,000 raise.'' . . . Penguins
free agent Robert Dome is another player threatening to play in
Europe. But in Dome's case, money doesn't appear to be the
stumbling block. According to his agent, Jiri Crha, it's about
opportunity. The 21-year-old native of Slovakia, who was the
Penguins' first-round draft pick in 1997, wants a better chance to
play in the NHL rather than the minors. ``For three years, they
didn't give him an opportunity to show anything, always sending him
to the farm team,'' said Crha. ``I don't want Robert to go through
that anymore. I don't want him to go up and down, with everybody
telling him over and over why he's not playing. Just let him play.
You need a chance at least to prove somebody wrong. If you play six
shifts a game, you're never going to produce.'' . . . Wendel Clark,
who retired in June after 15 NHL seasons, is having discussions
with the Maple Leafs about joining the club in some capacity.
Whether it be in marketing, community relations, scouting, or some
other area remains to be seen. ``I'm definitely interested,'' said
Clark. ``The discussions have been going very well. It's an honor
to be associated with the Leafs and it will be great if that
relationship continues. So far, things have been informal and that
has allowed me to sit back and think about what I might like to
do.'' Leafs president Ken Dryden said Clark is still adjusting to
the fact that he won't be playing pro hockey for the first time in
15 years. ``When you are changing lives, sometimes it takes awhile
to determine what you want to do,'' Dryden said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock, whose club made it to the Cup finals
before bowing to New Jersey, said he was ``decimated'' for three
weeks after the loss. ``But when I sat back and removed myself from
the emotion, I said, `Just a second here. We had a hell of a
season,' '' said Hitchcock. ``We had a great chance to win it
again. We had some great performances and I had to overplay some
role players along the way. At the end of the day, we didn't have
the freshness we needed to get by New Jersey.'' . . . The Vancouver
Canucks re-signed goalie Felix Potvin. The 29-year-old, who went
from the Islanders to Vancouver before Christmas, had a hard time
at first, with a 1-5-3 record in his first nine starts. But his
play picked up a great deal after the All-Star break as he went
11-8-4 . . . The $175 million sale of the Devils to the YankeeNets
group is finally complete. The deal had been scheduled to be
finalized July 14 but paperwork delayed it until last Tuesday. ``I
did the deal,'' said former owner John McMullen. ``It's over with,
that's it. It's been a long, drawn-out affair, as everyone knows.
It's too bad. It is. But I had to do it.'' Payments from YankeeNets
to McMullen are being deferred over three years. ``They call it
deferred payments,'' McMullen said. ``Basically it's a loan for
three years.'' Reportedly, the new owners are planning a new
stadium in Newark . . . The acting bug bit a few NHL players this
summer. Coyotes center Jeremy Roenick, Devils center Scott Gomez,
Canadiens defenseman Souray, Flyers defenseman Chris Therien, and
Lightning goalie Kevin Weekes participated in a one-day shoot for
the ABC soap opera ``One Life to Live.'' It will air Thursday at 2
p.m. on Channel 5. Roenick, who has appeared on the Disney
Channel's ``The Jersey,'' also will be featured in the HBO show
``Arliss'' Sept. 3 . . . Fitness guru Mike Boyle, who has helped
many NHL players, including former Bruin star Cam Neely, is
expanding his business. After Labor Day, he'll have gyms in
Winchester and Canton, with off-ice programs tailored for the
hockey athlete. For more information, call Bob Hanson at
781-729-1333 . . . 11 days to training camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
