<SLUG> BC-GLF-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING _ AND SHAKING _ HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AKRON, Ohio _ They were separated by just a few yards while the
action took place at the eighth hole of Firestone Country Club in
Akron, Ohio, Thursday. On the green, Tiger Woods was rolling in a
birdie to get to 5 under par. Outside the ropes, with the
ever-present cigar clenched between his teeth, Charlie Sifford was
watching.
</P>
<P>
   Woods and Sifford. They represent two spectrums of history in
the world of professional golf.
</P>
<P>
   At one end, you have arguably the most gifted player we have
ever seen, playing at a time when prize money is enormous, the
game's popularity is far-reaching, and the public's ignorance is
less of an obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end, you have a player of considerable talent who
toiled when financial rewards were minimal and a nation's shame
slammed shut the door of opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Racial barriers were knocked down years ago, but not until it
was too late for Sifford and the great black golfers of his era,
men such as Ted Rhodes and Pete Brown. They were good enough to
compete, good enough to win, but they were never allowed to get to
the first tee. Sifford has every reason to be bitter, but as he
stood behind the eighth green Thursday, he was a man filled with
appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the greatest thing that's ever come along for golf,''
said Sifford, watching not only Woods's birdie putt but the mass of
bodies off in a flash. The gallery was swift to the ninth tee, the
Tiger Trail moving as one. Children, some white, some black, some
Asian, battled to get to the ropes, holding their fists out in
hopes that Woods would lightly punch them the way he does with
caddie Steve Williams. Adults of all shapes and sizes _ from the
country club set in their Hilfiger shirts and Footjoy shoes to the
blue-collar crowd in their tank tops and high-top sneakers _
struggled to get a glimpse of this young man who has unlocked the
mystery to this impossible game.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Sifford stood quietly and nodded his head in
admiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, man, why I'm so happy to see him,'' said Sifford. ``He
made my dream come true, because when I started it's just what I
wanted to do. But I didn't have the opportunity to do it. I wasn't
as good a player, didn't have no (financial backing), not too much
instruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor did he have any doors opened for him. The game and the
people who ran it weren't colorblind black then, so we will never
know how good Sifford was and what he could have accomplished. At
78, his resentment has subsided, in large part because Woods has
helped people appreciate Sifford and the other black golfers who
endured a nation's bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt about that,'' said Sifford. ``He said that. I think I
played a major part in African-Americans in professional golf. Of
course, if I hadn't acted like a professional man when they first
sent me out, with all the obstacles I went through and done
something crazy, well, there might not be any blacks playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people were against me. But I toughed it out. I'm
proud of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sifford remembered another visit to Firestone CC, in 1958, when
he played in the Rubber City Open. An 18-year-old amateur from
nearby Columbus, Ohio, was in the field that day, a long-hitting
phenom named Jack Nicklaus. ``The greatest I ever saw,'' said
Sifford, though he agreed that Woods is quickly approaching such
stature.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the overwhelming presence of Woods, there still aren't
enough blacks making it professionally, said Sifford, and the game
is still not being introduced to minority children as much as it
should be. He met the game as a caddie in Charlotte, N.C. (``18
holes for 60 cents,'' he said, laughing) but even that avenue has
been taken away from kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows?'' said Sifford. ``There might be somebody who comes
along better than Tiger. You never know.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all about opportunity and hard work, he said. He was
speaking from a lifetime of experience.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not that they won't be charged up when it arrives, but the
American players certainly aren't in a fever about the Presidents
Cup. Want proof? Here was Paul Azinger, when asked about playing
the matches so late in the season: ``That's when we play the Ryder
Cup, in September.'' He was told that the Presidents Cup will be
Oct. 19-22. Trying to recover, Azinger laughed and said, ``It's in
October? Oh, well, I can't make it.'' A humorous exchange, but it
serves as a reminder that the Presidents Cup does not carry the
same intensity as the Ryder Cup, at least for the Americans. The
International Team players are genuinely geared up for it, but some
fear the US players could be drained playing these team events each
year. Hal Sutton thinks things will change as the event nears. ``I
think we're looking forward to playing,'' said Sutton, who praised
the addition of Azinger as one of Ken Venturi's captain's picks
(Loren Roberts was the other). ``Paul is such a fiery, spirited,
competitive, great player,'' he said. ``Those kind of guys are good
to have on a team like that.'' . . . Say what you will about the
Presidents Cup not being the Ryder Cup, but take note that
officials at Robert Trent Jones GC in Virginia have marketed the
event brilliantly. It is a virtual sellout, with a little more than
20,000 daily tickets _ not to mention the corporate tents _ gone .
. . Chris Perry, No. 12 in the standings and very passionate about
his desire to be on the team, learned a valuable lesson: If you are
going to blow a tournament, don't do it under the eye of the
Presidents Cup captain, particularly when he's one week away from
completing his team. But that's what Perry did, making bogey to
lose to playing partner Rocco Mediate at the 72d hole of the Buick
Classic, right below the CBS tower where Venturi sat. There may
have been sympathy for Perry, 38, who last year finished just
outside the top 10 and wasn't added to the Ryder Cup team. What
worked against him was his lack of experience in international team
matches, plus the fact that he's won just once. Not fair, he said.
``I've been out here 15 years,'' said Perry. ``I've been in enough
pressure situations that I don't think it's anything I can't
handle. I've been in the hunt a lot. Yeah, I haven't come through a
lot, but if he's going to base it on a guy's experience, then
again, why do we have a two-year process? Let's just take the
favorites and most popular players and let's go; let's not even
have a system.'' . . . As for the old Catch 22 regarding experience
_ that is, if a guy doesn't have it, how does he get it? _ Sutton
had a simple solution: ``You make the team first. Don't wait on
being picked. Make the team.'' . . . Biggest winner at Valhalla in
the PGA Championship? Woods? Well, yes, and Bob May wasn't far
behind, but Australian lefthander Greg Chalmers certainly came away
with a huge smile. When Jose Maria Olazabal missed a 3-foot putt
for par at the 72d hole, it dropped him into a tie for fourth with
Stuart Appleby and Chalmers. The top four and ties earn berths in
the Masters field . . . Lee Janzen wasn't in the chase for a
Presidents Cup berth, but he was asked about it. Laughing, Janzen
said, ``All I know is Tiger has won. I think he's further ahead
than the next guy has money. And he's already got enough points to
make the Ryder Cup team next year. Heck, they ought to make him
captain.'' Janzen turns 36 Monday and hasn't won since his second
US Open title in 1998, but after finishing in a tie for 19th at
Valhalla, he was upbeat and turning his attention toward the 2001
Ryder Cup. When told it was at the Belfry, he frowned. ``I've
played twice and both times (in Europe),'' he said. ``I'd like to
play over here once.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tough to figure out Karrie Webb. She apparently was caught by
BBC cameras taking an illegal drop, an infraction that cost her a
two-shot penalty, then announced she would never do an interview
with that network again. Then she bemoaned the fact that every week
she gets asked questions about Woods. Well, guess what. She's in
great company, because every member of the PGA Tour could say the
same thing. Instead of whining, she has to learn to live with it,
as so many others do. It's too bad, because Webb is the star around
whom the LPGA needs to build so much of its fan base . . .
Fortunately, there are LPGA players like Meg Mallon, who scorched
Walnut Hills CC in East Lansing, Mich., with a 62 in Thursday's
opening round of the Oldsmobile Classic. Mallon has had a splendid
season, capped by her du Maurier triumph a few weeks ago. OK, she
grew up in Michigan and went to Ohio State, but she was born in
Natick and will forever be a local girl. Right? ``Absolutely,'' she
said. Conversations with Mallon invariably turn to this: ``What is
up with the Celtics?'' No one has figured out how to answer her yet
. . . Michelle McGann, still on the comeback trail, played Loch
Lomond in Scotland last week, just in case she were to somehow make
her way onto the Solheim Cup team for October's event . . . Biggest
concern for Solheim Cup captain Pat Bradley has to be the condition
of Dottie Pepper, arguably the team's inspirational leader. She's
been out for a few weeks with a bad back . . . Juli Inkster chose
to stay in Europe and play in the Compaq Open in Stockholm . . . A
summer fixture could end Tuesday when Chi Chi Rodriguez appears at
New England CC in Bellingham on behalf of the Muscular Dystrophy
Association. That club is up for sale, and the future of the annual
benefit event is uncertain. Rodriguez puts on a great show and
he'll do a clinic at 10:30 a.m. Spots are also available in the
ensuing tournament. Call 617-266-3600 or 508-883-2300 for
information . . . So, Woods uses a Nike golf ball that isn't the
one you can buy? Shocking. And here I was thinking he stopped off
on his way to the course and picked up a couple sleeves at the pro
shop. His TV commercial may lead you to believe you can buy the
exact same ball he uses, and that is deceptive, which is why Nike
landed in court last week, sued by a consumer group. But before you
rail against this, understand that, for good or bad, this was not
exactly news on the driving range at the NEC Invitational. ``We get
the opportunity to test prototypes,'' said Darren Clarke. ``We get
clubs and things to try before it is made available to the public.
So I'm sure this is just another step along that line.'' A quick
survey indicated no fewer than 15 of the 37 players in the NEC
field had some prototype clubs in their bags, the most notable,
reported Golfweek, being Nick Price and Azinger. They were both
using a Callaway driver that industry sources believe is a tweaked
version of the ERC, the controversial club that was banned after
failing USGA testing for ``spring-like effect'' earlier this year.
Reportedly, the club now conforms, though Price and Azinger both
had tape covering the model name. Should Woods's ad be amended to
say something to the effect that you can play Nike balls, just as
Woods does? Absolutely. But keep in mind that, for the most part,
you can't buy the equipment that Woods and his colleagues are
using. What came of all this was no surprise. Nike announced
Thursday that those balls will be made available to the public
starting in October. You will then hear cash registers ringing from
a rush of people overlooking a simple truth: It ain't the ball,
it's the person hitting it.
</P>
</TEXT>
