<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NEC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS LEAVING COMPETITION BEHIND 
</HEADLINE>
 INVITATIONAL-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AKRON, Ohio _ It is a commentary on the current state of the PGA
Tour that Tiger Woods's opposition in the third round of the NEC
Invitational Saturday came not from one of his colleagues but from
a wasp that was using the 15th green as a resting area.
</P>
<P>
   Woods thought the insect was wounded and limping into his
putting line, so he picked it up to move it. Surprise. The wasp _
unlike the guys chasing Woods _ had life. ``I got stung,'' said
Woods. ``It hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   His dominance of this World Golf Championships event at
Firestone Country Club, however, was not damaged at all. Woods
broke from the gate with a birdie-eagle-birdie start, fell back
with a bogey at the par-4 fourth, then tore off 14 straight pars to
all but lay claim to his eighth PGA Tour win of the year. Despite
going into a protective mode, Woods shot a 3-under-par 67 for a 192
total, increasing his lead from seven to nine shots.
</P>
<P>
   It was his 29th consecutive round of par or better, a PGA Tour
record, and at 18 under he established a 54-hole scoring mark for
this tournament. Facts that made him virtually yawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did the right thing,'' he said. ``I fired away from pins.
Fairways and greens. That's all I tried to do.''
</P>
<P>
   An understandable game plan in light of the seven-shot lead he
had earned thanks to Friday's sizzling 61. And one that made it
nearly impossible for the field to make up any ground. Phil
Mickelson, Woods's playing partner, made a whimper of a rally,
trimming the deficit to six with birdies at the par-3 15th and
par-5 16th, but he chopped it up coming in.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson bogeyed the par-4 17th after driving into a fairway
bunker, then three-putted from 6 feet at the 18th to close with a
double bogey. With a disappointing 69_201, he fell into a three-way
tie for second.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Hal Sutton, whose hole-in-one at the par-3 12th
highlighted the day's best round, a 65, was first in at 9 under and
will play with Woods Sunday. Unheralded Phillip Price shot 66 to
join the trio in second place, and he showed that he has a firm
grasp of the situation. ``I'm 75th in the world,'' said Price.
``I'm not trying to compete with Tiger Woods.''
</P>
<P>
   Wise lad, this Welshman, for if anyone knows how to protect a
lead, it is Woods. In 21 tournaments in which he has enjoyed a
54-hole lead, Woods has prevailed 19 times. Hence, his logic for
Sunday: ``If I make a lot of pars, they're going to have to go
awfully low to get me. If they do, I'll take my hat off to them.''
</P>
<P>
   He can plan on keeping the hat on.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever hope Mickelson had of getting back into contention was
doused early _ and in electrifying fashion as Woods, one day after
bringing the magic number 59 into the equation, did it again. He
lofted a wedge to 10 feet at the opening hole, a ``soft 6-iron''
second shot from 178 yards to 15 feet behind the pin at the par-5
second, then a wedge to a foot at No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Birdie, eagle (his third straight at this hole), birdie.
Nineteen under par. More magic on the way?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' said Woods. ``I hit a couple of marginal
shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Such as? Well, said Woods, ``I skanked it off the heel'' at the
first tee, ``pulled it about 15 feet'' with his approach into the
second, and ``heel-skanked'' the tee ball at the par-4 third.
</P>
<P>
   But don't get the idea that Woods went storming to the practice
area. ``I'm very happy,'' he said. ``A couple of times I hit bad
shots, but overall, not bad.''
</P>
<P>
   That opening burst built a cushion that was impenetrable given
the way Woods was playing. And with Mickelson going about his work
quietly _ 12 pars and two lonely birdies _ there was very little
drama. Which is OK with Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big lead, any time,'' he said, when asked if he'd prefer
someone breathing down his neck, as Bob May did at last week's PGA
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Because Mickelson wasted that birdie-birdie effort, it was left
to Woods to supply what passed as drama: his second shot to the
par-4 18th. He had driven left into deep rough, drawing a nasty
lie, and had 162 to the front of the green, 182 to the pin. Club of
choice? Wedge, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Open face, more loft,'' he said of the wild, powerful swing on
which he nearly jumped out of his shoes. ``You've got to be able to
get the ball up over the trees and then hook it against the
left-to-right wind.''
</P>
<P>
   But the swing? So ugly, he was told.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's funny-looking, but the shot ended up pretty
good.''
</P>
<P>
   He was right, of course, because the ball came to rest no more
than 15 feet from the pin and set up a two-putt par. As Mickelson
struggled to find the final hole, with three putts from a short
distance, Woods stood quietly, trying like anything to shake things
off.
</P>
<P>
   Not the competition, mind you, but the sting. The stinger was
still in the ring finger of his left hand. The competition had long
since disappeared.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
