<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOT OFFENSE'S CAPACITY UP IN AIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For good or ill, what you saw Thursday night in the
first half of the Patriots' 29-21 exhibition win over the Carolina
Panthers is how they will play offense this season. They will play
it on the run but not with the run.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it's the Drew Bledsoe Show again.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive coordinator Charlie Weis has no choice and he knows
it. He is operating a flawed machine, one that is still capable of
producing but is out of balance, and the Greeks learned eons ago
that that seldom works in life or the arena.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe is diplomatic on such matters but even he said last
week, ``We're not the kind of offense that is going to plod
downfield with 15-, 16-play drives. We'll need some big plays to
score.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been very productive to this point. I think we can
be, but we're not going to drive anybody off the ball or overpower
people. To be successful we need to cut out the mistakes, stay out
of third and long, and hit some big plays.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, things haven't changed all that much except that
there appears to be a few less armaments at Bledsoe's disposal than
he had last season, when after a strong first half the offense
collapsed and took a solid defense down with it.
</P>
<P>
   That is the challenge Bledsoe and his associates face this year,
because that defense will be at least as good if not better despite
a glaring hole at right cornerback that wily 11-year veteran Otis
Smith may fill for a season until they can get reinforcements.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Bledsoe is up to that challenge is anyone's guess.
Certainly he can't be as confident as he was even a year ago
despite his public assurances that all is well. If you know
Bledsoe, you know that while he is the eternal optimist, he also is
a realist, and when he looks around the huddle, he knows the
offensive line is no better than a year ago and may not be as good;
he knows the tight ends standing in for Ben Coates are not as
dangerous as even the aging Coates was last year; and he knows he
hasn't had a game-controlling running back since the day Curtis
Martin left and that has not changed with the arrival of limping
J.R. Redmond and game-but-slowed Raymont Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Weis finally opened up his playbook Thursday and revealed a
number of different formations _ including a full-house backfield
and a set that opened the game with three wide receivers and no
tight end _ and attacked through the air. Bledsoe threw on eight of
the game's first 10 plays, and on one of the others, wide receiver
Troy Brown ran a reverse.
</P>
<P>
   Weis inserted scrambling Michael Bishop at quarterback on short
yardage three times, and Bishop ran the option for a 1-yard
touchdown. It was interesting to watch and it led to two solid
drives in the first half, but it was far from the approach the
Patriots would have taken if there was a semblance of a running
game. Just because you run 32 times and pass 33 doesn't mean you
have a balanced attack. Not when 75 percent of your yardage comes
from the pass.
</P>
<P>
   When the Patriots did try to run out of normal sets, they
averaged 2.2 yards a carry (32 carries for 71 yards). For the
summer, they averaged 3.9 yards a rush. In fact, the last time New
England averaged 4 yards a carry or better was 1985, but at least
in the Martin years (1996-98) they had one consistent back who
averaged 4 yards a rush (4.0, 3.6, 4.2).
</P>
<P>
   Since his departure, what has been consistent is that their
backs get tackled not long after they are handed the ball.
</P>
<P>
   By his own admittance, Bledsoe was dreadful in the second half
of last season, but who wouldn't have been while being sacked 33
times? After throwing 13 touchdown passes and only four
interceptions while being sacked only 22 times in the first half,
Bledsoe hurled 17 interceptions and only six TDs in the second half
to accompany those 33 sacks. Do we see a correlation here?
</P>
<P>
   Now he's with his fourth offensive coordinator in six years (Ray
Perkins, Larry Kennan, Ernie Zampese, and now Weis) and he's trying
to incorporate Weis's wisdom without a running game and with a
shaky line and reduced capabilities at wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   As good and tough as Brown might be _ and he may be the best
pure football player on the team _ he has scored only eight
touchdowns in 92 NFL games. That's not all his fault, because his
forte was as a third-down receiver who got open after double
coverage took out Glenn and Coates, but it is still a fact that he
couldn't convince anyone that the less-than-legendary Vincent
Brisby or Shawn Jefferson should be unseated in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is hard-nosed, fearless, and seldom drops a ball, but he's
opening the season as the No. 2 receiver only because Brisby and
Tony Simmons couldn't win the job, not because Weis thinks he's the
ideal man. Taking him out of the slot is not playing to a strength,
and Weis probably knows it but has no other choice.
</P>
<P>
   Where this leaves Bledsoe is anyone's guess, but his confidence
has to be shaken despite his remarkable numbers. He's been to three
Pro Bowls in eight years and was the youngest quarterback to do so,
at 23. He reached 10,000 passing yards faster than anyone in
history, and among the 10 quarterbacks who were taken with the
draft's first pick _ including John Elway, Troy Aikman, and Terry
Bradshaw _ his numbers are better at this stage of his career.
</P>
<P>
   But he hasn't won a Super Bowl and he very well may not until he
has what those other quarterbacks had: a running game behind him
and a solid line in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   Those simply do not exist in New England today, which is why
it's the same story in Foxborough: The Patriots will go only as far
as Drew Bledsoe can throw them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is said that no good deed goes unpunished. Lawyer Milloy
wouldn't argue with that. Recently, Bledsoe was late for his weekly
appearance on the Patriot-owned radio show, so Milloy was asked by
the team to pinch hit. Milloy was in a team meeting room, having
arrived early for a defensive session, but went to the interview
when asked. When it lasted longer than expected, Milloy finally
said on the air that he had to go or he'd be fined. By the time he
got downstairs, the door to the meeting room was locked and he was
told he'd be fined $2,000 for being late. His explanation fell upon
deaf ears initially, but an effort last week to rescind the fine at
least held it off until he gets his first regular-season paycheck .
. . One reason Brisby will get new life with the Jets is that he
stands tall. Brisby is 6 feet 3 inches, 200 pounds, the only target
Vinny Testaverde has over 6 feet, with starters Dedric Ward at 5-9
and Wayne Chrebet at 5-10 (liar). But what was Brisby talking about
when he told New York reporters last week that Jets camp was more
intense than Bill Belichick's in New England? Old friend Al Groh is
running a tight ship in New York but it's unlikely that he's more
intense than the smile-challenged Belichick . . . Lightning knocked
out the lights at Ewbank Hall one day last week so Groh had to send
somebody to Home Depot to buy lamps that could run off generators
so they could see in their meeting rooms . . . Jets linebacker
Bryan Cox was his own blackout last week _ as in news blackout. He
has refused to talk to the media since an altercation on the
practice field with defensive line coach Ray Hamilton was reported,
and he says his silence will continue all year. But even when he's
not talking, Cox gives better quotes than most guys. ``The go to
(quote) guy has left the building,'' the non-talking Cox said.
``I'm in it for the long haul. They can't make me talk. I'll talk
when I'm ready to talk.'' Sounds like he's saying more while not
talking than a lot of guys say giving a speech . . . Cox and
Hamilton reportedly got into a heated battle over defensive line
calls. Linebacker Mo Lewis and defensive back Victor Green had to
separate them . . . Groh claims this is the first time in NFL
history that a team has had a bye the final week of the exhibition
season, and he's not happy about it. Groh is afraid his team might
lose its edge. What they'll probably lose is a little soreness,
which can't hurt . . . The Bills took few chances in their final
exhibition game, keeping eight starters out. But they did get
running back Antowain Smith playing again. Smith has been limping
with a thigh bruise, a reminder that his durability remains in
question . . . Speaking of the Bills, some wondered whether Rob
Johnson's rip job on Doug Flutie in the upcoming issue of Penthouse
was a return to the old days of the Bickering Bills, which is what
they were called in Buffalo during some of their Super Bowl
seasons. The fact is, most of the Bills agreed with Johnson, who
said Flutie was selfish and had insulted the team when he told a
Canadian broadcaster in February they would have beaten the
Tennessee Titans if he had started the playoff game instead of
Johnson. ``If he was covering kicks maybe,'' Johnson told
Penthouse, a reference to the Titans' last-second kick-pass-and-run
play for the winning touchdown after Johnson had led the Bills to a
go-ahead field goal with only seconds to play. Flutie's willingness
to be a team player when not on the field has often been
challenged, in his days in Chicago and now. Last year, wide
receiver Andre Reed called Flutie selfish on his Web site. Now
Johnson has done the same, and no one rushed to Flutie's defense.
In fact, the honeymoon may be over for Flutie even with the Buffalo
media. A columnist in Rochester wrote last week, ``The concept of
team is lost on Flutie.'' Wisely, Flutie has remained mum, while
Johnson tried to downplay the fallout by saying, ``If it was that
bad something else would have happened by now if we hated each
other that much.'' I'm sure that's comforting for head coach Wade
Phillips to know.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame Senior Committee finally decided to honor the
first defensive player from the Dolphins' Super Bowl teams that
went 32-2 over two seasons in the 1970s, nominating Nick Buoniconti
to be a Hall of Fame finalist. Usually, that's a lock for
induction. Buoniconti got the news last week on a Florida golf
course, when his wife beeped him. His first thought was that
something had happened to his paralyzed son, Mark, who was injured
years ago playing football at Clemson. If he is inducted next July,
Buoniconti will have his son introduce him . . . Before he named
Jay Fiedler his starting quarterback Saturday, here was the essence
of the dilemma facing Dolphins coach Dave Wannstedt: Damon Huard
failed to lead his team to a single touchdown in seven quarters
with the first unit this summer, but Fiedler was injured and did
not play a down until Friday night. Huard was 4-1 as a starter
replacing Dan Marino last year, but Fiedler has more NFL
experience. Wide receiver Oronde Gadsden put Wannstedt's problem in
perfect perspective: ``He has a quiet confidence about him,''
Gadsden said of Fiedler. ``What everybody is waiting to see is
whether that translates into the ball getting to where it needs to
be.'' . . . Shaky quarterbacks are a problem not only in Miami.
What about in Pittsburgh, where the Steelers are on the hook for
millions with Kordell Stewart and watched in horror as he went 14
for 40 for 191 yards in exhibition games? Between Stewart and wide
receivers Plaxico Burress and Troy Edwards, the Steelers have spent
$18.5 million in signing-bonus money alone the last two years and
still don't have a passing game . . . Sometimes you have to know
whom to trust and sometimes you have to know better than to trust
anyone. At the end of a practice session last week, Titans safety
Marcus Robertson was doing a pass-catching drill using a machine
that shoots footballs out at a fast clip. Head coach Jeff Fisher
was walking behind Robertson, who stopped the drill as the coach
passed. Fisher told him, ``It's OK. I trust you.'' The next ball
went whistling through Robertson's fingers and bounced right in
front of the trusting coach . . . Andre Rison may have finally
landed with the right team, the Oakland Raiders. The troubled
former All-Pro receiver was signed last week after the Kansas City
Chiefs released him and he caught passes for 15 and 34 yards on his
first two plays against the Bears, the latter being the
second-longest gain of the summer by a Raider. He also got charged
in Kansas City with bouncing $158,000 in checks, was fined $219.50
last month in Wisconsin for giving a false name to a policeman
after a brawl in front of a bar, and will have to appear in an
Olathe, Kan., court before the Raiders play the Chiefs in Kansas
City Oct. 15 or face a felony theft charge for not returning a
borrowed tape recorder to a music store. Sounds like the perfect
Raider, don't you think? . . . If the Patriots are looking to
upgrade their punting, the Raiders may give them the chance. Lee
Johnson has struggled this summer, netting barely 36 yards a punt
in four exhibition games and averaging 37 yards in the final game
Thursday night, including a 17-yard shank. The Raiders have the
opposite problem. Rookie Shane Lechler is averaging 48.6 yards a
punt and incumbent Leo Araguz is averaging 46.6. Somebody has to
go.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers are ready to sign former Pro Bowl defensive end
Neil Smith to replace the injured Raylee Johnson, the team's best
pass-rushing defensive end. After the Broncos released him before
the summer, Smith turned down a $750,000 offer to play for the
lowly Saints and opted to wait for a better opportunity. He now has
one with one of the best defenses in the AFC. He flew into San
Diego last week to talk terms and was wise enough not to show up
with a suitcase, flying right back home to Kansas City the same day
while the Chargers formulated an offer. Smiling like a Cheshire
cat, Smith said, ``I'm feeling the warmness here. There's a need
for me to come here.'' All they have to do is show him a little
love, NFL style. That's green love . . . How jumbled is the AFC
West race? According to Chargers coach Mike Riley, ``We could
finish first or we could finish last.'' . . . Here's how the
best-laid plans can go astray. After spending $100 million in
signing bonuses and salaries to bring a potential Super Bowl team
to Washington, Redskins owner Dan Snyder will have to see his team
open the season with a guy who has never played a down as the
starting center. Cory Raymer will miss 4-6 games with injuries, so
untested Mark Fischer must step in. Center is a pivotal position,
so how well Fischer holds up may determine more about the Redskins'
future than all the high-priced players Snyder signed . . . Deion
Sanders has decided he is the Lawrence Taylor of cornerbacks _ a
man who changed the way his position is played. He's so convinced,
in fact, that he thinks more should change. ``I don't know why they
haven't changed the name of the position yet,'' Sanders said.
``Instead of cornerback, just call it Deion. Kids should say, `I
want to play quarterback. I want to play receiver. I want to play
Deion.' '' . . . When the Redskins played the Browns last week, the
contrast of how the teams are being built could not have been more
evident. The Redskins had a total of 71 years of NFL experience in
their starting lineup, Cleveland had 30. More to the point,
Washington wide receiver Irving Fryar has 16 years in the NFL.
Cleveland's entire receiving corps had a combined seven. The
Redskins are betting it all on this season. The Browns are trying
to build a contender piece by piece, which means they're going to
lose a lot of games again this year . . . Speaking of the Browns,
linebacker Rahim Abdullah seems to have the wrong first name for
his position. Rahim is Arabic for ``merciful.'' What linebacker is
merciful? . . . Certainly not Ravens Pro Bowler Ray Lewis, who
reportedly is so angry over the $250,000 fine levied against him by
the NFL for his misdemeanor guilty plea in a murder case in Atlanta
that he has bulked up from 240 to 265 and is playing even more
intensely than before, if that's possible. Lewis has made more than
200 tackles each of the last two seasons, so intensity has never
been an issue. He is refusing to talk to out-of-town media and
reportedly focusing all of his frustrations and anger on the team
in front of him . . . The same week Bob Kraft was selling naming
rights to his new stadium for a record figure, voters in Phoenix
were polled about a new stadium there, and 59 percent opposed it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
