<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-REDMOND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDMOND EAGER TO MAKE UP FOR LATE START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ J.R. Redmond is finding out firsthand the
difference between fans in the West and fans in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Adored, almost revered in the West, Redmond already has been
called slow, unexciting, and perhaps a waste of a third-round pick
here. There's been a steadfast refusal by some Patriots observers
to factor in a 10-day holdout and a groin injury that required
surgery and perhaps is still not 100 percent healed.
</P>
<P>
   It seems Redmond must prove himself quickly. It's not about what
they thought of you out there, it's what we think of you here.
</P>
<P>
   But Redmond has had plenty of practice at withstanding rancor.
The Arizona State star already has been divorced and forced to
mature beyond his 23 years after enduring an NCAA suspension last
October. In a sordid tale, he was pressured into marrying a member
of the ASU athletic department, whom he had been dating and whose
cell phone he had used. The woman told him that the use of her
phone would be an NCAA violation unless they were married. A month
later, the episode ended in bad publicity and a dissolved marriage.
Redmond has been through the wash and wrung out.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a little heat from impatient New England fans is nothing
compared with what he's been through.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, it is time to show them what he's all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game is much faster than in college,'' said Redmond. ``I
couldn't believe the speed of Tampa Bay's defensive line. But
that's the kind of thing I have to get used to. I think I'm making
progress. It'll come.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has ever been around Redmond believes it will come.
Bruce Snyder, his coach at ASU, said, ``He was born to play
football. He loves it. He enjoys every minute he's out there. This
is a neat kid. You're going to like him a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   What's not to like?
</P>
<P>
   Personable, and a bit cocky, Redmond is devout in the belief
that he is a big-time talent. He was typecast as a third-down back
by some teams because he could split wide and act as a receiver in
Snyder's offense. Many other teams, including the Patriots, didn't
believe in that narrow view.
</P>
<P>
   But he's started so slowly that Kevin Faulk has had time to
shake off his own third-down-back typecasting and become the de
facto No. 1 back. Redmond knows there's still time to emerge, still
time to make his mark as a rookie. But the opportunities may not
come as readily now that the preseason is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to help our team in any way I possibly can,''
said Redmond. ``I know I started late, but mentally I don't feel
behind because I was going through the reps and the playbooks even
when I was out. Physically, I hadn't been out there for a while but
the more I play the more comfortable I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Redmond had 13 carries for 28 yards Thursday vs. Carolina,
averaging 2.2 yards. His best run was for 6 yards. He also caught
three passes for 29 yards, including a 19-yarder. He fumbled an
end-over-end pitchout from Michael Bishop, but recovered it. The
spring he seemed to lack against Tampa Bay last Sunday was slightly
more visible.
</P>
<P>
   He returned three kickoffs for 59 yards with a long return of
24. He fielded one punt but didn't return it. Snyder once said that
Redmond didn't call for a fair catch in his first 2 1/2 years at
ASU and he was considered a ``courageous punt returner.''
</P>
<P>
   Such attributes have not shown up yet.
</P>
<P>
   Although his statistics may seem less than impressive, they are
a starting point. To think Redmond can't get better and explosive
once he's seen the pro game would be shortsighted, according to
those who know him. After all, Redmond has been the star at every
level of his career _ from midget football to college.
</P>
<P>
   In an Arizona Republic poll last fall, respondents voted Redmond
the ``most influential'' athlete in the state of Arizona. He got 33
percent of the vote to beat out Diamondbacks pitcher Randy Johnson
(24 percent), Suns guard Jason Kidd (19 percent), Diamondbacks
third baseman Matt Williams (13 percent) and Cardinals quarterback
Jake Plummer (6 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Right now he barely registers on the Boston-area radar screen,
but Redmond, who wears black-rimmed glasses off the field, always
has been seen and heard. He's always made an impact, even in his
new line of clothing, ``Just Run,'' which is soon to make its
debut. Redmond wants to make a splash with his clothes and football
ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to pay my dues,'' said Redmond. ``We have excellent
running backs here like Kevin and Raymont (Harris), who have been
around the league for a long time. I'm trying to learn things from
them, and there's a lot to learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your body has to adjust to the speed of the game. Everybody in
this league is strong and fast, so you have to keep ahead of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Redmond was the 76th pick in the third round _ considered ``a
steal'' by some of the top college scouts _ and the Patriots still
hope they have landed the next Curtis Martin and not the next
Reggie Dupard.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, the Patriots tried out linebacker Doug Coleman,
formerly with the Giants and Titans. He is considered a top special
teams player.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
