<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 02:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3278 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-VARGAS-THOMPSON-L     08-27 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-VARGAS-THOMPSON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAMP VARGAS GETS FOURTH-ROUND TKO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Ross Thompson stands ... er, sits corrected.
</P>
<P>
   IBF junior middleweight champion Fernando Vargas, almost
out-of-control angry, shut Thompson's big mouth the best way he
knew how on Saturday: by repeatedly putting his formidable fists
into it.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who had described Vargas as overrated and punched him
at a prefight news conference, went down three times as result of
Vargas' frightening fury before referee Joe Cortez put an end to
the slaughter at 1:07 of the fourth round in front of an energized
pro-Vargas crowd of 5,325.
</P>
<P>
   The victory sets up a juicy title-unification matchup with WBA
champ Felix Trinidad on Dec. 2, a tentative fight that is all the
more compelling after Vargas' spectacular performance Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ross Thompson had never been knocked out, never been knocked
down. I think that shows what kind of junior middleweight I am,''
said Vargas (20-0, with 18 knockouts).
</P>
<P>
   Vargas' anger was evident before the opening bell: The Oxnard,
Calif., resident refused to shake hands with Thompson (24-4-1, 16
KOs) until Cortez made it clear he had no choice.
</P>
<P>
   And, for the first time in his career, Vargas' emotion spilled
over into the ring. He went after Thompson immediately looking for
a knockout until his trainer, Eduardo Garcia, ordered him to calm
down and be patient.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he found it difficult to hit the slick, awkward Thompson
for 2{ relatively even rounds.
</P>
<P>
   And then opportunity knocked. Moments after Cortez took a point
from Vargas for hitting behind the head in the third round, Vargas
landed a straight right to Thompson's jaw and the challenger never
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas pinned him against the ropes and pummeled away until
Thompson fell again as the result of another right a split second
before the bell.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, it was clear Thompson hadn't recovered. He held
Vargas in an attempt to buy himself time but the champion broke his
grip and resumed his attack, knocking him down a third time a
minute into the round.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas then pinned a helpless Thompson against the ropes and
landed seven unanswered punches, which prompted Cortez to stop it
and Vargas to jump on the ropes and raise his arms in victory as
the crowd roared.
</P>
<P>
   The fans, the bulk of whom apparently made the trip from the
L.A. area, embraced Vargas like never before _ cheering his every
move and chanting repeatedly during the fight, ``Vargas! Vargas!
Vargas!''
</P>
<P>
   And he earned it: It was the kind of dominating performance that
fans don't forget.
</P>
<P>
   The only sour note this night was the fact Vargas spat at
Thompson after the last knockdown. Vargas apologized at the
postfight news conference, although Thompson never realized what
the champion had done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pissed off,'' he said. ``I've never been this pissed off
for a fight. It's over now, though. It's done.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who weighed an astonishing 173 pounds Saturday (to
Vargas' 163) after making the 154-pound limit on Friday, was
extremely humble afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave what I had,'' said the Buffalo, N.Y., resident.
``Fernando's a good fighter, a (ital)great(endital) fighter. ... He
just caught me. My mind was OK but my legs were gone.
</P>
<P>
   `` ... My head said get up, my legs said stay down.''
</P>
<P>
   Next up for Vargas is Trinidad, probably in Las Vegas, in what
could be a defining fight his career.
</P>
<P>
   He might have been overly enthusiastic when he predicted that
pay-per-view buy rates would exceed all nonheavyweight records.
However, he might not be far off _ those who are familiar with both
fighters can't wait to see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mega big, it's super big, it's definitely my biggest
fight,'' he said. ``I'm looking forward to it. And I think I can
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson might agree.
</P>
<P>
   Former Olympian Vernon Forrest, who had to wait a long time for
an opportunity to fight for a world championship, will have to wait
even longer.
</P>
<P>
   On the Vargas-Thompson undercard, Forrest's opponent, Raul Frank
(23-3-1, 12 KOs), suffered a deep gash on his forehead as the
result of an accidental head-butt and the fight for the vacant IBF
welterweight title was ruled no contest in the third round.
</P>
<P>
   Forrest (31-0, 25 KOs) wept at the postfight news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this was going to be my night. I'm just so
disappointed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, the fight will be rescheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Forrest, a member of the 1992 U.S. Olympic team, won the first
two rounds on one card while the other two were even.
</P>
<P>
   Many believe Forrest, 29 and a longtime welterweight contender,
should've received a title shot much earlier in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Shibata Flores (40-8, 20 KOs) of Los Angeles defeated
Robert Kamya (10-1, four KOs) when Kamya quit after seven rounds of
a scheduled 12-round junior middleweight bout.
</P>
<P>
   The give-and-take bout was close but Kamya complained of pain in
his eye and refused to come out for the eighth round. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-00 0242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
