<SLUG> BC-FBC-FLORIDA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEMINOLES OPEN FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-BRIGHAM YOUNG-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ In the grand scheme of things, it will be a
footnote in a season that figures to be filled with highlights.
</P>
<P>
   But championship seasons have to start somewhere, and if you are
a Florida State fan who believes the Seminoles can parlay last
season's 12-0 national championship run into a 13-0 national
championship rerun, you can point to Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's effort
against Brigham Young as a portent of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bobby Bowden's No. 2-ranked Seminoles did very little
wrong in opening with a 29-3 victory over the Cougars, who did
little right in a Pigskin Classic that was anything but classic.
</P>
<P>
   FSU, of course, was supposed to dominate. The Seminoles were
25-point favorites and nearly took care of that spread in the first
half when they climbed all over the Cougars in building a 22-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   For BYU, which was beginning coach Lavell Edwards's last hurrah
season after 29 years, it was a quick dose of life in the fast lane
of football at the top of the rankings. The Cougars are a preseason
pick to finish third in the Mountain West Conference behind Utah
and Colorado State.
</P>
<P>
   The Cougars were smaller and slower and looked clueless for most
of the evening, much to the delight of the majority of the 54,260
fans who nearly filled Alltel Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State was led by 28-year-old quarterback Chris Weinke _
who now is a dazzling 22-1 in career starts for the Seminoles. He
took care of business, throwing for a couple of touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did some good things and some not so good things,'' said
Weinke. ``We've got lots of room to improve, certainly. But we
moved the ball pretty consistently.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden said he saw a different game than he had expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game surprised me,'' he said. ``Our defense hadn't done a
thing all year and our offense had been very good. I expected a
high-scoring game and it was just the opposite. The defense
couldn't play any better. And the offense went hot and cold.''
</P>
<P>
   BYU starting quarterback Bret Engermann, whose main claim to
fame is that Larry King is his brother-in-law, could do little in
the first half against a Florida State defense that had done
nothing to instill any confidence in Bowden and his staff during
training camp.
</P>
<P>
   But when the bell rings, Florida State generally shows up. And
all went well, aside from some kicking problems. Freshman walk-on
Matt Munyon _ filling in for injured freshman scholarship kicker
Brett Cimorelli _ missed an extra point and two short field-goal
attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, however, it was business as usual for FSU, which
now can get on with the business of defending its national
championship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-00 0242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
