<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX FEELING POWERLESS IN AUGUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ That home run Mo Vaughn hit to deepest center
field in Fenway Park Wednesday night off Tomo Ohka wasn't a
game-winner, but it will do for a conversation starter.
</P>
<P>
   Namely, where have all the Red Sox home runs gone?
</P>
<P>
   We're in the middle of the biggest power show in the history of
the game, but instead of Roman candles every night, the Sox are
setting off only an occasional cherry bomb.
</P>
<P>
   With just a few days left in the month, the Sox have hit only 14
home runs in August, and that's only after Brian Daubach (twice)
and Carl Everett went deep on successive nights in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Everett and Daubach have four home runs this month, Nomar
Garciaparra two. No one else on the team has more than one.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have hit 44 home runs this month. The Sox,
meanwhile, are neck and neck with Sammy Sosa and Jeff Bagwell to
see who hits more home runs in August. So far, it's Sox 14, Sammy
and Bags 11 apiece, with Glenallen Hill (10) lurking.
</P>
<P>
   Trot Nixon hasn't hit a home run since June 23; you have to cut
him some slack, he missed a month with a bad hamstring, but it's
been a month since he's come back and he still hasn't gone deep.
Troy O'Leary, who hit 28 last season? One this month, on Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Offerman and Bernard Gilkey haven't hit a home run since
the Fourth of July. The catchers, Jason Varitek and Scott
Hatteberg, are 0 for the month.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox have played 12 games this month in which they did not
homer. Everett's home run Friday was just the fifth hit by the Sox
in 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   A Dodger pitcher, Darren Dreifort, hit two home runs in a game.
The Sox have had just two games this month in which they've hit two
home runs in a game, on back-to-back days (Aug. 9 and 11).
</P>
<P>
   So what's the big deal, you say? They're in the midst of the
playoff chase anyway?
</P>
<P>
   Here's the big deal: In games in which the Sox have hit two or
more home runs, they're 24-7. In games in which they hit no homers,
they're 16-29.
</P>
<P>
   That's not going to cut it, especially for a team that can't
run. Opposing pitchers are working around Everett, Nomar's in a
slump, O'Leary's home run stroke has been MIA all season, Daubach
is streaky, Nixon has been bounced around in the lineup, and the
new guys don't have ``slugger'' on their resumes.
</P>
<P>
   When the Sox return home Friday, they'll be facing one team of
big boppers after another: the Mariners, A's, Yankees, and Indians.
Popguns don't stand a chance. When that twinge in Garciaparra's
hamstring heals, Sox fans had better hope it sends tremors into his
bat, too.
</P>
<P>
   And who was that guy who hit one halfway to Revere Wednesday
night?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two position players, Rockies catcher Brent Mayne and Mets
outfielder Derek Bell, wound up pitching for their teams last week.
</P>
<P>
   Bell was cannon fodder in a 16-1 loss to his former team, the
Padres, allowing five runs (four earned) and walking three. His
first pitch was clocked at 47 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Mayne, meanwhile, had never pitched, not even in Little League,
but emerged with the win after Rockies manager Buddy Bell used him
in the 12th inning when his ninth pitcher, John Wasdin, was ejected
after hitting Andres Galarraga of the Braves with a pitch,
provoking a bench-clearing brawl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never thrown off a mound,'' Mayne said. ``Last week in New
York, I was in the bullpen and stood up on the mound and pretended
I was throwing, but I didn't have a ball. Five days later I'm in
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   He not only pitched an inning, retiring Chipper Jones on a
checked-swing grounder with two on and two out, but became the
first nonpitcher to win a game since Aug. 25, 1968, when Rocky
Colavito, with the Yankees at the end of his career, beat the
Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Jimy Williams once used a position player, Mike Benjamin, as a
pitcher, but he hates the concept, thinking it makes a mockery of
the game. But what would happen if he ran out of pitchers? Who
would pitch for Boston?
</P>
<P>
   The question was put to Varitek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no clue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Who would like to?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Nomar would,'' he said. ``He pitched a little bit when
he was young. I actually caught him once before, at Georgia Tech.
Not in a game, in an intrasquad game. He had a sinker and a
changeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe (Kerrigan, the pitching coach) always wants me to pitch.
`Just one inning,' he tells me. I throw mainly a four-seamer. I
don't know how to throw the ball curved. I'd rather keep my stuff
straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett pitched in high school in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want to see Carl on the mound,'' Varitek said.
``Nothing personal. I just wouldn't. He's a good enough athlete,
but he'd probably get too competitive out there and blow his arm
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon said he'd be willing to try.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be fun,'' he said. ``I can't tell you what I throw.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra said he would leap at the chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to,'' he said. ``I'd do anything they asked me to do
in a game. I'd even catch, though I probably wouldn't be able to
walk for a week afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside to Derek Lowe: If the Sox ever get tired of you, they
could go to Nomar. He was a closer in high school. He'd play eight
innings at short, then come in to nail down the last three batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sinker and splitter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those swarms of insects that invaded Detroit's Comerica Park
Wednesday night in Biblical numbers?
</P>
<P>
   ``They left us as quickly as they came in,'' said Tyler Barnes,
the Tigers' senior director of marketing and communications. ``And
they left no calling card.''
</P>
<P>
   Play was held up briefly in the bottom of the first inning of
the Tigers-Mariners game when the insects arrived, said Barnes,
``like a shadow over the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a two-minute bug delay. Someone in the press box said
that it looked like the fans were doing the Macarena; they were all
fanning the insects away from themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't blow my bubble gum 'cause I didn't want to get any
bugs in it,'' said Mariners starter Paul Abbott. ``I thought we
were going to have a bug-out. That would have been a first.''
</P>
<P>
   The invaders, Barnes said, were flying ants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not an entomologist,'' he said, ``but I think they came in
the millions. It was freaky. I've seen similar things _ bee swarms,
250 seagulls descend on a field _ but nothing of this magnitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Many fans retreated to the relative safety of the concourses,
Barnes said, until the insects began to lessen in number around the
fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players did a terrific job of playing through it,'' Barnes
said. ``The situation was somewhat similar to playing in a steady
rain. Certainly it was distracting, but by no means was it
impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   No one, as yet, has been able to offer a plausible explanation
for the insects' appearance (another sign from above that Juan
Gonzalez should sign elsewhere?). Or disappearance, for that
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was oppressively hot and humid that day, especially for
Detroit,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What blew me away was that I was asked by two TV stations, on
camera, what we planned to do to prevent this in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told 'em, `We're taking suggestions.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trivia question: What pitcher gave up a 431-foot home run to
Ramon Castro, the first blast hit this season by a Marlins catcher?
(Hint: He's a former Red Sox pitcher now laboring for the Colorado
Rockies.) No, not Johnny Waz. Too obvious. This was Brian Rose,
doing his part to keep the Marlins out of the record books. The
last team whose catchers hit no homers all season were the 1980
Mets. John Stearns was the regular catcher, but he played just 54
games because of a broken finger. His backups included Alex
Trevino, Jose Moreno, Ron Hodges, and Butch Benton. The last team
with any position that had no homers was the 1995 Texas Rangers.
Their center fielders, led by Otis Nixon, were shut out . . .
Garciaparra's younger brother is turning serious about baseball,
according to big brother. Michael Garciaparra, who is entering his
senior year in high school, played in the recent Area Code games,
which feature the top high school players in the country. He's also
a star soccer and football player . . . Angels manager Mike
Scioscia on left fielder Darin Erstad, who didn't play last week in
Boston because of a strained muscle in his rib cage: ``Did you see
that catch he made against the Yankees? Incredible. That's why he's
the MVP for my money, for what he does all around. I know he
doesn't get much ink back East, and Carlos Delgado and Nomar are
putting up some great numbers, but when you look at Darin's
production, his defense, stealing bases, power, clutch hitting, he
does it all. He reminds me a little bit of what Kirk Gibson did for
us on the Dodgers in 1988. Every time we needed a clutch hit, or a
clutch catch, or a clutch stolen base, any clutch play we needed,
Gibson did it. Erstad is like that.'' . . . Scioscia, like
Williams, is no proponent of the slide-step as a way to keep
runners from stealing. But he said there are other ways to control
the running game. ``We have our pitchers vary their hold counts,''
said Scioscia. ``You want to control the jump as well as the time
in between where you have to deliver the ball. Varitek is not the
problem. We have him at about 1.98 seconds to tag time from the
time he throws, which is above average. Pudge (Rodriguez) is
1.8-1.85 and we've even had him at 1.77 seconds, which is
incredible.'' Here's why fractions of seconds are important. An
above-average runner can go from his lead at first base to second
base in about 3.5 seconds. Red Sox pitchers, according to the
Angels' figures, are about 1.55-1.56 seconds to home plate. That
leaves the catcher little margin for error. ``I checked myself
after that Seattle series, when I was as humiliated as you can
be,'' Varitek said. ``I was consistently around 1.92 to 1.98.''
Martinez is very good at varying his holds, Varitek said. ``He
alters the pattern of his delivery,'' said the catcher. ``He might
wait two or three seconds one time before he releases the ball, one
second the next time. A lot of guys like to go, `Dum, dum, pitch.'
'' And did you know that when a Sox pitcher throws over to first
base, he has been instructed to do so from the bench? ``That's why
I'm always looking into the dugout,'' Varitek said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You may have missed it, but last week the Sox went over the 2
million mark in attendance for the 14th straight year (not
including the strike-interrupted 1994 season). They rank seventh in
the league in attendance, with all six teams ahead of them playing
in new ballparks, except for the Yankees, who are the defending
champs and play in New York. The Yanks are averaging more than
40,000 a night and are on pace to draw 3.2 million. They're
followed by Cleveland, Baltimore, Seattle, Texas, and Detroit. The
Sox have a shot at their all-time attendance record of 2,562,435,
set by the Sons of Joe Morgan in 1991. With a crowd of 20,000 and
change Friday night in Kansas City, the Sox joined the Yankees as
the only AL teams to draw more than 2 million on the road. It's the
fifth straight season and 14th time overall that the Sox have drawn
more than 2 million on the road . . . Tragedy struck former Sox
pitcher Pat Rapp, who last season went through a life-threatening
pregnancy with his wife, returning to his home in Louisiana several
times between starts. Rapp, now pitching for Baltimore, rushed home
recently to be with his father, who apparently contracted an
infection while fishing. Rapp then returned to the Orioles to pitch
and took a two-hitter into the eighth inning of what became a 4-1
loss to the Royals. He went back home, and two days later, James
Rapp died at 55. Our sympathies to Rapp and his family.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
