<SLUG> BC-OLY-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USOC WRESTLES WITH COMPLAINTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Only in America does the Olympic committee bring three
arbitrators to the Games to settle last-minute disputes over who
ought to be on the team. This year the post-selection griping is at
an all-time high, with 10 complaints from disgruntled athletes just
in the last two months. First, the softball team had to be picked
three times. Then it was boxers protesting decisions. Recently,
it's been Greco-Roman wrestling, cycling, tennis, and rowing.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, arbitration cases are about process _ how the team was
chosen. But the wrestling case, which still hasn't been decided
after two appeals, two arbitrators, and two levels of federal
court, is explosive because it deals with a ``field of play'' issue
_ a non-call by a referee at the trials.
</P>
<P>
   After Keith Sieracki beat Matt Lindland in the finals, Lindland
claimed he'd been tripped. After USA Wrestling turned down Lindland
twice, an arbitrator ordered a rematch, which Lindland won. After
Sieracki got an arbitrator to put him back on the team, Lindland
went to court. He was turned down at the district level, upheld at
the appellate level. Now, the issue has been dumped into the lap of
the US Olympic Committee, which will decide this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insanity, that's what's going on,'' Lindland said. ``I don't
know what decision is final.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though the US baseball team has no Tim Raines, Wade Boggs, or
Terry Steinbach, 13 of its players (including all of the catchers
and three of the four outfielders) have major league experience.
Most notable is 37-year-old catcher Pat Borders, who was the 1992
World Series MVP with Toronto and now plays for Tampa Bay's Triple
A club. As expected, the selectors couldn't get most parent clubs
to part with anybody who might make even a slight difference in a
pennant race. Still, manager Tommy Lasorda is bullish on the team's
medal chances. ``We're not going 6,000 miles to lose,'' he said.
The Americans won the bronze behind Cuba and Japan last time using
college kids . . . Even though she probably couldn't have played
more than half of any match at the Games, the loss of Michelle
Akers, 34, is an undeniable blow to the US women's soccer team. For
15 years, she was the team's Alpha female, its unquestioned
on-field leader, the one woman whom rivals actually were afraid of.
Finally, though, her body gave out after a dozen knee surgeries,
numerous concussions, and an ongoing battle with chronic fatigue
syndrome. The crusher, finally, was a reinjured shoulder this
month. ``I finally said to myself, this is insane,'' said Akers,
who said her body was ``ready for a MASH unit'' . . . Meanwhile,
the same malaise that's dogged the US men's (i.e. World Cup) soccer
team for years has spread to the women. Except for the seven-goal
outburst against the Russians (who won't be in Sydney), the Olympic
team hasn't scored more than one in its last eight games. After the
Americans drew, 1-1, with Canada last weekend (after 21 straight
wins) and missed the target with 21 of 31 shots, coach April
Heinrichs bluntly told them to snap out of it. ``I reminded them
that this is not going to be easy,'' she said. ``There is no team
in the world that is going to give them the gold medal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Did the US men's soccer team get the best three over-age players
in Jeff Agoos, Chris Armas, and Frankie Hejduk? No, but it got the
best three available. With the Olympics two months later than usual
(and halfway across the world), most European clubs are balking at
letting their better players go. The Nigerians, who won in Atlanta,
are having trouble prying loose captain Nwankwo Kanu from Arsenal.
And the Brazilians, who've never won the Olympics, didn't even
bother trying to get Rivaldo back from Barcelona (which did release
four regulars to the Spanish team). Meanwhile, Brazil turned down
Romario's plea to play at age 35 since they're using only
under-23s. Romario, who played on the 1988 squad that lost to the
Soviets in the final, has won every world bauble but an Olympic
gold . . . The most baffling aspect of the gymnastics trials was
the ``nolo contendere'' by Vanessa Atler, a former national
cochampion who still was one of the top three candidates coming
into the year. But she obviously hadn't trained all summer and
clearly didn't care whether she was on the team at all. Had Atler
done anything at the FleetCenter, the selectors would have picked
her as a vault and floor specialist. But they were worried that her
lassitude would rub off on her teammates, who'll need the meet of
their lives to win even a bronze at Sydney . . . Dominique Dawes
will be only the third US female gymnast to compete in three
Olympics, joining Muriel Davis Grossfeld (1956-60-64) and Linda
Metheny Mulvihill (1964-68-72). If she wins a medal, Dawes will be
the first American female gymnast to do that at three Games. Dawes
and Shannon Miller both made the podium in 1992 and 1996. Even at
23, Dawes isn't the oldest woman ever to make the team. Mulvihill
was 25 in 1972 and Kathy Johnson was 24 in 1984 . . . The oldest
swimmer on the US team _ 33-year-old Dara Torres _ will also be the
busiest in Sydney. Torres will be competing in the 50 and 100
freestyles, the 100 butterfly, and probably all three relays. If
she wins medals in each, which she could, Torres will have a career
10. That could still leave her short of teammate Jenny Thompson,
who can add five medals to the six she already has. Most ever by a
US female swimmer is eight by Shirley Babashoff . . . It wasn't the
record 1,300 competitors (more than double the usual) that made the
US Olympic swimming trials such a grind. ``The most onerous thing
about it was the eight days,'' said men's team coach Mark Schubert.
``But we needed to do it because NBC's making us do it for the
Olympic Games.'' . . . How much is the USOC cracking down on its
eight 2012 Olympic bid cities from schmoozing with the Lords of the
Rings at Sydney cocktail parties? Their representatives can't even
wear lapel pins. After the Salt Lake payoff scandal, the USOC
doesn't want even a hint of lobbying. A number of IOC members, most
notably Mexico's Mario Vasquez Rana, still blame the Utahans for
seducing them with the same goodies they'd been taking for years.
Anyway, lobbying the Lords makes little sense now. They won't even
choose the 2008 site until next year . . . If you can get yourself
Down Under, you'll have no problem getting Olympic tickets,
especially for soccer matches. More than a quarter of the 9 million
still remain unsold, even for the closing ceremonies. Last year's
distribution mess didn't help, but the current reason is seasonal:
It's still winter in Australia, so Summer Games seem distant. And
if you want Olympic arts festival tickets, the organizers may offer
to pick you up in a limo. Less than half of the seats for
orchestral, opera, and theater performances have been sold.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You're not imagining things if your Sydney-bound flight reeks of
roach spray. The Australian government requires every inbound plane
to be disinfected to keep foreign insects and other pests from
infesting the island continent. Problem is, the sprays (either
permethrin or d-phenothrin) have been known to make passengers sick
and may cause long-term health problems . . . Given Sydney's recent
airport woes, it may make more sense to go by tramp steamer. First,
recent power outages twice shut down the control tower. Then, the
baggage system broke down five times this month. All this after the
Aussies spent $350 million modernizing the place . . . The
five-ring Olympic logo stretching across Sydney's famous Harbor
Bridge, which will glow from dusk to dawn until the opening
ceremonies, is 248 feet long, 116 feet high, and contains 170,000
individual lights . . . Only in Japan: Travel agencies are offering
a $1,700 package that will fly spectators nine hours to Australia
to see one soccer match, then fly them back in time for work a day
later. No hotel room, no meal. ``We created this tour for people
who don't have much time,'' said a Japan Travel Bureau spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
