<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-TRAVERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNSHADED'S TIME ARRIVES 
</HEADLINE>
 STAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Racing may seem like a game geared to
instant gratification, but the results of Saturday's $1 million
Travers Stakes at Saratoga proved that long-range planning has its
place. Trainer Carl Nafzger had pointed Unshaded, a headstrong
gelding, toward the Travers since January, and, although there were
bumps in the road, Unshaded got the job done with a rippling run
through the stretch, justifying Nafzger's patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The horse wasn't focused before,'' said Nafzger. ``He was
always a nice horse, but he wasn't sharp. He got focused after his
last race (a third in the Jim Dandy at The Spa Aug. 5). He's just a
sharper, more focused horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been thinking about the Travers since January. He was a
talented horse, but he hadn't matured yet. Now, he's a man. We take
every race as a building race to learn as we're going until we get
to our ultimate goal. Truthfully, I was 100 percent certain he'd
win the Travers. As long as he kept developing, I knew he would do
it. I love it. I love it a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Unshaded, the second choice at 3-1 ($8.90 to win), received a
strong ride from Shane Sellers before a record Travers Day crowd of
54,116. The winner put in a determined drive to catch Albert The
Great, a 7-1 shot, who had shaken loose turning for home under
Jorge Chavez. Unshaded thrust his head in front as the pair hit the
wire, covering the 1 1/4 miles over a fast track in 2:02 2/5.
</P>
<P>
   Commendable, the Belmont Stakes victor, set the pace at 9-1
under Pat Day, and held on for third. Dixie Union, who was favored
at 5-2 after taking the Haskell at Monmouth Aug. 6, finished a
disappointing fourth after fading in the lane.
</P>
<P>
   Unshaded, a son of 1990 Kentucky Derby and Breeders' Cup Classic
winner Unbridled, was gelded because he was a bad actor who
resisted being trained. He's still a tough customer, as Sellers
knows well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a horse you can't put in a particular spot,'' said
Sellers. ``You just can't do it. He won't listen to you. He's just
a difficult horse. He's got a bad attitude. That's the tough part
for me. You tell him where to go, but he says `no.' You've got to
go with him. He's a big plodder, and I just can't get into a rhythm
with him. He was closer to the pace today, and I was able to get
him running. I listened to my horse today. I gave him my all, and
he gave me his all.''
</P>
<P>
   Sellers, who stands a respectable sixth in the Saratoga
standings with 18 winners, took the occasion to disclose some
information about his personal life in what was a remarkable moment
of unsolicited candor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've changed my attitude in the last year,'' he said. ``I now
know that the press and the people have their own opinions. I used
to try to change everybody's opinion. Mentally, I would fight with
the press. I'm just going to go out and ride like a professional. I
burned a lot of bridges. Whoever I did it to, I apologize. I hope
they give me a second chance. I've sought help for anger
management. I'm on medication, and I'm not embarrassed about it. I
never gave myself a chance to be a great rider, either mentally or
physically. Since this meet started, I've mended a few fences with
trainers that I burnt with my mouth. It was great to win the top
race of the meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Zito, conditioner of Albert The Great, also did a fine
training job. Albert The Great was considered a front-runner, but
Zito took the blinkers off him, and Chavez was able to rate him
behind Commendable untill he grabbed the lead on the far turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real disappointed that we didn't get there, but I can't
thank Albert enough for trying as hard as he did,'' said Zito. ``He
just got beat. That's racing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was at the quarter-pole, I saw Unshaded coming,'' said
Chavez. ``We were fighting neck-and-neck, head-and-head. I thought
Albert The Great ran a tremendous race. We're real happy with this
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Dixie Union had no real excuse. However, California jockey Alex
Solis did have him on the rail for most of the journey, and the
rail has been completely dead for the last two days.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lost his left front shoe, so that might have had something
to do with it,'' said Richard Mandella, who trains Dixie Union.
``Alex was trying to save ground part way around the track, and he
just got stuck inside. It was unfortunate. I just wasn't happy with
the way he ran the last quarter-mile.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the $7,371,991 bet on-track on the 10-race card, and the
commingled handle of $28,281,322, were Saratoga records.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
