r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-INDIANS-LA     08-27 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-INDIANS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS' RALLY FALLS SHORT IN LOSS TO TRIBE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ This time of year, with the Angels clearly in
the mix for the American League West crown, as well as the AL wild
card, there's always a tendency to scoreboard watch, to see what
everyone else is doing. Only Mike Scioscia, the Anaheim skipper,
says that's not the case with his young club.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not watching the scoreboard,'' he insists. ``We don't
need help. We need to win. And we're playing the teams we have to
beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings up a definite good news-bad news sort of thing.
</P>
<P>
   They're also playing the teams they can't be losing to.
</P>
<P>
   Like Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians withstood a furious comeback try by the Angels and
came away with a 9-5 victory Saturday night at Edison Field in
front of 37,697 fans.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 7-1 after seven innings, the Angels batted around in
the eighth, scoring four runs to cut the deficit to two, and they
had the tying runs on base. But Mo Vaughn, who had a rough night
all around _ he struck out three times and kicked a ground ball at
first base that led to a Cleveland run _ managed only a tapper down
the third base line and was thrown out by the pitcher, ending the
threat.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland then punctuated its 15th win in its last 22 games when
Travis Fryman welcomed Angels relief ace Troy Percival back from
the disabled list with a two-run homer in the top of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim won the first game of the three-game series Friday
night, not the second. The Angels haven't won two in a row against
the Indians in more than two years, since Aug. 3-4, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The win lifted Cleveland into second place in the wild-card
chase, just one-half game back of Boston, while the Angels fell 3{
games behind the Red Sox _ five games back in the loss column _ and
into fifth place in the wild card. They're also five back of
Seattle in the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the standings, sure,'' Scioscia said before the
game, ``but we're a little short of that time when you're saying,
`We're a game up or a game down with two weeks to play' ... stuff
like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of baseball left.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Schoeneweiss (6-7), in his first start since the numbing
loss last week in Boston, when he was within one out of his seventh
win before giving up a tying home run, pitched into the seventh and
was charged with six runs on eight hits. He is winless in his last
four starts.
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweiss limited the Indians to just one hit over the first
three innings, then his throwing error helped the Tribe take a 2-0
lead in the fourth. He gave up two more runs in the sixth and came
out in the seventh when the Indians added two more for a 6-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, meantime, were restricted by starter Jason Bere, who
worked 52/3 innings, to just one run on four hits in the first
seven innings, and reliever Paul Schuey, who fanned Ron Gant to end
a bases-loaded jam in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland picked up an unearned run in the top of the eighth and
led 7-1 when the Angels suddenly came alive in the bottom of the
eighth, fans furiously waving their towels on Rally Monkey Towel
Night.
</P>
<P>
   A walk to Tim Salmon, a single by Garret Anderson _ who had four
hits _ and a single by Troy Glaus produced one run. A bases-loaded
walk to Gant made the score 7-3, and Darin Erstad followed with a
run-scoring single to cut the deficit to 7-4. Kevin Stocker's
sacrifice fly made it 7-5, but left-hander Ricky Rincon, the fourth
of five Cleveland pitchers, retired Vaughn to snuff the flurry.
</P>
<P>
   And send the monkey back into the cage. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
