<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 08:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3295 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-GOODY-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      08-27 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODY-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-GOODY-COLUMN-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    SEA CHANGE FOR SUMMER TV(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL GOODYKOONTZ(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The funny thing about writing a wrap-up of summer television is
that there's never been a need for one before.
</P>
<P>
   Boy, has that changed.
</P>
<P>
   Once it became clear that huge chunks of people would spend
their summer clamoring to watch a bunch of would-be Gilligans chow
down on rats and bugs, and stab each other in the back
(figuratively, anyway), the whole game changed.
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)Survivor (enditalic)rocked, and TV executives
rolled out plans to put new shows and new episodes on during a time
when viewers traditionally switched off their sets and went outside
to play.
</P>
<P>
   Networks used to feel free to bombard us with reruns and crummy
shows they had lying around gathering dust but which they'd already
paid for and needed to get on the air sometime, ideally when no one
was watching.
</P>
<P>
   No more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two networks finally threw away the `Gone fishing' sign for
the summer,'' Les Moonves, the president of CBS Television, told
critics last month.
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to his own network, of course, because he looks
like a genius for putting (beginitalic)Survivor (enditalic)on the
air.
</P>
<P>
   But he was also throwing a bone to ABC, which trotted out a
little game show in August 1999 called (beginitalic)Who Wants to Be
a Millionaire(enditalic). What seemed like a cute, low-risk
throwaway at the time turned into a juggernaut, and television
hasn't been the same since.
</P>
<P>
   So CBS took a gamble with (beginitalic)Survivor (enditalic)- and
silly as that sounds now, it was a gamble - and it paid off big.
You couldn't swing a cat by the tail this summer without hearing
someone working ``Vote you off the island'' into conversation. (As
catch phrases go, it beats ``Is that your final answer?'' But not
by much.)
</P>
<P>
   CBS also launched (beginitalic)Big Brother(enditalic), which has
had neither the ratings nor the cultural impact of
(beginitalic)Survivor(enditalic), but it beats what the network had
been doing before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better to try these things than to come back to you with
(beginitalic)Diagnosis: Murder (enditalic)reruns,'' Moonves said.
</P>
<P>
   No argument there.
</P>
<P>
   What's good for CBS and ABC has been good for television
generally. Viewership was up this summer among 18- to 49-year-olds
(the only viewers TV honchos really care about). And you can bet
that other networks are scrambling already for next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we saw this summer is clear,'' said Scott Sassa,
president of NBC West Coast. ``The dinner bell went off and said,
you know, the 13 weeks of summer are no longer a time just to put
your reruns on. People want new, they want different, they want
distinctive and they're willing to accept different things based
upon the competition. And you will see us next year be very
aggressive in the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   I'll bet - Sassa has come under fire for not hitching NBC's
wagon to the ``reality TV'' star sooner. But don't worry, the
network is catching up with shows such as (beginitalic)Chains of
Love(enditalic), in which four men are chained to a woman, who
releases one every 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   That's the thing about this summer blitz - no one said it had to
be good TV. Just TV that people will watch, which is hardly the
same thing. How far down the taste meter TV will spiral is anyone's
guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were to tell you that we were going to do a show where
people would eat rats and eat bug larvae, you wouldn't get it,''
Sassa said. ``But for whatever reason, in this (beginitalic)Swiss
Family Robinson (enditalic)context of people being on an island,
the public seems to say, `It's fine.' They're OK with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't be misled - no one is talking about turning summer into a
``sweeps'' rating period. More people are watching, yes, but not so
many more that networks don't still toss off the occasional shelf
sitter just to get rid of it (David Spade's NBC cartoon
(beginitalic)Sammy(enditalic), for example).
</P>
<P>
   And some of the best risks, such as Fox's intriguing
(beginitalic)American High(enditalic), don't pay off; the network
canceled it after two episodes, subbing reruns of
(beginitalic)Futurama (enditalic)in its place.
</P>
<P>
   Still, (beginitalic)Survivor'(enditalic)s success means that TV
fans' watching habits will mirror what happens to students when
they graduate: no more summers off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all in this now for performance 52 weeks out of the
year,'' said Lloyd Braun, co-chairman of ABC Television.
</P>
<P>
   Just like the rest of us, pal. Just like the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Goodykoontz at bill.goodykoontz(a)arizonarepublic.
</P>
<P>
   com or (602) 444-8974.
</P>
</TEXT>
