<HEADER>
A3297 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-ROBB-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      08-27 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBB-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-ROBB-COLUMN-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    `SURVIVOR' SPURS CONFESSION OF CULTURAL DROPOUT(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By ROBERT ROBB(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hoopla over (beginitalic)Survivor(enditalic) leads me to a
confession: I've become an almost total dropout from popular
culture.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't watch a single episode of the show. I don't understand
the attraction of reality TV or even why it's called that.
</P>
<P>
   What's real about dumping a bunch of people on an island and
having them compete for a million dollars? And why was it called
(beginitalic)Survivor(enditalic) when the winner was chosen by a
vote?
</P>
<P>
   I didn't watch any of (beginitalic)Seinfeld(enditalic) until the
last episode. Which made me glad I hadn't watched any previously,
although I did finally understand why it was called a show about
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I haven't regularly watched a new television series for
over 15 years. Television in my house is carefully rationed and
consists mostly of sports, public affairs programming, and
(beginitalic)Star Trek: The Next Generation (enditalic)reruns.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, we'll watch one of the old sit-coms:
(beginitalic)Andy Griffith(enditalic), (beginitalic)Dick Van
Dyke(enditalic), the (beginitalic)Bob Newhart (enditalic)show. They
seem to involve real people, in real if exaggerated circumstances.
And each episode teaches a moral lesson, however subtly. Although
I'll admit I haven't seen much of it, modern television seems to
consist of weirdos in contrived circumstances, competing to defy
moral conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Three times this year, my wife and I decided to go to the movies
only to find there wasn't a single one we actually wanted to see.
In today's Hollywood, action seems to consist of bloodying bodies
or blowing things up. Dialogue is creative (or uncreative) cursing.
Love, or at least amorous coupling, is found in almost any
imaginable human configuration, except for a man and a woman who
happen to have been married to each other for some time.
</P>
<P>
   I asked her if it would be OK to walk out of the last movie we
saw: (beginitalic)Mission Impossible II(enditalic). A woman having
sex with a terrorist killer she despises. Now there's an edifying
story line.
</P>
<P>
   I look forward to kids movies more than my kids do. My youngest
is now 9 and will soon outgrow them. And then I'll be reduced to
trying to borrow a neighbor kid to take.
</P>
<P>
   But then again, maybe not. My wife and I went to see the
re-release of (beginitalic)Pinocchio(enditalic) even before we had
kids.
</P>
<P>
   There is no Nintendo, Sega or PlayStation in my house. The kids
do not have televisions or telephones in their rooms. They all have
computers in their rooms, but not telephone hookups that would
enable them to surf the Net unsupervised. Net access is through the
common computer in the family room.
</P>
<P>
   They grumble occasionally about their deprived living
conditions. I just tell them they pulled the short straw when it
came to assigning parents. They'll have to complain about it to God
when they get the chance.
</P>
<P>
   But, in reality, they don't cavil much. Dad's been stodgy ever
since they've been born. Besides, the oldest is now 17. They know
they'll eventually escape.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many other dropouts, I don't rail a lot against popular
culture. I share the critique of those who do rail against it. Our
popular culture is coarse, vulgar, violent and undermines important
moral principles and practices.
</P>
<P>
   But I believe in a free society. A large number of people want
to produce and consume what passes for popular culture today. So be
it.
</P>
<P>
   Denouncing popular culture is also an exercise in freedom. But I
just don't get the point. The people who produce and consume coarse
culture presumably like it. The rest of us don't need the sermon.
</P>
<P>
   So, creating and submerging yourself in an alternative culture
seems more productive. And as popular culture becomes increasingly
eccentric and insipid, I suspect more and more Americans are doing
just that: joining me as a dropout.
</P>
<P>
   After all, 50million Americans watched
(beginitalic)Survivor(enditalic) Wednesday night. That means
225million did not.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Robb at bob.robb(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602) 444-8472.
His column appears Sunday, Wednesday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Robb &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Republic
</P>
</TEXT>
