<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3363 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EZZARD-COLUMN0828-COX     08-27 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN0828-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Like much of society, UGA treading water on diversity
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When professor Mark Dawkins stands before his
Intermediate Accounting class at the University of Georgia, he is
greeted by 75 white faces and three black ones like his.
</P>
<P>
   But skin color isn't what's on the mind of the popular assistant
professor. Principles of accounting are. It's not easy to get into
the Terry College of Business. It's one of the nation's Top 20
among public universities. Even with the high caliber of students,
Dawkins said, about 30 percent of them in his survey course are
likely to fail or take it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a weeding-out class,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he doesn't think about race when he's teaching, the
37-year-old Dawkins knows deep down what it's like to feel
marginalized. He was the only black student among 110 entering the
MBA program at the University of Florida in 1986. He was recruited
to UGA in 1994 _ the second African-American to join the business
school faculty. Now there are four.
</P>
<P>
   Dawkins feels a personal responsibility to recruit top black
students. For the past two years, he has worked with professional
accountants' societies to bring black high school students
interested in business careers to the campus for a three-day
seminar.
</P>
<P>
   This past week I spoke with six black professors about what they
think needs to change at the state's still predominantly white
flagship institution (my alma mater).
</P>
<P>
   Four decades after Charlayne Hunter-Gault and Hamilton Holmes
broke the university's 175-year-old color barrier, 6 percent of the
31,000 students are black, the same as last fall. There are 94
black professors among the 1,780 full-time faculty members. All
those interviewed lauded President Michael Adams' commitment to
appeal a recent federal court ruling striking UGA's modest
affirmative action program _ one that makes race one of 12 positive
factors in choosing the last 10 percent of freshmen. But all of
them also criticized Adams' failure to implement an aggressive
black-student recruitment program. They said former university
President Charles Knapp did a better job in that area.
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Bennett-Alexander, a tenured professor who teaches business
law and employment discrimination, was the first black female
professor recruited to the university, 12 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was viewed as an affirmative action hire, and my competency
was questioned _ though indirectly _ by some faculty,'' she said.
Bennett-Alexander, whose daughter is a student at UGA, says black
students in many ways are just as isolated on campus as they were
30 years ago. ``There are still an amazing number of college
students who simply don't know much about people who aren't like
them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When her classes delve into employment discrimination,
Bennett-Alexander asks the students to visit an event or place
where they don't feel comfortable. White students often go to the
black sororities' and fraternities' ``step show,'' an elaborate
dance routine rooted in slavery. Some have been ridiculed by fellow
white students for attending, and that has ignited lively
discussions in class about equality in social and work situations.
``At least we get it out in the open,'' Bennett-Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   John Morrow, the Franklin Professor of Modern European History,
derides current black recruitment efforts. ``It's just window
dressing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Morrow thinks President Adams should go personally to
predominantly black high schools to send a message from the top
that the university is serious about diversity. Added his wife,
Dianne Morrow, who teaches 19th Century African-American History:
``Dare I say it _ it really should match the effort to recruit top
athletes.'' The black faculty organization, headed by Derrick
Aldridge, an education professor, has been asking for three years
for the appointment of a Vice President for Equity. Aldridge and
others are disappointed that the job, which remains unfilled, has
been relegated to a less powerful position: ``associate provost.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A symbolic post, yes, but symbols send powerful messages,''
said Maurice Daniels, a member of the School of Social Work faculty
for 20 years. Daniels, like other black professors, wouldn't trade
his teaching and research opportunities at Georgia. Still, he
senses the school, like society, is treading water on diversity
because a vocal minority has convinced so many that all vestiges of
discrimination have disappeared. If it's so, Daniels says, why is
the poverty level among black children still twice that of white
children?
</P>
<P>
   Daniels recalls the words of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.,
who worried about what he called ``the appalling silence of the
good people.''
</P>
<P>
