<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Last year 87 percent of Texas
students passed the reading, writing and math portions of the Texas
Assessment of Academic Skills. That means this year: (a) We should
pat ourselves on the back for figuring out this education thing.
(b) We should make the test tougher _ you know, ``raise the bar.''
(c) We should redouble our emphasis on TAAS, because it means
improved learning for everyone. (d) We should snap out of it. The
answer is (d). By review, the answer is: Snap out of it. There will
be a test at the end of this commentary. (Young, Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EZZARD-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ When professor Mark Dawkins stands
before his Intermediate Accounting class at the University of
Georgia, he is greeted by 75 white faces and three black ones like
his. But skin color isn't what's on the mind of the popular
assistant professor. Principles of accounting are. It's not easy to
get into the Terry College of Business. It's one of the nation's
Top 20 among public universities. Even with the high caliber of
students, Dawkins said, about 30 percent of them in his survey
course are likely to fail or take it again. (Ezzard, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ Joe Murray's column will resume shortly.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   TRANSITION _ ATLANTA _ If hearing all the high-tech hubbub makes
you think you're missing out, now may be the time for you to pack
up your skills and enter the fray. Although there are already some
10 million information technology workers in this country, there's
still plenty of room. The South has the highest number of IT
workers overall, according to the Information Technology
Association of America. Demand is hot, and it isn't expected to
cool off anytime soon. So many jobs, so few workers. One place they
will come from is the ranks of current jobholders, especially
women, who shift from the Old Economy to the New. (Mallory, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ISP-FUTURE _ ATLANTA _ What's a 21st century Internet service
provider to do? Stocks in traditional ISPs, such as Atlanta-based
EarthLink, are hovering near all-time lows as Wall Street's love
affair with the traditional dial-up ISP begins to wane. Investors
are demanding more products and services and evidence of additional
revenue streams from high-speed access, Web hosting, advertising
and electronic commerce. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPIC-FESTIVAL _ Preview of the Sydney Olympic Arts Festival,
how it compares to Atlanta and what to look for if you go. How is
this festival uniquely Australian, or is it? Whatever you say about
it, it's an extremely impressive lineup--plenty of sophisticated
contemporary work, classics, and such big names as Robert Spano and
Pinkas Zuckerman, Ricardo Muti with his La Scala orchestra; Pina
Bausch, Bill T. Jones, Ute Lemper, Bang on the Can All Stars, the
Dead Sea Scrolls and Bill and Melinda Gates' copex of Leonardo da
Vinci's Codex Leicester on display. The theater component looks
especially strong. An advance, with some analysis and nuts and
bolds stuff. (Brock, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 45.
</P>
<P>
   FALL-MOVIES _ You've heard it all summer long. Seen any good
movies lately? Well, no, we haven't. Ticket sales may have held
steady but the summer drought has to do with more than your front
yard. Outside of maybe ``Gladiator,'' it's been one stinking summer
at the movies. That's about to change. With the onset of fall, a
couple of solid, winning movies are coming: Neil LaBute's blue
collar ``Nurse Betty'' and Cameron Crowe's '70s rock tour film
``Almost Famous.'' Plus, get ready for Denzel Washington's
made-in-Atlanta movie ``Remember the Titans.'' All three point to
well-written tales about American obsessions: soap operas, rock
music and football. And each focus on average Americans. Not the
$3,000 Italian sofa crowd of ``American Beauty,'' but the
TV-watching waitresses of ``Nurse Betty'' and the shaggy haired and
ratty-jeaned concert fans of ``Almost Famous.'' (Longino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-WEBERN _ ATLANTA _ Modernism comes in waves. The first
wave of modern music ended in Mittersill, Austria, on Sept. 15,
1945, with three quick gunshots. The war in Europe had been over
since May. An American soldier, Raymond N. Bell, was on a policing
raid when he encountered a man breaking curfew, puffing a cigar in
a doorway. The events of that evening remain unclear. What's known
is that Anton Webern, an impoverished composer, had fled the
turmoil of Vienna and was visiting his son-in-law, a Nazi turned
black marketeer. Webern had stepped outside for a smoke _ a
contraband gift, undoubtedly _ just as Bell arrived. After a
scuffle, shots were fired. So ended the career of one of the most
unlikely giants of 20th-century music. (Ruhe, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   DEFIANT-PRAYER _ Determined not to be stopped by the U.S.
Supreme Court, students and grass-roots conservative groups across
the Bible Belt stood up last weekend and made a defiant statement:
They plan to pray at high school football games. The battle lines
were drawn, from the Carolinas across to Texas, with organized
efforts to challenge the Supreme Court's ruling in June prohibiting
student-led prayer at games and assemblies sanctioned by public
schools. Incidents were reported, with various levels of
participation, at scores of high school football games around the
South, and are likely to grow as word spreads. (Salzer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BOXER-EBO _ Ebo Elder's calling is to climb into a ring and
wreak havoc on another fighter. But Ebo, in many ways, is a proxy
for his dad, whose life's dream is to build a champion. (Torpy,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS. 89.
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPICS-WHEELCHAIR _ WARM SPRINGS, Ga. _ For most of the past
150 years, polio patients came to this sleepy Middle Georgia town.
They came to swim in the 88-degree water that flows from the
springs just east of the downtown business district. Now,
handicapped athletes from around the world come to Warm Springs
because of the accessible facilities at the Roosevelt Warm Springs
Institute for Rehabilitation. This past week, the top eight men's
wheelchair basketball teams in the world have played a round-robin
tournament in preparation for the Paralympics later this year in
Sydney, Australia. Canada defeated the United States 61-55 Saturday
to win the tournament undefeated. Seven women's teams will be on
the courts Thursday through next Saturday. (Minter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL
</P>
<P>
   FBC-FSU _ JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ If Florida State's purpose of
playing in Saturday's Pigskin Classic had something to do with
tuning up for its second consecutive run at a national
championship, it could not have found a better opponent. Brigham
Young provided tradition and even a national title in 1984, and not
the embarrassment of kicking around a McNeese State or a Ball
State. (D'Angelou, PALM BEACH POST) MOVED.
</P>
