<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3365 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0828-COX     08-27 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0828-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Schools must make room for enrichment amid basic skills
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Last year 87 percent of Texas students passed the
reading, writing and math portions of the Texas Assessment of
Academic Skills. That means this year:
</P>
<P>
   (a) We should pat ourselves on the back for figuring out this
education thing.
</P>
<P>
   (b) We should make the test tougher _ you know, ``raise the
bar.''
</P>
<P>
   (c) We should redouble our emphasis on TAAS, because it means
improved learning for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   (d) We should snap out of it.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is (d).
</P>
<P>
   By review, the answer is: Snap out of it.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a test at the end of this commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Texas, and many states following in its path, is becoming like a
cross-eyed ferret as it tracks the scores of one basic skills test.
Our path is becoming a rut, too often sapping education of its
richness, its color.
</P>
<P>
   There's no discounting the fact that rising TAAS scores are
desirable. They mean some students are acquiring basic skills they
might not have had. Good for us. Good for them.
</P>
<P>
   But a system that aspires to excellence does not rate itself on
something that 8.7 out of 10 children pass. Some will respond to
this statement with the ``raise the bar'' reflex.
</P>
<P>
   Raise the bar? Only to the extent to which TAAS truly reflects
grade-level skills. That's all TAAS is about. TAAS is a
criterion-based test, meaning it is based on skills every student
at a certain grade level should know. Not every high schooler needs
to know trigonometry. We could ``raise the bar'' by testing on it.
We also could test every sophomore on quantum physics.
</P>
<P>
   You should be able to see the problem inherent here: A
criterion-based basic-skills test is inadequate to judge schools.
</P>
<P>
   We are being told that a curriculum aligned with TAAS
grade-level skills improves learning for all students. Not true.
For some already at grade level it makes no difference. They know
the material and would have before TAAS. Indeed, for some who have
beyond-grade-level skills TAAS holds them back. TAAS is their worst
enemy.
</P>
<P>
   You cannot have a system based on a test of basic skills
everyone needs to know and assume that it benefits everyone. Get
real. What about the third-grader who reads at fifth-grade level?
The second grader with fourth-grade math skills?
</P>
<P>
   TAAS shouldn't even be given to the vast majority of students in
the spring. When should everyone take it? At the beginning of the
school year. Indeed, the best thing that could happen to education
in Texas would be to test all students on Day 1 of the school year,
exempt all who are at grade level or beyond, and spare them from
any mention of TAAS. Let those who need more emphasis on basic
skills have it, and test them often.
</P>
<P>
   And if one's response to that notion is to suggest ``raising the
bar'' to make TAAS tougher and justify itself by challenging more
students, the answer remains: Either you're going to have a
grade-level criterion-based test or you're not.
</P>
<P>
   There are other tests of students' skills _ norm-referenced like
the Iowa Test of Basic Skills _ that stretch every student.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of an entry-level diagnostic tool, as TAAS ought to be
at each grade, we use it as the climax of the school year, every
lesson building toward a common denominator that challenges some
and doesn't challenge others.
</P>
<P>
   The real benefit of TAAS, and basing promotion on passing it, is
to the portion of students who may have drifted along without
grade-level skills and can't hide anymore.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, even among those students who need basic skills: Are we
developing young thinkers or test drones? Young innovators or test
drones? Young citizens or test drones?
</P>
<P>
   A sad sight: Recently a retiring Waco grade-school teacher,
going through her classroom supplies, came across a sparkling set
of flash cards about the U.S. presidents. She hadn't been able to
use them. They weren't a TAAS objective. It reminds me of a
fourth-grader who didn't know what the Alamo was. Is he receiving
the kind of education an enlightened society needs?
</P>
<P>
   THINKERS OR TEST-TAKERS
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we going to do about this TAAS over-emphasis?''
</P>
<P>
   One hears this comment often from parents who think their
children have become lab rats to one wheel.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual thing about the above-quoted comment, however, is
that it came from a principal _ yes, a principal _ dread-filled
over the lack of higher-level skills among children. Are they being
inspired in class? Taught about the world and our country? Made to
feel in any way that learning is something you might enjoy doing
for life even after you pass TAAS?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, many are, in classrooms with teachers who are incredibly
skilled, or who have classes that come in with high levels of basic
skills and don't have to inch toward one test every day of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   For other teachers, TAAS is a treadmill test.
</P>
<P>
   So, back to that 87 percent passing rate on TAAS. Be careful
reading too much into those numbers and assigning too much to a
test that, by design, can only be so much.
</P>
<P>
   However, we could look at these improving figures in a better
way.
</P>
<P>
   They make possible a liberating notion: that we start focusing
intently on ways to flesh out education beyond the basic skills,
beyond TAAS objectives, using the test differently than we do now.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of where ``the bar'' is set, if passing a test pegged
to what every child should know meets your standard of excellence,
then you need to (d) snap out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
