<DOCNO> NYT20000827.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3381 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-WEATHER-CAREER0828-CO     08-27 1775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-CAREER0828-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Meteorology is becoming an increasingly popular career choice
 &HT;    By Dann Stupp
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If you think sleet is neat, if the barometric
pressure gets your blood pumping and if you hail to hail, a career
in weather might be for you.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since weather became a 24-hour-per-day fix for atmospheric
junkies, thanks to cable television and the Internet, an increasing
number of college students are considering careers in meteorology.
</P>
<P>
   And with an Air Force base, numerous media outlets and a
National Weather Service station in the area, Miami Valley hosts a
variety of possible weather-related careers for future forecasters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had always wanted to be a weather guy, even before The
Weather Channel made it seem cool,'' said David Milner, 18, who
plans to enter Ohio State University's atmospheric-science program
this fall. ``For Christmas one year, I asked for a rain gauge. And
Santa came through. I think you know at an early age if meteorology
is for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the job market is extremely tight for
meteorologists, the variety of weather-related jobs is limitless.
</P>
<P>
   Despite popular perception, meteorologists do more than
seven-day forecasts on the morning news. Opportunities exist in
teaching, research, aviation dispatching, military technology,
agricultural forecasting and even in the insurance industry.
Whether you're launching weather balloons or calculating damage
from a late-summer hurricane, you can have a meteorological career
without a green screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm probably not going to have the six-digit television
salary,'' said Miller. ``But I'm sure I'll be chasing storms
someday, even though Doppler Dave would be a great TV name for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   GETTING AN EDUCATION
</P>
<P>
   Few colleges and universities offer degrees in meteorology (also
called atmospheric science or geosciences). Ohio State University
offers a bachelor's degree in geography and a master's degree or
Ph.D. in atmospheric science. The Air Force Institute of Technology
at Wright-Patterson Air Force Base also offers a master's degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Programs are usually made up of geography, civil engineering,
geology, computer science and some other areas,'' said Jeff Rogers,
professor of atmospheric science and geography at Ohio State.
``People in the field need a diverse background.''
</P>
<P>
   Students are also encouraged to take classes in communications.
A recent survey by the American Meteorological Society found that
aside from meteorological aptitude, strong verbal and written
communications skills were the most important traits required by
employers, especially if you choose to work in the media side of
forecasting. And if you can navigate your way through various
computer-programming languages, you're going to be even more in
demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``While in high school, students should be taking as much
science and math as possible,'' said Rogers. ``And if possible,
they should be getting a foundation of computer skills.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the hard work can pay off _ handsomely. Salary figures
range from the mid $20,000s for entry-level research positions to
over hefty six-digit salaries for celebrity media forecasters in
large markets.
</P>
<P>
   GOVERNMENT/AVIATION
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Haydu, meteorologist in charge at the Wilmington
National Weather Service station, knows that people rely on the
forecasts put out by his government-funded station _ some more so
than others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put out something called a Nowcast, which lets people see
the potential precipitation for the next six hours,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the station's responsibilities stretch well beyond weather
forecasts for your afternoon plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Supplying international airports with weather is very typical
of an NWS station,'' said Haydu. ``Once the planes are in the air,
we control them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wilmington station, which supplies the Dayton International
Airport with up-to-the-minute forecasts, employs 16 of the 5,000
meteorologists nationwide who work for the National Weather
Service.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from alerting the public of severe weather, meteorologists
in Wilmington educate the public about their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``People might overlook the amount of community-relations work
we do,'' he said. ``We take a lot of phone calls from the public
and curious kids, talk at area schools and we work with counties'
emergency-management offices to make sure they're getting their
warnings out efficiently. That's why communication skills are so
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Like all segments of the weather industry, the job market for
government-based forecasting and researching is quite tight.
Because so many people are applying for a limited amount of jobs,
employers have the ability to pick and choose from many applicants.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be good at math and science, but you also need to
be a good writer,'' said Haydu. ``You need your meteorology degree,
but you just about need a double major in math to work at a place
like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of working at a National Weather Service station, you
could also work for the government-funded National Hurricane Center
in Florida, or the Storm Prediction Center in Oklahoma, to name a
few. Yup, with the help of the government, you could be a real
storm chaser.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY
</P>
<P>
   If you want to jump-start a weather career while on a tight
budget, Ron Rodney, a staff meteorologist for the Aircraft and
Sensors Team at Wright-Patterson Air Force Base, says he military
is the way to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get your meteorology degree _ and get paid doing it,''
he said. ``In fact, many people start their meteorology careers in
the military.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren Madden went from Dayton's WHIO-TV to The Weather Channel
in 1996. Madden, a major in the Air Force Reserve's 88th Weather
Squadron, now flies with the Mississippi-based Storm Trackers, a
team of hurricane reconnaissance pilots who track tropical storms
for the National Hurricane Center in Coral Gables, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Military meteorology has a little bit of everything for
everyone. Whether you hope to do some top-secret research,
traditional weather forecasting or air-traffic control, you might
want to consider using the U.S. Air Force as a way into the field.
</P>
<P>
   Just this year, the 19 members of the base weather operations
flight of Aeronautical Systems Center's 88th Weather Squadron at
Wright Patterson earned one of the highest ratings ever given by
the Air Force Weather Agency, which made the local meteorology
staff one of the best-qualified in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get into any type of weather, the military is probably the
best way to do it because that's what employers look for,'' said
1st Lt. Ginger Hayden, wing weather officer for the Base Weather
Operations Flight. ``Employers are going to look for experience,
and you're going to get the experience here that is going to be
very marketable.''
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA
</P>
<P>
   Media meteorology is often dubbed as the highest-profile career
in weather, and it pays accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a small market, you can be making $20,000-$25,000,'' said
Jamie Simpson, a staff meteorologist for WHIO-TV. ``But if you get
into a big market like New York, Los Angeles or Chicago, that
number can go (up to) $400,000 or $500,000.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to creating local forecasts, media meteorologists
often work as the alarm system for the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you have a weather radio, you aren't going to hear the
warnings put out,'' said Simpson. ``It's our job to alert the
public of severe weather.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two routes to delivering the weather on air. You can
get an education in meteorology and learn the television business
later on, or you can establish yourself in the TV business and
learn weather as you go along. The AMS views those with a degree in
meteorology who use ``scientific principles to explain, understand,
observe or forecast the Earth's atmospheric phenomenon'' as
meteorologists. Those without an education and little training are
called weathercasters. However, the National Weather Service offers
a 17-course, three-year curriculum for certification through
Mississippi State University's distant-learning program, which
allows experienced broadcasters the ability to work on a
meteorology degree in their spare time.
</P>
<P>
   Meteorologists for television, radio and newspapers also
sometimes serve as environmental reporters for their media and are
asked to generate stories on a variety of earth topics. As a TV
meteorologist, you might also be asked to develop forecasts and
Internet content for newspapers and radio stations that lack
weather staffs.
</P>
<P>
   It should be no surprise that the job market for media
meteorology is extremely limited. Because there are only 1,500 jobs
nationwide and a very low turnover rate, becoming a prime-time
weather forecaster will likely be a pipe dream for someone without
a top-notch education, an array of contacts and strong computer
skills.
</P>
<P>
   CONSULTING/RESEARCH
</P>
<P>
   In addition to positions with airlines, the government, media
and the military, there is a variety of lesser-known job options
for meteorologists.
</P>
<P>
   For example, many outdoor events must be insured, and some
meteorologists are contracted to monitor potential severe weather
for events such as outdoor concerts and sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   Many universities in the region also partake in research
projects, some of which are funded by government agencies such as
NASA. Private consulting firms and agencies also research
everything from global warming to tornado predicting. These
agencies can range from international corporations to one-person
operations run by free-lance meteorologists.
</P>
<P>
   You can also try your luck in the atmospheric measurements and
instrumentation industry, which works to improve existing
technologies in the weather field.
</P>
<P>
   Like all areas of meteorology, it takes a diverse educational
background, experience and a passion for weather to succeed in
research and consulting.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   Check out these sites for more information:
</P>
<P>
   _ American Meteorological Society's Career Guide:
www.ametsoc.org/AMS/atmoscareers/
</P>
<P>
   _ National Weather Service Wilmington: www.nws.noaa.gov/er/iln/
</P>
<P>
   _ NewsCenter 7 WHIO-TV Weather:
www.activedayton.com/partners/whiotv/forecast.html
</P>
<P>
   _ Ohio State University's atmospheric science program:
www-afa.adm.ohio-state.edu/u-majors/geograph.html
</P>
<P>
   _ Where to Major in Meteorology:
www.ametsoc.org/AMS/amsedu/98colleges.html
</P>
<P>
   _ Wright Patterson Air Force Base _ 88th Weather Squadron: www.
weather.wpafb.af.mil/
</P>
