<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3383 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TRANSITION0828-COX     08-27 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRANSITION0828-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The path to information technology is easier than you think
 &HT;    By Maria Mallory
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If hearing all the high-tech hubbub makes you think
you're missing out, now may be the time for you to pack up your
skills and enter the fray.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are already some 10 million information
technology workers in this country, there's still plenty of room.
The South has the highest number of IT workers overall, according
to the Information Technology Association of America. Demand is
hot, and it isn't expected to cool off anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   So many jobs, so few workers. One place they will come from is
the ranks of current jobholders, especially women, who shift from
the Old Economy to the New.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent Information Technology Association of
America report, Bridging the Gap: Information Technology Skills for
the New Millennium, ``Employers will attempt to fill 1.6 million
new IT jobs in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   And job seekers don't even have to look to technology companies
for work. Most IT workers are employed by non-IT companies, the
ITAA reported. Fully 9 million IT employees work at nontechnical
firms, while the remaining 1 million are at tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   The ITAA surveyed 700 hiring managers at IT and non-IT companies
alike. Though the job openings will be plentiful, more than 840,000
likely will go unfilled. There just aren't enough IT workers to go
around, the ITAA reported.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're not working a technical job now, how do you get
one?
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes called ``shifting'' or ``Transitioning,'' it is moving
from traditional, brick-and-mortar and nontechnical jobs into IT
positions. That was the topic of a conference held by Women In
Technology and sponsored by Matrix Resources Tuesday in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Among current IT workers, women account for approximately 30
percent of the work force, compared with being about half of the
population, noted Lisa Levinson, associate director in the
permanent-services division of Atlanta-based Matrix. The event was
planned to help educate women about transitioning, she said in an
interview prior to the conference. ``This is something we're doing
to help women excel.'' But the advice from Levinson and the other
panelists isn't gender-specific.
</P>
<P>
   So, where would a ``shifter'' begin?
</P>
<P>
   First, know there's still time and don't be afraid, counseled
keynote speaker Sonia Lucas, vice president for the strategic
account group at software maker Computer Associates.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason to feel like you're too late to get into the
tech area,'' Lucas said. ``Put a stake in the ground and decide to
commit to making the transition. . . . Fear will be one of your
biggest enemies. You have to be aware of it, get past it, get over
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Levinson advised the more than 100 conference attendees: ``The
first step in deciding the right career path is to look inward _
determine what you enjoy doing.''
</P>
<P>
   You'll want to make note of all your personal and professional
skills, your strengths, weaknesses and what you like to do,
Levinson added.
</P>
<P>
   A ``career model'' is one tool Levinson suggested to help direct
shifters to the right IT job. Finding a mentor and networking are
also keys to transitioning.
</P>
<P>
   After sharing her story of how she moved from the hotel industry
to her current position, Lucas endorsed finding allies in the tech
field to help you make the move. Have your mentor periodically
review your transition strategy at 30-, 60-, 90-day intervals.
</P>
<P>
   Talk to others in the field and be willing to learn from their
experiences and expertise, Lucas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surround yourself with people in the technology field and get
engaged,'' said Lucas, who herself joined the Women in Technology
organization shortly after relocating to Atlanta. ``I think you'll
be surprised there are lots of people willing to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Panelist Thomas Pilsch, director of Georgia Tech's
computer-training facility, also urged shifters to join local
technology interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be afraid. . . . People love to talk about what they're
doing,'' Pilsch said. ``Just walk into the meeting and say, `Hello,
I'm new . . .' and you won't have to buy another drink all night,''
he joked.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be shy to network in your current company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many IT professionals get started through
on-the-job-training,'' Levinson said. ``It's usually easier to make
this transition within your own company because you already have a
relationship there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Panelist Karen See, CEO of Abovo Marketing Group, noted
nontechnical workers should take the initiative, on their own time,
to learn from their tech peers and ``suck the knowledge out of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   For more formal training, the panelists noted several options,
including private learning centers, online training and two- and
four-year college degrees. ``The most important thing in learning
is to stay current,'' Pilsch said.
</P>
<P>
   Training options can range in cost from a few hundred dollars to
thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Panelist Salila Sharma, a senior Oracle database administrator
with Z-Tel Communications, warned conference participants to choose
their IT training carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be cautious in what you chose and what you want to do,''
Sharma said, citing research estimates that ``three to four years
from now, 50 percent of the current IT skills will be outdated.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
