<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000827.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3387 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BOXER-EBO0828-COX     08-27 2919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOXER-EBO0828-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shadow boxer
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The makeshift dressing area in the casino corridor
simmered with anxiety and expectation.
</P>
<P>
   Some fighters sat stone-faced in draped-off cubicles focusing on
the storm ahead. Others bounced about, firing jabs and uppercuts at
imaginary opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the last partition sat a short, thickly muscled young man
with a bleached buzz cut and canary yellow satin robe. Last time
out, in his pro debut, Newnan's Ebo Elder left his opponent
slack-jawed and hanging on the ropes. It took 91 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Elder sat calmly as his hands were wrapped in gauze. Behind Ebo
stood his dad, 5-foot-5, pony-tailed and ready to explode. The
night's fight card had wrongly added 10 pounds to Ebo, calling him
a 148-pound welterweight. Greg Elder, Ebo's father, manager and
spiritual leader, smelled a conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is done by design!'' Greg said, his red-clay twang rising
in anger. ``This is done so Ebo will outweigh his opponent by 8
pounds and the crowd will root for the other guy!''
</P>
<P>
   Heads turned. Ebo looked up, puzzled. Jim Troy, Ebo's
co-manager, stepped in as a diplomat but the irate dad shook him
off. They'd come too far, fought too many battles, to get
undermined like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I get hot, things are going to come down or I'll go to
jail,'' Greg said as Troy ushered him away. To keep Ebo focused on
the fight. And to avoid a scene.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Elder has become persona non grata in amateur boxing,
insisting that corrupt forces in the sport robbed his son of a spot
on the 2000 U.S. Olympic team. His plan had been for Ebo to soar
into the pro ranks this fall with Olympic pedigree and an
impressive contract. But rather than training for the summer Games
next month in Sydney, Ebo was on last month's undercard at Soaring
Eagle Casino in the Michigan sticks, hoping for an early knockout
in the headline fights so he could get a little exposure on ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   Greg's fire turned his son into a top-notch prospect during
nearly two decades of training. Fathers as coaches are as common in
boxing as hardluck stories. Someone has to exhort a youth through
the unnatural act of getting punched, but common wisdom is that
dads, at some point, must put down the spit bucket.
</P>
<P>
   So now the boxing intelligentsia say Ebo needs to break away
from his father.
</P>
<P>
   But the Elders' bond is more than training technique and
business strategy. It's about spirit, about attitude. They're
renegades. Dad has long fought against the world. And he has
enlisted his son in the fight.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes after the dressing room outburst, a serene Greg
returned and quietly slipped in behind Ebo, who was absorbed in
fight mode and did not acknowledge his father. Greg stared at his
son and smiled. Their dream was again on track: The ring was set
up, a good crowd had filed in, ESPN production crews were testing
their equipment. It was fight time.
</P>
<P>
   The grinning dad gently rubbed the son's hair and caressed his
cheek, like a proud papa admiring his powdered infant.
</P>
<P>
   RAISING A FIGHTER
</P>
<P>
   Greg Elder burst with that same proud grin 21 years ago when he
stopped by Mike Gaddy's home with his newborn son on the way home
from the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Weighing nearly 200 pounds, Gaddy was Mutt to Greg's Jeff in
high school. Except they were both hellions. Greg weighed barely
125 pounds but was so fierce, so ready to bring it on for no
apparent reason, that even the football players gave him wide berth
in the school hallways.
</P>
<P>
   But those battles were just preliminaries. In 1968, Greg signed
up with the Marines and went to Vietnam. He saw a man's legs blown
off. His buddy was killed. And he killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no mercy,'' Greg said. But he already knew that life
was tough. His dad, Tom, died on a Harley when Greg was 17. He was
going 90 when he slammed into the side of a locomotive. Greg barely
knew his father, who was so devoted to making his lumber business
thrive that he had little time for his five children. Greg, the
oldest, became the man of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Then he was a two-time state Golden Gloves champ, but he never
made it as a pro. He married, had a child and tried to keep the
family lumber business afloat. The business, he says, languished
because of unscrupulous management after Tom Elder's death. It was
later sold for pennies on the dollar. The bank was in on it, he
said. Again, a conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the pain of being a failure; I do not want my children
to feel that,'' said Greg, who also has a daughter, Heather, 28,
and a year-old grandson, Devin. ``I never had that kind of
mentoring.''
</P>
<P>
   Things would be different for Ebo _ born Eben, Greg's middle
name. He'd have that bond with his father Greg never knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had high hopes for him,'' Gaddy recalled. ``He was going to
make a fighter of Ebo _ whether he wanted to be one or not.''
</P>
<P>
   At 6 months, Eben was tied to Daddy's back for motorcycle rides.
At 3, he swapped punches with Dad. At 5, the boy challenged a
Marine to a push-up contest while visiting Dad's old base. At 6,
Eben got a chain saw, a gift from Dad. The chain saw absolutely
freaked out Eben's mother, Cindy. Don't worry, Greg assured her, I
know what I'm doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we did was to make him unintimidatable,'' Greg
said. ``In the garage, four nights a week, I took him to the
absolute point of breakdown in sparring with him. The madder and
more desperate he'd get, the more punishment I'd inflict.''
</P>
<P>
   Pop. Pop. Thwap! ``Son, you're stepping in without thinking.''
Pop. Pop. Thwap! ``Your hands are too low.''
</P>
<P>
   Cindy protested again. The no-mercy competition between father
and son was bound to leave some underlying damage, she reasoned.
But the boy seemed to thrive on the battling. She relented and
attended all his fights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all done with tender love,'' Greg said. ``There's a
tremendous thrill of purpose watching your flesh and blood
withstand that kind of strain.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy rarely whined. And he always tore into his dad with
resolve. He sought reassurance. The only way to get it was to suck
it up and fight back.
</P>
<P>
   Blows to the body suck a fighter's wind and resolve. Head shots
bring a flash of light and draw a boxer into a netherworld of
jumbled, slow-motion images and disjointed thoughts. Ebo learned to
maintain his compass during these eruptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never known anything else,'' Ebo said with a shrug. ``At
that age, the key is to not be scared to be hit; I got past that.
It's got everything to do with being able to war right now.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ebo added: ``I doubt I'll be with a 3-year-old with boxing
gloves on. I can teach my son to be a drummer, a lawyer, a
carpenter. I really don't want my son to box.''
</P>
<P>
   The life's too demanding, he said during a recent roadtrip to
spar some pros in Pensacola, Fla. Too many pitfalls. Too much pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I'm doing it for me and my family _ more them than
me. Anything this hard you have to be doing it for others, not just
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   A few feet away, Dad strutted around a pool table at a
nightspot, talking up a successful bank shot. Ebo smiled at the
sight.
</P>
<P>
   Dad's like that. A ham. He's out there, able to talk to anybody,
to ask a stranger the most personal questions. And they usually
answer _ especially after Greg smiles and narrows his icy blue eyes
like he's conducting a murder investigation. Under his questioning,
one waitress admitted that (a) she had kissed another girl, (b) was
adopted, and (c) had keyed a boy's car.
</P>
<P>
   Dad sings shrill falsetto to doo-wop songs while driving,
drawing sidelong glances of annoyance from his son. ``What's with
all that '30s music?'' Ebo asked.
</P>
<P>
   Ebo's not like that. He keeps it inside, not parceling it out
for others.
</P>
<P>
   Following Dad's footsteps hasn't always worked out. Greg is
still married to his high school sweetheart. Ebo married his and
the union lasted 18 months. They were just too young, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ebo then played the field and almost undermined the whole dream.
In March, he was charged with having sex with a 15-year-old girl.
The prosecutor termed it ``non-aggravating'' and it was quickly
pleaded out. Ebo got two years' probation.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Ebo bought the home he grew up in, while his father
_ like Ebo, a carpenter _ started remodeling another home nearby on
the 18 acres the Elder family owns south of Atlanta in Coweta
County. The idea was to keep Ebo close, where distractions are few,
yet afford him the independence a young man needs. It's a balancing
act.
</P>
<P>
   Dad now preaches about sins of the flesh: Beware the seductress.
Resist weakness. Something can always derail you.
</P>
<P>
   But a yearning, an emptiness remains in the younger man.
``What's going to happen the next few years is going to be
awesome,'' Ebo said. ``I want a family there. I want a wife there
to share the experience with me.''
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPIC HOPES DASHEd
</P>
<P>
   Ebo's rise through the amateurs was swift.
</P>
<P>
   Greg switched his son around to be a left-handed fighter because
the father couldn't figure out southpaws. He drove him through
calisthenics. They pored over tapes searching for flaws. They
traveled for hours to find sparring partners and fights. He started
calling his son ``Ebo'' because it sounded courageous. Ebo was the
name of an African tribe whose members drowned themselves in the
Atlantic rather than be enslaved. And the name was catchy.
</P>
<P>
   Ebo grew to become a physical dynamo. Strong, fast, fearless.
Never backing up. Greg calls him a gladiator. A warrior.
</P>
<P>
   He was going to make the Olympic team, win the gold and sign a
huge pro contract.
</P>
<P>
   But along came Ricardo Williams, a taller, quick-handed
Cincinnati teen two years Ebo's junior. In 1998, Ebo fielded pro
offers but saw his value drop after he finished second to Williams
in the Goodwill Games. Williams is the U.S. team's 139-pounder in
the Sydney Olympic Games. He's seen as the next Sugar Ray Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   In their last fight, an Olympic qualifier, Ebo was so fired up
to dislodge Williams that he employed a ``pro style,'' boring in
low and digging to the body with power shots. It was not the
stand-up, stick-and-move style the amateurs favor. The fight
devolved into an ugly clash of wrestling and Ebo was disqualified
after elbowing Williams. At the time, Williams was holding Ebo and
shoving him backward across the ring. Greg fired a towel into the
ring in disgust.
</P>
<P>
   The amateur boxing crowd, usually reticent with public
criticism, is vociferous in denouncing the Elders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a deliberate action to hurt him,'' Tom Mustin, coach of
the 2000 U.S. boxing team who worked Williams' corner, said of the
thrown elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Ebo is easy to hit, Mustin said, because he shifts his weight to
his forward foot when attacking and is off balance. ``Maybe his dad
didn't see it to change it. I don't think Ebo will progress with
his dad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(Ebo) has a lot of hate, and hate clouds judgment,'' said Al
Mitchell, the 1996 U.S. Olympic coach who saw the fight. ``He needs
to tone it down and stop listening to his dad. I saw his father
screaming and hollering that his kid got robbed. He told him he was
getting cheated.''
</P>
<P>
   A tape of that fight shows Williams frequently grabbing the
bulling Ebo, who was physically stronger and almost always the
aggressor. Greg slows the tape down to show Williams apparently
elbowing Ebo in the cheek. But when the ref stepped in, he warned
Ebo for grabbing his opponent's arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of his (Greg Elder's) ranting and ravings were
well-founded,'' said co-manager Troy.
</P>
<P>
   Greg realizes his expertise is limited and last year hired Eric
Bonilla to train his son and instill the intricacies needed to
survive the pro game. Bonilla was a player in the West Coast boxing
scene during the 1980s, working with several champions. But the
fast life burned Bonilla out and he disappeared for a few years to
compose himself. Bonilla gets 10 percent of Ebo's purses and lives
in an apartment on the Elder family compound.
</P>
<P>
   But entrusting the dream to others, even a sliver of it, can be
wrenching.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla and the two Elders were driving on the Massachusetts
Turnpike after a bout last year when Greg criticized his son for
not throwing enough jabs. We've been working on other stuff, Ebo
shot back, adding, ``Besides, who's training me anyways?''
</P>
<P>
   Greg swerved to the shoulder. Get out, he told Bonilla. You're
gone!
</P>
<P>
   You can't kick him out, protested Ebo. It's winter.
</P>
<P>
   Then you get out, too, Greg growled.
</P>
<P>
   Ebo refused. So Greg jumped out and stalked down the highway,
intending to walk to the next exit ramp, hail a cab to the airport
and fly to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Ebo drove back minutes later to collect his dad and tears were
shed. But tension bubbles near the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Creative tension is how Greg views it.
</P>
<P>
   And Bonilla gushes when talking about his prized pupil.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a unique fighter _ he's white, and he can fight!''
Bonilla said, glancing about like he's letting out a state secret.
``The toughest white boy I've ever seen. Gonna make a killing with
him. A killing.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a blue-eyed blond and unafraid to bring it on makes him a
more valuable commodity.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, who is black, said it's natural for white fans to pull
for a white fighter. ``People like to see that people like
themselves can do it,'' he said. ``They like to imagine themselves
in there.''
</P>
<P>
   FIGHTING FOR THE SPOTLIGHT
</P>
<P>
   But race is just one segment of a plan to cross-market Ebo and
expand him wider than boxing's narrow appeal. His nickname,
``Xtreme Machine,'' is aimed at young X-game types. He's an
explosive drummer, so they hope to tie in the MTV crowd. The
earrings, the motorcycle stories, the frequent smile, his
soft-spoken manner? Those, they hope, will draw women. (Although
his promoter insists he stay off motorcycles because of a crash
last fall.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about putting butts in seats,'' Troy said.
</P>
<P>
   Ebo signed a three-year, 20-fight contract in April with Frank
Warren, the English promoter who recently staged two Mike Tyson
fights. The contract pays Ebo $6,000 a fight for eight fights in
the first year and then more the second and third years as he moves
to eight- and 10-round affairs. Most fights are to be televised.
The plan is to get in the title picture in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing experts agree that the contract, negotiated by Greg, is
an excellent package for a non-Olympian. Normally, pro fighters
start out at a couple hundred bucks a round. Often, 10-round
fighters on ESPN2 collect $6,000.
</P>
<P>
   Between travel expenses, marketing, overhead and paying Ebo's
opponents' purses, Warren will likely invest $250,000 in Ebo the
first two years, said Cameron Duncan, a Las Vegas manager who
handles six world champions. ``We're all fighting for a limited
amount of TV time,'' Duncan said. ``(Warren) is taking a big risk,
a big risk. There's not a lot of $600,000 fights out there for a
140-pounder from Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   And to feed Greg's paranoia, the contract reads that one loss
allows the promoter to renegotiate. An undefeated record is a jewel
that an up-and-coming fighter must jealously protect. One bad night
or one unstudied, hard-punching opponent, and a year's worth of
progress vanishes.
</P>
<P>
   No one makes money off a loser.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, Greg vetoed a fight against Cory Peterson, a
hammer-handed ex-con who hails from that area. Greg feared hometown
bias.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, he's a white boy and that takes away the competitive
balance,'' Greg said.
</P>
<P>
   The casino matchmaker and ESPN execs bristled at the Elders'
veto.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want good fights; this is not the Ebo Elder show,'' said
one.
</P>
<P>
   Exit Peterson and enter Andre Baker, a wiry journeyman from
Lumberton, N.C., and a veteran of other ESPN shows. Good chin, a
3-3 record, won't stink up the joint. And most likely won't knock
your guy horizontal.
</P>
<P>
   Five seconds after the opening bell found Ebo digging ferocious
body shots. Ebo bulled. He grunted. He stomped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Settle down!'' Greg yelled.
</P>
<P>
   At the round's end, Greg jumped between the ropes to take over
as lead cornerman, a job supposedly handed over to current trainer
Bonilla. But the role had been Greg's during Ebo's 130 amateur
fights. Giving it up does not come easily.
</P>
<P>
   A vicious hook drew an ``Oooh!'' from the crowd. An uppercut
starting from Ebo's knees brought an ``Ahhh!'' But Baker wouldn't
go down and frustration furrowed on Ebo's brow.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the fourth round, Baker was out on his feet. The
ref was poised to stop the fight when the final bell rang. No
knockout. And no knockouts in the headliner fights, so Ebo didn't
get ESPN airtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was exactly like I was in there (fighting) too,'' Greg said
later, recounting the fight. ``I don't see anything wrong with
that. It's the most natural thing in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, Greg knows they say that he's living his dream through his
son, that he can't bring Ebo to the next level. But those are
simply more slights to overcome. No, he's not going anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can name on one hand where the son has become a
world-class fighter under a father's tutelage,'' Greg acknowledged,
``but how do you value something? It's by how rare it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Elder knows that he's that exception, that diamond in the
rough. He plans on being there in the corner when they place a
championship belt on Ebo. When they do, they will be strapping it
on him, too.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
