 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR MONDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, Aug. 28:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Questions or reruns: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1027. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The day supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken.
</P>
<P>
   The late-night supervisor will be Ray Krueger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Technical problems: &LR;  Peter Trigg.
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (212) 499-3332.
</P>
<P>
   Pager: (800) 946-4645 (PIN 599-4539).
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: triggp(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-AFRICA (Abuja, Nigeria) _ President Clinton goes to a
village outside of Abuja; he will speak later with women and with
businessmen. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   POLAND-EUROPE (Nieznany Bor, Poland) _ Whether the Poles like it
or not, much of the burden of blocking illegal trade and
immigration into a European Union without borders will fall on
them, doing real damage to the active cross-border trade that helps
keep this poorest part of Poland alive. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-VOTE (Beirut) _ First day of the heavily-contested
parliamentary elections. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-HAMAS (Dateline TK) _ A botched operation against Hamas
leaves three Israeli soldiers dead. By John F. Burns and Deborah
Sontag. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINES-HOSTAGES (Bangkok) _ Relieved, bitter and still
frightened for their companions, five foreign hostages were
released by Moslem kidnappers in the southern Philippines for a
reported $5 million ransom. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-DRINKING (Lisdoonvarna, Ireland) _ Ireland is changing
rapidly in many ways, among them its tradition of drinking stout.
By Dan Barry.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   SCOUTS-BACKLASH (Undated) _ In the wake of the Supreme Court
decision on homosexuals in scouting, schools and charities across
the country are considering whether they want to stay involved with
the program. Some are contemplating backing off from their level of
contribution and whether they want to make their facilities
available to the organization. The San Diego Police Department, as
well as the United Way in San Francisco and in Santa Fe, have
pulled out as sponsors. By Kate Zernike.
</P>
<P>
   IOWA-IMMIG (Marshalltown, Iowa) _ No one would call Iowa a
melting pot. Nearly 96 percent white, this state can seem to have
more kinds of cows and corn than nationalities. But Iowa, which
hemorrhaged families during the 1980s farm crisis and has an
unemployment rate of only 2 percent, is proposing something no
other state has done: an all-out immigrant recruitment drive to
encourage foreigners to call Iowa home. The plan is to make Iowa an
``immigration enterprise zone,'' and the ideas range from seeking
an exemption to immigration quotas to urging companies to recruit
abroad. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-CARMEL (Carmel, Calif.) _ The days of having to go to the
post office to pick up mail are ending for the residents of Carmel,
Calif. Home delivery is coming -- and with it, something this
quirky town has never seen before: street numbers. Now, residents
will no longer have to tell FedEx or UPS, or more importantly, 911,
that they live on Hollyhock, 3 doors down from Sparrow Road, or at
Stone Owl Cottage. But in a town which has kept out street lights,
fast food, and neon, not everyone thinks this is progress.
</P>
<P>
   BLACKS-DNA (Boston) _ This fall, some 300 African-American
children here are to be sent home with swabs meant to gather DNA
samples from the cheeks or gums of their family members, part of a
local molecular biologist's nascent project that he means to extend
to North Carolina and other spots with long-stable African-American
populations. Last spring, a Howard University geneticist announced
he would soon offer DNA analysis to African-Americans. And the
African Burial Ground Project in New York has been assembling a
data-base of DNA from long-buried African-Americans and living
Africans. The efforts may be disparate but this much seems clear:
black Americans hunger to trace their African ancestry is combining
with powerful new DNA technology, and the foundations are being
laid for a system that will use genetic analysis to satisfy it. By
Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   CRIME-RATE (Washington) _ The Justice Department's National
Crime Victimization Survey shows that the violent crime rate fell
by more than 10 percent during 1999, reaching the lowest level
since the survey began in 1973. The numbers are in line with the
more extensive FBI uniform crime rates. But they do not include
homicides, which are on the rise. By Warren E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded p)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BIO (Undated) _ The Bush biography series continues,
focusing on his father's 1988 campaign. By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Undated) _ Campaigning with Gore. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   GOVS-OUTLOOK (Undated) _ Early this year, with no candidate
reaching the required 50 percent plus one vote to win the popular
election, the Mississippi House of Representatives chose Ronnie
Musgrove, a Democrat, as governor. It is upon such thin reeds that
Democrats this year are building their hopes that their
gubernatorial comeback is underway in the 11 races for governor.
Republican governors currently outnumber them, 30 to 18. Maine is
led by an independent, Angus S. King Jr.; Minnesota, by Jesse
Ventura, now representing the Minnesota Independence Party. By
Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY (Undated) _ On morning news shows, Cheney talks about
defense spending; he also says the ticket is working on a
health-care plan. By Michael Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   POLLSTER-PROFILE (Washington) _ Pollster Stanley Greenberg,
mastermind of Gore's ``populist'' slant. By Robin Toner.
</P>
