<DOCNO> NYT20000827.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3393 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-OLYMPIC-FESTIVAL0828-     08-27 1464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPIC-FESTIVAL0828-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sydney Olympic festival planners learn lessons from Atlanta
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When NBC told Olympic Arts Festival artistic director
Leo Schofield how fabulous the billowing white sails of the Sydney
Opera House would look on television, the
restaurant-critic-turned-arts-impresario just smirked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leo thought, `Oh, no. Forget that. I want it to be full
color,' '' says festival general manager Craig Hassall, laughing
about his boss's determination to make the cultural component of
the Olympics as spectacular as the sports.
</P>
<P>
   Get ready to adjust your brightness button.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 14 (or ``Games Eve,'' as the Aussies call it), when the
Olympic torch arrives at the opera house, the fabled structure will
go up in bright red flames, thanks to lighting wizardry by trendy
Australian designer Marc Newson. Adding wattage to the ceremony,
Down Under diva Olivia Newton-John will hand the torch to Italian
tenor Andrea Bocelli, who'll pass it to Australian tennis star Pat
Rafter. Afterward, for world leaders with nothing to do, there'll
be glittery twin galas inside the performing arts palace: Bocelli
singing Donizetti arias in one room, the Australian Ballet dancing
in another.
</P>
<P>
   Just four years ago, Atlanta got what may have been its biggest
infusion of culture ever: a $25 million extravaganza where you
could catch Jessye Norman with the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra, the
Alliance Theater Company's world premiere of Alfred Uhry's ``The
Last Night of Ballyhoo'' or the High Museum's ``Rings'' exhibit of
world masterpieces, to name just a few of the more high-profile
events.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's Sydney's turn.
</P>
<P>
   And its festival organizers say they learned a few things from
Atlanta's missteps. They say Atlanta fumbled by scheduling too many
performances during the Games themselves, when sports took center
stage and traffic was chaotic. Though the Woodruff Arts Center
provided something of a cultural nexus, events were spread around
the city precisely at traffic crunch time. Ticket sales were
generally good, but artists often played to half-empty houses.
</P>
<P>
   To adjust for the problem, Sydney has scheduled a good number of
its performances before the Games begin. That isn't to say that
Games-goers won't have arts events to pick from. But almost all of
them will be at the opera house, which offers the kind of dramatic
pedestrian backdrop that Atlanta and Los Angeles, which hosted the
Games in 1984, never could. Like Barcelona, site of the 1992 Games,
Sydney offers a vibrant urban landscape where sports fans, arts
patrons _ and plain old strollers _ can play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We happen to have a tourist attraction that is also a cultural
venue, so we have to exploit that to its fullest,'' says Hassall,
who goes so far as to say it's like having the Olympics under the
Statue of Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of Southern hospitality, the Australians are using their
own blend of mellowness and megalomania to try to turn the world on
its ear. Even if you don't get to see the Codex Leicester _
Leonardo da Vinci's 75-page notebook, on loan from Bill and Melinda
Gates _ or any of the festival's top-notch musical, dance,
theatrical or visual arts offerings, you're liable to get wind of
the Disneyesque dimensions of this Cultural Olympiad. Last weekend,
for example, a sellout crowd of 14,000 heard the Sydney Symphony
Orchestra perform Gustav Mahler's rarely heard ``Symphony of a
Thousand,'' with organ music beamed in via satellite.
</P>
<P>
   When the Olympic Games start Sept. 15, Sydney already will have
been feted to Pina Bausch's Tanztheater Wuppertal (Germany), Cloud
Gate Dance Theatre (Taiwan), Bill T. Jones/Arnie Zane Dance Company
(the U.S. troupe that recently stood up Spoleto Festival USA
because of the Confederate flag controversy) and the Atlanta
Symphony Orchestra's Robert Spano conducting the Australian Youth
Orchestra with violin soloist Pinchas Zukerman. Too bad six of the
festival's seven theatrical productions will have closed by then.
</P>
<P>
   If that is frustrating for arts lovers who can't get to Sydney
three weeks before the Games, it's a gift to the locals, who can
catch the performances before the stampede begins. Conversely, when
the foreign crowd arrives, it can get a good taste of Australian
culture: the Bell Shakespeare Company's mostly nude adaptation of
``Troilus and Cressida,'' the Bangarra Dance Theatre, the
Australian Ballet, the Sydney Symphony, the Australian Chamber
Orchestra and three Opera Australia productions. And the Flying
Fruit Fly Circus of Australia is teaming up with the Shanghai
Acrobatic Troupe through Sept. 30 at Prince Alfred Park.
</P>
<P>
   Major international acts appearing during the Games include
Riccardo Muti conducting his Orchestra Filarmonia della Scala, the
George Shearing Trio, German cabaret singer Ute Lemper and American
chanteuse Barbara Cook.
</P>
<P>
   Hassall says ticket sales are at about 40 percent of capacity.
Only the Bocelli gala and the George Shearing Trio have sold out.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be discounted are the more than 20 exhibitions on
everything from contemporary Australian furniture design and
Aboriginal fishing to Korean masterpieces and photography. The
blockbuster shows are likely to be the Dead Sea Scrolls (Art
Gallery of New South Wales), Leonardo's Codex Leceister and ``1,000
Years of the Olympic Games,'' 50 ancient relics that Greece refused
to lend to Atlanta four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Fewster, director of the Powerhouse Museum _ where the
Leonardo notebook, the Greek treasures and the Korean show will be
on view _ is expecting big crowds. Fewster says he's experiencing
the same nervousness he observed at Atlanta's High Museum in 1996,
on the eve of the ``Rings'' opening.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you know, they did spectacularly well, so I think it would
be fair to say I sit in exactly the same position, on the edge of
my seat,'' says the director of Australia's largest museum. ``The
truth is that nobody can predict just how well it will go.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the big question: How will this festival play with
Australia and the rest of the world?
</P>
<P>
   Any Olympic arts festival, be it in Los Angeles, Atlanta,
Barcelona or Sydney, must walk a political tightrope, trying to be
at once local, national and international.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles festival was notorious for excluding its
constituent arts groups. But with the Los Angeles Times as its
major sponsor, the Cultural Olympiad put on a show of such depth
and international cachet that it's still considered the benchmark.
Barcelona's effort, on the other hand, ran out of money months
before the Games but still managed to roll out a tapestry of events
that captured the essence of Catalonian culture and the
cutting-edge attitude of that particular moment. Like Sydney,
Barcelona had scale: Montjuic and the cascading esplanades of the
National Palace.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta wanted to showcase Southern culture, but it couldn't get
over its inferiority complex. The solution was to diffuse the
Southern spotlight by focusing on the 100th anniversary of the
modern Games and on other host cities. ``We tended to go a little
more mainstream,'' says Jeffrey Babcock, director of Atlanta's
Cultural Olympiad and now general director and chief executive
officer of the Boston Ballet. The critical response to Atlanta's
festival was mixed, but some exciting work came to the attention of
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Inclusiveness in programming is always a good thing. But Atlanta
needed an arts focus _ a place.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent piece in the Sydney Morning Herald, Debra Good, a
doctoral student at the University of New South Wales' Centre for
Olympic Studies, wrote, ``Schofield's program has been criticized
in advance for not including a commissioned Australian play; for
being too Eurocentric; for being too Sydney-centric; and for being
too international in flavor.'' Anyone who was around for the
constant feuds among the Atlanta arts community, Olympic officials
and the media can't help but feel a little deja vu upon reading
that.
</P>
<P>
   Nunally Kersh, producer of Charleston's Spoleto Festival, says
the Sydney event is to be admired for its mix of avant-garde work
reflecting both Australia and the world. ``I think they have been
very courageous,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the legacy of Atlanta's Olympic Arts Festival,
Babcock mentioned the Uhry play, then paused. ``The important thing
was, when it was all said and done, we really included many local
artists, and they had an opportunity to participate in an event
that only happened once in Atlanta. I think that's vital.''
</P>
<P>
   If only Atlanta had had an architectural jewel doubling as a
performing-arts venue.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-00 1522EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000827.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
