</P>
<P>
   ``As you know, they did spectacularly well, so I think it would
be fair to say I sit in exactly the same position, on the edge of
my seat,'' says the director of Australia's largest museum. ``The
truth is that nobody can predict just how well it will go.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the big question: How will this festival play with
Australia and the rest of the world?
</P>
<P>
   Any Olympic arts festival, be it in Los Angeles, Atlanta,
Barcelona or Sydney, must walk a political tightrope, trying to be
at once local, national and international.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles festival was notorious for excluding its
constituent arts groups. But with the Los Angeles Times as its
major sponsor, the Cultural Olympiad put on a show of such depth
and international cachet that it's still considered the benchmark.
Barcelona's effort, on the other hand, ran out of money months
before the Games but still managed to roll out a tapestry of events
that captured the essence of Catalonian culture and the
cutting-edge attitude of that particular moment. Like Sydney,
Barcelona had scale: Montjuic and the cascading esplanades of the
National Palace.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta wanted to showcase Southern culture, but it couldn't get
over its inferiority complex. The solution was to diffuse the
Southern spotlight by focusing on the 100th anniversary of the
modern Games and on other host cities. ``We tended to go a little
more mainstream,'' says Jeffrey Babcock, director of Atlanta's
Cultural Olympiad and now general director and chief executive
officer of the Boston Ballet. The critical response to Atlanta's
festival was mixed, but some exciting work came to the attention of
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Inclusiveness in programming is always a good thing. But Atlanta
needed an arts focus _ a place.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent piece in the Sydney Morning Herald, Debra Good, a
doctoral student at the University of New South Wales' Centre for
Olympic Studies, wrote, ``Schofield's program has been criticized
in advance for not including a commissioned Australian play; for
being too Eurocentric; for being too Sydney-centric; and for being
too international in flavor.'' Anyone who was around for the
constant feuds among the Atlanta arts community, Olympic officials
and the media can't help but feel a little deja vu upon reading
that.
</P>
<P>
   Nunally Kersh, producer of Charleston's Spoleto Festival, says
the Sydney event is to be admired for its mix of avant-garde work
reflecting both Australia and the world. ``I think they have been
very courageous,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the legacy of Atlanta's Olympic Arts Festival,
Babcock mentioned the Uhry play, then paused. ``The important thing
was, when it was all said and done, we really included many local
artists, and they had an opportunity to participate in an event
that only happened once in Atlanta. I think that's vital.''
</P>
<P>
   If only Atlanta had had an architectural jewel doubling as a
performing-arts venue.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
