<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3396 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MUSIC-WEBERN0828-COX     08-27 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-WEBERN0828-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Conductor champions Webern's world
 &HT;    By Pierre Ruhe
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Modernism comes in waves. The first wave of modern
music ended in Mittersill, Austria, on Sept. 15, 1945, with three
quick gunshots. The war in Europe had been over since May. An
American soldier, Raymond N. Bell, was on a policing raid when he
encountered a man breaking curfew, puffing a cigar in a doorway.
</P>
<P>
   The events of that evening remain unclear. What's known is that
Anton Webern, an impoverished composer, had fled the turmoil of
Vienna and was visiting his son-in-law, a Nazi turned black
marketeer. Webern had stepped outside for a smoke _ a contraband
gift, undoubtedly _ just as Bell arrived. After a scuffle, shots
were fired. So ended the career of one of the most unlikely giants
of 20th-century music.
</P>
<P>
   After his death, Webern became a totem for the generation that
came of age after the war. With Europe in ruins, many headstrong
young artists, in all fields, started to question the value of
tradition. In Webern's music, composers found a break with the
musical establishment. New was better; new was the thing. Like
glass-and-steel architecture and abstract modern painting, Webern's
wispy miniatures were cool, clear, rational. They sounded
different. They fit the times. And a dead composer, especially one
who left no philosophical tracts, could be appropriated as
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Pierre Boulez. As composer, conductor and media-savvy
polemicist, Boulez became leader of the international Webern cult,
defining a musical style that steered composition toward the
angular, the abstract, the atonal. When people nowadays get grumpy
about ``modern music,'' whether or not they know it, they're
probably talking about Webern's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Boulez, 75, has been a passionate and compelling champion of the
cause. He has just released the complete works of Anton Webern, a
six-CD set, with help from the Emerson String Quartet, the Ensemble
Intercontemporain and others. The performances overall are
superlative, infused with a luminance and warmth that should dispel
any notion that this music is frigid.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we hear Webern's mature works as bracing, extremely
concentrated, sometimes achingly beautiful and almost always
intoxicating, like a dry martini with olives. And unlike a symphony
by Bruckner or a tone poem by Strauss, Webern's music can be taken
in one gulp.
</P>
<P>
   With the Berlin Philharmonic, Boulez finds a world of expression
in the Symphony, Op. 21. A quirky, highly original work, it lasts
just over nine minutes. His Opus 1, Passacaglia for Orchestra,
lasts 10 minutes and might be mistaken for a rather hyperactive
piece by Mahler. The Variations for Piano, subtly played by
Krystian Zimerman, is loose-limbed and without a tonal center.
Since there's no line to follow, a listener gets soaked in
atmosphere. One of the pointillistic Five Movements for Orchestra,
Op. 10, is just seven measures long _ yet manages to tell a
complete story.
</P>
<P>
   What Webern accomplished _ and his followers adored _ was a
rejection of bloated, rococo romanticism. Economy was important,
yet he never compromised on heightened expression.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Webern's output was vocal music, infrequently heard in
concert because of its difficulty. Soprano Christiane Oelze handles
the songs and the two cantatas, among the composer's most
compelling works, with a fluid grace and an occasional phrase
turned into a haunting statement.
</P>
<P>
   This is Boulez's second crack at a complete Webern edition. His
first, originally released in the 1970s, covered only music that
Webern allowed published in his lifetime. That set is available on
CD from Sony. These new Deutsche Grammophon discs, superior in
almost every way, also include the sins of Webern's youth, works
that reveal his starting point: as a sensuous high romantic, a
direct descendant of Wagner and Mahler. The early Piano Quintet
evokes Brahms; ``Im Sommerwind'' saunters along at a pastoral
Viennese pace.
</P>
<P>
   We also get the posthumously published late works and several of
Webern's arrangements, including Schubert's German Dances and the
``Ricercata'' from Bach's ``A Musical Offering.'' These
re-creations don't try to improve on the original masters so much
as add psychological underpinning.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, Webern's abstract music baffles many listeners, and
some never move beyond dismissing it as far-out stuff. Yet
listeners who admire the universality of J.S. Bach, or the tight
control found in sacred Renaissance polyphony, can't help but find
Webern a kindred spirit. Bach explored the cosmos, it's been said;
Webern the atom. In this new set, Boulez makes clear that between
the two exists an eerie bond.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
