<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3406 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-FALL-MOVIES0828-COX     08-27 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALL-MOVIES0828-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Three new movies to fall for
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ We've waited all summer long for a dazzling movie
scene as simple as this: Betty (Renee Zellweger) and George (Greg
Kinnear) quietly talking and getting to know each other.
</P>
<P>
   The dazzle comes with its kick. He's a big TV soap opera star,
thinking she's an actress with the perfect scam to land a part.
She's a small-town waitress psychologically zonked into a fantasy
state, thinking not only that her favorite daytime drama is the
real thing, but that George is the character he plays on television
and the one great love she's desperate to win.
</P>
<P>
   In the upcoming ``Nurse Betty,'' from director Neil LaBute (``In
the Company of Men''), Betty and George's encounters are sweet,
mesmerizing moments on film. And the movie has more _ lots more.
Hit men. Drugs. Torture. A cross-country chase. All wrapped in a
constant collision of fantasy and reality. It's ``Being There''
meets ``To Die For.''
</P>
<P>
   When the darkly comic ``Nurse Betty'' opens Sept. 8, you won't
have seen a movie quite like it in a long time. Qualitywise, this
summer has been one continuous pileup of flat films. (It speaks
volumes that the most exciting big-studio movie of the summer _
``Gladiator'' _ debuted May 5.)
</P>
<P>
   But the onset of fall is starting to look like a moviegoer's
salvation. Following ``Nurse Betty'' will come two more solid,
winning films: writer-director Cameron Crowe's (``Jerry Maguire'')
1970s rock tour movie ``Almost Famous,'' arriving Sept. 15, and
Denzel Washington's enjoyable, made-in-Atlanta high school football
flick ``Remember the Titans,'' which debuts Sept. 29.
</P>
<P>
   All three are deep, well-acted tales about American obsessions:
soap operas, rock music and football. And each focuses on average
Americans _ not the $4,000-Italian-silk-sofa crowd of last year's
autumn wonder ``American Beauty,'' but the TV-watching diner
waitresses of ``Nurse Betty'' and the shaggy-haired, ratty-jeaned
concert fanatics of ``Almost Famous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nurse Betty'' is one of those quirky joys like LaBute's own
critics' favorite, ``In the Company of Men,'' only brighter,
lighter and more resonant. ``Men'' was brutal in its depiction of
misogyny and relationships between the sexes, honing masculine
desires into razor-sharp weapons. His equally dark follow-up film,
``Your Friends and Neighbors,'' viewed friendship like the final
daze of ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nurse Betty'' not only benefits from being more accessible to
mainstream audiences than those movies (how can LaBute miss with
such a deeply talented, recognizable cast as Zellweger, Kinnear,
Morgan Freeman and Chris Rock?), but its satirical view is often
wrapped in genuine charm.
</P>
<P>
   True fascination is also the undercurrent of ``Almost Famous,''
Crowe's both unfettered examination of and sugary valentine to the
drug-filled, start-it-up rock music of the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Loosely based on Crowe's seminal years as a writer for Rolling
Stone magazine, which began when he was 16, the movie stars
newcomer Patrick Fugit as a teenage rock lover and aspiring
journalist who lands a plum assignment for the magazine: covering
the cross-country tour of Stillwater, a burgeoning band that's a
sort of cross between the Marshall Tucker Band and Led Zeppelin.
</P>
<P>
   Meticulous in its depictions of flower-power groupies and
long-haired musicians hanging _ and fighting _ backstage, the film
also mixes enticing original songs (composed by Crowe, his wife
Nancy Wilson of Heart, Ann Wilson and Peter Frampton) with classics
from Led Zeppelin, the Who, Elton John, Yes, Joni Mitchell, Black
Sabbath and the Allman Brothers. Frampton also served as the film's
technical consultant and appears briefly as the road manager for
Humble Pie.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar winner Frances McDormand co-stars as Fugit's mom, but the
film lacks a big mainstream marquee name (Brad Pitt was up for the
role of Stillwater's lead guitarist, but the part eventually went
to Billy Crudup).
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, that may work to the movie's advantage. Crudup, who
recently starred in ``Jesus' Son,'' lends a believable mixture of
everyday good looks and unkempt cool (reportedly, when Robert Plant
saw the film, he said he was sure he had met the guy playing the
part on the road). Jason Lee (a frequent fixture in Kevin Smith
films like ``Mall Rats'' and ``Chasing Amy''), plays Stillwater's
ego-tuned lead vocalist like a small-town Steve Perry.
</P>
<P>
   Like DreamWorks' early push for ``American Beauty'' last year,
the studio has been pumping press interest in ``Almost Famous,''
launching an interview mini-tour with Crowe, Fugit and Kate Hudson
(Goldie Hawn's daughter, she plays groupie Penny Lane) and holding
invitation-only early screenings to generate a buzz.
</P>
<P>
   Early special screenings are also part of Disney's gameplan for
the modestly budgeted ``Remember the Titans,'' which producer Jerry
Bruckheimer is lauding as ``a real slice of life'' and is
personally promoting.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a true story, reportedly budgeted at around $20
million, ``Titans'' is a classic American tale: a Virginia high
school football team, undergoing integration in 1971, erupts in
racial strife and, against great odds, winds up winning the state
championship.
</P>
<P>
   It's an extremely earnest script and one that Bruckheimer has
ratcheted up with his patented branding of employing popular tunes
from the era, including Norman Greenbaum's ``Spirit In The Sky,''
The Hollies' ``Long Cool Woman (In a Black Dress)'' and Creedence
Clearwater Revival's ``Up Around the Bend.''
</P>
<P>
   But the film also stars Denzel Washington as the school's
real-life head football coach Herman Boone. It's such a strong
performance, filled with stalwart speeches and unrelenting
determination, that it lifts the film above the normal ``we won''
sports movie. And it's quite possible Washington will be up for an
Oscar again (some thought his performance in ``The Hurricane'' was
wrongly overlooked when Kevin Spacey won best actor this year)
</P>
<P>
   ``Titans'' was filmed throughout metro Atlanta last fall. And
since its subject is Virginia, there's virtually nothing in it
that's uniformly recognizable about Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   That might disappoint a few moviegoers here. But fall's early
message is clear. Nobody has to wait months in hopes that Tom
Hanks' post-``Survivor'' desert-isle flick, ``Cast Away,'' or
Russell Crowe and Meg Ryan's on-screen, off-screen love-tinged
adventure movie, ``Proof of Life,'' will rejuvenate the megaplex.
Very soon, you'll be able to see a really good movie.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
