<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3427 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLYMPICS-WHEELCHAIR08     08-27 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPICS-WHEELCHAIR0828-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wheeling to Sydney
 &HT;    By Rick Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARM SPRINGS, Ga. _ For most of the past 150 years, polio
patients came to this sleepy Middle Georgia town. They came to swim
in the 88-degree water that flows from the springs just east of the
downtown business district.
</P>
<P>
   Now, handicapped athletes from around the world come to Warm
Springs because of the accessible facilities at the Roosevelt Warm
Springs Institute for Rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   This past week, the top eight men's wheelchair basketball teams
in the world have played a round-robin tournament in preparation
for the Paralympics later this year in Sydney, Australia. Canada
defeated the United States 61-55 Saturday to win the tournament
undefeated. Seven women's teams will be on the courts Thursday
through next Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The $11.2 million Center for Therapeutic Recreation, where the
2000 Roosevelt World Basketball Challenge is being held, includes
an indoor gym, pool, racquetball court and fitness room. It opened
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   David Kiley, who has won Paralympic gold medals in giant slalom,
track and wheelchair basketball, works at a rehab center in
Charlotte helping recently injured people get back into a
physically active lifestyle. But he doesn't have anything like the
facilities at Warm Springs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't know this is a rehab center, because it's such a
great sports complex,'' Kiley said.
</P>
<P>
   The recreation center is just one of the modern buildings that
sit on the 953-acre campus originally purchased by Franklin Delano
Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt first came to Warm Springs in 1924 after hearing that
the warm waters from the springs might help his legs, which had
been crippled by polio. He spent nearly two-thirds of his personal
wealth, plus money donated by friends from New York, to purchase a
run-down resort around the springs. He returned 41 times and was
next door at his Little White House when he died in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Warm Springs Foundation, which Roosevelt started,
treated polio patients until the disease essentially was conquered
in the 1960s. The state of Georgia took over the management of the
property in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Today, more than 500 people work there. The annual budget is
about $28 million, including $4 million in state funds. More than
5,000 patients are treated each year.
</P>
<P>
   The institute hosts several competitive events each year. The
wheelchair basketball games are especially significant because they
are the final international competition before the Paralympics.
</P>
<P>
   Rules for wheelchair basketball games are similar to stand-up
games, except ballhandlers are allowed to double-dribble.
</P>
<P>
   Players' level of disability is rated, and officials use those
numbers to even the competition.
</P>
<P>
   There are other differences, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no lateral movement, and the guys don't jump as
high,'' said Michael Frogley, coach of the Canadian team. ``It's
more a game of tactics and team play, whereas the NBA is to a large
extent a game of one on one.''
</P>
<P>
   Frogley, like his players, is in a wheelchair. He played
stand-up basketball before wrecking a sports car when he was a
teenager.
</P>
<P>
   In stand-up basketball, fans are accustomed to hearing the
squeak of tennis shoes. In wheelchair basketball, the sounds coming
from the court are the clanking of wheelchairs crashing together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty physical; that's the nature of the game,'' said
Troy Sachs, who plays for the Australian team and is one of the
better, and most aggressive, players in the Roosevelt Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs said his team has ``as good a chance as any other'' to
take the gold medal in the Paralympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe in ourselves as a team, and you definitely have to
have five players working together to succeed in this sport,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Team USA is favored to win the gold in Sydney, and team members
expect to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   Kiley, who has been on the U.S. team for 19 years, is hoping to
end his international basketball career with a win in the
Paralympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to come off as not giving other teams respect,
but we're a pretty confident bunch,'' said Kiley, who at 47 is
twice as old as some of his teammates and opponents.
</P>
<P>
   When he hits the courts in Sydney, Kiley will become the only
player in Olympic history to play in four decades.
</P>
<P>
   Team members say Team USA benefits from all of the wheelchair
teams playing across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the largest pool of players to draw from,'' he said.
``There are about 190 teams in North America, while some countries
have only 10 teams to choose from.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team might have the biggest talent pool, but the team's
bank balance is lagging, Kiley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the players pay out of their own pockets to go to
camps,'' he said. ``We've recently hired an executive director who
we hope will raise funds for us so we can just show up and play.''
</P>
<P>
   But even with the sacrifices, Kiley wouldn't take anything for
the time and money he spent playing the game. And he is most
appreciative of the backing he has gotten from his wife and two
kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been my main support through it all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
