<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANCELOT WARE, 85, CO-FOUNDER OF MENSA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain)   By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lancelot Ware, a British barrister who was the co-founder of
Mensa, the society for intellectually gifted people, died on Aug.
15 in a nursing home in Surrey, England. He was 85.
</P>
<P>
   Ware became interested in unusually bright people when his
father died, leaving him to care for his sister, who was ten years
younger than he. His realization that both of them were highly
intelligent led to an interest in intelligence testing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1945, when Ware was a postgraduate student of law at Lincoln
College, Oxford, he met Roland Berrill, an eccentric barrister from
Australia who had become fixated with Oxford since being rejected
by the school. Together the two men founded an association for
people with strong intellects.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there are about 100,000 Mensa members in 100 countries
and active Mensa organizations in over 40 countries, on every
continent except Antarctica.
</P>
<P>
   The only requirement for membership is proof that the applicant
has an IQ in the top 2 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Members range in age from 4 to 94, but most are between 20 and
49. They include both high school dropouts and people with multiple
doctorates. Some are on welfare, while some are millionaires. And
they hold many jobs _ professors, truck drivers, scientists,
firefighters, farmers, computer programmers, glass blowers, artists
and police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Smart as the two founders were, they could not at first settle
on a name for their aristocracy of intellect.
</P>
<P>
   They began by calling it the High IQ Club. When that sounded too
prosaic they considered ``Mens'' _ Latin for mind. But that was
also the name of a racy gentleman's magazine. So they made it
Mensa, and clung to that even though it was soon discovered that
Mensa, which means table in Latin, also means idiot in Mexican
slang.
</P>
<P>
   The original object of Mensa was to create a list of the names
and addresses of 600 of the most intelligent people in Britain so
that they could be contacted by scholars and governmental officials
in case of need. It was perhaps not surprising that Mensa's
courting of the government went unrequited.
</P>
<P>
   But Ware did not lose his enthusiasm. ``I found that people of
high intelligence were people I had an easy rapport with,'' he once
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mensa developed as its goals to identify and foster human
intelligence for the benefit of humanity, to encourage research in
the field of intelligence and to promote stimulating activities for
its members.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, though, the stated object of the association is
``enjoying each other's company and participating in a wide range
of social and cultural activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Membership is still determined by intelligence testing _ even
after the worth of such tests was challenged. In 1995,
International Mensa was attacked when its Los Angeles newsletter
proposed euthanasia for the old, ill or mentally retarded.
</P>
<P>
   Lancelot Lionel Ware was born in Mitcham, Surrey. During World
War II, he served as a research chemist, but later said he quit
because he was given three months' worth of work to do in three
days.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his study of law, he studied at the Imperial
College of Science and Technology in London, and was a medical
researcher and lecturer at St. Thomas' Hospital in London.
</P>
<P>
   In his legal work, Ware specialized in intellectual property,
copyright and patents.
</P>
<P>
   Ware is survived by his wife, Francesca Quint Ware, a fellow
member of Mensa.
</P>
<P>
   Ware lost interest in Mensa in 1950, but after Berrill died in
1961 Ware rejoined the society and became vigorously active in the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Ware had traveled widely to meet Mensa members.
Last year he was named president of the Mensa Foundation for Gifted
Children.
</P>
<P>
   But Mensa was still an organization in search of a purpose, and
to some degree remains so today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-00 1643EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000827.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3444 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-IRELAND-DRINKING-2TAK     08-27 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-DRINKING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER SIGN OF THE TIMES: THE IRISH ARE DRINKING LESS GUINNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAN BARRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LISDOONVARNA, Ireland _ From the doorway of his family's pub,
Peter Curtin has witnessed dramatic changes in Irish life. He
remembers when one man's trip to the United States was considered
so unusual that he was sent to the local schools to share what he
had seen. He remembers when farmers would come in for a pint of
Guinness while clutching the reins of horses poking their noses
into the pub.
</P>
<P>
   What makes this remarkable is that Curtin is only 46 years old.
So much of Ireland has changed in recent years that he avoids
general statements, for fear that another cultural upheaval will
occur before he completes the sentence.
</P>
<P>
   But today this much is true: Trips to the States are routine,
customers at the bar could have a BMW parked where the horses used
to stand _ and he is probably drinking something other than a
Guinness, the midnight-black stout consumed by his father and his
father before him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too individual a taste,'' Curtin, who now manages that
same pub, said with a hint of admiration. ``Plus, it doesn't have
the perception as a drink for younger people.''
</P>
<P>
   Something seismic is happening in Ireland _ apart from the
diminishing influence of the Roman Catholic Church, apart from an
economy so ferocious that a tiger has replaced the tamer metaphor
of a bull.
</P>
<P>
   In short, people here are not drinking Guinness stout as much as
they used to. Signs once proclaiming that ``Guinness is good for
you'' might now read: ``Guinness is no longer a given.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month Diageo, the international food and beverage giant
that owns Guinness along with Pillsbury, Burger King, Smirnoff and
Johnnie Walker, announced that worldwide sales for the stout were
booming, particularly in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But it also provided another, more intriguing statistic: While
Guinness stout remains the best-selling alcoholic beverage in
Ireland, over the last year its consumption here has declined by
nearly 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a blip. Pat Barry, the director of corporate affairs
for a subsidiary called Guinness Ireland, said that in the last
five years, the sale and consumption of lagers here, the light,
cold and transparent brews, have surpassed those of heavier, darker
stout for the first time in _ well, for the first time ever.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is this just a routine shift in consumer tastes _ this is
not Tayto's chips, it is ``the black stuff,'' something so
psychically connected to Ireland that in Dublin after donating
blood, you are given the choice between a free cup of tea or a
half-pint of Guinness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guinness is synonymous with Ireland and with Irish heritage,''
said Philip Hawkins, an analyst for Merrill Lynch in London. ``But
as prosperity comes to Ireland at a rapid pace, youngsters have
more money in their pockets than ever before, and are looking for a
more fashionable drinking experience in the fashionable clubs in
Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that means you don't walk around with a pint of Guinness
in your hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry agreed: ``The challenge for us is to ensure that Guinness
continues to be relevant to a wide range of consumers and to make
it more relevant to the newer consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   Having relevance in Ireland has never been an issue for
Guinness. Part of the national story includes how Arthur Guinness
began to brew ales and porter at St. James' Gate in Dublin in 1759;
how the brewery introduced a stronger porter called ``extra stout''
in the 1820s; how the prospering company built housing for the poor
and developed St. Stephen's Green as a gift to Dublin. When the
company adopted the patriotic symbol of a harp, it seemed more
fitting than impertinent.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, as the Irish writer Brendan Behan once observed,
Guinness has been good to the Irish, but so, too, have the Irish
been good to Guinness. Generations of men drank its stout as they
talked rebellion or shared gossip in pubs, long the community
centers of this country. The drink took on its own lore: how you
ate a Guinness as much as drank it; how it contained restorative
vitamins; how even a pregnant woman might benefit from its wonders.
</P>
<P>
   The famous ``Guinness is good for you'' slogan is no longer used
here _ the beverage is, after all, alcohol. But the company still
trumpets the phrase in a few countries, Barry said, where the stout
is perceived by some to be ``a source of power and strength and
virility.''
</P>
<P>
   In a country with more than 10,000 pubs and hotel bars, any
failure in the exacting delivery of a pint _ from the cleanliness
of the tap lines to the temperature of the beverage _ traditionally
could ruin a pub's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Curtin, a sociologist at the National University of
Ireland, Galway _ and Peter Curtin's older brother _ has spent
years studying rural communities like Lisdoonvarna, which is known
for its spa water and for an annual September festival at which
bachelor farmers once sought potential brides. His research has
focused in part on pub life _ a life he knows well, having been
born above the family pub, the Roadside Tavern.
</P>
<P>
   In that culture, Christopher Curtin recalled: ``To be a drinker
was to be drinking Guinness. And if you were to ask what single
drink would you have to have above any other, it would be
Guinness.''
</P>
<P>
   But that culture is in transformation. There is an architectural
shift away from the small, bevel-glassed windows, so perfect in
thwarting the curious from peering in. The ``holy hour'' law _
which forced pubs to close on Sunday afternoons to encourage
families to eat, and not drink, their Sunday dinners _ was recently
set aside. Finally, there is the diminishing influence of Guinness.
</P>
<P>
   When the Curtins were children, their family's pub offered
Guinness on tap, whiskey in the bottle, and gin for the
nonconformist. Now it offers an assortment of tapped and bottled
lagers, from Heineken to Budweiser, as well as ales, ciders, wine
and a new line of ready-to-drink concoctions made of vodka, rum and
other spirits.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, the choices at the Roadside Tavern reflect how far
Ireland has come from being an island unto itself, a parochial
place where Guinness profited from its captive audience.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The international market is now competing for the suddenly
abundant pocket money of the average Irish consumer. More people
are returning from intercontinental vacations with broadened
tastes. And the universal emphasis on slim figures, beamed daily
over satellite television, bedevils the Guinness marketing
executives who have tried for years to convey the difficult message
that its heavy product is not particularly fattening.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Guinness anticipated the changing tastes, and has
spent millions of dollars on technology to cool the stout _
traditionally served at room temperature _ and to make it available
in specially designed cans. But the younger drinkers are proving
ever more elusive, acknowledged Barry. ``Our interest at this stage
is to encourage the newer drinker to come on board at an earlier
age,'' he said. ``And we're doing that through a variety of
promotions.''
</P>
<P>
   One such promotion includes photographs of attractive young
people with the advice to ``Live life to the power of Guinness'' _
a phrase that, at least in Lisdoonvarna, has Peter Curtin asking:
``What the heck does that mean?''
</P>
<P>
   The Guinness tap is far from running dry. The company continues
to reap large profits in countries like Italy and Spain, to which
it routinely sends architects to help recreate authentic Irish
pubs. It still owns the brewing and marketing rights here for
Budweiser and Carlsberg beer and distributes various other brands
of ales and lagers.
</P>
<P>
   And while the company continues to streamline its operations _
it recently announced the closing of one brewery and layoffs at a
packaging plant and another brewery _ Barry dismisses rumors that
its parent company, Diageo, will either sell it or move its
operations out of the country. Guinness, he said, will stay _
sponsoring the Rose of Tralee festivals, providing free lunches to
the elderly of Dublin, remaining a part of the Irish psyche.
</P>
<P>
   Still, something has been lost. Forty years ago, who in
Lisdoonvarna could have imagined that the Curtin lad named Peter _
the one who watched over their horses while they had a pint of
Guinness _ would someday propose building a microbrewery next to
his family's pub? A microbrewery that he promises would make its
own brand of stout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
