</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLLSTER-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEWEST MEMBER OF GORE'S CAMPAIGN TEAM COMES FULL CIRCLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Conn.)   By ROBIN TONER    c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Stan Greenberg, who was President Clinton's
pollster throughout his long march to the White House, is back in
the fray of presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   The former Yale political science professor, a longtime
interpreter of the political yearnings of the white middle class,
quietly signed on with Vice President Al Gore's campaign five weeks
ago. It represented a certain closure: Greenberg had left Clinton
after the debacle of the 1994 election, when the Democrats lost the
House and the Senate and Clinton summarily replaced him with Dick
Morris.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to make a change, given the '94 losses, and he made
the change,'' said Greenberg, with the careful equanimity of a man
who landed well and wants you to know it. ``It worked out fine. I'm
very happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only question is why I'm so foolish to come back and do
this,'' he added with a short laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Since he left Clinton, Greenberg has worked on campaigns around
the world, developing a kind of specialty in helping center-left
parties return to power. He worked for Tony Blair's 1997 campaign
for prime minister of Britain; Blair's election broke 18 years of
Conservative Party rule. He also worked for Gerhard Schroeder's
1998 campaign for chancellor of Germany; his victory returned
Social Democrats to power for the first time in 16 years, And last
year, he worked for the campaign of Ehud Barak, the Israeli prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each battle has its uniqueness,'' Greenberg said. ``But each
of these parties has struggles in the postindustrial period, and
they're all trying to learn from each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg, 55, does not really want to talk about the strategy
of the Gore campaign, which has taken a markedly populist turn in
recent weeks. (A populist turn that escalated, by the way, with
Greenberg's arrival, although the Gore campaign dismisses the
connection.)
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg also dismisses the idea that there is a clear tension
between that economic populism and the ``new Democrat'' philosophy,
willing to break with liberal orthodoxy on issues like trade and
welfare reform, that that was championed by Clinton and Gore in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore's a new Democrat,'' Greenberg said. ``He's always been
a new Democrat. His message derives from who he is and what he's
been saying in his political life.''
</P>
<P>
   But the pollster contends that Gore's candidacy comes at a new
stage of American politics. Clinton's challenge was to deal with
the Democratic Party's past, to convince disaffected voters that
the Democrats were not ``a big-spending party that's culturally
elitist,'' Greenberg said. Gore's challenge is to build on that
credibility and show that Democrats ``can manage the future,''
Greenberg said, modernizing institutions like Medicare and the
public school system wisely and carefully, and using the surplus
for great national needs.
</P>
<P>
   In that context, Greenberg asserts, George W. Bush's huge tax
cut proposal represents a failure of vision: ``That we're going to
take the surplus and give it to individuals, now, to spend it, now,
with no sense of what it would mean for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Sen. John McCain, Bush's former rival for the
Republican presidential nomination, Greenberg added, ``McCain
understood this moment much better than Bush does.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg has spent much of his professional life trying to
synthesize the various themes of the Democratic Party and reconnect
it to the middle-class and working-class voters it lost in the '70s
and '80s. One of two sons of a bookkeeper and what he called a
``self-taught environmental engineer,'' Greenberg grew up in
Washington and Silver Spring, Md., a product of public schools and
the middle-class neighborhoods he studies so intensely today.
</P>
<P>
   He got his doctorate from Harvard, with a dissertation on the
politics of poor neighborhoods, and eventually joined the faculty
at Yale. One of his early academic passions was South Africa _ he
worked on Nelson Mandela's presidential campaign in 1994 _ but he
inexorably moved into American politics in the early 1980s. After
the Democrats' landslide defeat in 1984, the United Auto Workers
and the Michigan Democratic Party hired him to study Macomb County,
Mich., and determine why what was once the most Democratic suburb
in America gave Ronald Reagan 67 percent of its vote in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   He determined that middle-class voters believed that the
Democratic Party had abandoned them, was using their hard-earned
tax dollars on ``giveaway'' programs that did not benefit them, and
was out of touch with their values. Clinton, whose thinking was
headed in the same direction, hooked up with Greenberg in the late
1980s, and they soon began a campaign that revolved around ``the
forgotten middle class,'' ``the people who work hard and play by
the rules,'' Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg says he continues to have good relations with Clinton,
despite their break after 1994. When asked his opinion of
Greenberg, Dick Morris, now a commentator and president of
Voter.com, said: ``I'll quote President Clinton to you _ `He never
told me what to do. He would always tell me on the one hand, on the
other hand, but never tell me what to do.' '' (Greenberg said he
had no comment on that.)
</P>
<P>
   Married to Rep. Rosa DeLauro, D-Conn., Greenberg has a home in
New Haven, Conn., and a town house on Capitol Hill. He has three
children by a first marriage; one is Anna Greenberg, a political
scientist at Harvard, with whom he recent co-authored an essay on
the Democrats' need to promote ``family-centered values.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg said he did not worry that his opponents would think
he had gone global, lost touch with the nuances of American
politics. ``I'll leave it to them to figure out what I bring to the
table,'' he said. But he dismissed the notion that the Bush team,
clannish and focused, was the dangerous equivalent of the winning
Clinton team of 1992. ``They may have too tight a team and maybe
too mechanical a vision of how to get him elected president,''
Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   It's an unusual moment in American politics, he says _ one he
clearly did not want to miss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
