<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3459 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BAHA-MEN-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      08-27 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAHA-MEN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT LONG LAST, A BAHAMIAN BAND HAS A HIT ON ITS HANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When he was 7, Isaiah Taylor began having dreams that he
compares to the visions God sent Joseph in the Bible. His own
vision was of leading a group of musicians from his home in the
Bahamas to worldwide success.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, however, Taylor's dream could not have been further
from reality. He was 50, and his group, the Baha Men, had been
together in various incarnations for over two decades, merging pop
and funk with traditional Bahamian junkanoo music. The band had
been dropped from two major labels in the United States, most
recently from Mercury Records as a casualty in the merger of
Universal Music and Polygram. And there was a further blow when its
lead singer, Nehemiah Hield, left the group.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when pop music is ruled by the fresh-faced teen-age
dreams of Britney Spears and the Backstreet Boys, it did not seem
likely that an aging Bahamian band without a major label deal would
have a grain of a chance.
</P>
<P>
   But the world of pop music is strange, and no one knows why some
bands get second, third and fourth chances, while others do not get
even one. As much as music executives like to think they have the
market sewn up, popular music follows no one's rules but its own.
And this summer Taylor's childhood dream became a reality.
</P>
<P>
   The Baha Men's single ``Who Let the Dogs Out,'' released and
distributed independently, is turning into the summer anthem of
2000, say radio programmers like Ed Lambert of KISS-FM in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The Baha Men may be the first casualty of the Universal merger
to come back with a hit through an independent label. And the tale
of the making of that hit is one that crosses borders and spans
generations, changing the fortunes of a Trinidadian soca singer, a
Bahamian junkanoo band and a record executive who would not give
up.
</P>
<P>
   With its signature guttural barking and breezy island rapping,
the song can be heard blasting everywhere from passing convertibles
to baseball games. As is usually the case with such instant hits,
some find the song irresistible, others find it obnoxious, and many
find it both.
</P>
<P>
   One day last week viewers of Nickelodeon chose it as their video
of the day over 'N Sync's ``It's Gonna Be Me.'' On other days on
Nickelodeon the Baha Men have beaten out Britney Spears, the
Backstreet Boys, Aaron Carter and other teen-age idols. Since its
release in late July the band's album has been on fire. In its
first week it was not even on the pop charts; by last week, it had
climbed to No. 59 from 103, and it is likely to rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the great Cinderella story,'' said Steve Greenberg, who
put out the new Baha Men album as the first and only release so far
on his own independent label, S-Curve. Greenberg had signed the
group to two different record companies _ Atlantic and Mercury _ in
the last decade, with no success.
</P>
<P>
   ``The song's been floating around for two years, the band has
been floating around in some version for 30 years, and the label's
12 weeks old,'' Greenberg said. ``It's the most unlikely hit ever.
I couldn't even get arrested with this band on a major label.''
</P>
<P>
   If the band's story offers any lesson, it is that there is no
such thing as a final chapter in a pop music career. Whether it is
Santana reaping his greatest success 30 years after his prime, the
rap producer Dr. Dre engineering his own comeback years after
hip-hop advanced without him, or the Baha Men becoming a
teeny-bopper sensation long after having been written off by the
music business, the sweetest prizes in popular music sometimes go
to those who stay in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes way back, man,'' Taylor said of his band's success.
``God gave me the dream, and I actually had visions of doing all
these things as a kid. When I sat down with my band and told them
this, some of them probably thought I was crazy. But now they all
see it coming to pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said that as a child he had no interest in music and
would skip music classes in school. But he could not escape his
destiny, he said, and he formed the Baha Men in the early 1980s as
High Voltage, a collective of local junkanoo, rhythm-and-blues and
disco musicians who had already been playing for years.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg first heard High Voltage in 1991. He was working as a
talent scout at Big Beat/Atlantic records when a Bahamian
songwriter gave him a High Voltage cassette.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg changed the band's name to the Baha Men and released
two of its albums on Big Beat. When Greenberg left the label for
Mercury during an executive power struggle, Big Beat dropped the
Baha Men.
</P>
<P>
   At Mercury, where he signed successful bands like Hanson,
Greenberg stuck with the Baha Men as a pet project. He released two
more of the band's records, the last of which sold fewer than 700
copies, which is not only a failure in the music business but an
embarrassment as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became a standing joke in the industry that every time I
came to a new label, the first band I'd sign would be the Baha
Men,'' Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time in Trinidad a soca star named Anslem Douglas
was writing a song for the 1998 carnival. At previous carnivals,
Douglas said, there were songs in which men made coarse references
to women. Davis decided to create a way for women to respond and
wrote a song around a local street cry, ``Who let the dogs out!''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're always calling guys `dogs' anyway,'' Douglas said.
``This was a way to legitimize it.''
</P>
<P>
   The flirtatious, suggestive song begins with a party setting in
which the men start making passes at the women, who bark in
response, ``Get back, you flea-infested mongrel.''
</P>
<P>
   The song became a hit in the Caribbean and eventually found its
way onto Greenberg's desk when a musician stopped by his office at
Mercury with a version he had recorded himself. ``That version was
horrible,'' Greenberg said. ``But the song stayed in my head for
two years.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After the sale of Polygram's music holdings to Seagram, which
owns Universal, Greenberg left his job to write a novel, and the
Baha Men were dropped from the label. But Greenberg could not get
the song out of his head. He wrote in his diary last December:
``I'm going to record that song, `Who Let the Dogs Out,' with the
Baha Men, and we're going to have a worldwide hit. I'm sure of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time, Taylor lost Hield, who quit to pursue solo
projects and tour as a backup vocalist with Lenny Kravitz, who is
part-Bahamian. The band held open auditions in Nassau and ended up
with not one replacement singer but three.
</P>
<P>
   One was Hield's nephew, Omerit Hield. ``I was working as a
teller at a bank,'' he said. ``Being in the Baha Men was something
I always wanted to do, but I never thought I'd have a chance. When
I went to the audition, there were at least 75 people there.'' He
got the job.
</P>
<P>
   Then Taylor almost turned down the song that would catapult the
band to success. ``This is going to sound crazy,'' Taylor said.
``But when Steve Greenberg said `Who Let the Dogs Out' would be a
good song to cover, I said, `I don't want to do that song.'''
</P>
<P>
   In Taylor's mind the song was too popular in the Caribbean and
too specific to the region for audiences in other countries to
understand. But he finally relented. After recording the song using
a number of different singers, backing tracks and studios, the band
finally got it right by recording in the home of its producer,
Michael Mangini.
</P>
<P>
   The barking sounds, Hield said, came naturally. ``If you go to
Nassau, you'll see dogs running around in the streets. So we
listened to them, and it was easy to imitate.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg started his S-Curve label and made distribution and
promotion deals with the independent companies Red and Artemis,
owned by his former boss at Mercury, Danny Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg played the song for a friend, Winston Simone, who runs
a music publishing company, Desmone Music, with, among others, the
songwriter Desmond Child. ``I said, `Oh my god, this is a smash!'
when I heard it,'' Simone said.
</P>
<P>
   He tracked down the writer, Douglas, at his aunt's house and
bought his entire catalog of songs, secured a publishing deal for
him and helped place ``Who Let the Dogs Out'' on the ``Rugrats in
Paris'' soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   ``He probably stands to be a millionaire if things keep going
this way,'' Simone said of Douglas. ``In the middle of the night
sometimes I worry, `What's he going to do with his money?' He's
going to have a big hit, and I want to make sure he's always going
to be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas said not to worry. ``It's every writer's dream to be
published,'' he said excitedly. ``It takes the financial strain
off, the mental strain off. Finally, my ship has come in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trinidadian newspapers are already pinning their crossover
hopes for regional soca music on Douglas' lapels, with one
newspaper declaring that ``the future of soca is cash register
success on the Billboard charts, and Anslem's foot is in the
door.'' Douglas, however, is looking forward to new challenges. He
said he was awestruck when Simone suggested that he work on a song
with Child for the new Ricky Martin album.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been up there with the soca stars like Super Blue,
but now I'm seeing my career take a whole new turn,'' Douglas said.
</P>
<P>
   Life has changed for the Baha Men, too. Hield summed up the last
month most succinctly: ``I've never barked so much in my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
