<DOCNO> NYT20000827.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3464 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-R-LEBANON-VOTES-NYT     08-27 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-LEBANON-VOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TENSE POWER STRUGGLE SPILLS OVER INTO LEBANON ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(REPEATING to add map note)  (ART ADV: map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JOHN KIFNER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONSOURIEH, Lebanon _ Confident as an old-time Chicago ward
boss, Walid Khatter, Interior Minister Michel Murr's man in this
Greek Orthodox village, stood in the doorway of his polling station
Sunday afternoon and predicted the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have around 1,000 voters in this district. There will be
about 800 for the Michel Murr ticket,'' he said, adding
dismissively, ``about 200 for the others.''
</P>
<P>
   How could he be so sure? a visitor asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, we know,'' he said with a shrug and a grin, opening a hand
bedecked with three huge gold rings to show a stack of palm cards
listing Murr's slate of candidates. An aide materialized from the
crush of more than a dozen Murr campaign workers _ the whole area
around the polling station was festooned with portraits of Murr _
with numbers scratched on a sheet of paper and nodded assent.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by reminders of their tribal politics, Lebanese went
to the polls on Sunday in the beginning of a two-stage
parliamentary election overshadowed by Syrian dominance and a
bitter struggle between the current government and its critics.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the Christian heartland of Mt. Lebanon, among the
suburban sprawl running up the mountains from Beirut, the focus was
on the battle between a slate headed by the powerful Murr, one of
Syria's biggest supporters, and an opposition slate headed by
Nassib Lahoud, a wealthy businessman and former ambassador to the
United States, who is a cousin of the president, but nonetheless a
critic.
</P>
<P>
   Murr has come under fierce criticism from the opposition because
of his multiple roles as a candidate running for re-election, a
staunch supporter of the government, and ultimately the man in
charge of running the elections. With his government post, he
controls police and internal security forces, the granting or
withholding of various licenses and patronage over a huge number of
public employees.
</P>
<P>
   His power was evident on Sunday. Entrances to many of the
polling places were surrounded by election workers in baby blue
T-shirts and baseball hats. The Arabic legend on the T-shirts read
simply: ``Michel Murr.''
</P>
<P>
   Every seat in Parliament is assigned to one of the country's 17
officially recognized religions, minutely derived from a census
taken in 1932. (There has never been one since for fear of
political upset.) In the voting on Sunday, citizens went into
separate rooms in the polling places, divided both by men and women
and by each religious sect in a district: Maronite Catholic,
Armenian Catholic, Sunni Moslem and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Khattar's district here is so homogeneous that there are only
two sets of voting rooms: Greek Orthodox and, he said,
``assorted.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafik Hariri, the multibillionaire builder trying to make a
comeback as prime minister, is locked in a bitter struggle with
President Emile Lahoud, who has unleashed much of the government's
power against him, including hours of ill-supported accusations and
ridicule on state television.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict has become so intense in recent days that the new
Syrian President, Bashar Assad, has summoned leading Lebanese
political leaders to Damascus, and Syria's long effective regent in
Lebanon, Maj. Gen Ghazi Kanaan, has been meeting with them here in
an effort to restore calm.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's voting, 63 of the Parliament's 128 seats were at
stake in three districts: Northern Lebanon, largely Christian, but
with a big Sunni Moslem population in Tripoli; the Metn, the
mountains north and east of Beirut that are the Christian
heartland; and the Chouf, traditional home of the Druze. Beirut,
and the largely Shi'ite areas of the Bekaa Valley and southern
Lebanon, vote next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Taif agreement of 1989, which helped end the bloody
15-year civil war in which some 150,000 people died and much of the
country was destroyed, the president is to name the prime minister
supported by blocks forming a simple majority in Parliament after
``binding negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   While much of the voting seemed to go smoothly, there were
troubles throughout the day in Bourj Hammoud, an Armenian ghetto
near the port long dominated by its ethnic Tashnak Party, which is
supporting Murr. In a rare move, Lahoud's opposition slate put up a
candidate for an Armenian Orthodox seat in the Metn district
usually held by Tashnak.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition candidate, Raffi Madoyan, was attacked and beaten
twice during the day by Tashnak supporters, and local television
cameramen filmed men smashing windows in his fleeing car with
clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Lahoud's political adviser, Joe Bahout, said the opposition had
hoped to pick up between 8,000 and 10,000 votes in Bourj Hammoud
and was worried that Tashnak supporters were ``trying to create a
panic by physical violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the morning in Bourj Hammoud, an opposition poll
watcher, Wassim Lahoud, stood in frustration outside a polling
place at the Mar Youssef church, complaining that his crew had not
been given their proper credentials to go inside, and that Murr's
supporters had illegally set up a computer to track voters inside
another polling station. Indeed the computer operation so enraged
the opposition that one of its candidates, former Information
Minister Michel Samaha, stormed into the municipal building and
turned the table over.
</P>
<P>
   Murr turned up at that polling station toward midday in a
caravan of police vehicles, greeted warmly by all the election
workers inside with hugs, handshakes and a round of applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look around,'' he replied in French when asked about charges
of vote rigging. ``Do you see anyone who is pressuring?''
</P>
<P>
   By late afternoon, scores of blue-shirted Murr campaign workers
had set up their computer operation again on a series of tables
under a white sun umbrella inside the police lines and were busily
checking the voters in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-00 1748EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000827.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3465 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-2     08-27 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN-BACKED LEADER OF CHECHNYA BATTLES REBELS, AND THEIR
DISTRUST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TSENTORA-YURT, Russia _ The Russian-appointed leader of Chechnya
gestured toward the crowd that had gathered to wish him a happy
birthday at his heavily guarded home here in Chechnya. Some, he
noted dryly, could well be rebel agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are everywhere and nowhere,'' Akhmed Kadyrov said with a
shrug. ``Some of them might even be among these people.''
</P>
<P>
   Kadyrov ought to know. He has already survived several
assassination attempts, including one two months ago, which was
averted when a huge bomb was discovered along the road 100 yards
from his house. Last year, a bomb that was apparently intended for
Kadyrov killed five of his relatives.
</P>
<P>
   It is just another week in Chechnya, a battered, dispirited but
proud land that continues to present Russia's gravest security
challenge. A year after Russian troops poured into Chechnya, the
breakaway republic is no longer the scene of major Russian
artillery barrages and pitched battles involving thousands of
soldiers against rebels who are seeking an independent republic.
</P>
<P>
   But the war has not gone away. Russian casualties mount every
week as the fighting has shifted from large-scale assaults to
skirmishing and ambushes that have turned Chechnya into a nasty
quagmire for the Russian president, Vladimir V. Putin, and his top
generals.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone agrees that Russian firepower alone cannot bring
an end to the fighting and that a political solution is necessary.
That is where Kadyrov is supposed to come in, but so far a
resolution of the conflict seems as distant as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war can't be ended by military means,'' Kadyrov said. ``We
Chechens have to stop it ourselves. If we can't, the war will go on
for 10 or 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   In the baking summer heat, Chechnya often seems deceptively
quiet. There is a weary routine about the searches at the Russian
checkpoints, the noisy helicopter flights to and from the Russian
strongholds and the bustle at Chechen marketplaces.
</P>
<P>
   Even a good day, however, can be grim and frighteningly
unpredictable. Grozny, Chechnya's nominal capital and a ruin of a
city, still lacks gas, electricity and any visible efforts at
restoration. Only a few thousand people still seem to live there,
but now they include rebels who have managed to sneak back into the
city.
</P>
<P>
   They shoot at the Russian checkpoints at night, prompting noisy
firefights that residents say keep them awake. Squads of
Kalashnikov-bearing Russian soldiers move past the kiosks and
makeshift shops but do not linger long. In one brazen attack last
week, two Russian soldiers were shot to death at point-blank range
while they were shopping in Grozny's central market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's becoming more and more dangerous,'' said Yuri Vasilkov, a
19-year-old draftee from the southern Russian town of Taganrog who
was manning a Grozny checkpoint. ``A major attack could come at any
time _ tonight, tomorrow, now.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Russian generals contend that this is nothing to
worry about. The guerrilla attacks, they insist, are just the final
phase of a terrible war that is all but won. The Russian military,
in fact, has already made plans to station a permanent garrison in
Chechnya to secure the peace.
</P>
<P>
   It consists primarily of the army's 42nd Division, a new unit
whose members are being sent to four strategic locations. With
15,000 members, the unit is larger and better equipped than most.
But at Borzoy, a mountain village that sits astride a potential
rebel supply corridor to Georgia, half of the division's troops are
young conscripts with no previous experience in Chechnya. The other
half are ``kontraktniki,'' essentially mercenaries who often have
some military experience and fight for pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is peace,'' insists Andrei Fyodorov, the 39-year-old
colonel who commands the Borzoy detachment. ``The situation is
under control.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Russian officers, however, have a dimmer view. They say
the rebels may only have several thousand full-time fighters
compared with the approximately 80,000 soldiers and policemen the
Kremlin has sent to Chechnya, but the rebels have also adapted
their tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of mounting large and costly attacks against major
Russian bases and troop concentrations, the rebels plant mines, set
off bombs and try to pick off small groups of Russian soldiers _
pinprick attacks that are slowly bleeding Russian forces.
</P>
<P>
   According to official statistics, 17 Russian troops were killed
and 52 wounded the week of Aug. 13, a tranquil week by Chechnya
standards. All told, more than 2,500 Russian fighters have been
killed and 7,500 wounded in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have also sought to infiltrate village
administrations throughout Chechnya, hoping to gain control of food
and other supplies so they can divert them to their fighters in the
woods and mountains. When Russian officials uncovered a rebel camp
last month in the Shatoy mountain region, they discovered that it
was filled with goods sent to aid the civilian population.
</P>
<P>
   Village officials who resist the rebels are often the targets of
attacks, along with their relatives. In two weeks this month, local
officials in Meskety, Nozhay-Yurt and Urus-Martan were attacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we have cases where local administrations have been
infiltrated,'' Kadyrov said. ``We are setting up a new commission
now to check all of the officials in Chechnya, to find out who is
charge of what and check all aspects of what they are doing.`
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, nobody knows the difficulty of controlling Chechnya
better than Kadyrov, the 49-year-old Chechen whom Putin appointed
two months ago to administer the republic. Kadyrov is the first
Chechen leader to be installed by Moscow since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   A former Muslim cleric, Kadyrov opposed the Russians during the
first Chechen war, from 1994 to 1996, a rout against Russia that
gave Chechnya de facto independence. Kadyrov supported Aslan
Maskhadov, the Chechen commander who became the first president of
the breakaway republic after that war.
</P>
<P>
   But after Islamic militants based in Chechnya invaded
neighboring Dagestan and Russian troops responded by invading
Chechnya, Kadyrov broke with Maskhadov and decided to work with the
Russians. Each has denounced the other as a traitor, dimming the
already bleak prospect for negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Kadyrov appeared relaxed at his birthday celebration last
Wednesday with his family and Chechen officials, even as
machine-gun-toting bodyguards stood by, chanting Muslim prayers
before feasting on lamb, potatoes and soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not matter if we are part of Russia or independent,''
Kadyrov said. ``What does a man really need? He needs a permanent
job and salary. And he needs to be able to leave his house safely
to go to work and to come back safely in the evening. That is what
freedom means. And where should we go? We are surrounded by
Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   To encourage a political solution, he has been negotiating with
several field commanders, including Ruslan Gelayev. Several minor
rebel leaders have come over to his side. But Kadyrov says he will
never make a deal with Shamil Basayev or the rebel chief known as
Khattab, two of the best-known rebel commanders, or with Maskhadov.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics doubt that Kadyrov will be able to establish his
authority in Chechnya. They note that he cannot even control Bislan
Gantamirov, a former mayor of Grozny who was jailed for
embezzlement and released by the Russians so that he could fight on
their side. Unlike Kadyrov, Gantamirov controls a Chechen militia,
and he has especially close ties with much of the Russian military.
</P>
<P>
   When Kadyrov fired some local officials loyal to Gantamirov, the
former Grozny mayor led a band of his men to Gudermes, the
administrative capital of Chechnya and the site of Kadyrov's
government headquarters. It was a blunt show of force, and
relations between the two pro-Moscow Chechens are still frosty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kadyrov does not have the means to control the situation
inside the Chechen republic,'' said Malik Saidullayev, a Chechen
businessman and a rival.
</P>
<P>
   Kadyrov asserts that he can prevail. He plans to attend a
religious conference in the United States and, making use of his
common ground with them as a former cleric, ask the Arab conference
members not to provide the financial support that has been sent to
the rebels from Muslims around the world.
</P>
<P>
   His hardest task, however, is to convince the Chechen people
that they have more to gain by accepting Russian control over their
republic and putting down their guns. For all the Russian
firepower, he said, the fighting will not end until ordinary
Chechens stop giving aid and sanctuary to the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are hiding them,'' Kadyrov said. ``We Chechens, not
Kadyrov. We give them shelter. We feed them. If we closed all the
doors to them, then everyone would see them. This is the only way
to solve this problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-00 1749EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000827.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3467 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-R-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART     08-27 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN-BACKED LEADER OF CHECHNYA BATTLES REBELS, AND THEIR
DISTRUST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add photos to art advisory.)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 5,6 and locator map are being sent to NYT
photo/graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights
by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
