   But after Islamic militants based in Chechnya invaded
neighboring Dagestan and Russian troops responded by invading
Chechnya, Kadyrov broke with Maskhadov and decided to work with the
Russians. Each has denounced the other as a traitor, dimming the
already bleak prospect for negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Kadyrov appeared relaxed at his birthday celebration last
Wednesday with his family and Chechen officials, even as
machine-gun-toting bodyguards stood by, chanting Muslim prayers
before feasting on lamb, potatoes and soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not matter if we are part of Russia or independent,''
Kadyrov said. ``What does a man really need? He needs a permanent
job and salary. And he needs to be able to leave his house safely
to go to work and to come back safely in the evening. That is what
freedom means. And where should we go? We are surrounded by
Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   To encourage a political solution, he has been negotiating with
several field commanders, including Ruslan Gelayev. Several minor
rebel leaders have come over to his side. But Kadyrov says he will
never make a deal with Shamil Basayev or the rebel chief known as
Khattab, two of the best-known rebel commanders, or with Maskhadov.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics doubt that Kadyrov will be able to establish his
authority in Chechnya. They note that he cannot even control Bislan
Gantamirov, a former mayor of Grozny who was jailed for
embezzlement and released by the Russians so that he could fight on
their side. Unlike Kadyrov, Gantamirov controls a Chechen militia,
and he has especially close ties with much of the Russian military.
</P>
<P>
   When Kadyrov fired some local officials loyal to Gantamirov, the
former Grozny mayor led a band of his men to Gudermes, the
administrative capital of Chechnya and the site of Kadyrov's
government headquarters. It was a blunt show of force, and
relations between the two pro-Moscow Chechens are still frosty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kadyrov does not have the means to control the situation
inside the Chechen republic,'' said Malik Saidullayev, a Chechen
businessman and a rival.
</P>
<P>
   Kadyrov asserts that he can prevail. He plans to attend a
religious conference in the United States and, making use of his
common ground with them as a former cleric, ask the Arab conference
members not to provide the financial support that has been sent to
the rebels from Muslims around the world.
</P>
<P>
   His hardest task, however, is to convince the Chechen people
that they have more to gain by accepting Russian control over their
republic and putting down their guns. For all the Russian
firepower, he said, the fighting will not end until ordinary
Chechens stop giving aid and sanctuary to the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are hiding them,'' Kadyrov said. ``We Chechens, not
Kadyrov. We give them shelter. We feed them. If we closed all the
doors to them, then everyone would see them. This is the only way
to solve this problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
