<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BASH-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BASH': MONOLOGUES THAT REVEAL THE EVIL AND THE BANAL 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By JULIE SALAMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though Neil LaBute's ``Bash: Latter-Day Plays'' wasn't written
originally for television, it translates so well it could have
been. The intimacy of this trilogy of one-act monologues, designed
as sparely as a SoHo dress store, seems made for television, and
not just because one of the actors is Ally McBeal (aka Calista
Flockhart). The characters spill their secrets in a confessional
rush, like guests on a talk show.
</P>
<P>
   But the familiarity is deceptive, which simply adds another
layer to LaBute's insistent investigation of the nastiness lurking
beneath the most placid exteriors. As a filmmaker (``In the Company
of Men'') and a playwright, he specializes in exhuming the worm
within. Evil isn't always interesting, he insists. It exists in the
blandest of men and women. When you've stepped into LaBute's
fantasy neighborhood, you'd better watch out for the apple-cheeked
boy next door. He might go berserk and kill you.
</P>
<P>
   In each of these one-act confessionals LaBute has his characters
inflict a gory surprise on the audience that feels like a betrayal,
as it should, given his world view. People may want to be good, he
implies, but they will be bad.
</P>
<P>
   LaBute understands that words matter, especially in a work that
relies almost entirely on storytelling, not on dialogue or action.
He's tuned in to the strangely poetic rhythms in everyday speech
and the telling details of workaday life. When one of his
characters recalls her seduction and subsequent pregnancy at 13 by
her schoolteacher, she says: ``I went home with our baby inside me
and watched `Hogan's Heroes' on TV. Like I do every afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he misses a beat and contrives poetry where prose
would do. A callow character who fumbles trying to remember
contemporaries of F. Scott Fitzgerald, as well as proper grammar,
says of a man he's brutalized, ``We feasted on him like carrion and
left nothing but bones.'' You feel like flossing after taking in a
mouthful like that, from a man like that.
</P>
<P>
   LaBute has shrewdly directed this film version of his play
(which was directed for the theater by Joe Mantello) from a live
performance, using the camera mainly to emphasize the confidential
feeling the stark stage setting provides. Not surprisingly the
camera doesn't fail Flockhart, who appears in two of the pieces.
She's a giddy young woman in ``A Gaggle of Saints,'' about two
Boston College sweethearts recalling an unforgettable weekend in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Rudd, as her cute boyfriend, carries the drama in this
story, about a superficially good-natured frat boy whose banality
is laced with a lust for violence. He's so cocky and complacent
that he feels it's his birthright to attack anyone who disturbs his
vision of how things should be. Though he does nothing more than
narrow his eyes as he casually recalls his terrible crime, Rudd
seems transformed as he reveals his character's ugly soul.
Flockhart on the other hand remains innocent and chipper in her
pretty evening dress: more or less a corsage, a lovely, retro
adornment.
</P>
<P>
   But in ``Medea Redux'' her skill and bravery as an actress
emerge front and center in the role of the woman who as a girl was
impregnated and then abandoned by her teacher. Stringy-haired and
red-eyed, appearing even frailer than usual, she seems to be
clutching at language for dear life _ her character has already
lost her grip on sanity _ as she tells her story to a tape recorder
at a police station.
</P>
<P>
   The last ``bash,'' ``Iphigenia in Orem,'' is the least
convincing, through no fault of Ron Eldard's; he perfectly relays
the cautious banter of the bland businessman, a man who describes
himself as ``slightly above'' average. Here, too, LaBute captures
the incongruities in human behavior. When the businessman, whose
child suffocated under a blanket, explains that he and his wife ate
pizza afterward, he realizes how absurd it seems. But even when
tragedy strikes, he observes, you have to eat. LaBute recognizes
that the terrible and the mundane are inextricably linked.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the unexpected turns in the first two acts, however, the
chilling surprise here feels contrived. When the evil emerges from
circumstance (in ``Medea'') or character (in ``Gaggle''), it's
disturbing and calls up basic questions of morality and human
resilience. LaBute is a Mormon, and these works carry crosscurrents
of religious devotion and hypocrisy. But the events in the third
piece seem grounded only in the sour assumption that betrayal and
the raw desire for redress may be the only traits built into the
human genome. A grim conclusion, but spoken well.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `BASH: LATTER-DAY PLAYS'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. ET Monday on Showtime
</P>
<P>
   Directed for television by Neil LaBute; directed for the stage
by Joe Mantello; Stephen Pevner, executive producer; produced by
John Purdy; produced for the stage by Pevner and Canon Theatricals;
edited by Joel Plotch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
