<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3471 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-R2-LEBANON-VOTE-ART-N     08-27 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R2-LEBANON-VOTE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TENSE POWER STRUGGLE SPILLS OVER INTO LEBANON ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(REPEATING second time to add photo note)  (ART ADV:  Photos NYT8 and NYT9  and a  map  are being sent to NYT
photo clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOHN KIFNER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONSOURIEH, Lebanon _ Confident as an old-time Chicago ward
boss, Walid Khatter, Interior Minister Michel Murr's man in this
Greek Orthodox village, stood in the doorway of his polling station
Sunday afternoon and predicted the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have around 1,000 voters in this district. There will be
about 800 for the Michel Murr ticket,'' he said, adding
dismissively, ``about 200 for the others.''
</P>
<P>
   How could he be so sure? a visitor asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, we know,'' he said with a shrug and a grin, opening a hand
bedecked with three huge gold rings to show a stack of palm cards
listing Murr's slate of candidates. An aide materialized from the
crush of more than a dozen Murr campaign workers _ the whole area
around the polling station was festooned with portraits of Murr _
with numbers scratched on a sheet of paper and nodded assent.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by reminders of their tribal politics, Lebanese went
to the polls on Sunday in the beginning of a two-stage
parliamentary election overshadowed by Syrian dominance and a
bitter struggle between the current government and its critics.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the Christian heartland of Mt. Lebanon, among the
suburban sprawl running up the mountains from Beirut, the focus was
on the battle between a slate headed by the powerful Murr, one of
Syria's biggest supporters, and an opposition slate headed by
Nassib Lahoud, a wealthy businessman and former ambassador to the
United States, who is a cousin of the president, but nonetheless a
critic.
</P>
<P>
   Murr has come under fierce criticism from the opposition because
of his multiple roles as a candidate running for re-election, a
staunch supporter of the government, and ultimately the man in
charge of running the elections. With his government post, he
controls police and internal security forces, the granting or
withholding of various licenses and patronage over a huge number of
public employees.
</P>
<P>
   His power was evident on Sunday. Entrances to many of the
polling places were surrounded by election workers in baby blue
T-shirts and baseball hats. The Arabic legend on the T-shirts read
simply: ``Michel Murr.''
</P>
<P>
   Every seat in Parliament is assigned to one of the country's 17
officially recognized religions, minutely derived from a census
taken in 1932. (There has never been one since for fear of
political upset.) In the voting on Sunday, citizens went into
separate rooms in the polling places, divided both by men and women
and by each religious sect in a district: Maronite Catholic,
Armenian Catholic, Sunni Moslem and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Khattar's district here is so homogeneous that there are only
two sets of voting rooms: Greek Orthodox and, he said,
``assorted.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafik Hariri, the multibillionaire builder trying to make a
comeback as prime minister, is locked in a bitter struggle with
President Emile Lahoud, who has unleashed much of the government's
power against him, including hours of ill-supported accusations and
ridicule on state television.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict has become so intense in recent days that the new
Syrian President, Bashar Assad, has summoned leading Lebanese
political leaders to Damascus, and Syria's long effective regent in
Lebanon, Maj. Gen Ghazi Kanaan, has been meeting with them here in
an effort to restore calm.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's voting, 63 of the Parliament's 128 seats were at
stake in three districts: Northern Lebanon, largely Christian, but
with a big Sunni Moslem population in Tripoli; the Metn, the
mountains north and east of Beirut that are the Christian
heartland; and the Chouf, traditional home of the Druze. Beirut,
and the largely Shi'ite areas of the Bekaa Valley and southern
Lebanon, vote next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Taif agreement of 1989, which helped end the bloody
15-year civil war in which some 150,000 people died and much of the
country was destroyed, the president is to name the prime minister
supported by blocks forming a simple majority in Parliament after
``binding negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   While much of the voting seemed to go smoothly, there were
troubles throughout the day in Bourj Hammoud, an Armenian ghetto
near the port long dominated by its ethnic Tashnak Party, which is
supporting Murr. In a rare move, Lahoud's opposition slate put up a
candidate for an Armenian Orthodox seat in the Metn district
usually held by Tashnak.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition candidate, Raffi Madoyan, was attacked and beaten
twice during the day by Tashnak supporters, and local television
cameramen filmed men smashing windows in his fleeing car with
clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Lahoud's political adviser, Joe Bahout, said the opposition had
hoped to pick up between 8,000 and 10,000 votes in Bourj Hammoud
and was worried that Tashnak supporters were ``trying to create a
panic by physical violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the morning in Bourj Hammoud, an opposition poll
watcher, Wassim Lahoud, stood in frustration outside a polling
place at the Mar Youssef church, complaining that his crew had not
been given their proper credentials to go inside, and that Murr's
supporters had illegally set up a computer to track voters inside
another polling station. Indeed the computer operation so enraged
the opposition that one of its candidates, former Information
Minister Michel Samaha, stormed into the municipal building and
turned the table over.
</P>
<P>
   Murr turned up at that polling station toward midday in a
caravan of police vehicles, greeted warmly by all the election
workers inside with hugs, handshakes and a round of applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look around,'' he replied in French when asked about charges
of vote rigging. ``Do you see anyone who is pressuring?''
</P>
<P>
   By late afternoon, scores of blue-shirted Murr campaign workers
had set up their computer operation again on a series of tables
under a white sun umbrella inside the police lines and were busily
checking the voters in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
