<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCK-EXCHANGE-BID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEDISH BID FOR LONDON STOCK EXCHANGE IS EXPECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE KAPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ OM Gruppen, which runs the Stockholm stock exchange, is
expected to make a formal offer, which could include a hostile bid,
for the London Stock Exchange, which rejected an informal 800
million pounds ($1.18 billion) proposal last week, executives close
to the discussions said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The bid would come just weeks before a shareholder vote on the
proposed merger between the London and Frankfurt stock exchanges,
which, along with an alliance with the Nasdaq stock market, would
create a pan-European powerhouse with a 24-hour global market.
</P>
<P>
   The Swedish overture also revived interest from Euronext _ a
combination of the Amsterdam, Brussels and Paris exchanges _ which
had approached the London exchange about a link-up last spring but
was rebuffed. The details of its proposal were never made public to
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, OM Guppen offered 7 pounds ($10.30) in cash and 20
pounds ($29.50) worth of new OM stock for the London exchange,
which amounted to 15 percent more than the closing price of 23.50
pounds for the exchange's shares on Friday. A formal proposal is
expected to be roughly the same amount but would ``include more
specific numbers,'' said the executives close to the talks.
</P>
<P>
   With a market value of 2.6 billion pounds, OM shares are trading
at a richly valued 80 times trailing earnings, which leads some
analysts to worry that the offer consists mainly of ``inflated
paper.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The OM proposal was rejected out of hand because it didn't
make any sense commercially or financially,'' an executive close to
the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   The jostling for the London exchange underscores the problems
that old-school European exchanges are facing as they merge to
offer single-currency trading and to compete better with
fast-growing electronic exchanges. Even before the Swedish bid, it
was unclear whether the London and German partnership would win the
75 percent shareholder approval needed to push the deal through as
regulatory and operational questions have mounted. Shareholders are
expected to vote on the deal on Sept. 14.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the London exchange said there were no plans to
delay the vote in light of the Swedish bid.
</P>
<P>
   The London Stock Exchange is governed by the British takeover
panel, which could postpone the vote to allow shareholders more
time to assess the new information. Some shareholders have already
called for a delay.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to merge ``should be delayed so that all the
shareholders of the L.S.E. have information on the various
options,'' said Angela Knight, chief executive of Britain's
Association of Private Client Investment Managers and Stockbrokers.
</P>
<P>
   In its overtures to Frankfurt, the London stock exchange is
hoping to gain scale and influence, and it thinks the Stockholm
exchange would bring it less of both.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking to provide a strong European presence with
access to liquidity in a wide range of equities, which merging with
Germany would do,'' said the spokesman for the London exchange.
``Stockholm doesn't provide us with European consolidation.''
</P>
<P>
   The merger of the London and Frankfurt exchanges into iX, for
International Exchange, would control 53 percent of European equity
trading with a combined value of $4.29 trillion. That would make iX
the largest European exchange, ahead of Euronext, based in Paris,
which will trade stocks valued at $2.2 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Stockholm exchange has been aggressive and growing
quickly _ it is about to introduce an online system called Jiway in
a deal with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter _ it still controls only 5
percent of the European equity market. And its derivatives
operation, through the London-based OMLX, pales in comparison to
the Frankfurt exchange's Eurex, which is the world's largest market
for trading derivatives, the complex financial contracts whose
values are based on underlying assets like stocks, bonds,
commodities and currencies.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the Swedish interest, the iX merger was by no means
guaranteed. Stockbrokers and shareholders have questioned the
proposed operations of the new exchange, a concern echoed by the
Financial Services Authority of Britain and the Federal Securities
Trading Security Authority of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current terms of the merger, high growth stocks would
be traded under the rules laid out by Frankfurt, where the Neue
Market has different listing requirements than does Britain's
Alternative Investment Market.
</P>
<P>
   Blue-chip stocks will follow British guidelines, which require
immediate reporting of most large trades to the exchange, a
guideline not required in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Other issues include the cost of new technology. The merged
entity would use Germany's Xetra trading system. The London
exchange has said it will contribute 8 million pounds to help its
members cover the conversion costs, but it remains unclear whether
that amount will be sufficient, or whether any savings can be
derived from the new system. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-00 1816EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
