<DOCNO> NYT20000827.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3478 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-R-CLINTON-AFRICA-ART-     08-27 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CLINTON-AFRICA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES NIGERIA TO ACT ON AIDS AND ITS PREVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add map note)  (ART ADV: map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABUJA, Nigeria _ Seeking to breaking down the taboos shrouding a
disease that has devastated Africa, President Clinton on Sunday
urged Nigerians to show the same resolve they displayed in enduring
decades of dictatorship in confronting what he called the
``tyranny'' of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, standing beside a man infected with the same virus that
afflicts some 24 million Africans and has become the continent's
leading killer, applauded Nigeria's efforts to control the spread
of AIDS. But he offered a blunt reminder to Africans that AIDS is
preventable _ if people will only speak frankly about how it is
spread, and then act.
</P>
<P>
   ``AIDS is 100 percent preventable _ if we are willing to deal
with it openly and honestly,'' Clinton said. ``In every country, in
any culture, it is difficult, painful, at the very least,
embarrassing to talk about the issues involved with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``But is it harder to talk about these things than to watch a
child die of AIDS who could have lived if the rest of us had done
our part?'' the president added. ``Is it harder to talk about than
to comfort a child whose mother has died? We have to break the
silence about how this disease spreads and how to prevent it. And
we need to fight AIDS, not people with AIDS.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's remarks presented a bold challenge, not only to
Nigerians but to all in Africa, where health workers and experts
have lamented that the social stigma surrounding the disease and an
absence of public education and discussion of its dangers and
impact have contributed greatly to the spread of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced some increased aid for Nigeria's fight _ $20
million to control the spread of AIDS, malaria and polio, and a
plan to include AIDS education as part of the military training
that U.S. troops are giving to Nigerian peacekeepers headed to
nearby Sierra Leone, which has been ravaged by civil war.
</P>
<P>
   He told the audience of young people, religious leaders and
women leaders that Nigerians, despite the much-heralded
introduction of civilian rule last year, will never be free until
they bring infectious diseases under control. An estimated 5.4
percent of Nigeria's population of 114 million _ about 2.6 million
people _ are currently infected with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am amazed at the courage of the people of Nigeria in
struggling against the oppression that you endured for too long
until you got your democracy,'' Clinton said. ``I urge you now to
show that same kind of courage to beat the tyranny of this disease
so you can keep your democracy alive for all the children of
Nigeria and their future.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials, frustrated by the lack of action by some African
governments, have praised Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo for
making the fight against AIDS a priority. But the Nigerian
president stressed Sunday that it was a disease that his country
could not battle alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a disease you can say if you eradicate it in Nigeria
it is eradicated for good,'' said Obasanjo. ``Those from Nigeria
who go outside and have sexual relations with those who have
HIV-AIDS or have blood transfusions with them will bring it back.
We don't see it as a Nigerian disease. We see it as a world disease
that is ravaging Africa most.''
</P>
<P>
   Africans have reacted coolly to the United States' offer of $1
billion in annual loans to finance the purchase of anti-AIDS drugs
in sub-Saharan Africa, suggesting that the approach would add to
countries' already heavy debt burden of some $32 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Clinton's two-day visit here, Obasanjo has repeatedly
raised the issue of debt relief, encouraging the wealthy nations of
the world to forgive the large sums amassed by previous African
rulers.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo, elected 15 months ago as part of Nigeria's transition
to democracy, did not directly address the U.S. AIDS plan. But in
toasting Clinton at a state dinner on Saturday night, he made a
plea for financial relief from the United States and other wealthy
nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that we cannot achieve our desire for economic
development if we continue to bleed from the gushing wounds of an
ever-penetrating debt repayment lance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in addressing business leaders Sunday, said that past
leaders of Nigeria _ a country that has suffered under callous and
corrupt dictators for most of its modern history _ had squandered
the country's riches and that leaders now must be careful to focus
any debt relief on improving the lives of its people.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Sunday, Clinton toured a small African village, walking
through muddy paths past huts that were hooked up to electricity
only month ago. Guided by Mohammedu Baba, the chief of the village,
Ushafa, Clinton entered a small medical clinic that had been
stocked with supplies by the State Department just the day before.
</P>
<P>
   A clinic worker told the president that the clinic had treated
234 cases of malaria this year. There are no HIV cases, villagers
said, although nearby villages have cases and surrounded urban
areas are heavily affected.
</P>
<P>
   The assistance Clinton announced Sunday included $2 million in
the current budget to produce insecticide-treated bed nets to keep
malaria-infected mosquitoes at bay, as well as $9 million in new
money to battle polio and $10 million more to assist Nigeria's AIDS
fight. The White House has requested a $100 million increase, to
$342 million, in international AIDS financing in the 2001 fiscal
year budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just Nigeria's fight, or Africa's fight,'' Clinton
said. ``It is America's fight and the world's fight too.'' The
president's remarks heartened John Ibekwe, who heads an
organization in Nigeria for people living with AIDS. ``With you as
an advocate on our side, governments in Africa will do more than
they are doing,'' Ibekwe said in introducing the president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who leaves for Tanzania on Monday for an update from
former South African President Nelson Mandela on the Burundi peace
talks, began his day at a Baptist church in Abuja, where he heard
the Rev. Israel Akanji preach on the parable of the good Samaritan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robbers have come. Bandits have come. We have been left
wounded, bleeding and dying,'' Akanji said of his country's
struggles against its own leaders. ``Is there a good Samaritan
passing by?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
