<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3481 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LIVER-RECIPIENT0828-C     08-27 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVER-RECIPIENT0828-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlantan's gift of life proves temporary, but love endures
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It doesn't seem a fair exchange _ giving a healthy
liver and receiving a broken heart. But that was the painful price
for Curt Bludworth.
</P>
<P>
   On July 29, Bludworth said his goodbyes over the telephone to
Raymond Munoz, the California man who had gone from stranger to
everlasting friend when a liver transplant linked them on May 12.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz died of respiratory failure at the University of Southern
California Hospital. He was 54.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was devastated,'' said Bludworth, 33, of Atlanta. ``It's
been a very tough few weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Munoz had received about 60 percent of Bludworth's liver in what
was called the nation's first ``at-large'' liver donation,
involving two people who were not related and not connected by
community.
</P>
<P>
   Bludworth offered to donate part of his liver to a severely ill
patient after reading about the success of using living donors for
liver transplants. This is possible because the liver, the only
internal organ that regenerates, grows back in both the donor and
recipient. Although Bludworth and the Munoz family both welcomed
media coverage following the transplant, when the situation took a
turn for the worse, they sought privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't face the press,'' Bludworth said. ``I don't want
this to be about me with people saying, `I feel so badly for Curt.
Look at all he went through and what happened in the end.' I want
the focus on Ray. He suffered a lot and it breaks my heart that he
suffered so much.'' The transplant itself was considered a success,
and Munoz showed no signs of rejecting the organ. But he needed a
second surgery to repair a leaking bile duct. After that his
strength started faltering, and he contracted pneumonia from an
unknown infection, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, 562 liver transplants from living donors
have been performed. Among recipients, 85 percent are still alive
one year after the transplant, according to the United Network of
Organ Sharing. At least one donor, and possibly two, have died.
Among the 15 adult living-donor liver transplants performed at USC,
three recipients, and no donors, have died.
</P>
<P>
   Liver transplants using live donors are generally more
successful than those using cadaver organs because the organs are
healthier and doctors have flexibility in the timing of the
transplant, explained Dr. Reda Sobky of the Hepatitis C Global
Foundation. The majority of living-donor transplants are between
family members.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz' liver actually held up best of all his organs as
infection took hold in his weakened body. ``It was ironic,''
Bludworth said. ``The liver was the only thing functioning when he
died. It was maddening, because the liver transplant itself was
perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Suffering from hepatitis C and cirrhosis of the liver, Munoz was
running out of time early this year. For two years, he never went
anywhere without his pager, his link to USC's transplant center.
The beeper to signal a donor never went off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still consider Curt our angel,'' said Carmen Munoz, Ray's
wife. ``The only hope Ray had was that beeper in his hand. And
then, Curt came out of nowhere and gave us Ray back.''
</P>
<P>
   After the transplant, Munoz felt and saw an immediate
difference. ``Look at my hands,'' he said at the time. ``Look how
smooth my skin got overnight. I can't believe how good I feel. It's
something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His spirits were always up, even toward the end,'' Carmen
Munoz said. ``I know Curt feels really bad. But I told him, `You
did give him life, Curt. The three months we had with him gives us
100 more memories.'''
</P>
<P>
   Carmen and Ray Munoz would have celebrated their 18th wedding
anniversary today. Bludworth served as an honorary pallbearer and
delivered a eulogy at the memorial service in Munoz' longtime
family church, Our Lady of Solitude in East Los Angeles. He told
the gathering of about 200 family and friends that he learned much
about Munoz while they recuperated. They took long walks around the
hospital floor, talking about their differences and similarities.
</P>
<P>
   Bludworth is a white, gay, upper-middle-class Republican who
drives a Mercedes, tools around on a retro Harley-Davidson
motorcycle and lives in a high-rise loft. Munoz, a
Mexican-American, was a working-class family man, a Democrat who
cherished his red Pontiac Trans-Am and never moved from the block
where he was born, off Cesar Chavez Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd only known him for three months, but I learned how much he
loved his family,'' Bludworth said. ``Every time he spoke of
Carmen, his eyes lit up. He loved his country and he loved his
church. All he wanted was the simple things for the rest of his
life. To be able to pick up his grandkids and not feel bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Munoz had worked for 28 years with the Los Angeles Police
Department as a civilian police officer. He also was a soldier in
Vietnam. At the funeral he had a police escort, and an honor guard
of war veterans stood vigil at the graveside. He was buried with
full military honors.
</P>
<P>
   Carmen Munoz gave Bludworth the crucifix that rested upon
Munoz's casket, a Catholic gesture usually reserved for family.
``Carmen and I are going to be friends the rest of our lives,''
Bludworth declared.
</P>
<P>
   Bludworth's recovery has gone well except for some numbing and
pain in his right arm, a lingering effect of having his arm propped
up and rib cage spread during surgery. The nerve damage is expected
to heal. He is back at work as a director of human relations for
Morrison Management Specialists.
</P>
<P>
   Bludworth is continuing with plans for a foundation that would
help people become living organ donors, a procedure that is being
used increasingly for liver and kidney failure. ``Even though this
didn't turn out the way we wanted it to, a lot of good has come out
of this that we may not know for years to come,'' Bludworth said.
</P>
<P>
   Carmen Munoz said she considers the transplant a success because
it is opening people's eyes to the need to become organ donors. ``I
told Curt, `Keep going with your dream. Go with your belief that
this type of transplant can help people. My husband was part of
your belief. Pay tribute to Ray with the foundation.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
