<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Monday, Aug. 28. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: 888-603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-AFRICA (Abuja, Nigeria) _ Seeking to breaking down the
taboos surrounding a disease that has devastated Africa, President
Clinton on Sunday urged Nigerians to show the same resolve they
displayed in enduring decades of dictatorship as they confront what
he called the ``tyranny'' of AIDS. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Tsenturi, Russia) _ A year after Russian troops
poured into the region, the breakaway republic is no longer the
scene of huge Russian artillery barrages and pitched battles
involving thousands of soldiers and rebels seeking an independent
republic. But the war has not gone away. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-RESERVES (Washington) _ A look at the status of the
military's reserve forces. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Undated) _ Campaigning with Gore. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   IOWA-IMMIG (Marshalltown, Iowa) _ No one would call Iowa a
melting pot. Nearly 96 percent white, this state can seem to have
more kinds of cows and corn than nationalities. But Iowa, which
hemorrhaged families during the 1980s farm crisis and has an
unemployment rate of only 2 percent, is proposing something no
other state has done: an all-out immigrant recruitment drive to
encourage foreigners to call Iowa home. The plan is to make Iowa an
``immigration enterprise zone,'' and the ideas range from seeking
an exemption to immigration quotas to urging companies to recruit
abroad. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-DONATE (New York) _ David Chang is at the center of a
widening federal inquiry into the possibility that New Jersey Sen.
Robert Torricelli's 1996 campaign staff may have been complicit in
Chang's illegal political donations _ something the senator
strongly denies. Lawyers familiar with the case say Chang has given
prosecutors information suggesting that Torricelli's aides
accounted improperly for some of his contributions, and at least
two dozen FBI agents have been added to the inquiry in recent
weeks. Chang himself is something of an enigma. As a businessman,
many of his former employees say, Chang generated all sorts of
ambitious schemes but almost no apparent profit. So where did his
`political' money come from? By Tim Golden and David Kocieniewski.
</P>
</TEXT>
