<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3496 &Cx1f; tth-z
r l BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      08-27 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREATS FROM SUMMERS PAST GET A NEW TWIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The highlight of breakfast _ at the site of another Montana
forest fire many summers ago _ was burnt toast. It was made edible
only by a thick application of strawberry jam.
</P>
<P>
   But that posed a problem. Every displaced hornet within 15 miles
had collected in or around a single, large jam pot at one end of
the chow line. Fear collided with hunger, generated by 13
consecutive hours on a fire line. So you grabbed a spoon, shoved it
carefully into the buzzing pot and while the hornets swarmed around
your hand and wrist, you closed your eyes and took a scoop.
</P>
<P>
   If you survived unstung, that piece of toast served as one of
the highlights of a Montana summer.
</P>
<P>
   As a kid my favorite holiday was Independence Day, which ran
from June 15 to Aug. 30, or as long as my personal stock of
firecrackers held out.
</P>
<P>
   And no, I never started a forest fire.
</P>
<P>
   In those days a daily check of baseball scores and statistics
provided another summertime bonus, although there were no major
league teams in Montana or in Seattle, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   Movies _ particularly those featuring Humphrey Bogart, John
Wayne or Errol Flynn _ provided excitement and relief from the
Montana summer sun.
</P>
<P>
   Forest fires and _ I suppose _ hornets around jam pots are still
a reality of summertime in the West.
</P>
<P>
   But a lot of other things have changed. This past Fourth of
July, I did not hear one firecracker between dawn and 10 p.m., and
I mourned for the lost joys of youth. My disappointment was
tempered by the fact that the skyrockets from our community show
were ignited less than 100 yards from my door.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago, major league baseball executives admitted
that the biggest draws in baseball were not Mark McGwire, Sammy
Sosa or Alex Rodriguez _ but free Beanie Babies.
</P>
<P>
   When I saw Bogart, Wayne or Flynn as I sought relief from the
summer sun, they were often swigging cold beer, martinis or gin and
tonics.
</P>
<P>
   The summertime ``drinks'' of choice today _ if I am to believe
the latest edition of Gourmet Magazine _ are homemade Popsicles
spiked with gin, rum or tequila.
</P>
<P>
   It is perhaps fortunate that Bogart, Wayne and Flynn will never
see film cowboys, private eyes or pirates humiliated by directors
and prop men who hand them Mango Daiquiri Ice Pops to suck during
tense showdowns under the unrelenting summer sun.
</P>
<P>
   Hard lemonade is another ``with-it'' drink and recalls a cowboy
movie starring Bob Hope, who walked into a tavern filled with
desperadoes and said, ``Gimme a lemonade.'' When the barkeeper gave
him a look, Hope quickly added, `` ... in a dirty glass!''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a dessert alternative that may look like a Betty Crocker
recipe. But I'm pretty sure she got it from Alice's mother.
</P>
<P>
   EDNA'S LEMON PUDDING
</P>
<P>
   SERVES SIX
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sifted flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   grated rind of one lemon
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 egg yolks, well beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   2 egg whites, stiffly beaten
</P>
<P>
   Sift the flour, sugar and salt into a mixing bowl. Stir in the
lemon rind, lemon juice and egg yolks. Add the milk and then
carefully stir in the beaten egg whites.
</P>
<P>
   Pour this mess into a casserole, set in a pan of water 1 inch
deep and then shove the pan into a 350 degree oven and bake about
50 minutes. Serve warm or cold, with or without whipped cream.
</P>
<P>
   If you can keep the hornets away, this is a fitting and filling
breakfast choice for the last weeks of summer.
</P>
<P>
   A PEACHY PANCAKE
</P>
<P>
   SERVES TWO TO FOUR
</P>
<P>
   2 cups fresh peeled and sliced peaches
</P>
<P>
   6 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   vanilla yogurt
</P>
<P>
   Moosh peaches, sugar and lemon juice together in a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In another bowl, beat the eggs until fluffy. Add the flour, milk
and salt. Continue to beat until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Plop the butter into a 10-inch pan. Shove the pan into a 400
degree oven for three minutes. Remove and immediately pour the
batter into the pan, over the melted butter. Bake 20 to 25 minutes
or until the pancake has pooched up all over.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from oven, pour the peach mixture into the center of the
pancake and sprinkle with nutmeg.
</P>
<P>
   Cut pancake into two or four portions and top with vanilla
yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   If you are cooking something on the barbecue, baked beans and
this cornbread dish are appropriate side dishes.
</P>
<P>
   DOUBLE-C CORN BREAD
</P>
<P>
   1 can (8 ounces) creamed corn
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups yellow corn meal
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, slightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon cayenne pepper (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups grated cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 can (4 ounces) chopped green chilies
</P>
<P>
   If you are allergic to spicy foods, eliminate the cayenne
pepper. Or, you could eat a slice of Wonder Bread, instead.
</P>
<P>
   Combine in a bowl all of the ingredients except the cheese and
chilies. Mix until smooth. Stir in the cheese and chilies, stir
again and then pour this mess into a lightly greased, 8-by-11
baking pan. Bake in a 375 degree oven for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serve your barbecue meal with soft lemonade ... in a dirty
glass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-00 1833EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
