<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3503 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INSIDE-MAGAZINE-MEDIA     08-27 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSIDE-MAGAZINE-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBUT OF INSIDE, THE MAGAZINE, RAISES STICKY QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX KUCZYNSKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To listen to the editors and publishers of the Web site
Inside.com and the magazine Industry Standard talk about the new
technology and entertainment magazine they are planning is to
imagine the excitement of ancient Mesopotamians discussing their
newly invented wheel.
</P>
<P>
   For the participants, it all seems so revolutionary.
</P>
<P>
   The weekly magazine will be titled Inside: The Business of
Entertainment, Media and Technology. It is supposed to make its
debut by year's end, focusing on the effect of digital technology
on the media and entertainment industries. The magazine will be
published in a partnership between Standard Media International,
the parent company of the two-year-old Internet business magazine
Industry Standard, and Powerful Media, the parent of Inside.com, an
entertainment industry news Web site that started in June and is
still trying to find its way.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hirschorn, the editor in chief of Inside.com, said last
week that the Internet economy and digital technology were about to
undergo the long-predicted melding and transformation that would
make the magazine necessary reading across several industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't think I'm a geek, but for example, I consider Napster to
be an epochal event,'' said Hirschorn, referring to the service
that lets people swap digital music files online with little regard
to copyrights. ``It is one of the things that will change the
Internet profoundly, forever. You have to accept the idea that
digital technology is going to transform each of the industries we
cover _ film, television, music, book publishing, magazines and
newspapers, and that is why this magazine is right, right now.''
</P>
<P>
   For all its nowness, the debut of Inside, the magazine, prompts
several questions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Why would Inside.com, which initially introduced a
mediacentric Web site with high hopes for its solo success, now
introduce a print magazine, which is costly to produce and
distribute?
</P>
<P>
   _ What does Standard Media International, which is a unit of the
International Data Group and is already busy with the ad-rich
Industry Standard and the introduction of a European edition, get
from the deal?
</P>
<P>
   _ Perhaps most significantly, is the crowded magazine field
ready for a weekly title about the way that digital technology is
affecting the entertainment industry?
</P>
<P>
   Inside.com, as a Web site, has not attracted the number of
subscriptions it had hoped for.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had anticipated 30,000 subscriptions, but we fell short of
that,'' said Deanna Brown, the chief executive of Powerful Media,
declining to be more specific. Brown said the cost of subscriptions
_ originally planned for $217 annually _ was not the problem, but
the Web site started late in recruiting subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   But visitors to the free portions of the Inside.com have started
to come. Its 160,000 visitors in June compared with 80,000 that
same month for a competitor, Variety.com, according to Media
Metrix. Inside's new partner, the Industry Standard, which has a
free circulation in print of 200,000, drew many more visitors to
its own Web site in June: 490,000 more than Inside.com did.
</P>
<P>
   If subscriptions are the goal for the executives at Inside.com,
maybe a print magazine makes sense, even if it is expensive to
produce. It can offer the chance to attract more people who would
rather not cruise the Web, but it can also serve as an advertising
billboard for those who might also be interested in the site. Also
worth considering is the fact that the publishers of the Industry
Standard _ whose weekly circulation is relatively minuscule
compared with, say, Business Week's 950,000 _ are not expecting a
sudden, enormous circulation for the new publication.
</P>
<P>
   The Industry Standard has had a heady advertising success, with
ad pages up 376 percent this year, according to Mediaweek magazine.
But some advertising executives are wary of the new venture's
narrow focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing that all aspects of the media are getting
niche-ier and niche-ier and more narrow and more vertical,'' said
David Verklin, chief executive of Carat North America, a media
services company. ``It's gotten to the point where I am starting to
question whether some of these magazines ought to be newsletters.''
</P>
<P>
   Verklin also questioned whether a Web site that had failed to
meet its subscription demands could spin off a successful print
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, then you can turn around and look at how well the
Industry Standard is doing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Industry Standard, for its part, will get equity in the new
venture in exchange for the use of the Standard's back-office
operations to produce and distribute the magazine _ although the
Inside.com side of the partnership plans to supply much of the
editorial content.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly there is a financial component to this equation,
because they are providing a lot of services,'' Brown said. She
would not disclose the terms.
</P>
<P>
   John Battelle, the chief executive of Standard Media, who was a
founding editor at an earlier digital-revolution manifesto, Wired
magazine, said he did business with people if he liked them and
their work, and if he thought they would make money for his
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``And should they succeed, we want a piece of that success,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown added that the team at the Industry Standard would also
gain entree to an exclusive world.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get an introduction to the inner sanctums of some of
these industries,'' she said. ``You know, we did not hire a bunch
of 22-year-olds out of dot-com school to run this company. We hired
seasoned executives who have been around the block, and who know
people.'' (Last week, the magazine hired its first editor on a
consulting basis: Sarah Bartlett, the former editor in chief of
Oxygen Media.)
</P>
<P>
   Even some competing magazine editors said last week that the
concept behind Inside was a solid one. Ned Desmond, the editor in
chief of E-Company Now, a new monthly magazine published by Time
Inc., said the intersection of technology and entertainment was a
growth area that deserved watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is certainly the case that there is a lot going on, as a
whole bunch of industries try to figure out digital technologies
and entertainment,'' he said. ``And we are fascinated by the same
subject.''
</P>
<P>
   E-Company Now's own rate base _ the circulation guaranteed to
advertisers _ began at 200,000 earlier this year and will be
325,000 in January, Desmond said.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and one final question:
</P>
<P>
   What of Kurt Andersen _ book author, media celebrity, Giorgio
Armani model in the current issue of W magazine, former
contributing editor at the New Yorker, former editor in chief of
New York magazine, and one of Powerful Media's founders?
</P>
<P>
   Andersen said he would supervise and offer advice to the
magazine for the next few months, but he planned to devote most of
his energies to ratcheting up Powerful Media's conference business.
The first conference will take place on the West Coast in May,
Andersen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things you are obliged to do in this business is
conferences,'' he said. ``There are a jillion Internet,
tech-specific conferences, but relatively few coming from the side
we come from, which is entertainment and content and the media. So
that will be a big part of what I do here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
