<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3506 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ALA-AUTO-ASSEMBLY-NYT     08-27 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALA-AUTO-ASSEMBLY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAIMLERCHRYSLER TO DOUBLE PRODUCTION IN ALABAMA, CONSULTANTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEITH BRADSHER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ DaimlerChrysler AG plans to announce on Monday that it
will nearly double production in Alabama, adding another assembly
line close to the site where it already builds M-Class sport
utility vehicles, auto industry officials and consultants said over
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercedes-Benz unit of DaimlerChrysler said on Friday that it
would hold a news conference on Monday in Tuscaloosa, Ala., the
nearest large city to its sport utility vehicle factory in Vance.
The planned construction project is the latest sign that Alabama's
auto industry is growing. Honda has just begun building a minivan
factory near Vance, too.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler declined to comment on what the factory would
produce. But auto industry consultants working for automakers and
auto parts suppliers said the company would make a so-called
crossover vehicle that would combine the features of a minivan and
the M-Class sport utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the planned Mercedes project represents a new assembly
plant or an expansion of the existing one will likely be the
subject of some debate. State officials in Alabama began praising
the project on Friday as a new plant. But there is no consensus
among automakers over whether adding a second assembly line
represents a second plant or an expansion of an existing one.
</P>
<P>
   Because the second assembly line will produce a vehicle similar
to the M-Class, it is likely to work closely with the existing
assembly plant and receive shipments of many of the same parts.
``I'd put it more in terms of expansion'' of the existing factory,
rather than a second, independent assembly plant, said an auto
industry manager who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The Birmingham (Ala.) News reported that Mercedes would receive
$150 million in state incentives for the new operation and that it
would create 1,750 jobs. Mercedes received $235 million in
incentives for the existing factory.
</P>
<P>
   It will be to DaimlerChrysler's advantage to portray the new
operation as an entire assembly plant to people in Alabama, where
the company has been seeking tax breaks and other assistance, while
portraying it in Michigan as an expansion of the existing
operation. The United Automobile Workers union, which represents
workers of the former Chrysler Corp., has been unable to organize
workers at the factory in Vance, and there is considerable
nervousness among workers and state officials in Michigan about the
pace of automakers' expansion in the South.
</P>
<P>
   The UAW declined Sunday to comment on DaimlerChrysler's plans.
Although DaimlerChrysler has publicly declared its neutrality on
the question of whether the current assembly plant should be
organized, union officials have complained over the last year that
the company has remained hostile. Local businesses in the Vance
area have tried to rally factory workers against the UAW, fearing
that if the union is successful, that might discourage further
investment in the area. The UAW has not insisted on an actual vote
at the factory on whether to unionize, fearing that it might lose.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Robinet, the director of forecast services at CSM
Worldwide Inc., a big auto production consulting firm based in
Northville, said over the weekend that Mercedes would change the
M-Class sport utility vehicle considerably several years from now
and then use the underbody from the new model to build a similar
vehicle at an adjacent site.
</P>
<P>
   The current M-Class uses a stiff, heavy underbody like that of a
pickup truck, which made it cheap to develop but also gives a bumpy
ride. Robinet said Mercedes would switch to a lighter, carlike
underbody for the next generation of M-Class vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers are increasingly combining the features of sport
utility vehicles with those of cars and minivans, using carlike
underbodies for better handling, fuel economy and safety. Examples
include the Lexus RX-300 sport utility vehicle and the new Pontiac
Aztek and Ford Escape. Because these vehicles still look mostly
like sport utilities on the outside, automakers have been
successful, with few exceptions, in convincing regulators that
these crossover vehicles are still eligible for the more lenient
safety, air pollution and fuel economy standards that apply to
light trucks, instead of the more stringent standards applied to
cars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
