<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3507 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-KLEZMER-BOOK-REVIEW-2     08-27 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEZMER-BOOK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KLEZMER: TWO BOOKS ON A MUSICAL STYLE AND ITS YIDDISH ROOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that klezmer has become the generic name of a musical style,
it is worth noting that from medieval times until a few decades ago
the word referred not to a particular variety of music, but to a
particular kind of musician. Specifically this evocative
conjunction of the Yiddish words ``kley'' (vessel) and ``zemer''
(song) described the instrumentalists whose music enlivened
weddings in the shtetls of Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Klezmer as we know it today is newfangled, having evolved in
tandem with other streams of Western music over several hundred
years. At its heart is an instrumental imitation of cantorial
singing, an emphasis on melodies in minor keys with alternately
drooping and ecstatic ornamentation. But its structures borrow from
the shtetl's non-Jewish neighbors: many of klezmer's classic forms
_doinas, horas, freylekhs and bulgars _ have Romanian and Ukrainian
folk roots.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that both Henry Sapoznik and Seth Rogovoy show in
their very different but complementary studies is that the music
now considered authentic, ``pure'' klezmer is just a point on an
evolutionary continuum. Because composers did not write down their
works, it was not until the first decades of the 20th century, when
the nascent record industry identified Jewish immigrants as a niche
market, that the sound of klezmer was preserved.
</P>
<P>
   Those early recordings, though, are as misleading as they are
enlightening. They preserve the sound and technique of spectacular
players, and they offer an overview of the repertory. But these
works that thrived on expansive improvisation were squashed into
the three or four minutes of a disc side, and musicians were
encouraged to play to their audiences' changing tastes. That meant
not only touching on nostalgia for the Old World, but accounting
for New World interests like Yiddish theater songs and jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Both Sapoznik and Rogovoy cast wide nets to gather klezmer's
unruly history. In the case of Sapoznik's ``Klezmer! Jewish Music
From Old World to Our World,'' the historical discussion regularly
veers away from klezmer itself to look at Yiddish theater and its
stars, Jewish-American popular recordings and the practice of
bringing cantorial music into the concert hall and recording
studio. These developments are not irrelevant: Sapoznik clarifies
the degree to which they both drew on and fed into the klezmer
mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   Rogovoy, in ``The Essential Klezmer,'' focuses more fully on
recent trends in which traditional klezmer has mingled with jazz,
rock and avant-garde experimental music. He is particularly fond of
the amalgam now known as Radical Jewish Culture, a catchall
appellation invented by the composer John Zorn. If some of this
music has only tenuous klezmer links, one can argue, as Rogovoy
does, that its family bonds make it a legitimate part of the story.
</P>
<P>
   That the evolution from traditional to free-form klezmer took
place at all is something of a miracle, because for three decades
in the middle of the 20th century klezmer was entirely eclipsed.
After World War II the tendency among American Jews _ especially
those born here _ was to set aside the remnants of Eastern Europe
in favor of an emerging American culture that was driven by film,
television and popular music.
</P>
<P>
   Sapoznik, the son of a cantor, grew up in a Yiddish-speaking
household in Brooklyn. Like many in his generation (he is in his
mid-40s), he abandoned his parents' culture during his teen-age
years, having suffered the mortification of having a klezmer band,
rather than a rock group, perform at his bar mitzvah celebration.
But he was also among the first to return to it, having made a
detour as a member of the Delaware Water Gap, a moderately
successful folk music band. The story of his return has become
klezmer lore: In 1977 Tommy Jarrell, a North Carolina banjo player
with whom Sapoznik was studying, asked him, ``Hank, don't your
people have none of their own music?''  &QL; 
(MORE) &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Sapoznik's response was to become an architect of the movement
that brought klezmer back into the spotlight. He immersed himself
in the archives at YIVO, the New York Yiddish culture research
institute. He collected and cataloged countless recordings,
photographs and documents, and interviewed musicians. He was a
founder of Kapelye, one of the first and most accomplished of the
klezmer revival bands, and he produced scores for several
documentaries on the music and the culture that produced it.
</P>
<P>
   He also produced a string of crucial LP and CD reissues, among
them collections of recordings by Dave Tarras and Naftule
Brandwein, the two greatest klezmer clarinetists of the first half
of the 20th century, and the anthologies ``Klezmer Music
1910-1942,'' ``Klezmer Pioneers: European and American Recordings
1905-1952'' and ``Klezmer! Jewish Music From Old World to Our
World,'' released as a companion to his book. Sapoznik's liner
notes for these recordings, as well as a 1987 book of musical
transcriptions, ``The Compleat Klezmer,'' include a great deal of
historical information.
</P>
<P>
   All this puts Sapoznik in an odd position as a historian. His
research makes him the ideal person to write a history of klezmer,
but his active involvement in the music brings him too close for
objectivity. His book begins as a scholarly history, but at the
halfway point it becomes an autobiography, spiced with sharp,
amusing opinions but freighted with detail about the internal
politics of organizations like YIVO.
</P>
<P>
   This chattier, more personal section of the book has a certain
charm. But a reader looking for a dispassionate history will have
the sense of being yanked into a single tree after happily
contemplating the forest.
</P>
<P>
   Rogovoy, a music critic in western Massachusetts, began
listening to klezmer in 1997 and was so thoroughly seduced by it
that he listened to virtually every available recording with
klezmer links. His writing about the music's early history lacks
the depth and texture of Sapoznik's work, and it is beset by a
tendency to use contemporary pop as an all-purpose yardstick.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Essential Klezmer'' comes to life, though, in the chapters
on the bands that have sprouted since the late 1970s. Whereas
Sapoznik's telling is weighted with closely observed detail,
Rogovoy's offers more sweeping, comprehensive surveys of the work
of Andy Statman, David Krakauer, the Klezmatics, Brave Old World,
the Klezmer Conservatory Band and even Sapoznik's own band,
Kapelye, to say nothing of the post-klezmer renegades led by Zorn.
</P>
<P>
   But what makes ``The Essential Klezmer'' invaluable is its
second half. An enthusiast's source book, this section includes an
extensive critically annotated discography as well as a guide to
klezmer Web sites, films, festivals, books and publications.
</P>
<P>
   Both authors are conscientious about defining the Yiddish and
Hebrew terms that pepper their texts.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   KLEZMER! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jewish Music From Old World to Our World
</P>
<P>
   By Henry Sapoznik
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 340 pages. Schirmer Books. $29.95.
</P>
<P>
   THE ESSENTIAL KLEZMER
</P>
<P>
   By Seth Rogovoy
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 281 pages. Algonquin Books. $15.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
