<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME NEW MATH IN MSNBC'S BILLBOARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Bylines at end of each article)   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last few months, the cable network MSNBC has placed two
billboards along the West Side Highway in Manhattan that promote
its main nighttime news program in this way: ``THE NEWS WITH BRIAN
WILLIAMS _ Find Out Why 42 Million People are Watching.''
</P>
<P>
   The sign features a photograph of Williams, who is considered to
be among the heirs apparent to the NBC news anchor Tom Brokaw,
looking confident and authoritative. It tells viewers they can tune
in weeknights at 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   But the billboard has struck executives at some of MSNBC's
competitors as not only odd, but also a bit annoying because of the
large ratings figure the sign boasts.
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter of this year _ the most recent full
quarter for which cable ratings are available _ the 9 p.m. showing
of ``The News With Brian Williams'' was actually watched by an
average 203,000 people, according to Nielsen figures. It was in
fourth place in its time period among the cable news networks
behind CNN's ``Larry King Live,'' with 936,000 people watching each
night; CNBC's ``Rivera Live,'' with 374,000; and the Fox News
Channel's ``Hannity &AMP; Colmes,'' with about 308,000.
</P>
<P>
   So, how can MSNBC say the program is being watched by 42 million
people when its nightly audience is only a small fraction of that?
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to some statistical ingenuity and vague language, the
MSNBC number is basically correct, according to MSNBC executives.
</P>
<P>
   Here is the calculus: Williams' program, which runs Monday
through Friday, is repeated four times a night after its initial 9
p.m. showing _ twice on MSNBC and twice on CNBC, NBC's financial
network. MSNBC executives said they arrived at the figure by taking
the total number of people who watched at least one minute of the
program in any of its runs in April.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if while clicking through the channels in April,
a viewer happened to pause for 60 seconds on Williams' program, she
became one of the 42 million.
</P>
<P>
   That sort of method is not all that different from one used to
determine audiences for Web sites. But it is quite different from
that usually used to measure television audiences, in which
statisticians track the number of people watching a particular
program from minute to minute and then produce an average
viewership number.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at MSNBC said they thought their method for the
billboard would better represent the real audience for Williams in
the course of a night since, they contend, many of his his viewers
tune in briefly for information and then head elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people tune in to Brian Williams to get their news,''
said Robin Garfield, MSNBC's vice president for research. ``That's
the statement we want to make: We are the news broadcast of record
in cable.''
</P>
<P>
   _ JIM RUTENBERG &QR;
</P>
<P>
   PROGRAM IS HURT BY A LACK OF CHARACTERS
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' may have posted ratings last week that surpassed
everything this year but the Super Bowl, but ``Big Brother,'' the
other reality show on CBS, has muddled along with ratings so pale
by comparison that the show has had to fight off the impression
that it has been a total flop.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, one night after the ``Survivor'' finale soared to
a 28.4 rating, ``Big Brother'' scored a 6.3. (Each rating point
represents just over one million homes.)
</P>
<P>
   The network's official position on ``Big Brother,'' which has
locked 10 people all summer in a house filled with cameras, is
supportive. ``The show is putting up solid summer numbers,'' said
Chris Ender, CBS' spokesman for entertainment programs. ``Even its
lowest-rated broadcasts are doing far better than what we had in
those time periods last year.''
</P>
<P>
   But unofficially, many senior CBS executives are disappointed
with the show's ratings and its execution.
</P>
<P>
   The show is still pulling in more younger viewers than CBS is
accustomed to seeing. But it failed to capitalize on several
opportunities to build a steady audience in recent weeks when it
followed ``Survivor.'' Now it has to endure six nights a week until
Sept. 30 _ many of those nights going against the Olympics on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Michaels, a spokesman for Endemol, the Dutch company that
created ``Big Brother,'' said it expected interest to grow as the
number of people in the house dwindle in coming weeks. And he said
a series of provocative challenges were planned to increase the
tension among those who remain.
</P>
<P>
   Tension has been one factor cited as lacking in the show. Much
of the blame has fallen on the casting, the same element for which
``Survivor'' was widely praised. People close to the show say CBS
executives contend that Endemol had too much control over casting,
while Endemol has said that CBS executives had veto rights over the
final selections.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest shortcoming of ``Big Brother'' may be its inability
so far to create anything like the national discussion that
``Survivor'' has generated. In every other country where a version
of ``Big Brother'' has played _ including Britain, where the
country's version is now an enormous hit _ the show has generated
noisy public debate.
</P>
<P>
   That has not happened with ``Big Brother'' on CBS, where
``Survivor'' has been commanding so much attention.
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   EXPERIMENT IN SERIOUS NEWSCAST STUMBLES
</P>
<P>
   Last February, the CBS station in Chicago, WBBM-TV, began a bold
experiment in local television news: It unveiled a 10 p.m. program
that presented its audience with plain old news and information.
Gone was the genre's usual reliance on sensationalism and
entertainment-world gossip.
</P>
<P>
   The anchor was Carol Marin, who quit her job at the local NBC
station, WMAQ, two years earlier, when it hired Jerry Springer as a
news commentator. ``No water-skiing squirrels'' became the mantra
of the program's staff, who were enthusiastic about the new
approach. So were the station's executives, especially Pat
Costello, the news director, and Hank Price, the station's general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   But ``The 10 p.m. News With Carol Marin'' has done worse in the
ratings than the program that it had replaced. And, given recent
events, its once bright-eyed staff members are privately worried
about its future.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, Price and Costello left WBBM, citing opportunities
at other stations that they could not pass up. It is unclear who
will take Costello's place as news director at WBBM.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Cheatwood, who was the vice president for news at the NBC
station when Marin left in protest, is now in charge of news for
the 35 TV stations CBS owns around the country. People at the
station say Cheatwood could have at least some say in selecting the
new news director.
</P>
<P>
   The new station manager, Walter F. DeHaven Jr., has said that he
hoped Marin's newscast will catch on with viewers but that the
ratings will have to come up soon. He had no comment last week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ JIM RUTENBERG
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
