<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3514 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BLACKS-DNA-ART-1015(2     08-27 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKS-DNA-ART-1015(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DNA OFFERS LINK TO BLACK HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.C.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT7 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Add to the list of the wonders of DNA: the ability, in
the not-so-distant future, to help African-Americans figure out
where their ancestors probably came from before they were enslaved.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston this fall, some 300 African-American schoolchildren
are to be sent home with swabs to gather DNA samples from inside
the mouths of their relatives, part of a nascent project that a
local molecular biologist hopes to extend to North Carolina and
other sites with longstanding African-American populations.
</P>
<P>
   At Howard University in Washington, a geneticist announced last
spring that he would offer DNA analysis, possibly as early as this
summer, to African-Americans wanting to find out their ancestors'
homelands, at $200 or $300 per test. He has since withdrawn that
price and moved his starting date to next year.
</P>
<P>
   And in New York, the African Burial Ground project has been
assembling a database of the DNA of African-Americans buried long
ago on what is now the site of an office building. The project has
also been gathering the DNA of living Africans to help determine
where those buried on the site might have come from. It is open to
expanding the database to help the living find their past, project
scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely the ability to ``show reasonably accurate
probabilities of association'' between living African-Americans and
African cultures will be possible in two years or so, given enough
financing, said Dr. Michael L. Blakey, director of the project.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts may be disparate, but this much seems clear:
Powerful new gene technology is being enlisted in black Americans'
search for their African ancestry, and it promises some answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest travesty for African-Americans is not the
diseases we suffer, not the sickle-cell and high blood pressure,
nor is it the social injustices we have to face; it is that we are
disconnected from our beginnings,'' said Bruce Jackson, director of
the biotechnology and DNA forensics programs at Massachusetts Bay
Community College, and the leader of the project that is to involve
Boston schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no connection to where we came from,'' Jackson said,
``and that is an affliction which has followed us for centuries. It
really has to end.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind the DNA projects is that analysts can look for
telltale sequences in African-Americans' genes that also appear in
the current populations of various African regions, and thus link
the Americans to their probable point of origin.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists emphasize, however, that this DNA analysis is not
enough to provide decisive evidence for a link to a homeland and
that other fields of knowledge are essential, including history and
ethnology; also it will take time to develop the extensive
databases needed to encompass enough people and enough areas of
Africa. Researchers are tapping their African colleagues for help
in gathering those data.
</P>
<P>
   Such limitations contributed to some of the hubbub that arose in
recent months over the publicized plans of Rick Kittles, a
geneticist at Howard University, to offer individual DNA-based
origin-finding to African-Americans for a fee. In newspaper reports
last spring, he was quoted as saying that it would cost $200 or
$300 and would perhaps begin this summer; A Web site,
www.africanancestry.com, promotes the project.
</P>
<P>
   Objections arose from many quarters, including scientists who
said the databases could not yet provide findings meaningful enough
to market. Others argued that it was immoral to charge victims of
slavery for determining their homelands.
</P>
<P>
   Blakey of the African Burial Ground Project, where Kittles had
worked until last year, warned that the database still had major
gaps and technical problems. He also expressed unease about the
seeming commercial nature of Kittles' African Ancestry project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly seems to be a questionable matter that a former
researcher should take part of our program currently in development
and do what he is doing,'' Blakey said of Kittles.
</P>
<P>
   In general, said Thomas J. Parsons, the chief of research at the
Armed Forces DNA Identification Laboratory, who is not involved in
the projects, such databases are of scientific interest and
constitute ``a very interesting way of relating populations that
exist in the U.S. to potential progenitor populations in Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   But consider, Parsons added, the limitations on what can be
learned from mitochondrial DNA, which is one of two types of DNA
that the projects are using, because they are passed down virtually
unchanged. The mitochondrial DNA goes from mother to daughter and
Y-chromosome DNA follows the male line.
</P>
<P>
   If, for example, Parsons said, an African-American man is
seeking to trace his mitochondrial DNA to the lineage of his
great-great-great-great-great-grandmother, he may succeed, but that
woman would have contributed only one-128th of his genetic
composition. ``What that means in terms of who you are is: It's
only a small portion of a potentially giant admixture,'' the rest
of which would still be undetermined, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kittles has also acknowledged that although the project is meant
to trace African origins, it is likely to turn up a great deal of
European lineage, because slave owners and other whites interbred
with African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Kittles has declined interview requests in recent weeks.
University officials first said that he was too busy. Then they
said he could not comment because, as Donna Brock, a university
spokeswoman, put it, ``his work is incomplete and has not been
peer-reviewed.''
</P>
<P>
   Kittles did say a few words last week, when asked in a brief
telephone interview whether he would be working with Jackson, the
Boston molecular biologist. ``I'm not collaborating with him at all
as it relates to African-American ancestry,'' Kittles said. As for
his own project, Kittles said, ``We're still working out the
logistics, we're still working on the research.'' He did not
elaborate on what the financial arrangements would be.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely coming,'' he said of his project. ``If you
look at what I said before, it will do what I said.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said that he and Kittles had talked, and that he hoped
they could work together. Jackson is the head of what he called the
only degree-granting program in the United States on DNA forensic
science, at Massachusetts Bay Community College, and an assistant
professor at Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had dreamed for years of creating a database that
could let him and other African-Americans find their genetic roots.
He had been crestfallen to read last spring that Kittles had
already begun such an effort, but he decided to proceed anyway, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson plans to collect DNA samples from Boston as well as the
islands off North Carolina and other sites with centuries-old
African-American populations, he said, and to build a DNA database
with thousands of profiles. He is seeking money for the project
through grants and foundations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to have kids take an active part in determining their
ancestry and also get an interest in science at an age when they
can,'' Jackson said. ``We want to do both.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be some time before anyone is likely to find matches in
the database, he said, but with the Boston schoolchildren, who are
participating as part of a voluntary after-school program, ``We'll
take a wild shot in the dark with them _ a prayerful shot in the
dark.''
</P>
<P>
   At the African Burial Ground project, Blakey said the goal of
the DNA database was to analyze the remains of those buried. Once
that has been done, he said, the database ``will be available for
the people, as many members of the public had asked.''
</P>
<P>
   The African Burial Ground project is being financed by the
federal General Services Administration, which built the office
tower at the site.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Blakey said, using DNA to indicate their origins
could prove healing for African-Americans and could ``help restore
the specifics of identity that were deliberately damaged by
slaveholders in order to make enslaved Africans seem less human.''
</P>
</TEXT>
