u i BC-ISRAEL-HAMAS-ART-NYT     08-27 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-HAMAS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL DEFENDS ATTACK ON FUGITIVE'S HIDEOUT THAT KILLED 3
SOLDIERS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT2 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ ``Friendly fire'' may have been responsible for
killing three Israeli soldiers in a bungled West Bank anti-terror
operation Saturday, Israeli officials acknowledged Sunday. But they
defended the late-night attack on the hide-out of a man accused of
terrorism who heads Israel's most-wanted list.
</P>
<P>
   The wanted man, Mahmoud Abu Hanoud, fled during the assault to
the nearby Palestinian-governed city of Nablus, where he
surrendered to local security officials and remained in their
custody Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Hanoud, a leader of the underground military wing of Hamas,
is held responsible by Israel for the deaths of 21 civilians in the
terrorist bombings of an outdoor food market and pedestrian mall in
downtown Jerusalem in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   He is also accused of plotting further attacks in a calculated
attempt to disrupt peace negotiations between Israel and the
Palestinians, which are entering a critical and perhaps definitive
phase in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man, Abu Hanoud, whose capture and interception was the
objective of this operation, is responsible for the deaths of
dozens of people in the past,'' Prime Minister Ehud Barak said
Sunday. Had Abu Hanoud remained at large, the prime minister said,
it ``would have placed the lives of dozens of Israeli citizens in
jeopardy in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak said Israel may request Abu Hanoud's extradition. But
Palestinian officials, irked at Israel's failure to inform them of
the raid, insisted that Abu Hanoud would be tried in Palestinian
courts and if convicted would be sent to a Palestinian jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Israelis made a mistake and paid the price,'' said Jibril
Rajoub, the director of Palestinian security in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The raid involved hundreds of troops and was led by an
undercover Israeli brigade tht specializes in plainclothes work in
Arab communities. It took place in a northern West Bank village
near Nablus, called Asira al Shamaliya, where Palestinians run
their own municipal affairs but Israel retains ultimate security
control.
</P>
<P>
   If the Israeli officials had told their Palestinian counterparts
that they had identified Abu Hanoud's whereabouts, the two security
forces could have worked together to secure his arrest ``without
bloodshed,'' Rajoub asserted. A senior Palestinian security
official said Sunday night that Israel and the Palestinian
Authority have not yet had any high-level communications about the
episode.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli army officers confirmed Sunday that one soldier was
wounded in the raid by Israeli army fire and said they could not
rule out the possibility that all three solders who died were also
the victims of Israeli bullets. Lt. Gen. Shaul Mofaz, the Israeli
army chief of staff, said he had ordered an internal army inquiry
into the episode, which he tentatively attributed to planning
errors and the misidentification of undercover forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is possible that some of the dead and the injured soldiers
were hit by friendly fire _ a grave and painful operational mishap
second to none,'' Barak said.
</P>
<P>
   The three deaths constituted the worst loss of life by Israeli
security forces in the West Bank since 1996, when nine soldiers
died in clashes with Palestinian rioters.
</P>
<P>
   Still, both Mofaz and Barak vigorously defended the raid,
stressing that Abu Hanoud has been apprehended, along with other
accused members of the clandestine Hamas military wing. ``This
operation served to disrupt, put off and even thwart an operation
that was fully prepared, from the point of view of the Hamas
terrorists from the area in question, to be carried out,'' Mofaz
said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the awkward truth was that while the death of the
Israeli soldiers was a grievous embarrassment for the military _ as
well as a tragedy for the soldiers' friends and families _ it was
not the diplomatic disaster that was initially feared.
</P>
<P>
   If the soldiers had been killed by Palestinian gunmen, as was
first reported late Saturday night, the concern here was that it
could have put an abrupt halt to the peace negotiations, reviving
Israeli distrust of Palestinian negotiating partners. It also would
have brought the already weakened Barak government under further
attack for an apparent inability to rout out terror cells in
collaboration with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Israeli officials took pains Sunday to praise the
security cooperation of the Palestinian Authority, which they
consider crucial to the near cessation of terrorist attacks against
Israelis over the past year and a half. They also expressed
confidence that the authority would prosecute Abu Hanoud, who poses
as much of a political threat to Yasser Arafat as he does to Barak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no doubt that the fact that he was hit and later
captured by the Palestinians will disrupt Hamas activity and limit
their ability to carry out terror attacks in the near future,''
Mofaz said.
</P>
</TEXT>
