u r BC-NASCAR-BRISTOL0828-CO     08-27 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-BRISTOL0828-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Streaking Wallace all smiles over win, team
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRISTOL, Tenn. _ The swagger is back for Rusty Wallace, winner
of Saturday night's Goracing.com500. So is the smile and the
cockiness.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace is the hottest driver in the Winston Cup Series, winning
three of the last five races and finishing second at Indianapolis.
He isn't the points leader, but feels he has the best team in
Winston Cup right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a long time ago not to brag, but there's one thing I
can brag about; that's my team,'' Wallace said. ``Anytime you've
got eight poles . . . four wins this year and close to 2,000 laps
led, I'd have to say in my book they're the best team.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace has dominated the circuit this year. He is the leader in
victories and poles and has led twice as many laps (1,439) than the
next closest driver (Tony Stewart, 656).
</P>
<P>
   ``I can compare (this season) really close to 1993, when I won
10 races,'' Wallace said. ``But I think as tough as NASCAR is
nowadays, that this year is more dominating than that year was in
'93. I'm just really proud of those numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   The only numbers that do not favor Wallace are the most
important _ the Winston Cup points standings. He is fifth, 290
points behind leader Bobby Labonte, with 11 races remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's too late to get back in the battle,''
Wallace said. ``Right now, unfortunately, we're taking baby steps
at it, because the other (drivers) just won't break or blow up.
That's what we need to happen. They need to have some bad luck like
I had mine early (this year).
</P>
<P>
   ``In my eyes, if we just keep trucking along and giving them
everything they can stand until the year's over . . . if we don't
make it to the head table, we'll hopefully make it close.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago, Wallace was the runner-up to Dale Earnhardt for
the Winston Cup championship. Wallace's only title was in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   While Labonte has been a model of consistency this season,
Wallace has not _ and it is not all the driver's fault. He blew an
engine while leading at Talladega with 72 laps to go. He was part
of bad decisions at Martinsville and the first Pocono race.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace also has failed to take advantage of numerous pole
positions. Saturday night's race was the first time he started and
finished in the No. 1 position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally got a win by sitting on the pole,'' Wallace said.
``In fact, when I got the pole the other day, a couple of people
around me said, `I don't know if this is bad luck or not.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But we finally broke it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
