<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3520 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NEW-ECONOMY-COLUMN-NY     08-27 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-ECONOMY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ECONOMY: SKY-HIGH GERMAN TELECOM AUCTION RANKLES SOME BIDDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  By EDMUND L. ANDREWS     
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ It was a free-market contest of the purest
sort, an airwave auction of the kind pioneered in the United States
and taken to dizzying new heights in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ever since the bidding ended on Aug. 17 in Germany's auction
of wireless licenses for so-called third-generation mobile
networks, even devoted market enthusiasts have started to wonder if
this is really the most rational way to go.
</P>
<P>
   After two weeks and 173 rounds of bidding, six companies had bid
a total $46 billion for the rights to one license apiece. And that
total did not include an additional $4 billion or so that each
company would have to spend to build the new networks and drum up
customers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Investors have been reeling, dumping the stocks of all the
winners: Deutsche Telekom, Vodafone AirTouch of Britain, British
Telecommunications, France Telecom, Telefonica of Spain and Sonera
of Finland. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Standard &AMP; Poor's, the credit-rating agency, warned that it
would probably lower most of the companies' credit ratings and
might even drop some to the triple-B level, not much better than
junk-bond status. Bond investors are bracing for a flood of
gigantic telephone bond offerings, but the uncertainties were high
enough that British Telecommunications postponed an offering last
week until its rating was clarified.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, wireless opportunities are immense. Europe is well
ahead of the United States in rolling out digital wireless
telephones, and the new licenses will be used to offer high-speed
data communications that are eventually expected to galvanize
mobile electronic commerce. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As envisioned, the new third-generation mobile networks will
enable people to surf the Internet from a sidewalk, download video
clips onto their hand-held phones or simply locate a nearby
restaurant and book a table.
</P>
<P>
   But no one knows what consumers will really want or how much
they will be ready to pay. And because the new systems will
increase competition in ordinary mobile phone service, analysts
predict that prices and profitability in voice service will decline
sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Most economists argue that risks are simply part of the game. If
companies overbid, they may have to fold tent and sell their
licenses to someone else at a loss. The world will go on. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the German auctions also uncovered deep fissures in the
European telecommunications landscape that make the entire playing
field uneven. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Britain, Germany and the Netherlands have all held auctions, won
by a variety of European players. But Spain and Finland, using a
so-called beauty contest approach, simply awarded licenses to
companies deemed most worthy. The licenses, granted primarily to
domestic applicants, came at a fraction of the price they might
have fetched at auction. France will hold a beauty contest, too,
but will charge a flat fee of about $4 billion a license.
</P>
<P>
   Some executives complain that companies from countries with very
low license costs can save billions at home and then plow the money
into auctions elsewhere. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a level playing field in Europe,'' said Hans
Ehnert, a spokesman for Deutsche Telekom. ``We had to compete in
the bidding against companies like Telefonica from Spain, but we
were excluded from the Spanish market.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of auctions argue that they are the most effective way
to put licenses in the hands of those most likely to use them
profitably. Compared with beauty contests, auctions give the
participants no opportunity to exploit political connections or
bedazzle government bureaucrats with lofty promises that can later
be broken. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both the British and German auctions were open. But one of the
surprise winners in the German auction _ a bidder that Deutsche
Telekom and Vodafone both tried and failed to eliminate _ was a
group controlled by Telefonica of Spain and Sonera of Finland. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish and Finnish companies had received new wireless
licenses at negligible costs from their own governments.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom bid for a license earlier this year in Spain,
where the license fees were relative peanuts: about $130 million
and 0.15 percent of future revenues. Deutsche Telekom teamed up in
the beauty contest with Jazztel, a fast-growing Spanish competitor
to Telefonica, but the team lost to three Spanish operators and a
fourth group led by Vivendi of France.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As for Finland, Pirjo Kekalainen-Torvinen, Sonera's senior vice
president for international business development, said her company
had not unfairly benefited by getting a Finnish license almost
free. ``We paid as much for our license in Germany as anybody
else,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that Finland had strong policy reasons for awarding
wireless licenses as cheaply as possible. Finland, home to Nokia,
the world's biggest wireless phone producer, Nokia, considers
wireless technology its biggest national industry. By giving out
next-generation wireless licenses as quickly and cheaply as
possible, government officials hope to promote and indirectly
subsidize innovative new technology and services. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many industry executives blame Deutsche Telekom itself for the
high prices of the German licenses. Gerhard Schmid, chief executive
of Mobilcom, which was awarded a license in the auction, angrily
complained that the six final bidders could have ended up with the
same licenses and saved billions of dollars if they had simply
stopped bidding four days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Schmid blamed Deutsche Telekom for a misguided attempt to outbid
the Spanish-Finnish group for an extra license, a move that would
have reduced the number of rivals from six to five. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Telefonica and Sonera refused to give up, and Deutsche
Telekom executives capitulated after the total bidding had climbed
from 30 billion euros ($27.1 billion) to 50.5 billion euros. The
result was higher license prices and more licensees than most
investors had been expecting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, investors pummeled shares of Sonera and Telefonica
even more than they did those of Deutsche Telekom. Yet when Italy
begins auctions later this year, Deutsche Telekom plans to stay
out, saying it has no interest in Italy. But Telefonica and Sonera,
exuberant after their German adventure, plan to team up again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
