<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3533 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-TREES-AZR &LR;      08-27 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREES-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-TREES-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    FORESTS FIRE RISK PROGRAM(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By JUDD SLIVKA(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has seized upon a Flagstaff-area
fire-danger reduction program as a possible national model for the
country's fire-ravaged forests. But even some locals involved in
the plan say it's not the sweeping success the administration would
like to believe.
</P>
<P>
   The forest-thinning plan is being touted to Congress and the
public as way to make forests more fire resistant - in effect, to
undo 100 years of uninformed forest management, decisions that have
left the nation's forests snarled with underbrush and thick with
diseased trees.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan has critics - even among those instrumental in
designing and implementing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hesitant about calling it a success right now, because
we've made so little progress on the ground,'' says Brad Ack,
executive director of the Grand Canyon Forests Partnership, the
coalition that developed the plan. ``We have the foundations of
success, but we're a long way from being there.''
</P>
<P>
   Those foundations were laid after the severe fire summer of
1996. A coalition of groups - the Grand Canyon Trust, Arizona
Public Service Co. and Northern Arizona University among them -
worked with the U.S. Forest Service to begin rehabilitating the
area's crowded, diseased fire-hazard forests.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was not to make forests fireproof. It was to make the
forests more closely resemble the way they were before the massive
migrations of Manifest Destiny - and the desire for homes in
bucolic settings - changed the way humans interacted with ponderosa
pine.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that meant thinning forests out, selectively taking out
younger, less fire-resistant trees that fire could crawl up and
prey on. It means increasing the space between trees, letting grass
grow again in between them and introducing low-intensity fires back
into the forest.
</P>
<P>
   Works in some places
</P>
<P>
   It's worked before. This summer's ``Pumpkin'' fire was racing
along the crowns of trees in a densely wooded area, until it
reached a place that had been previously thinned.
</P>
<P>
   There the fire dived to the ground like a bird after a worm. The
trees ended up crispy, but not cooked. Most will live.
</P>
<P>
   But it also hasn't worked. In the fires currently burning in
Montana, flames have rampaged through areas that have been thinned
out by logging companies.
</P>
<P>
   Because lumber companies have long been the beneficiary of
thinning contracts, the practice is also anathema to many
environmentalists. Groups such as the Santa Fe-based Forest
Guardians have taken a no-thinning stance, a position going back to
the days when the U.S. Forest Service let timber companies run
roughshod over the nation's public forests.
</P>
<P>
   Using the National Environmental Protection Act, the Guardians
have successfully blocked timber sales and thinning across the
Southwest. Only in recent weeks has the group grudgingly
acknowledged that thinning might be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``A strategy that has no offense is a strategy that is doomed to
fail,'' said Ack, who works with the Grand Canyon Trust on Canyon
issues as well as heading up the partnership. ``The people saying
(don't cut) are people without offense. They say `We need to keep
bad things from happening.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, saying `We need to keep bad things from happening,' just
isn't good enough anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The partnership's most ambitious project: treating 1,300 acres
in the Fort Valley area near Flagstaff. Marking different sizes of
trees to be logged out by contractors. Increasing space in the
forest, bringing it back to ``pre-settlement'' conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Objection to logging
</P>
<P>
   A good plan, the partnership agreed. Then the lawsuit happened.
Filed by Forest Guardians and several other groups, the suit was
designed to stop the thinning.
</P>
<P>
   The Guardians and local critics have objected to the logging and
to the 10,000-acre size of the Fort Valley plot, and have used the
National Environmental Protection Act to slow the process.
</P>
<P>
   Today, a year later, only 300 acres - a test area exempted from
administrative appeals - has been treated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tragedy is that all those months and all that
(court-ordered) work didn't change the science in the document,''
Ack said. ``All we did was make it bulletproof for the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerns linger. The Sierra Club's Sharon Galbreath has been a
longtime critic of the plan. The Sierra Club is planning a lawsuit
to protect those nests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should commend them (the Partnership) for some things, like
saying `no more old-growth forests should be cut,''' Galbreath
said. ``But the larger the tests become, it just turns into another
timber sale.''
</P>
<P>
   When the partnership was created, no one envisioned a
presidential administration seizing the small gains it made as a
banner to wave over the charred landscape - something that is
``going to keep Congress from breathing down their necks,'' Ack
said.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the Flagstaff plan has been a success. Observers
note that to get the Grand Canyon Trust and other participants
working with corporations and the national forest system is a no
small feat.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at judd.slivka(a)arizonarepublic.com or at
602-444-8097.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
