<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-RENEWAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S VISIT SENDS CARTAGENA INTO A FRENZY 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARTAGENA, Colombia _ At age 84, Antonia Sarmiento, nearly
toothless and dressed in tattered rags, has seen a lot of tragedy
in her life but never a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Then Mayor Gina Benedetti de Velez knocked at the door of her
disheveled clapboard shack last week to say the local government
would rebuild her house for no charge. President Clinton would be
visiting the House of Justice across the street, the mayor
explained, and he should not have to see such misery in Cartagena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton is a saint brought to me from heaven,'' said a
smiling Sarmiento, a widow of a police officer who lives with a
disabled son on the charity of family members. Watching workers
struggle to complete the front facade in time for Clinton's visit
Wednesday, she added, ``I'd love to invite him inside for a bowl of
sancocho'' _ a stew of chicken, potatoes and plantains _ ``but he
would never visit a house like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Since local officials learned a month ago that Clinton would be
coming to this splendid Spanish colonial port of soaring church
steeples and mounted cannons, they have rushed into a breathless
urban renewal campaign perhaps not seen since Sir Francis Drake
sacked the city in 1586. A thousand workers are widening sidewalks,
fixing cracked streets, whitewashing government buildings and
planting palm trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most important event in Cartagena's history since
President Bush came here in 1990,'' Benedetti said. ``But this is
even bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's visit here to a regional presidential anti-narcotics
conference _ with the usual bevy of reporters and camera crews _
helped bring a 34 percent increase in tourists the following year,
local officials say.
</P>
<P>
   But the number of tourists has decreased because of the
country's expanding war with Marxist guerrilla groups, to 535,103
tourists in Cartagena last year from 865,379 in 1994. So people
here are hoping this visit will cause another surge in tourism,
this city's most important industry.
</P>
<P>
   Benedetti is lobbying to urge Clinton and his daughter, Chelsea,
to ride through the old city in a horse-drawn carriage, Cartagena's
answer to Venice's gondolas, to show off its quaint narrow streets
shaded by rococo balconies draped by lush tropical flowers. She
also hopes to have a word with Clinton to press him to include an
exception for Cartagena to the State Department travel advisory
warning that Colombia is an exceptionally risky place for American
tourists.
</P>
<P>
   No detail has been left to chance to create the perfect pictures
and sound bites. About 150 homeless children have been removed from
the streets to ``recreational centers'' on the outskirts of the
city, and 1,500 kiosk owners have been told to haul their rickety
wares off the presidential route on Tuesday and Wednesday. One
thoroughfare along the beach _ which taxi drivers have taken to
renaming Avenida Clinton _ has been closed entirely for a complete
repaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a girl fixing up her house for her boyfriend's first
visit,'' noted El Tiempo, Bogota's leading newspaper, ``and asking
that her parents and brothers behave themselves to make the best
impression.''
</P>
<P>
   The round-the-clock grooming effort will cost the city $1
million _ a handsome sum for a city with a total annual budget of
$160 million _ to fix up the route Clinton will take in his
eight-hour visit. And that does not count the contributions being
made by the local telephone, electric and water companies to fix up
damaged pipes, street holes and faulty wiring, or the efforts of
store owners, who are washing down everything from their curtains
to welcome mats.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton visit has produced an almost giddy response from
Cartagena residents, who seem to never tire of telling visitors
that they live in an ``oasis'' far from the kidnappings and
massacres that characterize the rest of the country. (Actually,
crime and violence in Cartagena are well below other Colombian
cities, and there have not been any major acts of violence since
two Medellin Cartel bombings here in 1989.)
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton's visit will show the world that not all
Colombians are bad,'' said Dimas Ortiz Rondono, 58, a lottery
ticket seller who wears a row of rosary beads around his neck and
works beside the old slave market in the Plaza de los Coches, which
Clinton is scheduled to visit. ``And then the tourists will flock
back to us.''
</P>
<P>
   As Victor Prieto Castro, a 53-year-old reporter for the local
Victoria AM radio station, looked for foreign correspondents to
interview, he appeared excited about covering the biggest story to
come his way in some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't buy this kind of publicity,'' he said, ``We couldn't
be happier. This trip is going to give Colombia a whole new
image.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all Cartagena residents are so certain a one-day visit by
Clinton will make a lasting difference for a country that has
suffered four decades of conflict or for a Caribbean tourist
destination that most cruise-ship companies would just as soon pass
on to keep their passengers calm. Some even express concerns that
the president could attract some terrorist attack, that would ruin
the city's reputation forever.
</P>
<P>
   Leonor Sanchez, a 40-year-old guide at the Palace of the
Inquisition, said she was happy Clinton was scheduled to visit the
Plaza de Bolivar outside the palace. But she said she was not sure
it was a good idea that Clinton visit the building's torture
chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the dark side of Colombia's history, when power was
terribly abused,'' said Sanchez, a jolly lady with an encyclopedic
knowledge of the old ways of stretching and mutilating bodies. ``He
could get the bad impression that we have always been a violent
country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
