<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3535 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NEW-ECONOMY-COLUMN-NY     08-27 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-ECONOMY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ECONOMY: SKY-HIGH GERMAN TELECOM AUCTION RANKLES SOME BIDDERS  

</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ After two weeks and 173 rounds of bidding
in Germany's auction of wireless licenses for so-called
third-generation mobile networks, six companies had bid a total $46
billion for the rights to one license apiece. And that total did
not include an additional $4 billion or so that each company would
have to spend to build the new networks and drum up customers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Investors have been reeling, dumping the stocks of all the
winners: Deutsche Telekom, Vodafone AirTouch of Britain, British
Telecommunications, France Telecom, Telefonica of Spain and Sonera
of Finland. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Standard &AMP; Poor's, the credit-rating agency, warned that it
would probably lower most of the companies' credit ratings and
might even drop some to the triple-B level, not much better than
junk-bond status.
</P>
<P>
   The German auctions also uncovered deep fissures in the European
telecommunications landscape that make the entire playing field
uneven. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Britain, Germany and the Netherlands have all held auctions, won
by a variety of European players. But Spain and Finland, using a
so-called beauty contest approach, simply awarded licenses to
companies deemed most worthy. The licenses, granted primarily to
domestic applicants, came at a fraction of the price they might
have fetched at auction.
</P>
<P>
   Some executives complain that companies from countries with very
low license costs can save billions at home and then plow the money
into auctions elsewhere. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a level playing field in Europe,'' said Hans
Ehnert, a spokesman for Deutsche Telekom.
</P>
<P>
   Both the British and German auctions were open. But one of the
surprise winners in the German auction _ a bidder that Deutsche
Telekom and Vodafone both tried and failed to eliminate _ was a
group controlled by Telefonica of Spain and Sonera of Finland. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish and Finnish companies had received new wireless
licenses at negligible costs from their own governments.
</P>
<P>
   Pirjo Kekalainen-Torvinen, Sonera's senior vice president for
international business development, said her company had not
unfairly benefited by getting a Finnish license almost free. ``We
paid as much for our license in Germany as anybody else,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Many industry executives blame Deutsche Telekom itself for the
high prices of the German licenses. Gerhard Schmid, chief executive
of Mobilcom, which was awarded a license in the auction, angrily
complained that the six final bidders could have ended up with the
same licenses and saved billions of dollars if they had simply
stopped bidding four days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-00 2024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000827.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3536 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-POLAND-EUROPE-ART-NYT     08-27 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLAND-EUROPE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLAND FINDS ITSELF THE BORDER COP OF WEST EUROPE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NIEZNANY BOR, Poland _ This is the border where Europe ends.
</P>
<P>
   In this little spot named ``the unknown forest,'' near
Bialowieza, is Poland's frontier with Belarus, which will soon
become the European Union's border with the wild, untamable,
unreformed east.
</P>
<P>
   Today you can walk into Belarus, at least for 100 yards or so.
Then you hit the border fences, with their electronic sensors and a
raked area to capture footprints, designed by the Soviet Union to
keep out even its allies the Poles.
</P>
<P>
   But Belarus is beginning to take down this Cold War barrier,
even as the European Union is urging the Poles to put up a new,
post-Communist one as part of the price of membership.
</P>
<P>
   Europe _ Germany and Austria most vocally _ want the Poles to
build what some are calling the ``Belgian Curtain,'' after the
country where the European Union has its headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Poles like it or not, much of the burden of blocking
illegal trade and immigration into the European Union will fall on
them. That will do real damage to the active cross-border trade
that helps keep this poorest part of Poland alive.
</P>
<P>
   Heavily agricultural, with little industry, this area east and
southeast of Bialystok has an average income only about 65 percent
of the national average, and a lot of hidden unemployment on the
farm.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Russian ruble collapsed in 1998, there was an enormous
amount of cross-border trade, with easterners bringing cheap vodka
to sell here, buying Polish and European products to sell at home,
then returning with more overvalued rubles with which to buy. Now
the ``suitcase trade'' is recovering along with the ruble, just as
Europe is pressing Poland to lock down the border.
</P>
<P>
   Wlodzimierz Cimoszewicz, Poland's prime minister until the end
of 1997, represents this area in Parliament, and he urges a soft
border regime that would allow families and small traders to
continue to cross with as little hindrance as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst would be to apply European standards to this border
and then have terra incognita on the other side of the wall,'' he
said, making a political argument, too, about the spread of ideas
and freedom, as a small eagle circled overhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to improve conditions on the other side,'' he said.
``Of course we have to control pathological aspects like crime and
illegal immigration, but not to stifle trade. But why should we
build a wall with our neighbors? We must rearrange Schengen not to
build too strong a border here.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1995 Schengen agreement allows people and goods to move
freely within the European Union without border checks, making it
vital to control the external borders.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the new outlying frontier of the European Union, Poland
will be in a very uncomfortable position,'' said Krzysztof
Bledowski, chief economist for the brokers Wood &AMP; Co. ``It will
have both the good and the bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Poland will be a magnet and clearinghouse for trade, he said,
but also for more crime and smuggling along the long land border of
people, drugs and goods.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bialowieza Forest, a national park here, is some of the
last remaining primeval forest in Europe, 12,350 acres with
lindens, maples, oak, spruce and ash _ strictly regulated now, full
of fox and lynx, bison and roe deer. Nearby, Cimoszewicz has
secured a hunting cabin, which he is refurbishing, combining
politicking with pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   But already, says the chief forester, Jerzy Lugowoj, tunnels
have been discovered under the Belarussian border fences, and at
least some illegal immigrants, including Afghans and Vietnamese,
have been captured.
</P>
<P>
   Poland's economy is growing at nearly 6 percent a year, while
Ukraine and Belarus have been stumbling backward. The average wage
in Ukraine is about $50 a month and in Poland nearly $400, so the
attraction of any kind of job in Poland, even temporary, is vivid.
</P>
<P>
   Witold M. Orlowski, of the Independent Center for Economic
Studies, specializes in the border question. The difference in
income levels between Poland and its eastern neighbors is now much
bigger than the difference between Poland and eastern Germany,
which is about 2.5 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   So Poland must satisfy its future European partners about its
ability to stop the smuggling of goods and people into the ``Europe
without borders'' while it is also trying to make life better for
those in Belarus and Ukraine to the east, to reduce the growing
economic divide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything depends on what the River Bug will be in the
future,'' Orlowski said. ``Will it be the Rio Grande or the St.
Lawrence Seaway?'' _ in other words, will Poland's relationship
with the east be more like that of the United States with Mexico or
with Canada?
</P>
<P>
   This border is actually relatively new, formalized in Yalta
after the end of World War II, when Stalin got what he wanted in
Eastern Europe _ including a chunk of Poland.
</P>
<P>
   The former unity of the area is obvious in the architecture and
the skyline. There are many Russian Orthodox churches, including a
huge modern cathedral in nearby Hajnowka, the Church of the Holy
Trinity, consecrated in 1992 after nearly 20 years of construction.
</P>
<P>
   This is where Roman Catholic Poland meets Eastern Orthodoxy.
Hajnowka has almost twice as many Russian Orthodox as Roman
Catholics, and in outlying areas, the percentage who are Orthodox
is even higher. The border divides families, and as many as 500,000
ethnic Poles live on the other side of the border, and 300,000
Belarussians on this side.
</P>
<P>
   But while Poland feels it has an eastern vocation, arguing
within the European Union and NATO for better relations and special
ties with Belarus and Ukraine, Cimoszewicz says, the Europeans are
not particularly interested.
</P>
<P>
   Western Europeans are reconciled to a larger European Union that
swallows large Poland and other countries of Central and Eastern
Europe, a European Union ambassador said. ``But if you want to kill
support in the E.U. for expansion and enlargement, just talk of
Turkey, Ukraine and Belarus,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What worries the Western Europeans as much as illegal
immigration is the smuggling of shoddy goods and unclean food, he
said, and Europe is pushing for big improvements in the Polish
customs service, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Poles will finally do what is necessary and apply full visa
regulations to Russians, Ukrainians and Belarussians as the
European Union is demanding, the ambassador said, as the Czechs
have already done.
</P>
<P>
   Orlowski says that despite the sometimes cogent arguments of
people like Cimoszewicz, Poland has no choice. With 70 percent of
its trade now with the European Union and only 10 percent with the
countries of the former Soviet Union, he said, Poland's future lies
with Europe and the West, not with the East.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Europeans are drawing the borderline of Europe for the
next 50 years and don't care about Ukraine, Belarus and Russia,''
he said. ``We think it's wrong, but what can we do? We don't really
have an option.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
