<SLUG> BC-PHILIPPINES-HOSTAGES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIVE HOSTAGES RELEASED IN PHILIPPINES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Changes end of 6th-last graf to prevent ambiguity.) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand _ Relieved, bitter and still frightened for
their companions, five foreign hostages were released by kidnappers
in the southern Philippines on Sunday for a reported $5 million
ransom.
</P>
<P>
   The releases were a half-step toward ending a strange
four-month-long standoff in which the tiny island of Jolo has been
flooded with ransom money both for the hostages and for a dozen
journalists who were seized and then released while trying to
interview them.
</P>
<P>
   Four of those freed Sunday were from the original group of 21
people kidnapped on April 23 at a nearby diving resort in Malaysia.
The fifth was a French television reporter who had been taken
captive when she trekked into the jungle to film them on July 9.
</P>
<P>
   Seven other Westerners remained hostages on the island,
including the last five kidnapped in Malaysia and two other members
of the same French television crew. A Filipino worker at the diving
resort was also being held, as well as 12 Filipino evangelical
Christians who walked into the mountains two months ago to pray
with the hostages.
</P>
<P>
   The kidnappers, a small band of gunmen calling themselves Abu
Sayyaf and saying that they were Muslim separatists, had already
received $5.5 million in ransom for 11 hostages who were released
earlier, the Philippine military said.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the government insists that no ransom has been paid,
but large amounts of cash are known to have been transferred to the
rebels. Kidnapping is a cottage industry in the southern
Philippines, and payoffs _ commonly described as ``room and board''
_ are part of the normal procedure.
</P>
<P>
   The kidnappers seem to have made a point on Sunday of dividing
the hostages, releasing a wife but not her husband, a father but
not his son, and a woman but not her boyfriend. The gunmen are
demanding more ransom for the remaining hostages.
</P>
<P>
   The chief government negotiator, Roberto Aventajado, said he
hoped the other hostages would be freed in the coming days but
added, ``There's still a lot of work to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   An earlier statement from the kidnappers said the partial
release Sunday was intended to discourage the government from a
military reprisal. It said further releases would depend on
additional payments.
</P>
<P>
   There was little joy among the hostages released Sunday as they
arrived by helicopter at the southern Philippine city of Zamboanga.
Some were in tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel relieved but we are not happy, because there are still
people left behind,'' said Marie Moarbes, 33, a French-Lebanese
woman. On videotapes taken during the captivity, she had been the
strong one, comforting her companions as they trembled at the sound
of distant gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   Still angry, as he had appeared on the videotapes, Werner
Wallert, 57, a German, said: ``My son is still there. You don't
expect me to be happy.'' An emissary said the father and son had
embraced and wept Sunday, each insisting that the other be the one
to leave. Wallert's wife, Renate, had been the first of the
hostages to be released, on July 17.
</P>
<P>
   The others freed Sunday were a French woman, Sonia Wendling, and
a South African, Monique Strydom, as well as the television
reporter, Maryse Burgot. They were to be flown to Libya, which was
the broker for the release. Libya was also reportedly paying the
ransom, which officials described as development aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Libyans, we know what we are doing,'' said the Libyan
ambassador, Saleem Adam, dismissing an accusation that his country
was trying to polish its international image by acting as
go-between. ``This is a humanitarian mission. It has no other
motivation.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Six Malaysians from the diving resort were freed earlier. One
French man, one South African, one German and two Finns, as well as
the Filipino resort worker, are still being held by the kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations have been difficult and seemingly amateurish,
with the Philippine side making sometimes contradictory and
counterproductive public statements and the kidnappers squabbling
among themselves, changing their demands and backing out of
agreements.
</P>
<P>
   A planned release was canceled two weeks ago when the gunmen
said they were afraid they would be attacked, and demanded more
money.
</P>
<P>
   There was another cancellation last week after two members of
the gang were arrested at a local bank when they tried to convert
$240,000 into Philippine pesos. The release proceeded Sunday after
the government released the two men, though not their money.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the earlier ransom money is reported to have been spent
on weapons, as the Abu Sayyaf band, originally numbering perhaps
200, has vigorously recruited new members to help guard the
hostages and secure them against a huge military deployment.
</P>
<P>
   While negotiators say they have assured the gunmen that they
will not be attacked, government officials have predicted strong
military action once the last of the hostages is freed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
