<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: COOPER LEAVING BEHIND A LEGACY OF GREATNESS
</HEADLINE>
  By IRA BERKOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Playing for Segovia in the plains in Spain, and for
Parma and Alcamo amid the hills of Italy, she had dreamed a fading
dream of one day playing professional basketball in America, maybe
in Los Angeles where she grew up in Watts _ or, well, anywhere in
the States, especially so that her mother, Mary Cobb, could see her
play regularly. So that her mother could see that she had truly
made something of herself.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, she said, she had wished to make her mother proud,
her mother who had raised her and her seven siblings on her own.
</P>
<P>
   She had been instrumental in the University of Southern
California making four trips to the Final Four, and winning two
national championships, but in 1987 there were no professional
leagues for women here. So she packed her sneakers and her
aspirations and went off to Europe to earn a living at what she did
best.
</P>
<P>
   The young woman had been playing in Europe for 10 years, been a
star there _ league-leading scorer or second in each of those years
_ but she was 33 years old. ``I knew that one day there would be a
women's professional basketball league in America,'' Cynthia Cooper
said, ``but I thought it would pass me by.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She was wrong. In January of 1997, Cynthia Cooper came home,
signing with Houston of the fledgling WNBA. Four seasons later, she
has established herself here as not only one of the most exciting
of contemporary athletes, but one of the grittiest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cynthia Cooper is the Michael Jordan, the Larry Bird, the
Magic Johnson of this league,'' Rich Adubato, the coach of the New
York Liberty, said. ``She's the type of person who will not let her
team lose.''
</P>
<P>
   He said this with full respect and full regrets, since Cooper
had just hit a twisting scoop shot to seal the victory against his
team in the first game of the WNBA finals Thursday in Madison
Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   In the league's four seasons, Cooper was the league's most
valuable player in the first two, and the MVP in each of its
championship series, all won by the Houston Comets. She had been
the league scoring leader in each of the first three seasons,
averaging more than 22 points a game each time.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of last week, with the Comets ahead by 1-0 in the
best-of-three title series against the Liberty, they had a chance
to win their fourth straight championship. The end of the road for
her, Cooper had said.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Cooper, the lithe, 5-foot-10-inch guard with the short
ponytail that appears to help propel her, had announced that she
was retiring after this season. No longer would crowds thrill to
her running one-hander in traffic that banks so sweetly off the
backboard, or see her move as stealthily as a fox to a hen's egg as
she picks off a pass.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper was reflecting on this Saturday morning, shortly before
Game 2 of the WNBA finals in Houston. What will she do when she
retires? Could she ever duplicate the excitement of basketball?
``No,'' she said, ``and I don't expect to. I don't think anything
can duplicate playing before 20,000 people, who are screaming for
you or at you. And nothing can duplicate the pressure that you feel
building before a big game like this, or being on the free-throw
line and having to make important free throws, or the big shot.''
</P>
<P>
   She untied a sneaker to relieve a cramp. ``But it's time to move
on,'' she said. ``I'll just have to redirect my energies beyond the
basketball court. I have a lot of interests. I might try
broadcasting or coaching. I have a foundation that I want to spend
more time with.'' She was referring to the Mary Cobb's Building
Dreams Foundation, which helps raise funds for breast cancer
research. She is also involved with many inner-city youth programs.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in Game 2 on Saturday, when the crunch came, she rose in
customary fashion to the occasion. She sank a 3-point shot with
21.5 seconds to go in the game to tie it at 64-64 and send it into
overtime. In the extra five-minute period, she scored on a drive
and one of her patented runners _ she finished with 25 points _ to
help give the Comets a lead they would not relinquish in their
79-73 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Then, fittingly, she grabbed a defensive rebound with just
seconds to go and she dribbled out the clock. When the buzzer
blared, she ran in little circles, and into the crowd, cradling the
ball in one hand and with the other waving four fingers, indicating
the number of WNBA titles won.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the Comets' victory celebration, as the confetti rained
onto the court like the deluge on Noah's ark, one recalled a moment
before the game. In the locker room, Cooper had talked about some
tough times, last year being one of the worst, when both her mother
and a dear friend and teammate, Kim Perrot, had died of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a toll on you,'' Cooper said. ``I can just see mom
jumping up and down when we won our championships, when she saw me
being successful, how much she'd love to have been here now.''
Cooper paused. ``I'd better stop before I start crying. ... I'm,
I'm just eternally grateful. ...''
</P>
<P>
   She turned away. ``OK,'' she said, her voice cracking slightly,
``that's enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite. But 40 game-minutes later _ no, 45 minutes, including
the overtime _ it was, finally, enough.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
