<SLUG> BC-TEN-HAMLET-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORMAN WINS U.S. OPEN TUNEUP BUT FEELS FOR A FRIEND
</HEADLINE>
  By JENNY KELLNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COMMACK, N.Y. _ When the double fault smacked into the net to
end his match Sunday afternoon, Magnus Norman frowned, picked at
his racket strings and walked slowly toward the net, his head down.
</P>
<P>
   Norman had not lost. He had just had a great tuneup for the U.S.
Open, staving off two championship points and winning his second
straight Hamlet Cup title, 6-3, 5-7, 7-5. But on the other side of
the net stood his close friend Thomas Enqvist, whom he had beaten
for the first time in five meetings and who had leg cramps during
the final two games of the match.
</P>
<P>
   The two exchanged a few words in Swedish before walking off the
court together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `This is not the way I wanted to beat you,''' said
Norman, who a few moments later was smiling and waving to his many
fans in the sellout crowd of 5,000. ``He said, `You deserve it.'''
</P>
<P>
   As Enqvist put it: ``I was close to winning, but I was also
close to losing in two straight sets. Too many unforced errors, too
many double faults.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Enqvist, 26, who will face the clay-court specialist
Mariano Puerta of Argentina in the first round of the U.S. Open as
the seventh-seeded player, had 11 double faults and 60 unforced
errors in the final _ this after not dropping a set on the way to
the final.
</P>
<P>
   Norman, 24, who made it to the fourth round of the U.S. Open
last year before retiring with a back injury, is seeded third this
year. He was quick to pounce Sunday, electing to receive and
getting the break he needed in the first game when Enqvist made
three straight unforced forehand errors.
</P>
<P>
   The mistakes continued to pile up for Enqvist, who served up
more double faults (five) than aces (four) in the first set and
handed point after point to Norman with unforced errors from both
his forehand and his backhand. Enqvist, seeded third here, had only
one chance to break Norman in the first set, during the fourth
game, but sent his backhand into the net to go back to deuce before
losing the game. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Norman quickly went up a break in the fourth game of the second
set on Enqvist's sixth double fault of the match and was serving
for the match at 5-3 when things inexplicably flip-flopped. Ahead
by 30-0, Norman got a bad bounce off the tape, then mis-hit a
forehand after an extended rally and hit two backhands into the net
to give Enqvist his first break.
</P>
<P>
   Enqvist, his forehands finally finding their mark, then ripped
through the next three games to take the second set, and went up by
5-2 in the third. But Norman stubbornly dug in, breaking back as
Enqvist, his upper left thigh beginning to cramp, was serving for
the match. Norman fought off two match points after going down by
30-40 on his serve, and then tied it at 5-5 on another Enqvist
double fault. He broke Enqvist again in the 10th game, on a double
fault, and then went ahead, 6-5, firing three aces along the way.
</P>
<P>
   After getting treatment from Alex Stober, the ATP trainer,
Enqvist was still having trouble with his first serve. Fighting off
one match point with a brilliant volley, Enqvist double-faulted
once, then twice, to hand Norman the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the cramps; it really didn't bother me,'' Enqvist
said. ``I lost because I was not able to put the match together.
Magnus is a very tough player''
</P>
<P>
   Norman, who with the victory earned his fourth title in five
finals this year, said he felt confident heading into this week's
Grand Slam event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great _ I couldn't ask for a better warm-up for the
Open,'' said Norman, who will face the baseliner Paul Goldstein in
the first round of the Open, which begins Monday. ``I got a lot of
confidence and I know I can build on that. I know I can go all the
way, but I'm only looking at the first match right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
