<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Assembly Line to Be Added At Daimler Plant in Alabama
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler plans to announce Monday that it will nearly
double production in Alabama, adding another assembly line close to
the site where it already builds Mercedes M-Class sport utility
vehicles, auto industry officials and consultants said over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Auto industry consultants and auto parts suppliers said that the
company would make a so-called crossover vehicle that would combine
the features of a minivan and the M-Class sport utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Offer Is Seen for London Exchange
</P>
<P>
   OM Gruppen, which runs the Stockholm stock exchange, is expected
to make a formal offer, which could include a hostile bid, for the
London Stock Exchange, which rejected an informal $1.18 billion
offer last week, executives close to the discussions said.
</P>
<P>
   A Mayor Backs a Web Business
</P>
<P>
   More than 750 local governments use the Web site operated by
NetClerk to put the construction-permit process online. But so far,
only the mayor of San Francisco, Willie Brown, has become part of
NetClerk's advertising campaign. Last week, NetClerk put a picture
of Brown and the city's seal on its Web site, www.netclerk.com,
along with a letter the mayor had written praising the company for,
among other things, helping reduce lines at city hall.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint in a Wireless Joint Venture
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's wireless unit and the Internet incubator Ecompanies
plan to announce a venture Monday to finance start-up companies in
wireless communications. The venture, Ecompanies Wireless, will
receive a $15 million investment from Sprint's wireless unit,
Sprint PCS.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Revamps Its Ads
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter may still measure success one
investor at a time, but in a new ad campaign starting this week,
its brokerage unit is dropping the slogan it has used for more than
a decade and is centering its $150 million advertising budget on a
blunter approach. The ads take dead aim at electronic brokerage
firms.
</P>
<P>
   A study to be released Monday found that a majority of online
advertisements had short life spans, running three weeks or less.
</P>
<P>
   Windows Software List Scrutinized
</P>
<P>
   The ruling against Microsoft said a crucial barrier confronting
the company's potential competitors were the 70,000 programs
written to run solely on the Windows operating system. But Richard
B. McKenzie, an economist, contends that there are probably fewer
than 10,000 Windows programs in use today. The lower figure
indicates that Microsoft is not the impregnable fortress depicted
at its trial, McKenzie writes in a paper.
</P>
<P>
   New Math in MSNBC's Billboards
</P>
<P>
   The cable network MSNBC has placed two billboards on the West
Side Highway in Manhattan that promote its main nighttime news
program and its host, Brian Williams, and boast of 42 million
viewers. Executives at some of MSNBC's rivals find the signs a bit
annoying because of the large ratings figure, which uses some
inventive arithmetic.
</P>
<P>
   Auction Uncovers Fissures in Europe
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the bidding ended in Germany's auction of new
wireless licenses, even devoted market enthusiasts have started to
wonder whether this is the way to go. Six companies bid a total $46
billion for licenses. Investors have been dumping shares of the
winners, and Standard &AMP; Poor's warned that it would probably lower
most of the companies' credit ratings. The auction also uncovered
an uneven playing field in Europe.
</P>
</TEXT>
