<DOCNO> NYT20000827.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3557 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-E-COMMERCE-COLUMN-NYT     08-27 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-COMMERCE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-COMMERCE: COMPANIES LEARNING HOW TO PERSONALIZE SERVICE ONLINE
</HEADLINE>
 By SUSAN STELLIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
  Ask a handful of Internet executives to define the term
``personalization,'' and invariably the conversation turns to the
analogy of a shopkeeper who knows not only his customers' names,
but how much they can afford to spend and what size shirt they
wear.
<TEXT>
<P>
   This old-fashioned ideal of personalized service _ albeit,
updated with new economy motives _ is the next hurdle for Internet
companies trying to achieve profitability in an increasingly
competitive environment.
</P>
<P>
   What this means in practice is that rather than displaying the
same set of pages to every visitor, a Web site would present
different information to each customer based on the person's data
profile. A person who has shown online interest in classical music
might be presented with a special price on Bach compact discs,
whereas someone who has bought a Britney Spears CD might be offered
a discount on N'Sync.
</P>
<P>
   This type of personalized experience, alternatively described as
``one to one marketing'' or ``targeted merchandising,'' has long
been touted as one of the key benefits of the Web. But so far, very
few Internet companies have been able to take advantage of this
potential, mainly because the technologies for delivering it are
still in the early stages of development.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the industry is gradually catching up to the hype
surrounding personalization, as a growing number of companies have
installed tools enabling them to present customized Web pages _ if
not to a single individual, then at least to groups that have been
identified as having a similar profile. This trend is going to
raise the ante for companies doing business online, both in terms
of investors' and customers' expectations. It is also going to
raise new privacy issues concerning what type of information is
collected about consumers and how that data is used.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, some degree of personalization has existed for years
online, most notably through sites like Yahoo or Excite, which
allow members to create a page that displays information based on
preferences they have entered, like stock symbols or categories of
news. That type of service is now referred to as ``customization,''
whereas the techniques known as ``personalization'' are based on
information companies have more discreetly gathered about
consumers, like their purchase history or the Web pages they have
viewed.
</P>
<P>
   Cormac Foster, an analyst at the research firm Jupiter
Communications, said the difference involves explicit versus
implicit data. ``Customization is giving users what they've told
you they want,'' he said, ``and personalization is anticipating
what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, one of the leaders in the personalization
arena is Amazon.com, which began its efforts in 1997 with a ``book
matcher'' feature. To use that feature, customers had to fill out a
form indicating their interests, and the system would match them
with books tailored to their entries. The problem with that
feature, according to Josh Petersen, Amazon's director of
personalization, was that it required too much work on the user's
part.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't have had to walk into a store of old and fill out
a questionnaire,'' Petersen said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Amazon focused its efforts on building a system
based on implicit data, like a customer's past purchases, which now
feeds into the site's ``New for You'' and ``Recommendations''
features. Using technology primarily developed by Amazon, these
services recommend products to customers based on algorithms that
take into account factors like the ratings a customer has assigned
various products on the site and the purchasing patterns of
customers with similar profiles.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce the impact of errant data, Amazon allows users to
exclude certain purchases from their profile; that way, a Pokemon
game purchased for a niece will not skew a pattern of buying
mystery novels and Woody Allen videos. The system also makes some
automatic assumptions, like excluding gift-wrapped items.
</P>
<P>
   John Samuel, vice president of interactive marketing for AMR's
American Airlines, would be the first to agree that current
implementations of personalization technologies are still in their
infancy. American overhauled its AA.com Web site in 1998, with a
new version that allows the site to present pages that have been
tailored for each individual.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel said the company had a head start in its personalization
efforts because of its AAdvantage frequent-flier program, which has
gathered information about 40 million members. American uses that
information, as well as data collected from customers who fill out
a profile online, to tailor the offers that customers see when they
visit the company's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, that translates to knowing someone is in college
versus knowing someone is retired or often flies business class,''
Samuel said. ``The communication to those customers should be very
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuel said that American has been careful to err on the side of
being explicit about collecting data, which is why the company asks
customers to fill out a profile, even if that information is easy
to deduce from an individual's travel history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not be hard for us to infer a customer's home
airport,'' he said. ``But we still ask on the Web site.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for American Airlines and other companies
experimenting with this level of personalization will be
negotiating a delicate balance between providing consumers with
services and offers they want, and appearing to know too much and
risk scaring those customers away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know a lot, and our customers know we know a lot,'' Samuels
said. The question is, ``What permission do we have from the
customer to use that knowledge?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-00 2107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
