<HEADER>
A3558 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GRIFFEY0828-COX     08-27 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIFFEY0828-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reds draw the fans for all the wrong reasons
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They are the best road draw in the game, better than
the Yankees or Braves, the Cowboys or the Ice Capades, a sum of 2.4
million people around the country inexorably drawn to the
Cincinnati Reds this season.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. has done that, his appeal to a new league and
its new cities undeniable, even if that appeal has changed as the
summer has drawn on. If advance sales were linked to the arrival in
the National League of one of the game's biggest stars, fans now
come to view the Reds not for who they are but what they aren't.
</P>
<P>
   What is today's folly? What's Junior's gripe today? What has
gone wrong now? It wasn't supposed to be this way.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves and Reds play the first of four tonight at Turner
Field in his first and only Atlanta appearance of the season. In
April, this series was gigantic. Today with the Reds (64-65)
struggling just to maintain a .500 record, none of the four games
is sold out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get on a roll and get a winning streak going, we've got
a shot,'' said outfielder Dante Bichette.
</P>
<P>
   There is little reason to believe. The Reds, who took two of
three in Florida over the weekend, just recently lost seven of nine
to bottom-feeders Milwaukee, Pittsburgh and Philadelphia, including
a three-game sweep by the Brewers. They are 31-34 at Cinergy Field,
the only team with a winning road record and losing home record.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey has been criticized and he has bristled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's human,'' he said. ``You're not some piece of
meat.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds have gone 5-5 against NL Central front-runner St. Louis
(while being outscored 47-55) but two of those wins belong to the
departed Denny Neagle. Nor have the Reds seen the Cardinals since
they fortified themselves with Will Clark, Carlos Hernandez and
Mike Timlin. Cincinnati comes to Atlanta trailing the Cards by
8-1/2 games and are 12-1/2 back for the wild card.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing we have going for us is we have the final three
games of the year with the Cardinals,'' general manager Jim Bowden
said. ``If we're within three games going into that series and we
sweep, we're in the postseason.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden also punctuated his week by hanging his head to close to
the netting of the batting cage and took a foul face to the face,
drawing blood. Reds Fever.
</P>
<P>
   It had all begun so warmly. The franchise made a marketing
campaign of saluting the 10th and 25th anniversaries of Reds
championship teams of 1990 and 1975. Tony Perez and Sparky Anderson
were going to be inducted into the Hall of Fame and broadcaster
Marty Brennaman was voted the Ford C. Frick Award, getting him into
Cooperstown too.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly every publication with a national circulation
picked the Reds to win the Central, the club started coolly. Then
in June, it fell apart. Between June 5 and July 5, Cincinnati went
from a modest one-game divisional lead to trailing St. Louis by 10.
Neagle was dealt to the New York Yankees and the clubhouse wondered
why. Captain Barry Larkin was dealt to the New York Mets, refused
to go and the clubhouse wondered about Bowden's medication.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest lightning rod has been Griffey, who has hopped
from one loud issue to another. While he reached 100 RBIs in the
second-shortest time in his career, public opinion had waned early
in the season, when he hit just .212 over the first two months. A
Cincinnati Enquirer poll, when asking who was to blame for this
season, found only 4 percent of respondents blame Griffey (Bowden
led with 35 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Yet ranked fourth in NL RBIs and six in homers (35), Griffey
found his performance severely questioned for perhaps the first
time in his career and has not enjoyed the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when you're mistreated and you say something, they
tell you to stop whining,'' Griffey said. ``It ain't about whining.
If you get mistreated at a 9-to-5 job, when you say something, they
don't say you're whining. But since it's me or any other athlete
who says something, that's what they say.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Griffey has found himself in headlines all
year. He pushed the Reds to un-retire Perez's No. 24 so he might
where it, until Perez finally spoke out on how the episode hurt
him. (Griffey wears No. 30, his father's old number).
</P>
<P>
   He was vilified back in Seattle for manipulating the Mariners to
trade him. He bristled again when asked why his old team is playing
better without him. The ESPN story broke, charging Griffey had been
in contact with the station for showing less Junior highlights and
more involving St. Louis' Jim Edmonds. Junior grappled briefly in
the dugout with his father, the team's bench coach, after he was
pulled from a game.
</P>
<P>
   Then came last week's dust-up with Brennaman, a local legend in
his 26th year calling Reds games. Criticized on the air by
Brennaman for not running out what he thought to be a potential
double, Griffey stopped on his way to batting practice Wednesday to
challenge his opinion. Not wisely, Griffey did so right in front of
the writers who cover the team daily.
</P>
<P>
   Unfairly or not, the residual of all this has been to identify
Griffey as image-obsessed and thin-skinned. He joshed about
retaining Johnny Cochran to defend him. He said ``I play better
when I stir things up.'' But in a season where the Reds are
celebrating their rich past, a current team has fallen far short of
its own expectations, which hurts most of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has some type of feelings,'' Griffey said. ``Some
people block it out and some can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
