<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UP NEXT, VARGAS VS. TRINIDAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ People are beginning to believe Fernando Vargas
could actually beat Felix Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   A victory over capable but overmatched Ross Thompson doesn't
mean much in boxing terms. Even a victory as emphatic as the IBF
junior middleweight champion's fourth-round stoppage here on an
electric Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   However, that, combined with impressive victories over Ike
Quartey, Raul Marquez and Yory Boy Campas and a gutsy decision over
Winky Wright, have lifted Vargas to the top of his field. This all
comes at the age of 22 _ after a mere 20 fights _ and makes his
tentative title-unification bout with Trinidad on Dec. 2 as
compelling as any in boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Fascinating questions abound:
</P>
<P>
   Is Trinidad too experienced for Vargas, as he was against David
Reid? How will Vargas react if he encounters a crisis? Can Vargas
handle Trinidad's punching power? Is Trinidad too strong for
Vargas?
</P>
<P>
   Is Vargas technically too efficient for Trinidad? Is Vargas too
strong for Trindad? If Vargas puts Trinidad down early in the
fight, will he be able to put him away? Is it simply Vargas' time?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Vargas would say the answer to that last question is
yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will doubt me again,'' he said. ``If you analyze it, I
definitely have better legs than him, I'm a better boxer than him
in the sense of being intelligent, using my legs, my ring
generalship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's say the power is equal, although I don't think so. I've
been at 154 (pounds) longer. And I think I'm stronger than he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``... I just think I'm a more well-rounded fighter than he is
regardless of experience. I respect him. He's a great fighter. I
just know I can beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   Vargas' performance against Thompson was just what he needed
going into the Trinidad fight.
</P>
<P>
   His confidence didn't need a boost but it got one anyway. That
kind of annihilation of a No.1 contender _ three knockdowns before
the referee stopped the fight _ has that affect on a fighter.
</P>
<P>
   And the victory added to Vargas' already considerable
credibility. He'll probably be an underdog because of the relative
inexperience, but the odds just got a little tighter.
</P>
<P>
   Also, he surely won more fans, who yearn for such violent
destruction. The crowd at Mandalay Bay Resort and Casino went nuts
Saturday as Vargas ripped Thompson apart. Certainly, the same thing
must have happened in living rooms across the country.
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth, a CBS Sportsline poll asked after
Saturday's fight who of the following seven nonheavyweight fighters
is the best in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The results: Roy Jones Jr., 48.9 percent; Trinidad, 16.7;
Vargas, 15.7, Shane Mosley, 8.4, Oscar De La Hoya 5.9, Naseem Hamed
3.4 and Zab Judah, 1.0.
</P>
<P>
   That Vargas and Trinidad are so close in the minds of fans is a
testament as to how far Vargas has come in a very short time.
</P>
<P>
   He and Trinidad are both hard-punching, aggressive, exciting,
supremely confident champions who could combine to create the
classic bout so many had hoped De La Hoya-Trinidad would be. All
the ingredients are there:
</P>
<P>
   NEGOTIATIONS: Vargas and Trinidad have agreed to meet but no one
has signed a contract. An announcement could come within a few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   OLD FRIENDS: Vargas met Trinidad while traveling as a young
amateur and the two hit it off. They remain friends _ for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a nice guy, a great human being'' Vargas said. ``But in
the ring, there are no friends. When we fight, it will be like two
lions in there fighting over two steaks _ his belt (WBA) and my
belt.''
</P>
<P>
   FORGIVENESS: The anger melted away after Saturday's fight.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas, livid over Thompson's prefight behavior, was impressed
that the challenger showed up at the postfight news conference
after such a beating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy to get up there after being defeated like that.
He showed me he's a man,'' Vargas said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who said repeatedly before the fight that Vargas is
overrated, admitted he was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be one of the top fighters,'' Thompson said.
``His speed is much better than I thought. Fernando is a true
warrior, a true champion.''
</P>
<P>
   MR. GARCIA: Many marvel at Vargas' calm demeanor in the ring,
particularly in light of his age.
</P>
<P>
   That trait can be attributed in part to his soft-spoken trainer,
Eduardo Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Thompson's behavior, Vargas lost his cool Saturday
more than in any other fight. It was Garcia who reeled him back in.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Hey, what's going on? Be intelligent first and then
be brave,''' Vargas recalled. ``He said, `Take your time and
eventually you'll get this guy.' And I did.''
</P>
<P>
   TYSON SIGHTING: Mike Tyson, apparently a fan of Vargas, asked in
Vargas' dressing room prior to the fight whether he could accompany
the junior middleweight champ into the ring on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas said with a laugh that he had no choice, a reference to
the former heavyweight title holder's imposing presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `Hey, no one is going to tell you you can't,'''
Vargas said.
</P>
<P>
   VARGAS-DE LA HOYA? Vargas gave De La Hoya a bit more of his own
medicine at the postfight news conference, saying he'd never fight
De La Hoya because ``I want to fight the best fighters out there
and he's not one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   However, one thing could change his mind: money.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked immediately after he made those statements what he
would do if he received the right offer to fight his rival.
</P>
<P>
   He paused and then said with a sheepish grin, ``Well, we'd have
to sit down at the table.''
</P>
<P>
   The hundred or so people at the news conference laughed at the
slightly awkward situation and Vargas responded with a big smile:
``Hey, I'm a businessman, too.''
</P>
<P>
   DE LA HOYA-MOSLEY: Mosley wants to know this week whether De La
Hoya is interested in a rematch of their June bout at Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya has been busier with his singing career and trying to
sort out a reportedly strained relationship with his promoter, Bob
Arum, than negotiating with Mosley's people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to know what he wants to do,'' said Norman Horton,
Mosley's publicist. ``If he doesn't want to fight, then we'll move
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Mosley reportedly will fight Arturo Gatti in December if he
doesn't reach terms with De La Hoya. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Michael Rosenthal's boxing column appears Mondays in the Daily
News. He can be reached at (818) 713-3618 or on the Internet at
boxwriteraol.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
