<HEADLINE>
WIND RIVER SYSTEMS AGREES TO ACQUISITION OF ICESOFT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   Wind River Systems, the maker of
software that is embedded in dozens of digital devices, is expected
to announce on Monday that it has agreed to acquire ICEsoft, a
Norwegian developer of Web-browsing software for Internet
appliances, for $24.5 million in cash.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The deal will allow Wind River, based in Alameda, Calif., to
integrate Internet browsing functions into devices like set-top
boxes, digital televisions, Web phones and other devices. Wind
River's embedded software powers devices like Sony's Network
Walkman NW-E3, Hewlett-Packard's printers and Eastman Kodak's
digital cameras. The software is embedded into microchips that are
designed by companies like Intel and Hitachi.
</P>
<P>
   ``The era of smart, connected devices is just beginning,'' said
Tom St. Dennis, the president and chief executive of Wind River.
``Already millions and every soon billions of devices will be
connected to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ICEsoft, based in Bergen, Norway, developed a highly popular Web
browser for devices with limited computing power called ICE
Browser. The program is written in Java, the software standard
developed by Sun Microsystems, and supports XML, a type of software
coding that will allow for the seamless interchange of all sorts of
dynamic data across different computer programs. ICEsoft will
continue to operate in Bergen. Wind River has 15 other offices in
Europe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
