<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORGAN-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORGAN STANLEY DROPS A FAMILIAR IMAGE TO TAKE AIM AT ONLINE
BROKERAGE FIRMS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK McGEEHAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Remember those grainy commercials that showed a
white-haired actor portraying a brokerage firm executive that many
people mistook for the real Dean Witter? Well, Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter &AMP; Co. wants you to forget them.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley may still measure success one investor at a time,
but the firm has a more urgent message for investors in the
Internet age: ``Move your money.'' In a new ad campaign coming this
week to newspapers, magazine and TV screens, Morgan Stanley's
brokerage unit is dropping the slogan it has used for more than a
decade and is centering its $150 million advertising budget on a
bolder, blunter approach.
</P>
<P>
   Under the theme ``Well connected,'' the ads take dead aim at the
electronic brokerage firms that have flooded the airwaves with
pitches for stock trading at discounted prices. They equate online
brokerage firms with con men and depict investors being led by them
onto paths that dead-end in the woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a departure from some of the ethereal, aspirational
images out there,'' said Bob Sloss, the firm's executive vice
president for brokerage marketing. Sloss said the firm's research
showed that consumers recalled the ads of traditional brokerage
firms but had trouble distinguishing among their messages.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Internet came along and spawned a new breed of
competitors, most brokerage firms relied on images of trust and
wisdom. In the 1980s, Dean Witter briefly used the slogan ``You
look like you just heard from Dean Witter,'' while a defunct
competitor used ``When E.F. Hutton speaks, people listen.''
</P>
<P>
   That sameness was shattered in the late 1990s by big-spending
newcomers, like the ETrade Group and Ameritrade Holdings. Those
electronic brokers built their brands with irreverent ads mocking
stockbrokers and treating stock trading like a sport.
</P>
<P>
   Even Morgan Stanley joined in the fun. Two years ago, it ran a
separate online brokerage operation named Discover Brokerage
Direct, after the firm's Discover credit card. Discover Brokerage
ran a pair of popular TV ads that depicted a truck driver who had
bought his own island with his stock-trading profits and a
teen-ager who had his own helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   Those ads incurred the wrath of Arthur Levitt, the chairman of
the Securities and Exchange Commission. Levitt said they were
inappropriate and could create false expectations of instant riches
among small investors, and the commission began scrutinizing online
brokerage firm ads. (Last week, ETrade, which has been sued for
advertising said to be deceptive, disclosed that regulators were
screening its ads before they were published or broadcast.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw that, and we definitely addressed that head on,'' Sloss
said, referring to the regulators' displeasure.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, after a rival securities firm, Merrill Lynch,
announced that it would offer online trading, Morgan Stanley folded
Discover Brokerage into its traditional brokerage operation and
renamed it Morgan Stanley Dean Witter Online. The first ads for the
renamed unit struck a decidedly more conservative tone, cautioning
investors to ``know your source'' of stock tips.
</P>
<P>
   The new ads, led by one bearing the headline ``Life's not
fair,'' tell investors that there are no shortcuts to investment
success. The ads lay out the resources the firm has that the
upstarts do not, like proprietary stock research and a high ranking
as an underwriter of technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we can repatriate some of that group of investors who
thought that full-service brokers could not meet their needs,''
Sloss said.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, some ads show a younger and more diverse group of
faces than those that usually appear in ads for Wall Street firms.
But the mood is not as upbeat as in a spot for, say, Gap khakis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not mollycoddling people,'' said Jeff Finkler, executive
creative director at Leo Burnett USA. in Chicago, which created the
ads. ``We're going to be very blunt. Nowhere is there a vague
promise of some promised land.''
</P>
<P>
   Also absent is any glimpse of a Morgan Stanley broker, a marked
contrast to the TV and print ads Merrill Lynch started running this
year. Merrill's ads profile particular brokers and clients to
emphasize that providing advice to individuals and small businesses
is the heart of its brokerage business.
</P>
<P>
   Sloss said the brokers will get more attention after the first
round of ads in the campaign. He described the ``well connected''
theme as a ``platform'' that could be part of Morgan Stanley's
advertising for years to come, as the firm evolves and incorporates
new technology, like access to its services from cellular phones
and other wireless devices.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the firm is taking a risk in shifting away from a
tried-and-true advertising formula, said Bruce Brittain, president
of Brittain Associates, a marketing consulting firm in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers tend to think of Morgan Stanley before most other
financial services companies ``because of their long-standing
campaign, which stuck with a particular theme,'' he said. ``It's
very well known and highly associative. If they do walk away from
that, I think they're giving up a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The long-running ads with an actor playing a brokerage firm
chief became so ingrained in the popular consciousness that they
were the object of a classic parody on ``Saturday Night Live.''
Even Finkler seemed to have been flattered by the imitation, which
he called ``hilarious.''
</P>
<P>
   Sloss said the firm intended to work the ``one investor at a
time'' line into some of the new ads. More than 10 print ads have
been created to promote different aspects of the firm's business to
different audiences. The headline on one is ``Hear the word on the
street before it's on the street.'' Another reads: ``The new old
boys' club. Less old. Less boys.''
</P>
<P>
   The TV ads will make their debut next weekend during the
broadcast of the U.S. Open tennis tournament, Sloss said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-00 2132EDT &QL; 
