<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-ADS-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME IS SHORT FOR ADS AT TOP OF WEB PAGES
</HEADLINE>
 By SUSAN STELLIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an effort to give media planners more information about
advertising patterns online, a study to be released on Monday found
that a majority of online advertisements had short life spans,
running three weeks or less.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in keeping with the short attention spans of most
Internet users, 23.7 percent of all online advertisements run one
week, while 16 percent run two weeks, and 11.9 percent run three
weeks, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, most advertisers reach a very small audience, the
study said, with a huge majority getting less than a 0.01 percent
share among all online advertisements running at a particular time.
</P>
<P>
   The study, done by AdRelevance, a unit of the Internet measuring
service Media Metrix, analyzed standard ad banners on the top 500
Web sites, as determined by Media Metrix, between July 1999 and
June 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Buchwalter, vice president for media research for
AdRelevance and an author of the study, said the findings indicated
that advertisers were using online ads more for short-term direct
marketing than to create brand awareness. ``As time goes by,'' he
said, ``the average duration of campaigns will start increasing as
people understand more about the brand impact.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey did find differences in the length of online
campaigns run by various industries. While the auto industry
scheduled online ads to run the longest, an average 7.8 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that the average online ad campaign in the
second quarter of 2000 registered 7,265,000 impressions, a measure
of the number of times an ad is viewed. But more than half of all
advertisers ran campaigns that registered fewer than 44,000
impressions in the second quarter, equivalent to about 0.0003
percent of all ads displayed in that period on a site like Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   Buchwalter said that over all, the study's findings reflected
the fact that advertisers were still learning what works best in a
relatively new medium. ``With all the growth that is happening in
the online ad industry,'' he said, ``It's still in its infancy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-00 2140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000827.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3574 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-DIVERSITY-AZR &LR;      08-27 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIVERSITY-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-DIVERSITY-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    DIVERSITY ISSUE SPLITS SCOTTSDALE(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By CHIP SCUTARI(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A city office designed to improve race relations in Scottsdale
has spent nearly $1.2 million in three years to tout diversity, but
critics say it's more spin than substance.
</P>
<P>
   And next month, the City Council will appoint its first Human
Relations Commission, an arm of the office, but only 10 citizens -
including three Blacks and apparently no Hispanics - have applied
for the seven volunteer positions.
</P>
<P>
   Sales representative Kim Bass, 33, a five-year resident, hopes
to be one of the minorities named to the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that the African-American community be
represented on this board,'' she said. ``I'd like to see more
minorities living in Scottsdale.''
</P>
<P>
   Scottsdale's Diversity and Dialogue Office - the first in the
Valley - was created in 1998 after a lawsuit alleging that police
racism sparked a threat of protest at the nationally known Phoenix
Open golf tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Diversity Director Don Logan oversees a $400,000 annual budget
and a three-person staff. He says the office does diversity
training, education and recruiting, handles discrimination
complaints and sponsors multicultural events. Critics - White,
Black and Hispanic - call the office an overreaction to the
perception of Scottsdale as an unfriendly place for minorities. The
city's population is about 91 percent White, 6 percent Hispanic and
less than 2 percent African-American, Native American or
Asian-American. Logan says he expects the city's volunteer
commission to mirror Scottsdale's White majority.
</P>
<P>
   Resident Sandra Rembrandt calls the diversity office a ``snow
job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, he (Don Logan) has absolutely no
integrity when it comes to looking at and addressing the problems
of ethnic minorities in Scottsdale,'' said Rembrandt, a Black
entrepreneur who runs a Web site devoted to health care issues for
minorities. ``He doesn't live in this community. You have people in
this community who would do this job for free.''
</P>
<P>
   Logan, a Chandler resident who is Black, said the ``window
dressing'' criticism is inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   Logan said some critics expect him to be especially tough on the
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's not my style. I'm doing this job because I'm
sincere,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Logan, a 21-year city employee who is paid $84,000 a year,
attends police internal affairs briefings every Wednesday. He says
his office deals in intangibles, such as ``community dialogues,''
that can't be measured. Logan has to sign off on every city
employee who's slated to be fired. He said he prevented the
dismissals of two Hispanic employees for visiting X-rated web sites
because White employees had done the same thing and received a
lesser penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Though Logan stepped up for those men, Jess Torrez said Logan
misled him. Torrez, a former city police officer, was awarded
$100,000 in 1997 after he sued, arguing that he was fired for
exposing racism in the department. Logan worked in the city
manager's office at the time, but part of his job dealt with
diversity issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don Logan guaranteed me I would not get fired, and the day
after I went to see him I was fired,'' Torrez said. ``Don Logan is
a schmoozer; he's a token mouthpiece.''
</P>
<P>
   Logan said he didn't know Torrez was going to be fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Torrez's termination had nothing to do with his meeting
with me,'' he said. The diversity office was created three months
after Torrez's trial.
</P>
<P>
   Logan has kept a low profile in the city's most recent racial
controversy, and he's defending the city. In July, 10 city
employees filed a $10million lawsuit claiming deliberate
mistreatment of Hispanic workers at the city-owned WestWorld horse
and entertainment park.
</P>
<P>
   Long-time Scottsdale activist Frances Young says the diversity
office is missing its mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't need a cultural diversity office to put on a Cinco
de Mayo lunch or to put on an MLK breakfast,'' she said ``I would
love for someone in the city to admit there are problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The diversity office's first annual report, released this
summer, was criticized because it carried portraits of minority
people who don't live or work in Scottsdale. Logan said using a
commercial photo collection saved the city $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   City Council members have sharply different views of the office.
Councilman George Zraket calls it a waste of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see these so-called accomplishments having a value of
$1 million to the taxpayers,'' Zraket said. ``To me, these are
simple tasks that could be done by one part-time employee.''
</P>
<P>
   But David Ortega, elected last spring as the first Hispanic on
City Council, said the department is ``essential.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of the human need side of the city,'' Ortega said.
``I don't get involved in racial politics, but Scottsdale has a
large influx of people from diverse backgrounds. This office should
not be viewed as public relations.''
</P>
<P>
   Retiring Scottsdale City Manager Dick Bowers, who pushed for the
creation of the diversity, said criticism is part of being a trend
setter in government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most major corporations have a diversity office. And they
don't do it for the return on investment,'' he said. ``We're better
off today.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at chip.scutari(a)arizonarepublic.com or at
(602) 444-7482.
</P>
<P>
   Republic reporter Hernan Rozemberg contributed to this article.
</P>
</TEXT>
