<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-CUBS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVEN A HIT FOR DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The pennant race was in other cities while the Chicago
Cubs and Dodgers were at Wrigley Field, but that doesn't mean there
can't be a little edge.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides were agitated with the other for pitches that seemed
to have intent and it started when Dodgers' fill-in left fielder
Bruce Aven hit his second homer Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   And though the game dragged nearly four hours and the Cubs
bullpen showed exactly why general manager Ed Lynch was fired
earlier this season, there was still plenty of emotion after the
Dodgers' 7-6 victory in 10 innings in the series finale. The
winning run scored on a two-out wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The commotion began when Cubs starter Kerry Wood _ who struck
out 11 in seven innings only to have the bullpen blow it _ allowed
a two-run homer to Aven in the fifth, pulling the Dodgers to within
5-3. Wood followed with a pitch he threw behind Alex Cora's head,
the ball actually bouncing off his bat.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the inning, Dodgers right-hander Ismael Valdes
threw his first pitch high and inside to Mark Grace. Home plate
umpire Mark Wegner warned the benches, causing Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson to argue. He was ejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is head-hunting, behind him, and (Wegner) does nothing,''
Johnson said of Wood's pitch. ``My guy comes (inside) and it's a
warning. When you throw (behind the head), that's totally out of
line.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes' 3-1 pitch to Grace plunked the first baseman on the
shoulder and earned a stunned Valdes and bench coach Jim Tracy, the
acting manager, ejections of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can gain respect, but not by throwing at the head of
hitters,'' said Valdes, whose ejection came after a miserable
four-inning outing in which he allowed five runs. ``That could be
your career, who knows? Nobody knows. I think he learned his
lesson. He has to learn how to get respect and that's not the way.
There are a lot of ways to get respect, but throwing at the head of
a guy, you're messing with his career.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers weren't the only ones upset. Though Valdes said he
and Grace are friends, it was Grace who criticized Valdes during
his time with the Cubs earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Wood) did what he had to do,'' Grace said. ``Had the roles
been reversed, we would've retaliated. Once they hit me, it was
even. It was bad timing on my part (to be leading off).''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers (68-62) pulled to within six games of first-place
San Francisco after being nine out a week ago, and did it without
their staple of late _ the long ball.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros tied it 5-5 with a two-run, one-out single in the
top of the eighth and the Dodgers took a 6-5 lead on Adrian
Beltre's sacrifice fly. Left-handers were batting .159 against
Dodgers reliever Mike Fetters until Roosevelt Brown, called up
earlier in the day to replace Rondell White, homered to the
opposite field with two outs in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers, with their $98 million payroll, used the
bargain boys to scratch across the go-ahead run in the 10th. Jeff
Branson led off with a walk, was sacrificed by Beltre to second and
went to third on Aven's groundout. With Cora at the plate, Cubs
reliever Todd Van Poppel's wild pitch allowed Aven to score. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
