<SLUG> BC-VOICESTREAM-POWERTEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOICESTREAM IS SAID TO SEEK TO BUY WIRELESS PLAYER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Tenn., Fla., Wash.)   By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN and SIMON ROMERO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VoiceStream Wireless, the U.S. wireless carrier that Deutsche
Telekom plans to acquire, is expected to announce Monday that it
has agreed to buy Powertel, a wireless operator in the Southeast,
for as much as $5.8 billion, according to executives close to the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Powertel would fill a crucial gap in
VoiceStream's network and its goal of offering seamless access
across the nation. The deal would give VoiceStream coverage in 24
of the nation's top 25 markets, adding cities including Atlanta;
Jacksonville, Fla.; and Memphis and Nashville, Tenn. VoiceStream's
network now covers 22 of the top 25 markets.
</P>
<P>
   The deal illustrates how consolidation in the telecommunications
industry, and in wireless communications in particular, is picking
up speed. Use of wireless services is also increasing, with
carriers adding an estimated 30,000 subscribers each day.
</P>
<P>
   While Powertel has only about 720,000 customers and is not one
of the top 10 wireless companies in the United States, its network
uses the same technical standard _ global system for mobile
communications _ that VoiceStream uses and is compatible with
Deutsche Telekom's network and most others in Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   According to executives close to the deal, shareholders of
Powertel, which is based in West Point, Ga., would receive about
$85 for each of their shares. That represents no premium, because
Powertel shares rose $4.69 to close at $86.63 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   VoiceStream would assume about $1.2 billion of Powertel's debt.
</P>
<P>
   The complex deal also involves a collar, which is a method to
determine stock prices in which a specific price range is agreed
upon instead of the establishment of an exact cost per share. If
VoiceStream's shares increased beyond $130.77, shareholders of
Powertel would receive 0.65 of a share of VoiceStream for each of
their shares. If VoiceStream shares fell below $113.33, Powertel
shareholders would receive 0.75 of a Voicetream share for each
Powertel share.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also includes a bonus payout if Deutsche Telekom's
acquisition of VoiceStream receives regulatory approval.
Shareholders of Powertel would receive $105.36 a share in Deutsche
Telekom stock, representing 2.6353 Deutsche Telekom shares for
every one share of Powertel. In this instance, there is no collar.
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, the transaction would guarantee that
Powertel shareholders would receive about the same amount of money
for their shares regardless of how VoiceStream shares fluctuate.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to the VoiceStream-Powertel deal said they
hoped that both transactions would be completed in six to nine
months. Some analysts have questioned whether Deutsche Telekom is
paying too much for VoiceStream, which is based in Bellevue, Wash.,
but others have suggested that the acquisition of Powertel would
make the VoiceStream deal more palatable to Deutsche Telekom
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Powertel is a critical enabler in VoiceStream's need for
nationwide coverage,'' said Andrew Cole, a wireless communications
consultant with Renaissance Strategy Worldwide. ``Now, Deutsche
Telekom is at least buying a car with the brakes included.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it is not clear yet whether Deutsche Telekom's plan
to buy VoiceStream for more than $50 billion will be approved after
resistance to the transaction emerged in Congress. Critics were
concerned about the acquisition of a U.S. telecommunications
company by a large foreign concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was shrewd for Deutsche Telekom to expand in the U.S. by
buying a minor player in the wireless industry, but now it seems
that strategy is changing,'' said Jeffrey Kagan, an independent
telecommunications analyst based in Atlanta. ``The bigger the deal
appears, the more resistance the Germans could get from
regulators.''
</P>
<P>
   John Stanton, VoiceStream's chief executive, sees things
differently. ``Just because this deal scales us up in the Southeast
isn't that meaningful when it comes to the regulatory issues,''
Stanton said in a telephone interview. ``I would say passionately
that there are still no national security or technical reasons why
the Deutsche Telekom deal should not be approved.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the deal was announced in July, VoiceStream's shares have
declined 8 percent, to $118.19 from $128.50, while Deutsche Telekom
has fallen more than 10 percent, to $40.31 from $45.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-00 2146EDT &QL; 
