<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3578 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS     08-27 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEARLESS HAMPTON LETS THE METS CATCH THEIR BREATH 
</HEADLINE>
   By RAFAEL HERMOSO 
 
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The sight of Mike Hampton sliding on the infield
grass and swinging like he was the cleanup hitter Sunday left Bobby
Valentine shaking his head. How could the Mets pitcher risk another
injury? But the concern in the visiting dugout at Shea did not set
in until Hampton remained on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton returned from a stress fracture in his right ribs Sunday
and did everything possible to boost the Mets' playoff chances and
demoralize the Diamondbacks. His eight dominant innings led the
Mets to a 2-1 victory and helped them win this three-game series.
They gained a game on the Diamondbacks in the wild-card standing,
and many more in their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a comfort level to see Mike out there today,'' Mets
pitcher Al Leiter said. ``You know if he gets in trouble, he's
going to get out of it and that translates into their dugout. They
know it's going to be a tough game.''
</P>
<P>
   As disheartening as it was on Friday for Arizona to see Randy
Johnson again look mortal against the Mets, they had to sense a
bigger loss Sunday. The victory put the Mets five and a half games
ahead of the Diamondbacks in the National League wild-card race. A
sweep this weekend would have written off Arizona. Losing two of
three came close. Hampton's return made it worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is a sign of relief that he's healthy, or
almost healthy,'' John Franco said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wasn't 100 percent, I'd hate to see him healthy,''
Arizona Manager Buck Showalter said. ``He was outstanding. He was
the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton's cracked right rib originated from a high school
football injury. But he also strained an oblique muscle on Aug. 17
and missed his last scheduled start. Hampton (13-7) allowed one run
on three hits in eight innings Sunday and is 4-0 with a 2.18 earned
run average in his past six starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's late in the season,'' Hampton said. ``I'm not out there
just trying to get through. I'm out there trying to help my team
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Benny Agbayani's solo homer in the fourth inning gave the Mets a
1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton's only struggle came in the fifth inning, when seven of
his first eight pitches were balls. Catcher Mike Piazza thought
Hampton was rushing his delivery. Arizona's Kelly Stinnett, who led
off with a walk, scored when Danny Bautista lined a two-out single
over Edgardo Alfonzo's outstretched glove at second base to tie the
score, 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Ventura nearly gave the Mets the lead in the bottom of the
fifth, but settled for nostalgia. Ventura hit a leadoff drive to
straight-away center field, where last October Steve Finley leaped
in vain for Todd Pratt's division series-clinching 10th-inning home
run. Finley robbed Piazza of an extra-base hit at the wall earlier
Sunday, but finally scaled the wall on Ventura. Finley leaped,
turned his back toward home plate and reached 3 feet above the wall
for the catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to get it out of his reach to be sure,'' Ventura
said. ``You just shake your head and go back to the dugout.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks needed this victory and let the starter Armando
Reynoso (10-9) pitch the game's decisive moment. Alfonzo and Piazza
each had one-out singles in the seventh to put runners on first and
second. With a 1-1 count on Ventura, Reynoso tried to pick Alfonzo
off second base and nearly did. But he appeared upset when Alfonzo
was ruled safe, which television replays verified.
</P>
<P>
   The call either rattled Reynoso or he was extra cautious
pitching to Ventura. Three straight balls loaded the bases for Todd
Zeile, who hit a slow roller to the hole between shortstop and
third. Hanley Frias caught the ball but could only get a forceout
at second, allowing the eventual winning run to score.
</P>
<P>
   That was enough for Hampton. His delivery was unaffected by the
injury, which had been the Mets' greatest fear. Athletic trainers
said Hampton could do no further damage, basing his ability to
pitch on tolerating pain. Hampton admitted he had lingering pain
and said he would most likely pitch with some discomfort for the
rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a difference between having pain and being hurt,''
Hampton said. ``This is just a pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine did not stop worrying about Hampton. He cringed when
Hampton slid on his knees to field a grounder down the first-base
line in the third inning and appeared displeased when Hampton took
a full cut in his first at-bat despite the advice from the pitching
coach Dave Wallace, which was, Valentine said: ``Be smart with this
thing. Use your head.'' Hampton said the swing was instinctive when
he saw a pitch over the plate.
</P>
<P>
   The rib pain flares mostly when Hampton throws his four-seam
fastball, a pitch that can reach 92 miles an hour. Hampton threw
only 10 of those Sunday, relying instead on his lively sinking
fastball, changeup and breaking ball.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton did not, however, buy Valentine's contention that
missing one start may have been a blessing in disguise by resting
him for the playoff race. Hampton said he has felt strong for
months and plans on feeling that way come October.
</P>
<P>
   With Hampton out of the game, Jay Bell made a long out to the
left-field wall and Jay Payton dropped a line drive for an error in
the ninth before Armando Benitez recorded his 35th save. Later,
Hampton wore a straight face while answering reporters' question
until he was reminded that other pitchers have started in the
playoffs with similar injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will too,'' he said with a smile. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
