<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS HUNDLEY A CUB IN DODGERS' CLOTHING?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley spent a significant
portion of his life in Chicago when his father, Randy, played for
the Cubs, and the younger Hundley said he's thought about playing
for his hometown team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I'm concentrating on this team and this year, and in
time that will take care of itself,'' said Hundley, who admitted to
harboring a feeling of one day playing for the Cubs. ``That's
always the case. A guy's home team is always special to them. But
the bottom line is I want to play on a winning team next year.
That's the bottom line with me. Of course, you think of your home
town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty-one games. That's what it would be. It's my hometown.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley's eligible for free agency after the season, and one
area the Dodgers may be able to trim their $98 million payroll is
with their catcher. Hundley's making $6 million this season, and
signing him to a big contract next season probably won't make much
financial sense _ even to the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers management will make a hard run at re-signing
right-hander Darren Dreifort, also eligible for free agency after
the season, and extending the contract of right-hander Chan Ho
Park. The Dodgers are also expected to be heavily involved in the
courting of free-agent-to-be Mike Hampton of the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have already said they were interested in re-signing
catcher Chad Kreuter after the season. And with catching prospects
Angel Pena and Paul LoDuca both at Triple-A Albuquerque, Hundley is
considered expendable despite producing well offensively.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley went to high school in nearby Palantine, Ill., and his
parents still live in the Chicago area.
</P>
<P>
   Though Hundley's been on the disabled list twice (strained
oblique muscle, broken right thumb) this season, he's still having
a big year at the plate. Hundley, who recently stopped
switch-hitting and is batting only left-handed, is hitting .303
with 22 homers and 56 RBI in 69 games.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, Hundley's nine errors are tied for most among
National League catchers. Though he's thrown much better this
season, he's still thrown out just 16 of 77 runners (20.7 percent)
trying to steal.
</P>
<P>
   BROWN, SHEFFIELD STATUS: Dodgers right-hander Kevin Brown, ill
through the weekend, said he plans to make his scheduled start
today in the series opener at Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling much better than I was a few days ago,'' Brown
said. ``I'm just going to go out and do what I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Sheffield's status isn't as simple to determine. He was
eligible to play Sunday after serving his five-game suspension, but
he missed his seventh straight game with a flu-like illness.
Sheffield's status continues to be a mystery to the Dodgers, who
remain hopeful he can return to the lineup Tuesday. However, as of
late Sunday they weren't sure when Sheffield was coming to
Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   ODDS AND ENDS: Manager Davey Johnson's ejection in the fifth
inning was his third of the season. ... Cubs pitcher Kerry Wood
batted left-handed against right-hander Ismael Valdes to protect
his tender left oblique muscle. He had a base hit in his first
at-bat. Wood batted right-handed against lefty Carlos Perez in the
sixth inning. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
