</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-DONATE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENIGMATIC FIGURE IS FOCUS OF CAMPAIGN-FINANCE INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Wyo.)   (Eds: Inserts McAuliffe's first name in the first reference to him,
in graf that begins ``Nonetheless, ...'')  
(Eds: An abridged version of this story, slugged
CAMPAIGN-DONATE-ABR, is being sent.) 
(ART ADV: Graphics are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By TIM GOLDEN and DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At his small suite of offices in Fort Lee, N.J., David Chang was
a tycoon without much to do.
</P>
<P>
   Chang, 56, often rode to work in a Rolls-Royce and strode
through the door in a long mink coat, a cigarette dangling from his
lips. But although his holding company boasted of big, global deals
in everything from oil exploration to telecommunications, almost
none of those ventures ever got off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really saw anybody there do anything,'' said Clark R.
Wilcox, a former banking executive who was hired to help run the
firm in 1997, only to quit soon after and successfully sue his
former employer for breach of contract.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, however, Chang cut a different figure. There he
attended state dinners at the White House and visited informally
with the president. He hired President Clinton's chief fund-raiser
as a consultant, and cultivated senators and congressmen from both
parties. The chairman of his company, a retired Navy admiral, had
been chief of staff to George Bush when he was vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The secret of Chang's popularity among American politicians was
no secret: He and his employees gave generously to favored
candidates and their parties _ more than 100 contributions,
totaling $325,000. Chang also pledged at least $1 million toward
the presidential library that Clinton hopes to build in Little
Rock, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Chang's activities finally caught the attention of federal
campaign-finance investigators, who learned that he was spending
more money on politicians than he was reporting in taxable income.
In June he pleaded guilty to channeling over $53,000 in illegal
contributions to one of the Democratic Party's most important
fund-raisers, Sen. Robert Torricelli of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Now Chang is at the center of a widening federal inquiry into
the possibility that Torricelli's 1996 campaign staff may have been
complicit in Chang's illegal donations _ something the senator
strongly denies.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers familiar with the case say Chang has given prosecutors
information suggesting that Torricelli's aides accounted improperly
for some of his contributions, and at least two dozen FBI agents
have been added to the inquiry in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli and other politicians now cast Chang as an
unscrupulous con man, and themselves as his unwitting victims.
Through his Washington lawyer, Chang declined to comment. But
Chang's credibility is likely to be a central issue in any new case
that is brought.
</P>
<P>
   A portrait of Chang _ drawn from interviews, court records and a
thick file of lawsuits by and against him _ shows a man of glaring,
sometimes comical contradictions: He claims to have been educated
at England's best schools but speaks broken English; his closest
business contacts included communist officials from North Korea and
a former Republican congressman from New Jersey; he rallied
American politicians to help him buy a billion-dollar South Korean
insurance company but never had even a small fraction of the money
he needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can a guy like Chang can get hooked up with all these
people?'' asked Wilcox, his former employee. ``As a citizen, quite
frankly, it makes me very angry.''
</P>
<P>
   As a businessman, many of his former employees say, Chang
generated all sorts of ambitious schemes but almost no apparent
profit. Though he has owned large houses, expensive cars and the
235-room Fort Lee Hilton hotel, just across the George Washington
Bridge from New York City, it is unclear where he has gotten his
money, large chunks of which have arrived in wire transfers from
abroad, court records show.
</P>
<P>
   And while Chang's generosity won him many attentive friends in
Washington, it did not buy him all the political favors he sought.
His most important request, that the Clinton administration help
him win repayment of tens of millions of dollars that he said he
was owed by North Korea for grain shipments, made almost no
progress at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did anything go wrong?'' said a spokesman for Clinton, Jake
Seiwert. ``His proposals were neither accepted nor acted upon. What
he wanted to do didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the story of Chang's education in money politics is a
remarkable chapter in the saga of Washington influence bought and
sold. In a world of fund-raiser business executives, deal-savvy
senators and retired officials who increasingly exploit their
connections abroad, Chang was a magnet for the powerful _ even
after he was publicly identified as having given illegal donations
to two different election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Basic Contradictions
</P>
<P>
   Who David Chang is has been difficult to ascertain.
</P>
<P>
   At a bail hearing earlier this year, prosecutors noted that
Chang had used at least two passports and three Social Security
numbers, listed two different birthplaces and three different birth
dates, and was married to two women at the same time _ not
including a reputed girlfriend who has also been listed as his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Chang is a chronic liar,'' one of his many former
lawyers, Michael S. Kimm, asserted in a recent lawsuit, which, like
several suits by other people, claims that Chang failed to pay him
what he owed. ``David Chang believes that he can say anything at a
given moment and get away with it because he is arrogant.''
</P>
<P>
   Even on the basic facts of his background, Chang has
contradicted himself repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   In one set of court papers, he said he was born in Beijing in
1943 and emigrated to South Korea soon after the communist takeover
of China six years later. In an interview last year with a South
Korean newspaper, he said he was born in Korea and left his
homeland in 1963, when he hopped a freighter and sailed to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, Chang told his employees that he spent the '70s
and '80s working as a high-flying oil trader in London and the
Middle East, cultivating friendships with members of the Saudi
royal family. Through his Washington lawyer, David Schertler, Chang
said he had worked abroad for his own oil company, Nikko Petroleum,
and moved its operations to New York in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Chang's profile began to rise in the United States around 1990,
when he became an American citizen. By then he was calling his firm
Nikko Enterprises Inc. and had moved it into offices in Fort Lee.
</P>
<P>
   He portrayed himself as a man of discreet but powerful patrons.
He told associates that he had named his firm for its sponsorship
by Nikko Securities Co., Japan's third-largest brokerage, and that
he had a rich young wife in Japan, the daughter of a Nikko
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Nikko Securities have nothing to do with Chang but
it also apparently persuaded him to stop using its name, prompting
him to reincorporate his company in 1994 as Bright &AMP; Bright. Soon
enough, though, he found new sources of respectability in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Among the first and most important of Chang's Washington
contacts was Daniel J. Murphy, a high-profile lobbyist with a
gleaming government resume. A retired four-star admiral, Murphy had
commanded the Navy's 6th Fleet, had served as chief of staff to
George Bush when he was vice president, and had been a deputy
director of the CIA, and a deputy undersecretary of defense.
</P>
<P>
   After resigning from Bush's staff in 1985, Murphy went to work
as a lobbyist, first for Gray &AMP; Co., a firm closely tied to the
Reagan administration, and then on his own.
</P>
<P>
   He quickly built a reputation for putting business ahead of
politics, representing the Marxist government of Angola, trying to
drum up business in Gen. Manuel Noriega's Panama, and maintaining a
friendship with the former South Korean lobbyist and intelligence
agent Tongsun Park long after Park's ties to American congressmen
touched off a political scandal involving U.S. officials in the
late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, who declined to say anything about his relationship with
Chang, began working for him as a consultant and lobbyist by at
least 1990, according to Schertler, Chang's lawyer. Murphy soon
became a business partner as well, helping Chang open some of the
more important doors in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was at the White House once a month, when I was there,''
said one former assistant who worked for Chang during the latter
half of the Bush administration. Bush's spokesman said the former
president did not recall ever meeting Chang, and there are no
records that Chang ever made a private visit to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Creating a Niche
</P>
<P>
   Chang used his Washington contacts in part to carve out an
unusual business niche, trying to supply goods and services to
countries hostile to the United States. Besides shipping wheat to
North Korea, his former employees said, he tried to send ambulances
and other equipment to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   On a more mundane level, he bought U.S. real estate and Asian
stocks, tried to sell repackaged cigarettes in Russia and beer
snacks in South Korea, and explored building a fleet of miniblimps
for advertising. Almost none of his start-ups, however, seem to
have even gotten off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear what Chang was using for capital. For his grain
deal with North Korea, he received at least $60 million from South
Korea's Shinhan Bank, and from L.G. International, the New Jersey
subsidiary of one of South Korea's biggest conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Chang obtained one of the first Commerce Department
licenses authorizing the sale of food to North Korea, which was
then subject to U.S. trade sanctions. By 1994, court records show,
he had shipped the government there some 560,000 tons of wheat,
with a value of $110 million.
</P>
<P>
   Chang accused the North Korean government of failing to pay him
$71 million on the deal and reneging on a $1.2-billion contract for
further shipments. He made the accusations in a libel suit filed
against a Korean-language newspaper based in New York, which
published an article accusing him of giving free rooms at the Fort
Lee Hilton to visiting North Korean officials.
</P>
<P>
   The paper stood by its story; Chang dropped his suit three years
later.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever misgivings Chang had about doing business with the
North Koreans apparently eased. By 1998, he had been back to North
Korea on a contract to provide logistical support for a U.S. Army
team that sought to recover the remains of American soldiers
missing there since the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   New Alliances
</P>
<P>
   With Bush out of the White House and South Korean financiers
pressing him for repayment on the grain deal, Chang began to
cultivate new allies among the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Until then he had been a relatively modest and mainly Republican
donor. In 1992, for instance, he gave $25,000 to Republicans and
$1,000 to Torricelli, then his local congressman. But by the
1995-96 election cycle, the balance of his generosity shifted to
Democrats, and Torricelli became his most favored politician.
</P>
<P>
   When pressed, a spokesman for Torricelli said his campaign
fund-raisers merely found Chang's name _ along with hundreds of
others _ on a list of New Jersey donors provided by the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee. ``He was not one of the senator's
inner circle of fund-raisers,'' the senator's chief of staff, Eric
B. Shuffler, said. ``Not in any way, shape or form anything close
to that.''
</P>
<P>
   But many of Torricelli's friends and former aides tell of a much
closer relationship. ``All of a sudden,'' one former aide recalled,
``he became a player.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few years, Chang and his aides gave $8,000 to
Torricelli, and Chang was named to the finance committee for
Torricelli's 1996 campaign. Chang gave Torricelli use of his
corporate jet during his 1996 Senate campaign, and investigators
are now examining whether the campaign fully reimbursed Chang for
the 19 flights.
</P>
<P>
   Chang gave another $30,000 to the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee, of which Torricelli was named vice chairman and then
chairman, and $5,000 to a legal-defense fund set up on Torricelli's
behalf for a House ethics inquiry involving Torricelli, who was
ultimately cleared.
</P>
<P>
   As his relationship with the White House grew, Chang and his
companies gave $100,000 to the Democratic National Committee and
$70,000 to the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee. Over
the same period, Chang, his aides and his companies gave only about
$44,000 to the Republican party.
</P>
<P>
   Between late 1995 and 1996, Chang also arranged for another
$53,700 in illegal contributions to Torricelli's campaign,
funneling the money through friends, business associates and even
the former chairman of the Bergen County Republican Party, Berek
Don. Don has pleaded guilty to campaign finance violations and is
cooperating with prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Torricelli, who declined to answer questions
about the matter himself, said the senator's office did almost
nothing for Chang in return for his support.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it looks strange, but this is not a guy who we did
anything for,'' Shuffler said. ``No one on our staff, in our
Washington office, ever spoke to Chang or met him.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, however, several other politicians and current and former
Torricelli aides remember the relationship differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was seen as someone who Torricelli was actively engaged
with,'' one former aide said. ``This was a guy who was important to
Bob.''
</P>
<P>
   In December 1997, Torricelli went to South Korea just days
before a presidential election there. The U.S. Embassy, concerned
that Torricelli might be seen as meddling in the campaign, balked
at setting up political meetings for him. Chang swept into the
void.
</P>
<P>
   In a one-page statement issued in response to written questions,
Torricelli's office denied that Chang was present on the trip, made
any of the arrangements for it, or communicated about it with any
members of the senator's staff.
</P>
<P>
   But two people with detailed knowledge of the trip said Chang
did stay in the same hotel as Torricelli, while Chang's aide,
Christopher Kim, helped set up meetings for the senator with the
two opposition candidates, Kim Dae-jung, who won the vote, and Rhee
In-je. In a brief interview, Kim also acknowledged that Chang sent
him to Seoul to help with the arrangements and to act as the
senator's tour guide as he met with Korean officials and
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In the week of Torricelli's visit, one of Chang's companies also
made a $30,000 donation to the Democratic Congressional Campaign
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking Payback
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Torricelli also insisted that despite all of
Chang's financial support, Torricelli never helped his patron with
the matter of his greatest concern _ persuading the Clinton
administration to transfer frozen North Korean assets to him, or to
pressure the North Korean government to repay the debt. But other
politicians were apparently more forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as last fall, a handful of legislators, from the
relatively liberal Sen. Frank Lautenberg of New Jersey to
conservative Republicans like Sen. Craig Thomas of Wyoming, wrote
to the administration on Chang's behalf, urging it not to ease the
sanctions on North Korea without pressing for the repayment of
debts to U.S. companies like Bright &AMP; Bright.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Lautenberg said they wrote a pro forma letter for him
because he was a New Jersey resident. An aide to Thomas said the
Wyoming senator supported Chang's appeal after being lobbied on his
behalf by one of his business partners, James A. Courter, the
former Republican congressman from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   According to two politicians close to Clinton, Chang was
introduced to the president by Torricelli at a fund-raising event
for the senator. Under questioning by the head of the Justice
Department's campaign-finance task force, Robert J. Conrad Jr.,
Clinton said that Torricelli might have made the introduction, but
that he could not remember.
</P>
<P>
   When South Korea's president visited Washington in June 1998,
Chang and his then 30-year-old assistant, Audrey Yu, were among the
guests at a state dinner. Barely a month later, on July 14, Clinton
invited Chang again, this time to watch a movie in the White House
screening room.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton traveled to Seoul, South Korea, that November,
Chang and others said, he was invited to the president's hotel room
for conversation and pizza. Days before Christmas, Chang was
invited to the White House again, this time for a holiday dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Early the following spring, Chang was invited to the White House
to watch the NCAA basketball finals with Clinton. And when the
Chinese prime minister, Zhu Rongji, visited that April, Chang and
Yu were invited to another state dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Over the year that he was so assiduously wined, dined and
entertained by Clinton and other administration officials, Chang
and his companies donated over $150,000 to the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Terry McAuliffe, the president's close friend and
chief fund-raiser, said, Chang ``was treated no differently from
any other supporter.'' White House officials suggested that while
senior National Security Council officials were dispatched twice in
1998 to meet with Chang and listened to his ideas about U.S. policy
on the Middle East, North Korea and Iraq, mostly they just humored
him.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as Chang became a more prized Democratic donor, his
legal troubles were in fairly plain sight.
</P>
<P>
   The Biggest Deal
</P>
<P>
   His role in making $12,000 in illegal campaign contributions to
the 1992 campaign of former Rep. Jay Kim, a Korean-American
Republican from California, had come to light in news articles by
August 1997. (Chang was not charged, after agreeing to cooperate
with federal prosecutors.) His involvement in illegal contributions
to the 1996 Torricelli campaign surfaced clearly in May 1999, when
Don, the former Bergen County chairman, pleaded guilty to funneling
Chang's money through employees at his law firm.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was there much evidence that Chang was flourishing in
business.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1996 and 1998, while he donated over $270,000 to various
political causes, Chang reported only $183,000 in income. Over a
one-year period starting in the fall of 1998, he also lost nearly
$300,000 gambling in Atlantic City, N.J., federal prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Seiwert, the White house spokesman, said a White House visitor
and major donor like Chang should typically have been vetted by the
Democratic National Committee, the Secret Service and a White House
research unit. He said administration officials were ``still
checking'' to determine how that vetting was done in his case.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-1998, Chang hired McAuliffe to help him try to buy a bank
in South Korea. McAuliffe said that before signing a yearlong
consulting contract with Chang, he checked with several people,
including Courter, the former congressman who was listed on company
documents as the president of the new trading company that Chang
established in late 1997, Panacom Inc.
</P>
<P>
   A person familiar with the contract said Torricelli provided an
enthusiastic reference, telling McAuliffe: ``He's a legitimate
person, a legitimate businessman. His wife's family owns Nikko
Securities.''
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli's aides deny that he or any staff member ever vouched
for Chang.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe said that he never discussed Chang's business deals
with Clinton, and that he ended his consulting arrangement after
about six months. Roughly six months after that, however, he agreed
to work for Chang again, this time as an investment banker when
Panacom sought to buy the troubled Korea Life Insurance Co., South
Korea's third-largest insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe said he went back after learning that Murphy was
acting as Panacom's chairman, and after Courter assured him that
Chang had enough money to buy the company. He said one of Chang's
lawyers also gave him a Korean newspaper clipping indicating that
Bush had already met with Korean officials on Panacom's behalf,
something that one of Chang's former lawyers, Michael Critchley,
also asserted during a hearing in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Bush, Gian-Carlo A. Peressutti, said this was
untrue. The former president, he said, had been in Korea on behalf
of another U.S. firm, Carlyle Group, which is headed by former
senior officials from Republican administrations.
</P>
<P>
   The Korea Life deal would have been by far Chang's biggest yet,
one that three of the world's largest multinational insurance
companies had already bid on and lost by the summer of 1999, when
Murphy and Chang stepped into the void.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bit of a surprise, because no one had ever heard of
them,'' recalled Lee Jong-Koo, a senior Finance Ministry official
who attended the meeting. ``Chang and Admiral Murphy asked
questions about KLI and they indicated that they could raise
abundant funds to acquire the company from various sources,
especially New Jersey pension funds.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview at his office in Seoul, Lee said Korean
officials repeatedly sought further evidence from Chang that
Panacom could assemble the roughly $1.5 billion that they were
seeking for the company. Instead, they heard about Chang's
politician friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember David Chang said he knew Senator Torricelli and
other politicians,'' Lee said. ``He also said that he knew
President Clinton and that he had eaten pizza with the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks, the Korean prime minister, Kim Jong-pil, began to
receive letters from politicians in Washington and New Jersey. Rep.
Gregory Meeks, D-N.Y., wrote to ``highly recommend Panacom for this
acquisition because of their strong record in investment, trade and
finance for many years.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Carolyn Maloney, D-N.Y., who received $2,000 from Chang and
his assistant in 1998, wrote a similar letter, as did Torricelli
and a New Jersey state finance official, Korean officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The two representatives said through spokesmen that they did so
because they believed Panacom was a legitimate business with
operations in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to one lawmaker said they also checked first with
Torricelli's staff, which vouched strongly for Chang. A spokesman
for Torricelli denied that this happened.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli agreed to provide The New York Times with a copy of
the letter he wrote to the Korean government on Panacom's behalf.
After several weeks, however, his aides said the letter could not
be found.
</P>
<P>
   Deepening Troubles
</P>
<P>
   As Chang's push for the insurance deal continued last summer,
Korean officials became openly suspicious that he was acting as a
front man for the former owner of the insurance company, who had
been imprisoned on corruption charges but was trying to win it
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew this guy Chang was lying to me,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe flew to Seoul in late August to help move the deal
ahead. But he said that after only two discussions with Panacom
lawyers, he turned around and flew home, refusing to meet with
Korean officials.
</P>
<P>
   The Korea Life deal finally fell through last fall, as Chang's
legal troubles were deepening in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   With the pressure from federal prosecutors growing, the lawyer
then leading Chang's defense, Critchley, did something that stunned
many of the lawyers following the case.
</P>
<P>
   After Chang's arrest on campaign-finance, conspiracy and
obstruction-of-justice charges, Critchley announced in court that
Chang had ``no information about any criminal wrongdoing'' by any
public officials, mentioning Clinton, Torricelli and McAuliffe by
name. With that, Critchley, who is active in Democratic Party
politics in New Jersey, seemed to foreclose the possibility that
Chang would ever cooperate with the government.
</P>
<P>
   Less than six months later, however, as Chang prepared to go to
trial with a new lawyer, he indicated to prosecutors that he might
in fact have that kind of information and agreed to cooperate with
the authorities. He became the sixth person to plead guilty to
making illegal contributions to Torricelli's campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
