u a BC-LAZIO-CLINTON-SENATE-     08-27 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAZIO-CLINTON-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO, FUND RAISING IN CHAPPAQUA, TAKES RACE TO RIVAL'S NEW HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPPAQUA, N.Y. _ Rep. Rick Lazio took his U.S. Senate campaign
almost literally to Hillary Rodham Clinton's back yard Sunday,
appearing at a fund-raiser at a private home four miles from
Clinton's new house.
</P>
<P>
   And, as is typical in this contentious race, he had some
unneighborly words for his opponent, who moved here just seven
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look at New York as being Mrs. Clinton's
neighborhood,'' Lazio said when asked how it felt to stand just
four miles from the house President and Mrs. Clinton bought here in
December to establish residency for her Senate bid.
</P>
<P>
   But, as he dashed off to begin the fund-raiser, he added with a
grin, ``It's great to be here in Chappaqua.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Lazio's first trip here, but aides would not rule out a
follow-up visit to the community, which voted for Bill Clinton in
the last two elections. Recent polls have shown Lazio doing well in
the New York City suburbs, a swing battleground fruitful in votes
and money. The fund-raiser here was one of four he attended in and
near Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton was not in town during Lazio's two-hour visit,
which also included an unscheduled stop at a downtown pizzeria.
</P>
<P>
   But Lazio certainly has a friend in the host of the fund-raiser,
Ed O'Keefe, a retired corporate lawyer and chairman of the New
Castle Republican Committee. (Chappaqua is a village in the town of
New Castle; those who pay taxes to its school district, like
O'Keefe and the Clintons, consider themselves residents of the
village.)
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's aides said he did not schedule the fund-raiser here to
deliberately tweak the first lady. O'Keefe said he offered to hold
it as a loyal Republican ``because I thought it was time for Rick
to come up here to Chappaqua to say hello to the folks.'' O'Keefe
estimated that 130 people, paying on average $300 each, would
attend. (As usual, campaign officials declined to give the actual
attendance or total raised.)
</P>
<P>
   It was clear that the Lazio campaign relished the idea of
Lazio's stomping on Mrs. Clinton's turf; his fund-raisers are
usually closed to the news media. But this time, after word spread
that Lazio would be in Chappaqua, his campaign office called a
brief news conference on O'Keefe's lawn before the event.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, for his part, said he would talk up his plan to cut taxes
by $776 billion over 10 years, an issue that has dominated the
campaign since Lazio unveiled it Thursday in his first major policy
address.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio defended the plan again Sunday, attacking his opponent for
asserting that his numbers understate the effect on the economy.
Clinton says Lazio's plan would actually cost $1.24 trillion, an
amount she said would threaten the surplus, drive up interest rates
and destroy the economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are in fantasyland,'' Lazio told reporters. ``They have
no plan. All they can do is attack and pull down and rip apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton does have a tax-fighting plan, though more modest than
Lazio's. Hers amounts to about $496 billion in cuts over 10 years,
a less risky course, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``His first plan is a big tax scheme that just doesn't add up,''
Clinton told supporters at a rally in Kingston Sunday, citing
reports Sunday in Newsday and the New York Daily News asserting
that some of Lazio's figures are wrong. She also accused the
congressman of trying to be ``Bush Lite'' with his plan.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to comment on Lazio's visit and his remark about New
York's not being Clinton's neighborhood, her spokesman, Howard
Wolfson, replied, ``Congressman Lazio can't defend his phony tax
plan, so he has to resort to personal insults.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
