<SLUG> BC-NY-CARRIAGE-ACCIDENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER CARRIAGE RIDE, A SCARY TIP 
</HEADLINE>
   By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Four tourists were slightly hurt Sunday when a
horse-drawn carriage tipped onto its side in Central Park, tossing
the tourists, a vacationing British family, onto the asphalt, the
police said.
</P>
<P>
   The accident occurred at 11:15 a.m. just inside the park near
its entrance at Central Park South and the Avenue of the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   The carriage driver, Naim Aydin, said he had just completed a
circuit of the park with the family aboard and had stopped at a
trough to water the horse, a 13-year-old black Persian. As he led
the animal through a left turn, the old green carriage tilted past
its balance point and suddenly slammed onto its side, dumping out
Colin Howe, 55, his wife, Pauline, 54, and Charlotte and Michael,
their two children, who are 13 and 10. The police did not know
where the Howes lived in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just fell over,'' Aydin said. ``I am unhappy.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the accident created an alarming scene _ the Howes were
strapped to immobilizing back boards and then taken away in
ambulances _ the authorities said the accident was not serious. The
Howes were treated at New York Weill Cornell Medical Center and
released. A hospital administrator said they had minor cuts in
bruises and planned to resume their vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Aydin nor the horse, which he said was brought to the
city from upstate two days before, were injured. The horse
apparently did not tip with the carriage.
</P>
<P>
   The only apparent damage to the carriage was a dent on the left
fender. The horse was led by hand back to its stable on West 52nd
Street and 12th Avenue, leaving Aydin and a friend to grunt and
sweat as they pushed the carriage 13 blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Two men familiar with the carriage said it was a model, made 50
to 100 years ago in Canada, that is known to be easily tipped.
Aydin said he did not own the carriage and declined to give the
owner's name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
