u a BC-NY-BOND-PROJECT-NYT &LR;      08-27 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BOND-PROJECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARGEST STATE BOND ACT STILL MISSING DETAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It just may be the quietest $3.8 billion in New York political
history. In November, voters will be asked to decide the largest
bond act in state history, to pay for transportation projects. But
so far, there has been barely any campaign for it, and none against
it.
</P>
<P>
   Just as unsettling for people inclined to support the measure is
that it is more than two months after the deadline set by Gov.
George Pataki and legislative leaders for producing an agreement on
how the money would be spent. The lack of such an agreement makes
it hard for anyone to know what it is they may be campaigning for
or against.
</P>
<P>
   All of this could bode ill for a borrowing measure that has been
billed as a necessary step for building the first stages of a
Second Avenue subway line and other projects in the ambitious
capital building program for the New York mass transit network. New
York voters have turned down bond acts more often than they have
approved them, and the ones that have passed, like the 1996
environmental bond act championed by the governor, have been
supported by broad-based coalitions that raised large amounts of
money for television advertising _ exactly the kind of thing that
has been nowhere in sight this time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get bond issues passed, you really have to do a job in
terms of selling it to the public,'' State Comptroller Carl McCall
said. ``This is reducing the amount of time you can go out and
educate the public about what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall described himself as being inclined to support the
measure, and said he was asked daily ``by reporters, the financial
community, by union leaders, environmentalists'' what he thought of
it. But he added that he ``can't render an opinion until I see the
specifics.''
</P>
<P>
   A major sponsor of the measure, Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver,
said he was not concerned about the late start. In fact, Silver,
who heads the state's most potent Democratic machinery, said he had
no plans to organize a campaign for it or to raise money for such a
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that in the last two months, the local officials, the
contractors, the unions, who are all interested in making it
happen, will get the message out,'' he said. ``I would expect to
see an across-the-board campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The bond act is a crucial piece of the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority's $17.1 billion, five-year capital plan
for upgrading the region's rail and bus system, including the first
work in a generation on a Second Avenue line, and the start of work
on a connection between the Long Island Rail Road and Grand Central
Terminal. Of the $3.8 billion the state would borrow under the bond
act, $1.6 billion would go to the authority and the rest would go
to other transit agencies across the state and to pay for highways
and bridges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-00 2204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000827.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3590 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-WOODY-NYT &LR;      08-27 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WOODY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLEN WOODY, 44, BASS PLAYER WITH ALLMAN BROTHERS BAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn.)   By NEIL STRAUSS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Douglas Allen Woody, a former bass guitarist for the Allman
Brothers Band and a spinoff group, Gov't Mule, died on Saturday at
the Marriott Courtyard motel in Queens. He was 44.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was unknown, said Ellen Borakove, a spokeswoman for
the New York City medical examiner's office. An autopsy performed
Sunday was inconclusive, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Woody, as he was known, was born in Nashville, Tenn.,
where his father, a truck driver, weaned him on the blues, country
and rock oldies. Inspired by watching Paul McCartney play with the
Beatles, he began learning the bass guitar at age 14. Not long
afterward he first heard the Allman Brothers Band on the radio and
became interested in exploratory Southern rock.
</P>
<P>
   Woody majored in music at Middle Tennessee State University and
sold instruments at Gruhn Guitars in Nashville, where he met many
of the city's top musicians. In the mid-'80s, he joined the Artimus
Pyle Band, led by the former drummer for Lynyrd Skynyrd. Pyle
introduced Woody to Butch Trucks of the Allman Brothers Band, who
suggested that Woody audition as bass guitarist.
</P>
<P>
   Woody joined the Allman Brothers Band when the group re-formed
after a seven-year hiatus in 1989. The band had lost three members
to early deaths, two of them bass guitarists and the other its
co-founder, Duane Allman, who was killed in a 1971 motorcycle
accident.
</P>
<P>
   The revised lineup, with Woody on bass and another newcomer,
Warren Haynes, on guitar, helped bring the band new commercial and
critical success. In 1994, while still touring with the Allmans,
Woody and Haynes formed a side trio with a drummer, Matt Abts,
called Gov't Mule. They recorded for Capricorn, a label that had a
long-standing feud with the Allman Brothers over record royalties.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, Woody and Haynes left the Allman Brothers to
devote themselves to their trio. Gov't Mule added a harder edge to
its jams and explored a wide terrain that included free jazz and
the alternative rock of Radiohead.
</P>
<P>
   An avid biker with tattoos and a handlebar mustache, Woody was
distinguished by his ability to move from slow, blues-drenched
playing to fast, pronounced runs. He was also known for playing
customized instruments, like a double-necked combination of a
guitar and a mandolin.
</P>
<P>
   Gov't Mule recorded five albums for Capricorn and was set to
begin a tour on Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Woody is survived by his wife, Jenny, and a daughter, Savannah,
both of Nashville. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-00 2206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
