<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3592 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT     08-27 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO BASKETBALL: KNICKS NEED TO PUT SUMMER OF ADVERSITY BEHIND
THEM 
</HEADLINE>
  By CHRIS BROUSSARD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When this summer to forget began, the Knicks had four
items on their to-do list, and trading Patrick Ewing was not one of
them.
</P>
<P>
   They wanted to acquire Grant Hill _ a long shot, they knew, but
one they hoped a videotaped presentation featuring some of their
celebrity fans and the many opportunities that New York City
presented Hill's songstress wife, Tamia, might actually make
happen.
</P>
<P>
   They also wanted to obtain a rugged power forward who would
catapult them from the bottom of the league's offensive rebounding
ranking, and improve themselves at point guard by acquiring a
penetrating playmaker who would end the every-basket-is-a-war
nature of their halfcourt set. Beyond that, in what would have been
a bonus, the Knicks hoped to get a small forward with touch from
the outside.
</P>
<P>
   But an off-season that began with cheery optimism and grand
aspirations has degenerated into one of the franchise's most
fruitless and embarrassing summers in recent memory. Not only have
the Knicks failed to reach even one of their goals, but their
well-publicized string of near misses has left them facing a
potential disaster, one that nothing less than complete and
selfless professionalism on the part of their players can avert. In
a profession where egotism abounds, and to a degree is beneficial,
the Knicks must grudgingly check theirs at the doors of the College
of Charleston at the start of training camp in October.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's sloppy handling of the Ewing saga _ in which the
great center was essentially traded, castigated by the public and
the news media and then untraded _ has left the Knicks in the
awkward position of having to coexist with an angry and humiliated
star who is growing old ungracefully. But there are also the
potentially bruised egos of some of Ewing's teammates. Who knows
how feeling unappreciated and perhaps unwanted could affect the
games of Marcus Camby, Chris Childs, Larry Johnson and Allan
Houston?
</P>
<P>
   Camby, a rising star a year ago, watched in silent aggravation
as the Knicks all but drooled over Brian Grant and then battled the
Golden State Warriors for Danny Fortson, both of whom threatened to
slice his already limited minutes. As for Childs and Johnson, they
must know that the Knicks have shopped them and their burdensome
contracts all over the place, only to find no takers. And while
Houston knows he is valued by the club he is also smart enough to
realize that the Knicks' fascination with Glen Rice most likely
meant they had intentions of dealing him for a power player up
front.
</P>
<P>
   The potential for debilitating discontent in the locker room is
so strong that before figuring out a way to squeeze more offensive
rebounding out of the same old crew, Jeff Van Gundy must take into
account that five of his top players _ including three starters _
know that if the Knicks had their druthers, they would be
elsewhere. A coach whose team always seems to be embroiled in
turmoil could be facing his toughest challenge yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really going to test their professionalism and Van
Gundy's professionalism,'' said one Eastern Conference coach, who
spoke on condition of anonymity. ``Van Gundy is good at turning a
negative into a positive and that's what he'll have to do in this
case.''
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse is that while General Manager Scott
Layden's every plan was being foiled, the Miami Heat, the Knicks'
fiercest rival, was emerging as one of the champions of the
off-season. While Layden found himself shackled by the Knicks'
surplus of high salary-low production players, Riley found ways to
pull off two complicated trades that landed Eddie Jones, Anthony
Mason and the coveted Grant.
</P>
<P>
   But while on the surface there appears to be little reason to
feel good about the Knicks, Layden's statement to the news media on
Thursday that ``we feel good about our chances'' was not totally
baseless. Hope can be justified.
</P>
<P>
   Though Ewing is upset about remaining in New York and probably
hurt by the mean-spirited boot out of town he was about to receive,
he is, even so, one of the hardest working and most professional
players in the league. He has performed admirably in light of
public scorn and perceived slights by the organization before and
will probably do so again. And even if Ewing's bitterness is too
deep, his desire to earn big money for two more years after this
season will force him to put forth his best effort on the court.
</P>
<P>
   If he does not stay healthy for most of the season, play well
and show that he can handle being a supporting offensive player
rather than the focal point, he can forget about any team giving
him a lucrative contract. So a mad but motivated Ewing could play
even better than he did last season, when he gave the Knicks a
solid 15.1 points and 9.7 rebounds a game.
</P>
<P>
   For the Knicks to recapture the magic of two seasons ago, it is
imperative that Ewing and his humbled teammates behave as
professionals, shaking off the off-season affronts and just playing
ball.
</P>
<P>
   Camby, as he was in the 1999 playoffs, could be the X-factor,
but only if he thickens his skin and ignores the Knicks' pursuit of
front-line reinforcements, or in Grant's case replacements, and
stays healthy. Before his plague of injuries began in late
November, Camby averaged 15 points and 10.3 rebounds through the
first six games while starting at center for the injured Ewing. But
when he returned from the injuries, he did so without his
explosiveness, and the Knicks were much the worse for it.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible that an injury free Camby, who is expected to be
100 percent for training camp, can re-energize the Knicks,
particularly on the offensive glass. If that happens, it will be as
if the Knicks did add a new player this summer, and that would go a
long way in eliminating the distress of this off-season of
disappointment and adversity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
