<HEADER>
A3597 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-GLF-NEC-NYT &LR;      08-27 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NEC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS BEATS NIGHTFALL TOO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio, Calif.)   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AKRON, Ohio _ Tiger Woods won the race against nightfall,
winning $1 million in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Playing the last few holes in near darkness, Woods cruised to an
11-stroke victory Sunday in the NEC Invitational and set a
tournament scoring record that added to his remarkable year. Woods
was 21-under par for the tournament (259, 64-61-67-67), breaking
the previous record (262) set by Jose Maria Olazabal in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Leonard, who shot a 4-under 66, and Phillip Price of
Wales, who shot 68, tied for second place at 10-under, sharing the
second-place check worth $437,000, in this 37-player World Golf
Championships event with a $5 million purse.
</P>
<P>
   It was Woods' second consecutive victory, his fifth in his last
seven starts, and his eighth in 16 starts on the PGA Tour this
year. How can a professional golfer complete August winning 50
percent of the tour events he has played? How could Woods not only
avoid a letdown after winning the PGA Championship, but also
dominate a world-class field a week later?
</P>
<P>
   What Woods has done this year almost defies belief, yet he
continues to take his game to new levels while leaving the
competition further behind. Sunday, after a nearly three-hour delay
because of bad weather that threatened to extend the tournament
until Monday, Woods finished his round, and ended the tournament
with another magic moment. At the par-4 No. 18, Woods hit a
spectacular 8-iron approach shot from 169 yards that landed 2 feet
from the pin. It was almost impossible to see the pin from where
Woods was standing in the fairway, yet he hit a near-perfect shot
that set up an easy birdie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminded me of how I played growing up, playing a few holes
trying to beat the dark,'' Woods said. ``Because of the lead I had,
everyone wanted to finish. I guarantee if it had been tied, we
wouldn't have finished.''
</P>
<P>
   As Woods walked to the 18th green at Firestone Country Club, it
was a surreal scene, with the gallery applauding in the dark,
photographers' lights providing a strobe effect, and people holding
cigarette lighters aloft as if they were attending an outdoor
concert. But when it comes to professional golf, everyone sees the
light: Woods is the world's best player, by a margin that seems to
be growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a better player than I was last year,'' said Woods, who
also won eight times last year, but who won this year's last three
majors _ the U.S. Open, the British Open and the PGA. ``I'm going
to try and keep getting better.'' For the opposition, that must be
a disturbing thought.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, this tournament was decided Saturday, when Woods
built a nine-stroke lead and left his pursuers to battle for second
place. That battle became Sunday's day's subplot, especially for
Price, who probably secured his PGA Tour card for next year by
winning $437,000, although a bogey on No. 18 cost him $63,500.
</P>
<P>
   Woods will fly to California for Monday night's exhibition
against Sergio Garcia, a made-for-television event that will be
shown live on ABC. Woods would have still made it to California if
play had been suspended Sunday, but finishing Sunday night, instead
of playing a few holes Sunday, will make the cross-country trip a
lot less rushed.
</P>
<P>
   Hal Sutton, who was paired in the final group with Woods, tried
to put early heat on the world's No. 1 player, but it did not last.
Sutton birdied three of the first five holes, and when Woods
bogeyed No. 6, his lead was over Sutton down to five strokes.
</P>
<P>
   The momentum changed, however, with a two-shot swing at No. 8,
when Woods birdied and Sutton bogeyed. Woods never led by fewer
than six strokes thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   And by making his birdie at No. 18, Woods satisfied his caddie,
Steve Williams, by finishing 21 under par. Twenty-one is Williams'
favorite number.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got to the last hole, I asked for a new glove, and
Steve handed me a glove that he wrote No. 21 on,'' Woods said.
``When my shot landed on the green, I've never seen him that
excited. I've won major championships before and I've never seen
him have that kind of reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   And for Woods, it has been some kind of year. He has already set
a tour record with more than $7.69 million this year, and he has a
realistic chance to become the first player to win $10 million in a
season.
</P>
<P>
   But after Monday, Woods plans to take time off. He has battled
the flu for a few days, and after what he has accomplished this
year, he could use a rest. However, his opponents could use a break
as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
