<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3600 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MUSIC-REVIEW-GOOGOOSH     08-27 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-REVIEW-GOOGOOSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAN'S SILENCED STAR, BRIDGING A 21-YEAR GAP
</HEADLINE>
 (With NY-IRANIAN-DIVA) 
By JON PARELES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Googoosh kept having to wipe tears from her eyes when she
performed on Saturday night at the Nassau Coliseum. So did many of
her fans. Googoosh, who was Iran's queen of pop in the 1970s, was
performing again after 21 years of public silence and seclusion,
the 21 years since Iran's Islamic revolutionary government came to
power and banned nearly all music.
</P>
<P>
   In prerevolutionary Iran, Googoosh was Iran's Barbra Streisand,
Linda Ronstadt, Cher, Edith Piaf and Madonna rolled into one: not
just a magnificent singer but a fashion trailblazer and a symbol of
modernity. Her songs were romantic, not political, and while they
drew on Western styles, they held onto both the fervor of Persian
love poetry and the sliding, quivering, impassioned phrasing of
traditional Persian music.
</P>
<P>
   Although Googoosh stopped singing and performing, her old songs
stayed popular both among Iranian expatriates and, sold illegally,
within Iran. Like the Buena Vista Social Club from Cuba, she now
carries forward music from a prerevolutionary era that has taken on
new connotations.
</P>
<P>
   Her songs about eternal love and the pain of separation have,
two decades later, become not just vows of devotion but invocations
of nostalgia, longing and, for Iranians in North America, the pain
of exile. They also hint at a cultural path Iran rejected, one that
it may resume under its current reformist government: not trying to
seal itself off from Western pop culture, but using Western
elements to create something distinctly Persian.
</P>
<P>
   This year Googoosh, who is now 50, was given permission to tour
abroad, where she will also make movies directed by her husband,
Massoud Kimiai. (In Iran women are still not allowed to sing as
soloists for audiences that include men.) Onstage Googoosh had all
the trappings of a Western pop diva: giant video screens,
scaffolding full of lights and an eight-violin string section along
with her pop-rock band. But she was decidedly modest, wearing long
dresses and gesturing almost entirely with graceful arms and hands,
restraining herself from motion below the shoulders. For her encore
she came back barefoot. It was an uptempo song, and she was shaking
with, apparently, the suppressed urge to dance, until she allowed
herself a final kick.
</P>
<P>
   Her voice is intact: lustrous, supple, full of heartache and
tender determination. Songs rose to imperious declarations, then
turned gentle in the course of a sustained note. Where many Western
divas work their way through songs until they get a chance to let
loose and belt, Googoosh treats the peaks of her songs like a
Persian singer, letting notes slide and cascade as if her melodies
were melting in the heat of her emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Every old song brought shouts and ululations of recognition, and
many audience members sang every word. In lyrics suffused with
imagery from nature, Googoosh sang about love so luxuriant it could
make the desert bloom, so joyful it could fill the air with bird
songs. There were bouncy tunes that harked back to 1960s bubble-gum
and spy-movie themes. There were uptempo songs that seemed to be
rooted in old Persian dance rhythms, and others with a touch of
disco. There were cabaret-style ballads with Romantic piano
flourishes. And there were slow songs, accompanied only by a piano
or a guitar, that Googoosh sang with elaborate Middle Eastern
ornamentation and a melancholy dignity.
</P>
<P>
   She has just released a new album, ``Zoroaster'' (Kia
Entertainment), that updates her music; she performed one new song
on Saturday that used flamenco guitar along the lines of the Gipsy
Kings. A few of her new songs also hinted at messages that were not
only personal.
</P>
<P>
   One, which can be translated from the Farsi as ``The Captive
Soil'' or ``The Captive Land,'' was about having her heart torn
into tiny pieces; at the end in a spoken coda she said, ``I have a
million sisters like 50 suns shining, and a million brothers, who
are green and red around me.'' The Iranian flag is red, green and
white. She continued, ``Imprisonment was cold/I have patience that
is old/I have love that is warm.'' And in ``Zoroaster,'' the
album's title song, she sang about crying for the children of war,
and promised, ``I will lend my voice to history.''
</P>
<P>
   What such declarations mean in Iran, to which Googoosh has said
she will return, is impossible to determine from abroad. For fans
who never expected to see her perform again, her reappearance was
cause enough for gratitude.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
