<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TORRE-605&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORRE SAYS HE PLANS ON MANAGING NEXT SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Joe Torre intends to return as the New York
Yankees' manager next year, the last season of his current
contract, and he said Sunday he hadn't ruled out the possibility of
managing in 2002 or beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm assuming I'm coming back,'' he said. ``And being under
contract, in my mind, I'm going to manage next year, because that's
what I'm under contract to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre could have left the Yankees last year, when he was treated
for prostate cancer, but he came back for this season. ``I'm
probably more interested in coming back this year than I was last
year,'' he said, referring to his plans for the upcoming season,
``only because healthwise I'd come through a lot emotionally, and I
had to think about it a little bit. But this year it's like, `This
is my job and that's what I'm going to do until I decide not to
work.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having fun,'' Torre said. ``You work your whole life to
get to that point, you work to make that choice, and it's your
choice. I'm fortunate at this point in time, that when it stops
being fun, I'd think I'd be content enough to move on. But right
now, I'm enjoying it. I still enjoy winning. I still have the fire
in my belly, and that's the important thing. Plus my wife is
wonderful: She wants me to retire right now, but not if this is
something I want to do. She's been saying that for three years.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre said he hadn't thought about whether to manage in 2002.
``But I'll tell you one thing, I haven't dismissed it either,'' he
said while sitting in the visitors' dugout of the Network
Associates Coliseum. ``Once you make that decision, that's probably
it. It's not like I would leave the game for five years and come
back at 65.''
</P>
<P>
   A columnist speculated in Newsday on Sunday morning that Torre
had become fed up with the management style of George Steinbrenner,
the Yankees' principal owner. ``I don't think I've ever said that
to anybody,'' Torre said. ``I don't feel any different than I did a
year ago, or even two years ago, for that matter. Five years ago,
over the last couple of years, I've gotten into a comfort zone of
knowing what it's like here. I don't think that has changed since
I've settled into that.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago, Steinbrenner released a statement that
subtly chastised Torre after he did not publicly embrace the
acquisition of the slugger Jose Canseco. At the time, Torre was
asked about this and responded simply that Steinbrenner was the
boss, effectively defusing a potentially explosive situation.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Torre nor Steinbrenner has discussed that matter since,
and they have maintained communication. ``In fact, I was talking to
George yesterday morning,'' Torre said. ``We're fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre did not seem as sure about whether Don Zimmer, his bench
coach for five seasons, would be back. Zimmer has been hobbled for
almost two years by knee trouble. ``I don't know,'' Torre said,
grimacing a bit. ``Every year it's the same thing. He's had a tough
year physically this year, the knee didn't respond.'' Torre said he
hoped Zimmer would return.
</P>
<P>
   Torre mentioned that when he retired, he would think about going
into broadcasting, something he did before resuming his managerial
career with the St. Louis Cardinals. He will also become eligible
to be selected by the Veterans Committee for baseball's Hall of
Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hall of Fame, if that ever happens, would be a wonderful
honor,'' he said. ``But after waiting as long as I did to get to
the World Series and then winning, God, it's going to have to go a
long way to make me feel as good as that did _ or does now, after
winning two more.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   O'Neill Still in Pain
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill, the Yankees' right fielder, is out indefinitely
with a hip pointer that has not improved. O'Neill, who has not
played since last Tuesday, took batting practice Sunday, tried
running and then walked off the field disconsolately. He received a
shot of cortisone before Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get out there,'' said O'Neill, who could play
Wednesday. ``The last few days, I didn't get to where I wanted to
be. Hopefully, this will knock it out and we'll get on with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre suggested before the game that if O'Neill's condition did
not improve, the outfielder might return to New York for rest and
treatment. ``I know he's getting frustrated with it,'' Torre said.
``He's a guy who's used to being able to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramiro Mendoza, on the disabled list with weakness in the back
of his right shoulder, will throw off a mound this week as part of
his effort to rejoin the team by mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are likely to add outfielder Ryan Thompson from
Triple-A Columbus when the major-league rosters expand on Sept. 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-00 2250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
