<HEADER>
A3603 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-R-FBC-PENNST-USC-NYT     08-27 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-FBC-PENNST-USC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN CAL REDUCES PENN STATE OFFENSE TO A DULL ROAR 
</HEADLINE>
 (Repeating to add photo note) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT13 and NYT14 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Penn State's first play Sunday
short-circuited with a false start and a 5-yard penalty. Moments
later, split end Eddie Drummond sustained a knee injury that put
him out of the game. Before long, the Nittany Lions' first
possession imploded with a blocked punt that created a Southern
California touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Three tedious hours later, Penn State's first game of the season
ended in a sloppy 29-5 victory for the Trojans in the Kickoff
Classic in Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   These two teams first met in the Rose Bowl of 1923. If they are
to meet there again this winter as winners of their conferences,
both will need to improve upon Sunday's ragged display of nerves
and errors.
</P>
<P>
   As the season opener for both sides, it was almost an exhibition
game in terms of impact. The leaves on most trees have not changed
color yet; conference games are still weeks away for USC and Penn
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a chance to be a good team and maybe this will
accelerate it,'' said USC Coach Paul Hackett, whose team finished
6-6 in 1999. ``Defensively, wow! They could not run the football
against us. There was some question about USC football. We took a
step nationally. We were carrying the banner for the Pac 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn State, a member of the Big Ten, gained only 6 net yards
rushing, the lowest total in Joe Paterno's 35 years as head coach.
The Nittany Lions had 142 yards of total offense.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the margin of victory, the Trojans' offense had little
to show for its ball control (USC ran 50 times) _ probably because
quarterback Carson Palmer was rusty in his return from a broken
collarbone.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to scoring on the blocked punt, USC scored another
first-half touchdown on a 43-yard interception return by Troy
Polamalu, who picked off a pass from Rashard Casey, Penn State's
troubled quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans also made a few mistakes. They gave up a safety on a
blocked punt and missed an extra point. Their best attacker was
Sultan McCullough, who ran 28 times for 128 yards. Much of that
yardage was gained on runs up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Voted the most valuable player of the game, McCullough said he
was ready to assume the starring role in the USC tailback
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say I'm a track star, but my first love is football,''
McCullough said. ``I can do it all.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had run the 40-yard dash in 4.2 seconds and could
probably run it in 4.1. He said his coaches told him: ```It's your
turn to shine,' so that's what I did. It's my first game. It's my
big opener. It feels good.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so good was Casey, who returned to his home state and some
troubling memories. He was charged with assaulting an off-duty
police officer in nearby Hoboken, his hometown, last May. The case
is still pending as is a civil suit.
</P>
<P>
   Casey ``lacked some consistency,'' according to Paterno, in
completing 7 of 24 passes for 106 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's capable of playing better than that, let's put it that
way,'' Paterno said. ``It was a tough outing for him, for a lot of
reasons. This was a tough preseason for him, for a lot of reasons.
He's got this one out of his craw. He can concentrate on having a
little more fun. It's not easy for him to come back here.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey, replaced early in the fourth quarter by Matt Senneca,
said: ``I'm glad to have this one out of the way, but I'm not glad
the way it turned out. You take the good with the bad. Today, I
think I might have put too much pressure on myself.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his linemen, tackle Kareem McKenzie, said Penn State's
five penalties for false starts resulted from ``not being focused
on the plays called and the snap count itself; not being as focused
as we should have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had our number all day long,'' McKenzie said.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat kept Paterno six victories short of Bear Bryant's
Division I-A record of 323.
</P>
<P>
   Including the end of last season, Penn State has lost four
consecutive regular-season games (although the Lions won the Alamo
Bowl last December).
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth consecutive victory for USC, which won its
final three games in 1999 after losing six of the previous seven
after a season-ending injury to Palmer. A sophomore, Palmer
completed 10 of 20 passes for 87 yards Sunday against Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   Petros Papadakis scored on a 2-yard touchdown run and David
Newbury kicked field goals of 47, 27 and 44 yards for Southern Cal.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State's best chance to rally came in the third quarter,
when the Lions blocked a punt into the USC end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Had Penn State fallen on the ball for a touchdown, as the
Trojans had earlier, the score and an extra point could have cut
the lead to 23-10 and changed the momentum.
</P>
<P>
   But Southern Cal's Marcell Allmond recovered, the Lions got only
2 points and the crowd of 78,902 soon began to file out. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-00 2253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000827.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3604 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-KICKOFF-USC-LADN     08-27 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KICKOFF-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC DISMANTLES PENN STATE IN KICKOFF CLASSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ It just figured that USC would celebrate
wildly for its fans gathered behind an end zone at Giants Stadium.
Nothing else the Trojans did Sunday was at half-speed, so why
should the party be any different?
</P>
<P>
   Even USC coach Paul Hackett was still clutching the Kickoff
Classic championship trophy 45 minutes after the Trojans routed
Penn State 29-5 in front of a record crowd of 78,902.
</P>
<P>
   This was not a normal day for a USC football team, at least not
in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The energy of the team was the one thing that we had out
there,'' Hackett said. ``The energy, and a lot of it came from
coaches, was different. And everyone on the team believed in it.
There was just a lot of energy everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   It could be argued the Trojans were wired up like rarely before
in recent memory. USC's victory over the 22nd-ranked Nittany Lions
was the first over a ranked team on a road or neutral site since
the 1996 Rose Bowl. It was just the second time they have done it
since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that explains why everyone was so eager to explain what
it all meant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a force to be reckoned with,'' offensive lineman Faasea
Mailo said. ``A lot of people thought we would get dominated the
way we dominated them.''
</P>
<P>
   Added linebacker Zeke Moreno: ``We know that everyone now knows
that we're no joke. I came here because of the football and
tradition and all of that is back. I think we got a lot of
respect.''
</P>
<P>
   The 15th-ranked Trojans (1-0) dominated Penn State (0-1)
offensively and defensively in ways that were not totally expected:
</P>
<P>
   -- Tailback Sultan McCullough, the game's most valuable player,
gained a career high 128 yards in 29 carries. But instead of
breaking long runs, he became a power back.
</P>
<P>
   -- Kicker David Newbury, who was 11 for 20 last season, made all
three field goals, which Hackett called ``mind-boggling.''
</P>
<P>
   -- The offensive line, the Trojans' weak link, actually wore
down Penn State's defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see their defense say, `Oh no, here they come
again,''' Mailo said.
</P>
<P>
   And they did it without a single false start, an almost
unheard-of occurrence.
</P>
<P>
   -- Then there was the defense, which USC thought was its
strength, and which did little to dispel that theory. They held
Penn State's star quarterback, Rashard Casey, to 106 yards passing,
including zero in the second half, and minus-20 yards rushing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had nowhere to go,'' Moreno said. ``We had great
containment on him. We showed what we are capable of.''
</P>
<P>
   USC also won without its vaunted passing game. Quarterback
Carson Palmer, considered the Trojans' single most important
player, completed just 10 of 20 passes for 87 yards and one
interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can have a nonexistent quarterback and still win, that
says a lot about us,'' Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Want more bizarreness?
</P>
<P>
   The Nittany Lions were held to six yards rushing, the lowest
total in any game Penn State legend Joe Paterno has coached in his
35 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   It was also the first time the Nittany Lions had not scored a
touchdown since 1998. And when USC strong safety Troy Polamalu
returned an interception 43 yards for a touchdown, it was the first
time that happened in six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't have it,'' Paterno said. ``They're very
aggressive. They were certainly a better team than we were today.''
</P>
<P>
   That was apparent from the outset. On the game's first
possession, USC safety Frank Strong broke through the line and
blocked David Royer's punt. The ball skipped off Kris Richard's
fingers and into the hands of Sandy Fletcher, who ran six yards for
a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Nittany Lions cut the lead to 7-3 on a 37-yard field goal by
Ryan Primanti, but that hardly fazed the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   USC turned into a power-running team, with the line opening
holes for McCullough, who carried the ball five times for 42 yards
on the drive, and also caught a 6-yard pass. Palmer then hit
Marcell Allmond on a 22-yard pass before Petros Papadakis scored on
a 2-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   That gave USC a 14-3 lead, and began to place doubts in the
minds of the overwhelmingly pro-Penn State crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``The line was telling me, `Run behind me.' They were all
motivated to run the ball,'' McCullough said. ``We ran the ball
down their throat.''
</P>
<P>
   Already with an unexpected special-teams touchdown, the Trojans
got another one from their defense. Polamalu, in his first career
start at strong safety, snagged a terrible Casey pass and
zig-zagged 43 yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was reacting to what I saw,'' Polamalu said. ``I just saw
Casey but I had three blockers in front of me and I tried to use
them. It felt great.''
</P>
<P>
   If Paterno wasn't already feeling fate was against him, Newbury
stunned Hackett by hitting field goals of 47, 27 and 44 yards. His
only slip-up was a missed extra point, but it hardly mattered.
USC's defense never allowed another point after Primanti's field
goal, with Penn State managing only a safety after blocking Mike
MacGillivray's punt in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we were real tired of hearing the myth that Pac-10
football was done and that we couldn't stop the run,'' defensive
tackle Ennis Davis said. ``Sultan is running the ball like he owns
it, he's running real hard, and the defense is playing tough. I
think we've got a nice team.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
