(Courtney Kealy/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Aug. 27, 2000 -- BLACKS-DNA -- In Boston this
fall, some 300 African-American schoolchildren are to be sent home
with swabs to gather DNA samples from inside the mouths of their
relatives, part of a nascent project that a local molecular
biologist hopes to extend to North Carolina and other sites with
longstanding African-American populations. A technician involved in
compiling DNA databases, cleaning a skeleton in the African Burial
Ground project in New York. (The New York Times/African Burial
Ground Project)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) TSENTORA-YURT, Russia -- Aug. 27, 2000 --
RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-2 -- A year after Russian troops poured into
Chechnya, the breakaway republic is a battered, dispirited but
proud land that continues to present Russia's gravest security
challenge. Recently, rebels have sought to infiltrate village
administrations throughout Chechnya, hoping to gain control of food
and other supplies so they can divert them to their fighters in the
woods and mountains. In Tsentora-Yurt, women and children make
their way home after collecting water at a local well. (James
Hill/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) GROZNY, Russia -- Aug. 27, 2000 -- RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-1 -- A
year after Russian troops poured into Chechnya, the breakaway
republic is a battered, dispirited but proud land that continues to
present Russia's gravest security challenge. Russian casualties
mount every week as the fighting has shifted from large-scale
assaults to skirmishing and ambushes that have turned Chechnya into
a nasty quagmire for the Russian president, Vladimir V. Putin, and
his top generals. In Grozny, a Russian soldier rests near Minutka
Square, site of some of the fiercest fighting in the war. (James
Hill/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Aug. 27, 2000 -- WRITERS-ON-WRITING -- Andre
Acimen says he writes ``to give my life a form, a narrative. (Angel
Franco/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) HAJNOWKA, Poland -- Aug. 27, 2000 -- POLAND-EUROPE --
Whether the citizens of Poland like it or not, much of the burden
of blocking illegal trade and immigration into the European Union
will fall on them. That will do real damage to the active
cross-border trade that helps keep some of the poorest parts of
Poland alive. Farmers on top of a haystack in Hajnowka, very close
to the Polish-Belarussian frontier. (Alan Chin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) RAMLE, Israel -- Aug. 27, 2000 -- ISRAEL-HAMAS -- A
botched raid on an Islamic militant hide-out in the West Bank
village of Assira Ashmalia, late Saturday night, ended with three
Israeli soldiers dead -- all possibly by friendly fire -- and
Palestinian officials angry at how Israel handles threats to peace
between the two peoples. The target of the nighttime raid was
Mahmoud Abu Hanoud, known as the leader of the militant Hamas
group's military wing and a fugitive at the top of Israel's
most-wanted list. At a grave site in Ramle, Israel, on Sunday,
soldiers, friends and family, mourn the loss of one of the soldiers
killed in the raid. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) SAN DIEGO, Calif. -- Aug. 27, 2000 -- OPEN-SOURCE -- In a
report to President Clinton last year, a group of leading computer
scientists warned that the nation faced a troubling ``software
gap.'' The group, made up of corporate executives and university
researchers, said that programmers simply could not keep pace with
exploding demand for high-quality software -- the computer code
needed for everything from Internet commerce to nuclear weapons
design. Larry Smarr, right, a presidential committee member, speaks
with Yannick Lemieux at Entropia, a Web server in San Diego, Calif.
(Bob Greiser/The New York Times)
</P>
