republic is a battered, dispirited but proud land that continues to
present Russia's gravest security challenge. Grozny, Chechnya's
nominal capital and a ruin of a city, still lacks gas, electricity
and any visible efforts at restoration. Only a few thousand people
still seem to live there, but now they include rebels who have
managed to sneak back into the city. A Russian soldier stood guard
near the market in Grozny while a woman and her children waited for
a bus. (James Hill/The New York Times)
