<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3756 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-CALSTATE-QUAKE-LADN     08-27 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALSTATE-QUAKE-LADN </SLUG>
 
UNIVERSITY FINALLY FINISHED RECOVERING FROM NORTHRIDGE EARTHQUAKE &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIK NELSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For the first time since the 1994 Northridge
Earthquake, Susan Curzon will stretch her legs and enjoy silence as
the new academic year begins at California State University,
Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the whining saws now that the campus's $407 million
reconstruction project is complete.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the office and classroom trailers spread over fields
and parking lots across campus for the last six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't leave them fast enough,'' said Curzon, dean of the
university's Oviatt Library, which sports a $22 million face lift
featuring 100,000-square-foot east and west wings. The library, the
first campus building to reopen this year, will be dedicated in
September.
</P>
<P>
   By March, faculty and staff will move into the last of five
rebuilt university buildings, and the campus will be whole once
again.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, enrollment is expected to surge to a record 28,000
students this fall, while 70 new faculty members will start Monday
and more parking will be available thanks to the removal of
temporary classrooms. Also, CSUN will debut its first cybercafe _
complete with a Krispy Kreme doughnut shop.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN's new president, Jolene Koester, said she's looking forward
to the start of the academic year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful time for me to be starting here because this
year sees the completion and restoration of all of our buildings,
which symbolize the university's renewed sense of mission and
purpose,'' Koester said.
</P>
<P>
   Now that library services have moved back, Curzon can take
pleasure in watching students spread their books and papers out in
one of the building's new study rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really enjoy seeing the library patrons making themselves
comfortable all over the library,'' Curzon said.
</P>
<P>
   In October, officials expect to start moving into the $5.7
million, 31,000-square-foot expansion of the Art and Design Center,
and after that the $14 million, 85,500 square-foot College of
Health and Human Development and University Technology Center.
</P>
<P>
   By semester's end on Dec. 21, Koester will move into new
quarters in the $13 million, 82,000-square-foot Administration
Building. The biggest of the rebuilding projects, the $17 million,
88,000-square-foot Arts, Media and Communication Building, is
slated to open in March.
</P>
<P>
   The school has also rebuilt its enrollment, which was at 27,300
when the earthquake hit, dropped and then rose back to 27,700 in
1997 and has risen slightly ever since. This year, registration is
running about 600 more students than last year at the same time, so
officials expect enrollment will easily pass a record 28,000 this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to all of the fresh concrete, bricks and mortar,
there will be new blood added to the university, Koester said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, 70 new full-time faculty members will start their first
semester at the university. Most of them will replace retiring
faculty, many of whom were hired in the 1960s when the campus was
young.
</P>
<P>
   Students will also come back to a new treat: A Krispy Kreme
outlet like no other in the nation. This purveyor of doughnuts and
coffee will feature six IMac desktop computers plugged into the
campus network and the Internet and 14 ports to provide network
access for patrons' laptops.
</P>
<P>
   And parking, a chronic problem since trailers took up so much
space after the earthquake, will be relieved slightly this year. A
village of temporary classrooms will be removed in September,
freeing up about 70 spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Washington, who was accompanying his 18-year-old
daughter, Paige, to an orientation last week, said he is impressed
with how quickly the campus has recovered from the earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like things are really state-of-the-art now,'' said
Washington, who knows something about recovering from earthquakes.
He works for the city of Oakland, which he says is still working on
replacing buildings damaged by the 1989 Loma Prieta Earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore Marcos Morales, who works part time at the library,
has a more practical reason to enjoy the near-completion of the
campus' reconstruction project. Last year, Morales had to walk
several blocks to make copies of newspaper and magazine articles,
kept on microfilm and microfiche in a trailer far from the Oviatt
Library.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to take all day,'' Morales said. ``Now I just go
upstairs. It's like, really convenient; everything's right there.''
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
